the 9-year-old son of a zimbabwean diplomat who had been accused of abusing the boy has been returned to his native land, according to a published report
u.s. officials said terence karamba left new york for zimbabwe on sunday, accompanied by a zimbabwean social worker, but was not to be returned to his father's custody, the washington post reported in tuesday's editions
the boy was to be placed in foster care under the auspices of the courts and the zimbabwean ministry of social welfare, said robert j. mcmahon, director of the social services agency that had cared for the boy for the past two months
mcmahon, executive director of st. christopher-ottile services for children and families, said the karamba family would undergo counseling in hopes of eventually being reunited with terence
with any of these cases, there's always a lump at the bottom of your stomach, but i think the level of risk is as low as you can possibly get it,'' mcmahon told the newspaper
a city agency had charged that the boy's father, floyd, had beaten the boy and the child in december was removed from his home and placed in foster care
the father, who served for more than a year as a member of zimbabwe's delegation to the united nations, was ordered to leave the united states because of what state department officials called ``clear evidence of child abuse.''
in january, the supreme court refused to block the u.s. government from sending the boy home after the legal aid society's juvenile rights division had argued that the boy was afraid to go home
mcmahon said sen. daniel patrick moynihan, d-n.y., interceded and persuaded the state department that the boy should not be returned immediately
we received what we asked for, which was time to work with the boy, said gary kipling, a st. christopher-ottilie official who served as terence's foster father part of the time
the state department had a psychiatric consultant accompany the boy on his trip home and also engaged a law firm in zimbabwe to monitor his case, the post reported
plo leader yasser arafat met monday with five western diplomats and delivered messages about the ``dangers'' of the u.s. plan for a middle east peace settlement, the palestinian wafa news agency reported
it said arafat met with the ambassadors of france, britain, greece, spain and turkey in tunis, the headquarters of the palestine liberation organization
wafa said arafat asked the diplomats to transmit to their nations his concern about ``the dangers to the palestinian people of the new american demarche.''
a two-day summit conference of the north atlantic treaty organization is to open wednesday in brussels, belgium, with president reagan among the leaders scheduled to attend
according to wafa, arafat's messages said the u.s. plan proposed by secretary of state george shultz on his mideast tour ``ignores the national rights of the palestinian people, notably their right to self-determination and the creation of an independent state on their own territory under the plo, the sole, legitimate representative.''
shultz has called for a palestinian role in negotiations, but not participation by the plo
james h. douglas jr., an air force secretary under president dwight d. eisenhower who presided over the planning and construction of the air force academy in colorado springs, colo., died wednesday. he was 88
douglas graduated from princeton university after serving as an army officer in world war i. he earned a law degree from harvard in 1924
douglas, an attorney and investment banker, also served for two years as deputy secretary of defense beginning in 1959. he held a high post in the treasury department under presidents herbert hoover and franklin d. roosevelt. douglas was appointed undersecretary of the air force in 1953 and secretary in 1957
joseph kiselewski, an internationally known sculptor, died friday at the age of 87
kiselewski work included the world war ii memorial in holland's veterans cemetery, the statue of harold vanderbilt in nashville, tenn., and four plaques for the house chamber of the capitol in washington, d.c
he received many awards for his work, including the prix de rome and the beaux arts prize and he's listed in who's who in america
beatrice major van fleet burns, the wife of former governor of hawaii john anthony burns, died sunday at age 82
burns was elected governor of hawaii in 1962. mrs. burns served as hawaii's first lady for 12 years. her husband died in april 1975
leslie h. turner, 88, the artist who wrote and illustrated the ``captain easy'' adventure comic strip for 27 years, died sunday
turner graduated with an english degree in 1922 from southern methodist university in dallas. considered one of the top magazine illustrators of the 1920s and '30s, turner was best remembered for ``captain easy,'' which at its peak appeared in more than 600 daily newspapers
the strip addressed unpleasant subjects such as alcoholism as early as 1949, and it won praise for being scientifically correct. turner wrote and illustrated ``captain easy'' until he retired in 1970. cocktail party.</note>
prince andrew and his pregnant wife, sarah, lingered over a museum incubator but declined to cuddle the kicking mechanical infant inside monday, the fourth day of a 10-day trade trip by the royal entourage
the couple awoke aboard the 416-foot royal yacht britannia beneath typically british gray skies with rain stalking their motorcade to a museum, department store and a supermarket sojourn described as a first royal visit to an american supermarket
it was retail day for the duke and duchess of york
the day began with andrew welcoming top u.s executives for an investment seminar on the royal yacht, aimed at attracting american money to britain. the couple then went ashore
the incubator was the final stop on the royal couple's walk through the los angeles county museum of science and industry, which also included a tour of an exhibit on british technology. despite repeated entreaties from a british photographer, sarah wouldn't pick up the kicking pink babe, dubbed samantha by the exhibitors
can you believe them?'' she asked her guides, laughing at the jostling crowd of newsmen kept in check by a chain barrier and u.s. state department security guards. the duchess is expecting a child in august
at the vons pavilions market, a deluxe, high-tech supermarket in suburban arcadia, the duchess tasted coffee-toffee-chip ice cream and turned up her nose at a corn dog, and both she and the prince tried their hand at cake decorating as they cruised the aisles
earlier, andrew told u.s. executives that anglo-american business bonds are as important as historical and cultural ties
britain wants american investments, the duke of york said during a brief appearance before 80 delegates attending a daylong investment seminar aboard the royal yacht britannia, which included a five-hour luncheon cruise
greetings from queen elizabeth ii were relayed by sir paul greening, chairman of the royal household
the queen says she hopes you have a worthwhile day. the queen has personally chosen what you'll have for lunch today,'' said greening, who didn't divulge the menu
the economic ties between our two nations are no less important than our cultural ones,'' andrew said
there were delegates from such companies as hewlett-packard, hughes aircraft, ford motor co., apple computers and lockheed aircraft. among them was henry termeer of boston-based genzyme, a biotechnology firm
it's definitely a public relations ploy to create good will. i think it's an excellent idea. every european country does this sort of thing, but not every country has a royal family with a ship like this,'' said termeer
the day's events also included a visit to bullocks wilshire department store, which was touting british goods
celebrities michael york, morgan fairchild and roddy mcdowell and hundreds of store employees were among those who greeted the royal couple's arrival at the posh art deco landmark
at one point during the tour, the duchess scanned the first floor vestibule and was asked by a guest if she was looking for her husband, who had gone ahead. ``no, i see him every day,'' sarah replied
monday evening, the royal couple took a moonlit stroll through the lush wetherly gardens at the four seasons hotel in los angeles
the cocktail party was tossed by british consul general donald ballentyne, and guests who noshed on hors d'oeuvres and sipped champagne included ``dynasty'' actress emma samms and actor vincent price
when cara dunne listened to broadcasters narrate the olympic skiing events, she recalled the thrill of winning her own medals last month at international games for the disabled
the 17-year-old chicagoan was blinded by cancer as a baby. after years of training, she won two silver medals in the 1988 winter olympic games for the disabled in innsbruck, austria
miss dunne, a senior at william howard taft high school on the northwest side, said she feels every bit an olympian
in the opening ceremonies, when you march in with your teammates, you feel so proud because you are representing your country,'' she said
miss dunne said the olympic coverage from calgary reminded her of her own triumphs and defeats
when people are falling, you can relate to them,'' said miss dunne. she said she lost the gold in austria because she slipped in the second run of the giant slalom
basically you work all your life for the goals you set. when you are competing you feel an enormous amount of pressure,'' she said
but when the race is over you feel this great spirit. i think that is what the olympics _ whether able-bodied or disabled _ is all about.''
miss dunne's parents started teaching her to ski when she was 7
when we got into skiing ... i looked at it as a chance for cara to prove to her friends and her schoolmates that she is just as capable as they are,'' said her stepfather, richard zabelski
zabelski, a lawyer, has been her guide, skiing in front of miss dunne, yelling directions
initially i was trying to get the attention of a new step-child,'' he said. ``now we are strictly training for success.''
prior to the latest competition, miss dunne and zabelski trained full time for about six weeks. he pays for most of the training because disabled athletes are not sponsored by the government and landing corporate sponsors is tough
miss dunne, the youngest member of the disabled olympic ski team, said she has won nine medals in international competition
she said she received an acceptance letter from harvard university last week, ``so i don't know how much time i'll have for training.''
but she is already looking forward to the 1992 games, when the disabled and able-bodied winter olympics will be held simultaneously in albertville, france
a roman catholic high school wrestling team is traveling to the soviet union this week to compete against soviet athletes in what school officials have dubbed an ``experiment in glasnost.''
the sacred heart high school team is apparently the first roman catholic group officially welcomed to the soviet union to compete, said the rev. philip j. cascia, the school's chaplain and wrestling coach
the soviets are very conscious of their image,'' he said. ``this could be a very positive statement from them that they are willing to take steps toward more openness.''
one team member is gary shvartsbeyn, a 16-year-old soviet jew who immigrated to the united states in 1980. shvartsbeyn says the trip will be a chance for him to avoid the severe travel restrictions he faced when he lived in the soviet union
i'd just like to see something in russia i never saw before,'' said shvartsbeyn, a native of the village of donetzk in the ukraine
the 30 wrestlers are set to leave wednesday. the team, which had a disappointing 2-22 record this season, has scheduled three matches with soviet wrestling clubs _ one at the olympic village in moscow and two at the sports complex in leningrad
also making the trip are 20 honor students from sacred heart along with 37 coaches, teachers and parents who will act as chaperones
cascia said he wants to make sure the energetic teen-agers are on their best behavior, because they will be acting as goodwill ambassadors not only for the united states but for the roman catholic church as well
cascia hatched the idea for the trip seven months ago. formal approval came from the soviet government the day that mikhail s. gorbachev headed home after his summit meeting with president reagan in december
cascia thinks the timing was evidence that the school's trip is another ``experiment in glasnost,'' the soviet leader's much-touted policy of openness
the fact that they've given us the olympic village, which is their showpiece ... indicated right away they are going to give us a lot of attention,'' he said
the students are paying just $200 apiece, with the rest being financed by a $25,000 grant from the u.s. government, $5,000 from the waterbury tourism council, and the sale of t-shirts bearing the message in english and russian that ``glasnost is real.''
the soviet government is donating $5,000 in services, the school said
the cia and the agriculture department have teamed up to report that the cabbage is king in the soviet union, while americans bow to the tomato
the study of food supplies in the united states and the soviet union says that radish and carrot tops are common fare among soviet consumers but are rarely found on american grocery lists. but then, the united states has the sweet potato while the soviet union doesn't
on the other hand, the overall nutrient levels in the two nations are not too far apart. on the average, the soviet union supplies about 3,200 calories per day to each citizen, compared with 3,500 for the average american
protein availability, at an average of 100 grams per day, is a tossup. but americans have more fat and cholesterol in their food supply, while soviet people get more carbohydrates
the study was conducted jointly by the cia and the agriculture department's human nutrition information service. the report by cia and hnis analysts was published in the latest national food review, a quarterly magazine of the department's economic research service
a 16-year period, 1965 to 1981, was used in the study. information about soviet per capita food use was supplied by the cia's office of soviet analysis from ``various published and unpublished sources,'' the report said. the usda agency drew on extensive food statistics kept on americans
the report cautioned that the food use statistics for both countries were derived mathematically from production, exports, imports, year-end inventories and other annual figures
but within those limitations, analysts said the study ``reveals some interesting differences and similarities'' between the united states and the soviet union
for instance, sources of food energy differed,'' the report said. ``carbohydrate provided most of the energy in the soviet food supply, while carbohydrate and fat provided almost equal proportions in the u.s. supply. protein provided the same proportion in both countries.''
among the soviet vegetables, cabbage ranked number one,'' the report said. ``soviet use reached 66 pounds per capita in 1981, compared with 55 pounds 16 years earlier. u.s. use stayed at about 10 or 12 pounds.''
cabbages accounted for 34 percent of all vegetables used in the soviet union in 1981, while providing only 6 percent of the u.s. vegetable menu
tomatoes led the u.s. list, accounting for 24 percent of all vegetables, while ranking second in the soviet union at 28 percent. carrots and beets were next among soviet vegetables, while lettuce was second in the united states, followed by cucumbers
the per capita use of foods in nine major categories increased between 1965 and 1981 in the soviet union. those included poultry, eggs, fruit, fish, vegetable fats, dairy products, vegetables, sugars and sweeteners, and meat
at the same time, the united states gained in the use of meat, poultry, vegetable fats, and sugars and sweeteners, the report said. potato and grain use declined in the soviet union, while the use of animal fats, eggs, dairy products and potatoes dropped in the united states
one of the reasons behind huge soviet grain imports of recent years is a drive by moscow to increase the production of livestock and poultry to help upgrade the diets of soviet consumers. the report shows how the situation has changed
in 1965, the soviet union's per capita use of dairy products was 244 pounds, compared with 453 pounds in the united states. by 1981, soviet use rose to 347 pounds, while the u.s. average dropped to 405 pounds
meat use by the soviets in 1965 was 78 pounds per capita against the u.s. average of 146 pounds. in 1981, the averages, respectively, were 98 and 154 pounds
the soviet per capita use of potatoes in 1965 was reported at 313 pounds, compared with 86 pounds in the united states. in 1981, potato use had dropped to 232 and 78 pounds, respectively
although soviet use of grain products declined from 343 pounds per capita in 1965 to 304 pounds in 1981, it was still approximately twice as much as in the united states (145 pounds in 1965 and 151 pounds in 1981),'' the report said
wheat accounted for the largest share in both countries, but rye, rice, barley, corn, buckwheat and oats were also used.''
grain products in the soviet union were primarily in the form of whole grains and groats, or coarsely ground, hulled grain, the report said. white flour was the major grain product used in the united states
it may be the most implausible gambit of the year, or the most naive, or just the dumbest _ but there isn't any doubt that paul simon's decision to skip the south on super tuesday turns 1988 political theology on its head
we urged him to take a midwestern industrial strategy,'' said illinois democratic chairman vince demuzio, perhaps with a straight face
the accepted dogma is that no democrat in this lifetime will grace the white house without winning a fair share of states in the south
it's simple arithmetic. the republicans have had a lock on the west; they've done whatever it takes to win california and they've added support from the farm belt and the upper reaches of new england
democrats _ who won ``hubert humphreyland'' in 1984, but little else _ generally can rely on some industrial states, the islands of hawaii and the four corners of the district of columbia
of course that doesn't add up to a democratic victory in the electoral college and during a 20-year stretch, the republicans have lost the white house just once, to georgia's jimmy carter
and so party leaders agree the democrats must work the south; the need for a southern strategy was an underlying rationale for creating next week's super tuesday primaries and is one explanation for the tremendous effort being poured into the region this week by massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, jesse jackson, rep. richard gephardt of missouri and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee
but not paul simon
simon is the senator from illinois whose campaign is floundering, to be polite. after a second-place finish in iowa, third-place finishes in new hampshire and minnesota and a complete collapse in south dakota, he is out of money and out of the running
the book of campaign etiquette says this is where simon thanks his staff, thanks his supporters and gets out of the race _ perhaps throwing his endorsement to a candidate who shares his values. maybe dukakis, or maybe a dramatic, home-state boost for jackson
yes, that's the way it's generally done
simon embraced the etiquette just after new hampshire
if i don't win either minnesota or south dakota, i'm going to drop out of the race,'' he said. ``i don't want to just continue indefinitely running second or third.''
he expressed high hopes for victory, declaring, ``the place where my natural roots are is right here in hubert humphreyland.''
the logic was unassailable but his resolve didn't last
before 24 hours, simon was hedging ``because of the reaction we've been getting from around the country.'' (whose reaction was he talking about? certainly not the reaction of the voters in hubert humphreyland; he finished just behind uncommitted, just behind jackson and way behind dukakis
and so simon announced that he's going to skip the south and pick up in illinois on march 15, in michigan on march 26, and so on. he says the southern vote will be ``scattered'' and that, ``we're not going to have a first-ballot nominee. we're going to have a very open convention.''
fair enough. but will the convention turn to paul simon?
the dogma of 1988 says the last thing the democrats will do is nominate a candidate who bypassed the south. he could put minnie pearl on his ticket and it wouldn't keep the republicans from rubbing their hands together in excitement
not that simon is talking about a southerner for his ticket. no, he's got a ``midwestern industrial strategy.'' in michigan the other day he said he'd want to consider lee iacocca as a running mate
it's possible that simon, blinded by presidential ambition, simply does not see this strategy as futile. but simon didn't enter the race until failing to draft sen. dale bumpers of arkansas, so blind ambition doesn't ring true. and naive, or stupid, he is not
instead, this skip-the-south gambit is probably a reluctant deference to local pols who want to ride his home-state coattails into atlanta
there are people in illinois who want to go to the convention and who are simon delegates,'' simon said last week
that's all well and good for them, but simon himself stands to become a quintessential spoiler, draining votes from compatible liberal candidates without a prayer of winning himself. in return, he might hope to amass the kind of good will in illinois democratic clubrooms that provides an uncontested primary for re-election in 1990
jonathan wolman is assistant bureau chief in washington for the associated press. case</head>
if lawyer e. robert wallach had stayed with his original plan, attorney general edwin meese iii's files would never have contained a 1985 memo outlining a plan to pay the israeli labor party to ensure the safety of a proposed $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline
the memo to meese is part of a three-document package that wallach gave to the attorney general on the same day in september 1985 in an attempt to revive the project, which was foundering over iraq's demand for an insurance package against israeli bombing
the documents, now part of special prosecutor james mckay's criminal investigation into meese's activities, were released last week by the attorney general's lawyers. in addition, three telex messages from wallach to a swiss oilman who was a partner in the pipeline project surfaced last week and showed that wallach and other project backers attempted to have pentagon budget money paid to the israelis not to bomb the pipeline
the pipeline memos also have drawn the attention of iran-contra independent counsel lawrence walsh because they draw the first link between the pipeline project and the trade of arms for hostages
the burgeoning paper trail in the meese-pipeline episode includes a sept. 19, 1985 handwritten letter from then-israeli prime minister shimon peres expressing support for the proposed pipeline
but mckay, who is investigating meese's role in the pipeline project, is focusing on two memos, both dated sept. 25, 1985, from wallach to meese. the peres letter was attached to the first memo, a four-page explanation of the problems surrounding the project. in it, wallach urged meese to help round up support from top u.s. officials
one problem, wallach wrote, was that seeking the insurance package required disclosing to a number of bankers and others the nature of the ``security package'' guaranteeing that israel wouldn't destroy the line
wallach said this package involved the ``never-to-be-stated but fully understood quid pro quo.''
meese's lawyers say the quid pro quo was a reference to plans by wallach's client, swiss oilman bruce rappaport, to make available to israel substantial amounts of oil from the pipeline. discounts on the oil were to amount to $650 million to $700 million over 10 years
however, government sources familiar with the investigation of meese say mckay is trying to determine whether the ``quid pro quo'' memo is related to the second memo that wallach handed over to meese at the same time
the second memo, marked ``personal &amp; confidential _ for your eyes, only,'' contains a paragraph which says that rappaport confirmed with peres the ``arrangement'' in which israel was to receive up to $700 million over 10 years from the pipeline. the next sentence says: ``what was also indicated to me, and which would be denied everywhere, is that a portion of those funds will go directly to labor.''
mckay wants to know whether the money for the israeli labor party headed by peres is the ``quid pro quo'' mentioned in the first memo
if it is, the two memos suggest that meese may have known about a plan to bribe israeli politicians as a way to assure the safety of the planned pipeline. if meese knew about such a proposed payoff, he might be charged with violating or conspiring to violate the foreign corrupt practices act. that law bars bribes to foreign officials and gives the attorney general authority to file civil suits to stop u.s. companies from bribing potential foreign customers
in the ``quid pro quo'' memo, wallach was trying to explain to meese the importance of rappaport to the pipeline project. to demonstrate the ``credibility and relationship'' of rappaport to israel, wallach, a longtime friend of the attorney general, also said that he was ``preparing ... a memorandum for my own files'' on other matters wallach said he had discussed with the swiss oilman
i will communicate orally the contents of that memorandum,'' wallach said
but he changed his mind _ for reasons as yet undisclosed
instead of giving meese a verbal summary of that memo, wallach gave the document to meese, thus allowing the special prosecutor and the public to see what wallach said were rappaport's thoughts about money for the israeli labor party
was this a planned bribe?
peres, who is now israel's foreign minister, denies receiving any bribe offer; a peres aide is quoted as saying the then-prime minister was told israel would get oil discounts but peres didn't take that seriously. rappaport denies making any payoffs. and meese says he doesn't recall reading the portion of the second memo mentioning labor party payments. iran-contra</head>
republican jack kemp, trying to breathe life into his lagging presidential campaign, blasted george bush and bob dole as tax-raising twins in a southern debate and said if either is nominated, ``the reagan revolution is over, gone, dead.''
and bush and dole tangled repeatedly at a debate sunday afternoon on their differing calls for a budget freeze, on the iran-contra affair and on protecting the south's textile industry from foreign competition
the gop debate may be the last confrontation of the four gop candidates before the big round of primaries across the south on march 8, super tuesday
bush forces, confident that the vice president commands the field in dixie, said after the debate that bush had no plans to attend the next scheduled debate, set sunday in nashville and sponsored by the league of women voters. his move could scrap the final gop debate of the southern campaign
we're simply at a point where we've got 20 states,'' bush campaign manager lee atwater said. ``we've got a pretty busy schedule.''
only a week ago, the bush forces expressed shock that sen. dole of kansas and the fourth contender, pat robertson, backed out of a similar debate in dallas
rep. kemp of new york, whose white house aspirations are on the ropes after a series of poor showings in the earlier primaries and caucuses, tried to depict himself as the true conservative in the race and lumped bush and dole together as moderates who would raise taxes and turn their backs on the legacy of president reagan
frankly under bob dole or george bush you're going to get exactly the same thing,'' kemp said in the debate sponsored by the atlanta journal-constitution newspapers
they sound alike. they talk alike. and they have supported together every single tax increase in the last eight years
if they're nominated, i want you folks to know, the reagan revolution is over, gone, dead,'' he said
bush and dole both objected, saying they have fought against tax increases and for the reagan administration's agenda for the past seven years. they charged that kemp wasn't willing to take steps to solve the federal budget deficit, even as both said raising taxes wasn't the way they would do it
jack's never met a deficit he didn't like,'' dole said
bush told kemp: ``you don't care about deficits. you never have, and they're public enemy no. 1.''
dole raised the iran-contra subject and, holding a copy of a report by a commission bush headed that recommended no deals with terrorists, charged that bush had condoned selling weapons to iran in exchange for hostages
we should never trade arms for hostages. we shouldn't issue these reports and say we shouldn't trade arms for hostages _ the vice president's report _ and then later go to a meeting and say it's all right. we shouldn't do those things,'' dole said
bush, who contends he did not know the arms were being exchanged for hostages, said only that ``mistakes were made'' in the iran-contra affair
asked later if the affair had occurred on ``his watch,'' bush replied: ``i think when the president found out what happened, he took the proper steps.''
robertson, the former television preacher, offered a defense of embattled attorney general edwin meese iii, saying intense scrutiny has made it difficult to attract people to government. meese is under investigation by an independent counsel
after spending the last two weeks explaning his own remarks _ that nuclear missiles are in cuba, that bush forces have engaged in dirty tricks and that his christian broadcasting network knew where american hostages were held in lebanon _ robertson criticized the press
i know it's very difficult dealing with the press of america to get the truth out. they love to distort our words,'' robertson said
kemp accused dole and robertson of changing positions to please southern voters with their support for legislation limiting textile imports. the textile industry is particularly large in south carolina, which holds a key southern test on saturday, two days before primaries across the rest of the south
he referred to rep. richard gephardt of missouri, a democratic candidate who has called for tough trade sanctions against unfair trading partners, when he said after the debate, ``pat robertson and bob dole sound like dick gephardt to me on trade.''
robertson said that foreign imports now make up a large portion of the domestic textile market and asked, ``how much do you want to give them, communist china and communist russia?''
bush and dole attacked each other's proposals for a federal budget freeze as a way to deal with the deficit. bush said his was more flexible, and that dole's plan would cut defense spending
dole countered that bush's plan was a ``four-year cop-out.''
the confrontations of the two gop leaders _ bush and dole _ so dominated the first part of the gathering that kemp protested, ``this is a four-man debate.''
actor sean penn says being married to a star like madonna is a strain, but that recent reports the couple was close to divorce were created by the press
penn discussed his marriage in a story published in sunday's chicago tribune, which said it was the first interview with filmdom's bad boy since he was jailed for 32 days after striking a movie extra
penn, 27, vowed to ``refocus'' himself to avoid outbursts. he said reports of his marital problems with madonna, 29, stem from her fans' possessiveness of her and their view of him as less-than-ideal marriage material
she belonged to them, to the public,'' penn said. ``and if anybody took her, i think they thought it should have been someone more acceptable, like donald trump.''
madonna filed divorce papers in santa monica, calif., on dec. 4, citing irreconcilable differences. two weeks later, she asked to withdraw the petition and the court granted the request the same day, court records show. no reason was given in the court papers for her change of heart
but penn said the divorce story ``was more people magazine than reality. my attitude with the press right now is that i hope they've had their share of me. they've been very busy trying to find or make dirt. i'd like to get back to acting.''
freddy gorman, co-writer of the song ``please mr. postman,'' says he's content to be a full-time mail carrier again, like he was in 1960 when he wrote the motown classic that led him into a musical career
it honestly didn't bother me to have to return to the post office,'' he said in an interview in this week's people magazine. ``i started looking around but realized i wasn't qualified for too many other jobs. it was sort of ironic that i ended up back where i started.''
the song gorman co-wrote for the marvelettes put him on the route to fame with his own group, the originals. but gorman says he went back to his appointed rounds after 15 years in the music industry because his career never brought him ``the big money,'' and he had family responsibilities
gorman, 48, lives in the los angeles suburb duarte with his wife of 27 years, dodie, and their 18-year-old son, dillon
planners of nebraska's annual celebration of its heritage said they had a shrinking range of cowboy actors to consider for their buffalo bill award, but are happy with their choice: bruce boxleitner
boxleitner, who co-starred in the television series ``scarecrow and mrs. king,'' was named last weekend to receive award at the 1988 nebraskaland days, a june celebration that includes rodeo performances and a parade
nebraskaland days president kim baxter said boxleitner has an interest in quarter horses and has played western roles
he appeared as james arness' nephew in ``the macahans,'' which inspired the ``how the west was won'' series. he was kenny rogers' co-star in three ``gambler'' television movies
to be honest, they're not making as many westerns as they used to,'' baxter said. ``we've gone to choosing a person who represents good family entertainment. but it's good when you can get someone who has been in westerns.''
betty friedan, author of the women's liberation classic ``the feminine mystique,'' says women working in the media face ``the threat of a new feminine mystique to send them home again.''
there are patterns here. a pattern where disproportionately in the restructuring of networks and movie studios, women are being dislocated,'' friedan said sunday at women, men and media, a conference she chaired at the university of southern california
marlene sanders, a former correspondent and news executive at abc, said the setbacks resulted from cutbacks caused by takeovers and mergers of media corporations and reduced federal regulation of broadcasting
los angeles times television critic howard rosenberg told the conference male media executives were less likely to take women seriously in entertainment shows. he said a study found that men were the central characters in 42 tv series and women in only 17, and in dramas the ratio was 23 men to 3 women
levar burton, who played the rebellious slave kunte kinte in ``roots,'' says he took an ``inner journey'' on his way back from years of relative obscurity to a role in ``star trek: the next generation.''
i hadn't come to terms with the bottom line _ myself,'' burton said in an interview in this week's people magazine. ``i wasn't in touch with my feelings. i was floating. i can't point to a particular date in my life, but i finally decided to find some balance within myself, regardless of what was happening in the outside world.''
he said his spiritual voyage has involved some unusual therapies, including rolfing, yogic breathing, fire walking and, to prepare for his latest role, jumping blindfolded off a telephone pole
burton, 31, plays the blind lt. geordi la forge, who uses special glasses to pilot the starship enterprise on the syndicated science fiction tv series
a small fire caused a 40-minute interruption in a performance of the tony-award-winning musical ``me and my girl,'' but it didn't squelch the sense of humor of star jim dale
you've got to expect this if you come to see the hottest show on broadway,'' dale told the audience of 1,600 after they filed back into the theater saturday afternoon
no injuries were reported. marquis theater stage manager john bonanni blamed the blaze on an overheated cable igniting rope in the proscenium arch
dale, who plays a cockney-commoner-turned-aristocrat, recalled sunday that he ``couldn't resist an ad lib'' in a later scene
i say to the butler, `you haven't got a cigarette, have you, mate?' then i turned to the audience and said, `i promise i won't light up,''' he said. and hardin, a0814. an ams separate on kuenn also moved on sports circuits.</note>
harvey kuenn, a former hard-hitting major leaguer who managed the milwaukee brewers to their only world series appearance, died at home sunday at age 57
kuenn, the 1953 american league rookie of the year and the 1959 al batting champion, had been the brewers' major-league scouting consultant since 1983
in 1982, after taking over the brewers in june, he led milwaukee to the world series. the brewers lost to the st. louis cardinals in seven games. he was fired after milwaukee finished fifth in its division the following season
under kuenn, the hard-hitting brewers were known as harvey's wallbangers, kuenn had a lifetime batting average of .303 in 15 major-league seasons with detroit, cleveland, san francisco, the chicago cubs and philadelphia. he retired as a player in 1966
amy lynn hardin, who underwent a liver transplant at 11 months thanks to vigorous community fund-raising, died at home saturday at the age of 5
amy was born with biliary atresia, in which the bile ducts malfunction and the liver becomes hard. she underwent surgery when she was 6 weeks old and again at 3 months, but the operations were unsuccessful
doctors said her only chance for survival was a liver transplant. community residents rallied to raise more than $260,000 for the operation. the rock group kiss gave a benefit concert, and president reagan sent a letter of support
the liver amy received on may 10, 1983, began to fail around thanksgiving, and she returned to the hospital for a month, said her mother, robin hardin
she couldn't stand it anymore,'' mrs. hardin said. ``we made a promise that we wouldn't take her back to the hospital. we brought her home and the family took turns being with her.''
louis zhang jiashu, bishop of shanghai under china's independent catholic church, died thursday at age 96, the official xinhua news agency reported
the ``patriotic'' catholic church in china broke with the vatican in 1957 after accusing rome of interfering in china's internal affairs. the church claims more than 3 million followers in china
xinhua said zhang studied in britain and france for 10 years before returning to china in 1924. in 1960, he was elected bishop of the shanghai diocese, which has an estimated 100,000 parishioners and about 20 churches
the report said he was vice chairman of the china patriotic catholic association
edward m. knabusch, who began making chairs in a garage behind his father's home in the 1920s and founded the la-z-boy chair co. with his cousin, died thursday at age 88
knabusch and cousin edwin j. shoemaker built novelty chairs such as the gossiper, a telephone stand with a built-in seat, before modifying a wooden porch chair so its seat moved forward as its back reclined
on the advice of dealers they made an upholstered version. in 1929, the la-z-boy recliner was patented, and in 1941 the la-z-boy chair co. was incorporated. sales topped $420 million in the company's 1987 fiscal year
the company halted chair production during world war ii to make seats and backs for tanks, torpedo boats, turret guns and armored cars
knabusch resigned as chairman in 1985 but continued as a director. shoemaker, 81, continues as vice chairman, executive vice president of engineering and a director
mary dunhill, the last surviving child of alfred dunhill, founder of the tobacco and pipe-making company, died wednesday at age 81
the only daughter among dunhill's four children, ms. dunhill joined the board of dunhill holdings in 1944, explaining ``they were rather short of men,'' and in 1961 became chairman, succeeding her eldest brother, alfred
miss mary,'' as she was known, became president when she retired as chairman in 1975, and continued to work two days a week
emelyn jewett, daughter of former oakland tribune publisher sen. william knowland and a former president of the newspaper, died of cancer thursday. she was 59
jewett had served on the tribune board of directors since 1950 and was named president upon her father's death in 1974. she was senior vice president of the tribune publishing co. through three other owners, resigning in 1985
marjorie holwill breffeilh, commander of the women's army volunteer corps in the hawaiian islands during world war ii, died thursday of complications following surgery. she was 76
breffeilh fled shanghai, china, after the japanese bombed the international settlement, where she had lived with her parents for 20 years
she was put in charge of volunteer women's services and given the rank of major when the bombing of pearl harbor forced evacuation of the regular women's army corp
her volunteers performed clerical and administrative chores for the military during the war
composer, pianist and musical arranger gene vincent de paul, whose collaboration with lyricist don raye on the song ``pigfoot pete'' earned them an oscar nomination, died saturday at age 68
de paul worked with johnny mercer on music for the 1954 film ``seven brides for seven brothers'' and the broadway play ``l'il abner.''
he and raye were nominated for an academy award in 1942 for ``pigfoot pete'' from the film ``hellzapoppin.''
among his biggest hits were ``cow cow boogie,'' ``star eyes,'' ``irresistible,'' ``when you're in love'' and ``mr. five by five.''
james h. douglas jr., who as air force secretary under president dwight d. eisenhower presided over the planning and construction of the air force academy in colorado springs, colo., died wednesday at age 88
douglas, an attorney and investment banker, also served for two years as deputy secretary of defense beginning in 1959
he held a high post in the treasury department under presidents herbert hoover and franklin d. roosevelt. he was appointed undersecretary of the air force in 1953 and secretary in 1957
a native of cedar rapids, iowa, douglas graduated from princeton university after serving as an army officer in world war i. he earned a law degree from harvard in 1924
vincenzo celli, former principal dancer and choreographer at la scala opera house in milan and the last pupil of ballet master enrico cecchetti, died sunday at age 87
born in salerno, italy, celli immigrated to the united states with his parents in 1904. celli said he was inspired at age 14 when, as an usher in a chicago theater, he saw nijinsky dance with the diaghilev company
celli studied for six years with cecchetti, the teacher of nijinsky and pavlova. he debuted at la scala in 1926 in ``petrouchka'' and was named ballet master in 1929, a post he held for 12 years
later he opened a studio in new york and taught ballet for 40 years. his pupils included alicia markova, jerome robbins and agnes demille
the federal government is paying about $203 million a year in irrigation subsidies in the west for crops that also receive price supports or other farm subsidies, according to the first estimate of the double subsidy ever made by the bureau of reclamation
the bureau also calculated its total 1986 subsidy to farmers as $534 million, about $54 an acre
the calculations have been given to rep. george miller, d-calif., chairman of the water and power subcommittee of the house interior committee, who conducted hearings on the double-subsidy issue last may and october
miller has been a skeptic of reclamation projects and has sponsored legislation, opposed by the bureau, to make farmers eventually pay the full cost of water used to irrigate crops that get other subsidies
in a letter to miller, wayne marchant, deputy assistant secretary of interior for water and science, defended the irrigation subsidies
the irrigation subsidy reported here is responsible for much of the current character of the western united states,'' marchant said. ``without the support for development of irrigation established by congress, much of the agricultural development in the west, especially in california, would not have occurred.''
he said the projects also have provided important electricity and recreational benefits
but the bureau's own calculations also show that those benefits have come at a substantial price
the bureau provides all or part of the irrigation of 9.9 million acres on 150,300 farms in 17 states. crops subsidized in the farm program were grown on 5.7 million acres
overall water revenues averaged only $19 million a year for 1983, 1984 and 1985, while irrigation subsidies just on the subsidized crops were estimated at $203 million a year
since the bureau was created in 1902 through 1986, the total irrigation subsidy was estimated at $9.8 billion, calculated in 1986 dollars
farmers are supposed to pay for construction, operation and maintenance of the irrigation systems. but congress often has specified that construction repayments be made at zero interest or a rate well below the treasury rate _ what it costs the government to borrow
critics say the bureau has devised other subsidies as well, persuading congress to allocate a too-small share of a project's cost to irrigation, and allowing farmers to postpone capital repayments until a project is complete even though their part may be delivering water
the bureau calculated the double subsidy indirectly. in the previous 10 years, an average of 38 percent of the land irrigated by the bureau was used to produce crops with farm subsidies, so the bureau estimated the value of the irrigation subsidy as 38 percent of its total 1986 subsidy of $534 million
the bureau said it could not answer three questions from miller _ how much the water might have been worth in alternate uses, how much would have been collected if it had charged full cost, and how much it would collect if it had to charge full cost in 1995
miller's bill would apply as contracts came up for renewal, but marchant said the bureau thought it unfair to farmers who had invested under a promise of subsidy
the effect of the bill ``may vary from area to area. the westlands water district (in california's san joaquin valley) could probably afford to pay full cost. but in our view a lot of farmers could be driven out of business, with all the attendant social costs,'' marchant said
he said he was disappointed that congress last year forbade a change in administration policy that would require agriculture subsidies to be disregarded when project costs and benefits are calculated. ``this would have been the right thing to do,'' he said. ``i do not think we should be piling one subsidy on top of another.''
westlands is served by one of two projects for which miller requested subsidy costs, the central valley project and the columbia basin project in washington state. the bureau said central valley got an annual subsidy of $135 million, $60 per acre, and columbia basin got $54 million or $102 per acre
annual subsidies for some uncompleted projects will be larger, up to $719 per acre for the garrison diversion project in north dakota, where 52 percent of the crops are in the farm program
these are outrageous subsidies,'' said ed osann, water specialist for the national wildlife federation and longtime critic of water projects
third-graders in mary alice blanton's class look at each other knowingly these days whenever she takes an unruly child out into the hall
they say mrs. blanton is going to give the kid the same thing she gave that gunman who came into our school three weeks ago,'' said west end christian school headmaster dan carden. ``it's become a sort of standing joke.''
carden was referring to the morning of feb. 2, when mrs. blanton, 57, whacked one of two intruders with a book of bible stories. the man she struck, james l. harvey, fended off the blow and went on to hold mrs. blanton and her pupils hostage for the next 12 hours
harvey, a 43-year-old tuscaloosa native, was wrestled to the ground after he was lured out by a phony pardon from gov. guy hunt and a false promise that he would be able to air his complaints about poverty and homelessness at a news conference. he has undergone psychiatric evaluation, authorities said. a preliminary hearing on the kidnapping charges against him is set for wednesday
carden, whose two sons were in school during the takeover, said his children and the other pupils seem to have survived the episode in remarkable fashion
everything is going very smoothly here,'' he said last week. ``i can honestly say i don't know of any serious repercussions among our staff, students or their parents.''
allan goodwin, a psychologist who helped out during and after the hostage taking, which involved 80 of the baptist school's 280 students, said he is amazed by the lack of psychological fallout
it's hard to believe but it's true that everything has returned to normal at the school,'' said goodwin, director of the indian rivers community health center here. ``i don't detect any malice _ even the parents have been able to forgive and forget. i think this may have something to do with the fatalism that goes along with their fundamentalist faith, a feeling that such events are out of our hands.''
john rhodes jr., who accompanied harvey during the school invasion, apparently was duped by harvey. all charges against rhodes, an unemployed laborer who first met harvey only minutes before they went to the school, were dropped
as for harvey, goodwin said, the children apparently viewed him as a harmless blowhard
i think they see harvey as someone who was strange, but not as a menacing figure,'' goodwin said. ``i don't think the children inside the room with him ever picked up the degree of tension that existed among the law enforcement officers and parents outside the school.''
mrs. blanton, who spent 12 hours as a hostage, said much the same thing
after the first few minutes i don't think the children really felt threatened,'' she said last week. ``frankly, the biggest adjustment problem we've had has been adjusting to the flu. it has really been going around.''
however, she said she did have the class write about the episode
a couple of the kids who were released early in return for pizzas seemed a little indignant,'' she said. ``they thought they were worth more than a pizza.''
as for her own role, and her brief attempt to disarm harvey with her book, she said, ``i never thought about being a hero, i was just acting on instinct. in retrospect, it was probably a pretty dangerous thing to do.''
carden is still confused by one aspect of the case
i still don't know why harvey picked our school,'' he said. ``i'll be interested to hear what he has to say about that at his trial.''
wyoming this week becomes the first state in the west to allocate presidential delegates, but the contest has gotten relatively little attention in the rush to the super tuesday states
still, state officials and wyoming political leaders are touting their caucuses this saturday as the kickoff contest in the region, saying results in the state will help set the stage for larger contests to come
we have a real potential to influence the process, especially since we're the first western state'' to assign delegates, said muffy moore, state democratic party chairman
it's not our numbers that are important. it's our position on the calendar,'' she added
the wyoming caucuses are three days before super tuesday, march 8, when 20 states, mainly southern and border states, will hold caucuses and primaries
wyoming's caucus process, according to republican and democratic campaign directors, calls for little in the way of media advertising. instead, campaign staffers spend most of their days on the phones to individuals who will attend the county conventions
you make the calls. you make the personal contacts. this is a retail state,'' said mickey munley, a co-director for tennessee sen. albert gore jr.'s wyoming campaign. ``down south, there are so many people all the candidates are buying tv. ... in wyoming, it's more personal. people want a phone call.''
state gop chairman mark hughes said he expected the republican race to come down to sen. bob dole and vice president george bush, who have spent more time and effort in wyoming than rep. jack kemp and pat robertson
my opinion is that bush and dole are far more organized and have been in the state a much longer period of time,'' said hughes
i don't believe jack kemp has campaigned extensively here and don't think his campaign has been that strong here,'' he said, adding that robertson also has been weak in wyoming
on the democratic side, leaders are reluctant to make predictions. 
it's hard to tell how people are going to vote at this point,'' moore said late last week. ``i still think we have a very large portion of our democrats who haven't made up their minds yet.''
twenty-eight years ago it was wyoming's position in the alphabet that brought it glory as the state's democratic delegation cast the deciding vote in los angeles that gave john f. kennedy the party's presidential nomination
some state and party officials believe that with that in mind, it might be in wyoming's best interest to send an uncommitted delegation to the convention
gov. mike sullivan holds that belief, at least for the time being. one of wyoming's five ``super delegates'' to the democratic national convention, sullivan does not have to commit himself to any candidate prior to the convention
so far he has remained uncommitted, although he's been lobbied by the candidates to cast his support prior to super tuesday
not all democratic leaders are taking that tack, however
former gov. ed herschler, the state's chief executive officer for 12 years before sullivan took over in 1987, will get an idea this saturday of how much political clout he carries. he endorsed sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee last month
mike beson, deputy campaign director for rep. richard gephardt, said endorsements aren't the only thing that count
we're not going to let that hinder our campaign,'' he said. ``we have a grassroots, aggressive campaign.''
on the democratic side, each of the 23 counties will hold party conventions saturday at which a secret ballot will determine the allocation of 13 delegates. once the results are known, nominees for delegates to the state party convention on may 7 in sheridan will campaign on behalf of a certain candidate, or perhaps as an uncommitted delegate
later in the day, delegates to the state convention will be selected, and at the convention the 13 delegates to the national convention will be chosen
on the republican side, things are not so simple
precinct caucuses started earlier this month at which delegates to the county conventions were selected. at the county conventions, which start tuesday and end the following saturday, there will be no formal presidential preference poll taken to base delegate selection, said mary ann collins, state gop executive director
twelve counties are considered delegate counties and will send 12 presidential delegates to the state gop convention on may 7 in cheyenne. the nominees for these positions must declare which candidate they are supporting, according to party bylaws
the remaining counties, plus one, will send alternate delegates to the state convention. at the state convention the remaining six delegates will be selected. visit</head> detail on gun incident lower and deleting some material to tighten. no pickup.</note>
prince andrew and his wife, sarah, went to church with everyday americans on sunday morning and later dined with hollywood elite in the evening at a gala that included a british celebrity entourage
the duke and duchess of york, who are on a tour to promote british trade, arrived at st. luke's episcopal church shortly after 11 a.m. after a motorcade from the royal yacht britannia, which is docked at long beach naval station
unknown to the royal retinue and the press, police officers sweeping the motorcade route had detained a man they spotted carrying a rifle. but it turned out that the man's presence had nothing to do with the royal visit and the rifle was unloaded, police said
later in the evening, the duke and duchess were the guests of honor at a star-studded dinner at the biltmore hotel in downtown los angeles
among the 700 guests paying $1,000 apiece to dine with british royalty were zsa zsa gabor, her husband prince frederick von anhalt, british-born ``dynasty'' star joan collins, her date george hamilton, and british actors michael york and roger moore. moore served as master of ceremonies
money raised by the event benefits the three-month uk-la '88 art festival and a fund to salvage books damaged in disastrous 1986 fires at the los angeles central library
earlier, the couple were greeted by a cheering crowd waving miniature union jacks as they went to church under british-style drizzly skies
the rev. a. leroy young, rector of st. luke's, officated over matins, a morning service of prayer and song. andrew read the day's lesson from romans 8:31
in his sermon, young noted the presence of the couple
i think the majority will agree with me that their presence here today is the biggest thing that has happened in this city since the richfield oil refinery exploded, and that was in 1933,'' he said
ten minutes before the royal couple arrived, british ambassador anthony acland, consul general donald ballentyne and their wives, pulled up in a limousine that had been smashed on one side. the accident, which caused no injuries, was blamed on a driver who ran a red light a few blocks from the church, said british consulate official stewart granger
about 300 people lined the sidewalk across from the church, some packed under a bus shelter to avoid the occasional showers
blanche schulman, a war bride originally from london who sported a british-made umbrella, said the event reminded her of damp monarch-watching excursions of her youth
i'm very excited. ... the rain to me is part of everything. it's just like home,'' said mrs. schulman, 64
elaine tuttle, 73, and myrna dillon, 48, both of long beach, perched on stepladders in hopes of catching a glimpse
we love them, we really do. we follow their every move,'' said ms. dillon
asked if she had watched the weddings of andrew and sarah and charles and diana on television, she replied, ``we didn't just watch them, we watch them all the time. we have them on tape.''
the incident with the man with a gun did not change the royal couple's itinerary sunday morning
john kasser of long beach had retrieved a .22-caliber rifle from the police station there and was headed to his car when los angeles city police officers spotted him, said long beach lt. rod mickelson. the gun had been held by police for safekeeping for several days after officers confiscated it during a domestic dispute, mickelson said
kasser was later freed and allowed to keep his gun, police said. he was not charged sunday, nor had he been charged in the domestic dispute, mickelson said
there's absolutely no relation between him and the motorcade,'' he said
arrests for driving under the influence of alcohol rose more than 220 percent from 1970 to 1986, while the number of licensed drivers increased by just 42 percent in that period, a government report says
in 1986, some 1.8 million people were arrested for driving under the influence, compared to 556,000 in 1970, said a report issued sunday by the bureau of justice statistics. in 1983, the peak year, there were 1.9 million such arrests, one for every 80 drivers
the study also found that rates for driving under the influence were highest among 21-year-olds, reaching a peak in 1983 with a rate of one arrest for every 39 licensed drivers of that age
since 1983, most states have phased in new laws raising the minimum age for buying or selling alcohol to 21. arrest rates for dui for the ages 18 to 20 have declined by 14 percent since then, more than twice the rate of decrease for those aged 21-24
another portion of the study found that half the jail inmates convicted of drunken driving had consumed the equivalent of at least 12 bottles of beer or eight mixed drinks before their arrests
almost half of the people jailed on drunken driving charges or serving a sentence for that offense had been sentenced for the same offense previously
the jail portion of the study, based on a 1983 survey of inmates in 407 locations, also found that one in five of the convicted drunken drivers had been consuming two or more kinds of alcoholic beverages when arrested
the median age for those in jail for drunken driving was 32, about 5 years older than the median age for all jail inmates. some 95 percent of the jailed drunken drivers were men and nearly 80 percent were unmarried, separated, divorced or were widows or widowers
telephone credit cards make it easier to charge calls but they're also making it easier for thieves to steal the numbers and run up huge long-distance bills
the thieves are not necessarily the users. they often sell the stolen numbers to others who use them to dial around the world
toll fraud costs the long-distance companies about half a billion dollars a year, about 1 percent of the industry's revenues, according to the industry-sponsored communications fraud control association
despite phone companies' security efforts, thieves are coming up with bold new deceptions aimed at the unsuspecting
officials at the mexico (mo.) ledger fell into such a trap with a southwestern bell calling card, which the newspaper used to make long-distance calls on american telephone &amp; telegraph co.'s network, according to editor robert m. white ii
southwestern bell, using a computer to monitor calling-card use by its customers, detected unusually high use by the newspaper one weekend in january. after consulting the newspaper, it canceled the card and issued a new one
publisher max thomson says that on the same day the new code was issued, he got a call from a man who said he was from at&amp;t and needed to verify the new credit card number assigned to the newspaper because someone was trying to use it. unsuspecting, thomson gave the caller the new number
within days, the card again was being used to charge calls around the world, and by the time southwestern bell's computer sent up another red flag, the newspaper's card had run up charges of more than $4,500
the calls included one for $155.46 from a new york pay phone to mali and another costing $105.27 from the same phone to the same number in mali 12 hours later; a $144.15 call that lasted two and a half hours between a jersey city, n.j., phone booth and china. others calls went to kuwait, bangladesh, gambia, senegal, spain, taiwan and the dominican republic, among other places
as is the practice of most phone companies, southwestern bell didn't charge the newspaper for the unauthorized calls
but the ledger has ensured that it won't happen again: ``we no longer have credit cards,'' thomson said
southwestern bell officials aren't sure how the newspaper's card number was stolen initially. some codes are obtained by computer hackers who dial into a long-distance company's electronic files and find secret billing codes
long-distance companies are improving their network software to help detect unauthorized access quickly, and they are phasing out their shorter codes and adopting 14-digit replacements, which are harder for hackers to crack
but thieves don't need a computer to get a code. some hang around phone booths where callers are dialing from cards and ``they'll use binoculars, mirrors, anything they possibly can'' to read the numbers off the cards or even memorize the numbers as the caller is punching them into the phone, said everick bowens, president of the fraud control association
with codes in hand, hustlers and hackers then look for customers
at banks of pay phones in transit areas, the hustlers offer domestic and international calls at deeply discounted rates, aware that with frequent use the life of a code can be just a few hours
bolder hustlers are passing themselves off as legitimate resellers of long-distance service or even as a representative of a long-distance company
us sprint communications co., which lost $80 million to toll fraud last year and is one of the most active long-distance companies in going after code theft, recently uncovered a ``multi-level marketing operation'' that sold codes to about 200 people and businesses _ including insurance companies, accountants, lawyers and retailers, said security director robert f. fox
a man walks in wearing a three-piece suit and says he's a reseller with a contract with a major long-distance company and that he can cut your long-distance phone bill,'' fox said, recounting the scam
he looks at a company's phone bill. say it's $10,000 a month. he says, `i can cut it to $5,000 a month,''' fox said. ``he says he'll give you authorization codes, and for your protection the codes will be changed every few days.''
some of the buyers are caught unaware, fox said, but ``some people don't ask a lot of questions because they don't want a lot of answers.''
sprint has been going after many of these buyers in civil court actions and collecting restitution, he said
fox advises: ``it may sound legitimate, but if it sounds too good to be true, it probably is.''
the u.s. economy has shrugged off the worst effects of the october stock market collapse and should be able to escape a recession this election year, economists for top u.s. corporations predicted today
the national association of business economists said optimism among its members has risen appreciably since the last survey conducted in the month following the oct. 19 plunge in stock prices
in november, more than half of the business economists were predicting a recession would begin before the end of 1988, an outlook that could have spelled bad news for republican hopes of holding onto the white house
now, the number of economists expecting a recession this year has dropped to about one-fourth
as we move farther away from october, we are a little less nervous. we are seeing continued improvement in manufacturing and other good signs that the expansion will keep going,'' said kathleen cooper, chief economist for security pacific national bank of los angeles
the next president is likely to face a recession soon after taking office, the analysts believe, with about 60 percent of them picking 1989 as the most likely year the downturn will begin
but for 1988, the economists are projecting further growth at a modest pace, stable interest rates and a slight drop in inflation
the analysts predicted that the economy, as measured by the gross national product, will expand just 2 percent this year, down from a 3.9 percent gnp increase in 1987, when measured from the fourth quarter of 1986
this is more pessimistic than the reagan administration, which is calling for gnp growth this year of 2.4 percent
ms. cooper, who compiled the association's survey, said the decline in the stock market caused the majority of economists to reduce their growth forecasts for this year, but she said most of them had cut back their projections by less than 1 percent
economists see the largest effect of the market's plunge on consumer spending for durable goods,'' she said, noting that they are now expecting car sales to total only 9.8 million units this year, down from an expectation of 10.5 million sales made before the market decline. the forecast of housing starts also was trimmed to 1.52 million units this year, compared to 1.62 million new houses built in 1987
ms. cooper said the analysts expect growth to be most sluggish in the first half of the year, as businesses cut back on production to reduce high inventories. gnp growth will average 1.5 percent in the first six months and then improve to 2.5 percent growth for the rest of the year, the economists forecast
this sluggish growth rate will not be enough to keep the unemployment rate from rising. the economists forecast that unemployment, which now stands at 5.8 percent, will rise to 6.1 percent by the end of the year
but the slow growth will help to keep inflation from getting out of control. the analysts predicted that consumer prices will rise 4.2 percent this year, slightly slower than the 4.4 percent increase in 1987
in other predictions, the economists said:
_interest rates, as measured by the prime lending rate, will stay steady. banks cut their prime rate, used to set interest rates on a variety of corporate and consumer loans, to 8.5 percent in early february, and analysts forecast it will remain at this level through the end of the year
_the federal budget deficit, which fell to $150.4 billion in 1987, will rise to $157 billion in the current fiscal year, but then resume falling, dropping to $140 billion by 1990. this is more pessimistic than the reagan administration, which sees this year's deficit falling to $146.7 billion and a further decline to $104.2 billion by 1990
_the country's foreign trade deficit, which hit a record $171 billion last year, will finally start to come down, dipping to $150 billion this year and $130 billion in 1989
the optimism on the trade deficit is based on a belief that the dollar has finally fallen far enough to stem americans' appetite for imports while making u.s. products competitive once again on overseas markets
ms. cooper said the economists are now less pessimistic about the fate of the dollar with less than one-fifth of them thinking the dollar will drop by 10 percent in value this year against other major currencies. in november, more than 40 percent were looking for a decline in the dollar that was at least that large
the internal revenue service has put out the definitive word on a confusing new law affecting taxation of investors in mutual funds
investors will not have to report certain operating expenses of their publicly offered mutual funds as 1987 income because the funds will not pass along those expenses to shareholders, said irs spokesman rod young
people don't have to be concerned at all about those expenses on the returns they are filing now,'' said mike delaney of the investment company institute, which represents most of the nation's 2,400 mutual funds
this means investors will have to do nothing on their 1987 returns to get a one-year reprieve from a new tax
however, unless congress intervenes, about 20 million shareholders will have to count such expenses as income on future tax returns and then attempt to write them off as a miscellaneous itemized deduction
the taxation of these expenses has been surrounded by confusion because of the wording of a new provision affecting them that was signed into law by president reagan only last dec. 22. that provision delayed for one year implementation of a section of the big tax overhaul enacted in 1986
because of the december change, publicly offered mutual funds will not allocate their 1987 operating expenses among shareholders. thus, shareholders will not have to mention such amounts on their tax returns at all
but all that changes for 1988. mutual funds will be required to pass on operating expenses to shareholders. in turn, shareholders will list that amount as income and hope they can deduct it as a miscellaneous expense
that is, unless congress intervenes again
under the 1986 tax overhaul, the deduction for all kinds of miscellaneous expenses is limited to those that exceed 2 percent of adjusted gross income. a mutual-fund shareholder whose miscellaneous expenses did not reach that threshold would have no way of deducting the fund's expenses and, as a result, would be taxed on income never received. the same would be true for a taxpayer who did not itemize deductions
reagan has asked congress to grant shareholders permanent relief from taxation on that ``phantom income'' at a cost of $400 million a year
the lion's share of money invested in mutual funds is in those that are regularly traded on securities markets. but there are numerous non-public funds that are traded privately
the irs notes those that are not publicly offered or owned by at least 500 persons may have to allocate expenses among shareholders for 1987. any fund that is so affected should be advising shareholders to report as income the expenses that are designated in ``box 2'' on form 1099-div
if you are not sure that your fund qualifies as publicly offered, you should contact your fund,'' advises young of the irs
a bitter, open debate marked by charges that some prominent historians are trying to tone down the horror of nazi atrocities is capturing the attention of west germans
the controversy has been the topic of a best-selling book, numerous newspaper articles and tv reports. it is known as the ``historians' dispute'' and has split prominent professors into feuding camps
one group, represented chiefly by prominent berlin historian ernst nolte, is calling for a new perspective on the third reich and german identity 43 years after world war ii
six million jews were killed in europe between 1933 and 1945 as part of adolf hitler's ``final solution.''
nolte and his supporters tend to compare what happened under hitler to atrocities carried out by other governments, such as the deaths of millions in the soviet union under stalin
but their opponents, led by frankfurt university philosophy professor juergen habermas, say the conservative historians are trying to lessen the magnitude of nazi crimes through such comparisons. habermas, one of west germany's best known intellectuals, also says his opponents are paving the way for nationalistic impulses
in december more than 300 historians, sociologists, and philosophers met in frankfurt to discuss the dispute's impact. no resolutions were passed there, but lectures held at the meeting will be published in a book scheduled for release in march
the debate, however, has moved far beyond academic circles
a book documenting the dispute made the best-seller list in the news magazine stern last year, and new arguments regularly make headlines in leading newspapers. as recently as jan. 20, regional television in the state of bavaria devoted a book-review show to new history books associated with the dispute
nolte told the associated press in a telephone interview wednesday that he stands by his arguments
those who want to make the nazis' mass murder stand alone by forbidding every comparison with other events are guilty of having an incredibly unhistorical attitude,'' nolte said
nolte sparked the historians' dispute with an essay called ``the past that won't go away,'' published in the conservative frankfurter allgemeine zeitung newspaper in june 1986
he suggested that stalin's infamous forced labor camps and the communists' murder of millions of peasants were in a sense a forerunner of the nazi death camp auschwitz and hitler's genocide program
wasn't the bolsheviks' `class murder' the logical and actual precursor of the national socialists' `racial murder'?'' nolte asked in the essay
nolte's opponents have frequently called his phrasing unclear and open to many interpretations
his critics also say he tries to justify hitler's motives for attacking the soviet union in world war ii by arguing that the dictator was mainly responding to the soviets' goal of spreading communism
to nolte, hitler is a european citizen who was historically in the right in that he unwillingly went to war for democracy,'' the bayerischen rundfunk television show ``lesezeichen'' said in reviewing nolte's new book
nolte and his supporters, however, say their arguments raise valid questions in historical interpretation
other nolte arguments include comparing nazi atrocities with those of cambodia's pol pot regime in the 1970s
nolte says that he does not adhere to any one political party, but many historians call him a conservative
i would say nolte is a conservative,'' historian christian meier of the university of munich told the ap. ``conservatives in this dispute are those who see the horrible events of world war ii and the holocaust as an instance of fascism, which also took hold in other european countries, and not as a failure of german society and values.''
habermas, in a newspaper essay, charged several conservative historians with reinterpreting history to justify and minimize the nazi regime's crimes. the article appeared in the hamburg-based weekly newspaper, die zeit, in july 1986
the nazi crimes ``lose their singularity'' in nolte's arguments, habermas wrote in the article
many historians hold that the nazis' genocide cannot validly be compared with other atrocities
never before had a state, with the authority of its responsible leader, decided and announced it would completely kill off a specific group of people'' and put the plan into aciton, historian eberhard jaeckel of stuttgart university wrote about the nazi genocide in a 1986 essay as a response to conservative arguments
some historians say that too much dwelling on the nazi past could cause west germans today, particularly younger ones, to resent what they may see as a steady stream of accusation
many (west) germans today are at least one generation removed from the nazi period,'' meier said. ``but the (west) germans are constantly being reminded of past actions. if it goes too far, it could even provoke a counter-reaction.''
some liberal historians attribute the airing of conservative views to a new, conservative ``political climate'' in west germany. in 1982, chancellor helmut kohl's conservative christian democrats toppled the leftist social democrats
ten years ago they (the conservative historians) wouldn't have risked advancing such notions,'' historian hans-ulrich wehler told the ap. ``the conservative historians' arguments fit into today's political climate.''
the food and drug administration says it is concerned about possibly misleading advertisements that describe regular aspirin use as a way to prevent heart attacks
the agency has summoned the nation's aspirin makers to a meeting this week to discuss to what degree they can make that claim in their ads, an fda official said sunday
the meeting is scheduled for wednesday at the agency's headquarters in rockville, md. it comes a month after the new england journal of medicine published preliminary results of a study showing that aspirin taken every other day could reduce the risk of heart attacks in middle-aged men
we do have some concerns about this,'' said fda spokesman donald mclearn. ``even the study itself was accompanied by an editorial saying, `don't jump to conclusions, folks.'''
some aspirin makers have launched advertising campaigns featuring young men who have suffered heart attacks
the study was conducted on physicians aged 40 to 65 years old
it was clear from the preliminary results that it could be helpful for heart attacks for men between 40 and 65,'' mclearn said. ``our concern is people will read about the study and say, `i'm a 20-year-old female, maybe i should take aspirin every day.' that's not what the study was all about.''
mclearn said that because the study's results are still preliminary, doctors still may need to know more before prescribing regular aspirin dosages to patients. one possible side effect is an increased risk of strokes, he said
also asked to participate in the meeting were associations representing the prescription and over-the-counter drug industries. also likely to attend are officials of the federal trade commission, which oversees advertising of over-the-counter drugs
a survey suggests the mailing of surgeon general c. everett koop's report on aids to individual households in alaska was well received and helped those who read it understand the disease
the alaska department of health and social services mailed 217,000 copies of the report last november and had a professional polling company assess the impact the following month
officials believe it is the first followup study of a mass mailing of aids material in the united states
that study by dittman research corp. found 91 percent of the people who read some or all of the booklet judged it ``appropriate, well done and covered the topic adequately.'' only 3 percent found it ``inappropriate, too sexually explicit and offensive.''
among other things, the report says people who do not limit themselves to one aids-free sexual partner should use condoms. it contains a photograph of a condom and instructions on use
the report, issued in october 1986, also contains a brief section calling for sex education in schools as one way to help control spread of the deadly disease
those who read the surgeon general's report had distinctly different understanding of aids compared to those who hadn't read the report,'' the research company wrote in its analysis
dittman's scientific telephone survey of 521 residents from 51 communities found that 58 percent of those contacted reported receiving the booklet and that 76 percent of those read at least some of it
moreover, 46 percent of those questioned said other household members had read at least part of the report
dr. john middaugh, the alaska state epidemiologist, said the pollsters _ who did not include a margin of error in their summary _ told him they considered the 58 percent who recalled receiving the booklet unusually high for an unsolicited mailing
he said some copies probably did not reach their destination for a variety of reasons, but that a majority of those who could not recall the booklet probably discarded it without realizing what it was
the significance of the study, he said, was the high ratio of those who did recall getting the 36-page booklet, who then read it and the even higher proportion who approved of it
this proves the acceptability of doing this and the effectiveness of doing it,'' middaugh said in a telephone interview. ``this was an overwhelming response that should forever lay to rest whether this is an appropriate step to take.''
he referred to controversy at the federal level over whether to mail aids information to every household, whether the surgeon general's report or some other format
middaugh said republican state sen. tim kelly pushed authorization for the alaska mailer through the legislature after it became apparent the federal government was not going to do it last year
u.s. public health service spokesman jim brown said 12 million copies of the report have been printed, including 9 million supplied to members of congress for mailing to their constituents
congress allocated money for a national mailing last year _ although not necessarily the surgeon general's full report _ but it was never done. the current phs budget contains more explicit language directing a national mailer and health and human services department officials say a brochure now under preparation will be in the mail by june
i'm delighted that the state of alaska has chosen to educate its people by using the surgeon general's report,'' said koop. ``i'm even more thrilled that they did a followup survey to see the reaction to it. we've had good general reaction to the surgeon general's report, but this is the first real formal tracking that i know of.''
the dittman survey included an analysis of different responses from 345 ``readers'' and a 176-person non-reader ``control group'' on a variety of questions such as ``can you get aids by being bitten by a mosquito?'' twenty-three percent of the non-readers said yes, compared to 17 percent of the readers. the report says the answer is no
twenty-two percent of non-readers said you can get aids from donating blood, compared to 11 percent for readers
eighty-two percent of the readers said they would let their children attend school with an aids-infected child compared to 75 percent non-readers
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,242.81 points, down 42.06 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on monday. separates two sides, but union maintaining that strike threat remains. no pickup.</note>
the union representing 6,700 northwest airlines flight attendants continued to threaten to strike sunday night although both sides in the labor talks said just one issue divided them
negotiators for the airline and the union met with a federal mediator for four hours sunday and agreed on all but one contract issue, according to northwest spokesman william wren
william genoese, international director of the international brotherhood of teamsters airline division, agreed that only one issue separated the two sides _the issue of how long newly hired workers will stay on a lower pay scale. but he declined to characterize the rest of the day's discussions except to say ``we talked around'' other issues
a strike was still a possibility, he said late sunday
at this moment we're in strike position. it can happen two minutes from now or any other time. under the law, we have that right,'' genoese said about 9:30 p.m. cst sunday
about two hours later, after meeting with other union negotiators, genoese said ``tomorrow (monday) will be the really big day.'' monday is the first weekday since the contract expired at midnight friday
northwest officials said sunday the airline continued to operate a normal flight schedule. no delays were reported at airports served by the carrier
genoese and northwest agreed that the only sticking point in the negotiations is northwest's proposal to stretch from five to nine years the time in which an employee advances from a ``b'' or lower pay scale to the ``a'' pay rate. the union is resisting the proposal
the airline issued a press release sunday night saying that its contract offered the union would make the flight attendants the second-highest-paid in the airline industry
according to northwest, the contract, which would run through dec. 31, 1992, also calls for two 2 percent wage increases for all flight attendants through 1992 and lump sum bonus payments in 1988 and 1989
earlier in the day, the two sides had been reported to be apart on other issues such as the length of the contract and retroactive pay
a strike deadline last friday night was extended as the two sides continued negotiations that began wednesday. the two sides resumed talks one day after the teamsters airline division announced that nearly 95 percent of the attendants had authorized a strike
on saturday, the talks broke off, but a union spokesman said strike preparations had been ``put on hold.''
genoese said late saturday that a request by the federal mediator to delay a strike helped avert a walkout saturday morning
meanwhile, there was no word on whether flight attendant picket lines would be honored by pilots or machinists if there is a strike
spokesmen for the pilots' union were in a meeting sunday morning to discuss the flight attendants' matter and were unavailable for comment
if flight attendants do strike, the airline has said it will keep flying
about 2,000 managers trained as flight attendants were posted throughout the northwest system with 200 newly hired replacement flight attendants also ready to move, terry erskine, the airline's vice president for law and labor relations, said saturday
the justice department says it made an ``honest error'' by erroneously giving the impression for nine months that attorney general edwin meese removed himself from the pollard spy case
it now acknowledges he was briefed twice about the case and he never was excluded
in what chief department spokesman terry eastland called a correction, he said meese is only excluded from the espionage case against the israeli air force officer who recruited jonathan pollard, a navy counterterrorism analyst, to spy for israel
meese is free to be briefed and even to make decisions in the still-open pollard case to the extent that they don't involve the case against israeli brig. gen. aviem sella, eastland said
we were confused about the sella case,'' eastland said. ``it was an honest error.''
eastland acknowledged that last month and on one previously undisclosed occasion assistant attorney general william weld, head of the criminal division, had briefed meese about the pollard case ``without touching on sella.''
meese's own lawyer, nathan lewin, was unaware of the situation as recently as last week even though it was lewin's work for meese and sella in separate cases that triggered the exclusion, known as a recusal
the turnabout comes as a government source said independent counsel james mckay is examining another meese recusal for clues about his motives in dealing with a mideast oil pipeline proposal in 1985
meese hired lewin last may to represent him in mckay's investigation of whether the attorney general and his attorney, e. robert wallach, violated or conspired to violate a federal law barring bribes to foreign officials
in may 1985, meese was recused from all matters involving wallach, but arranged for wallach to meet national security adviser robert mcfarlane to promote the pipeline. investigators say that examining that meese recusal might help determine whether the attorney general was aiding wallach's plan or, as lewin argues, directing it to the proper official
at the office of government ethics last week, general counsel donald campbell explained: ``if you're a federal official and you've hired a law firm to represent you, you should recuse yourself, that is, take no action in any matter involving that firm _ just as a matter of appearances even if you have no financial stake.''
for that reason, eastland said, meese advised justice officials last may: ``i hereby recuse myself from participating in any matter before the department in which the law firm (of miller, cassidy, larroca &amp; lewin) represents any party or is otherwise involved.''
the washington post reported then that the recusal covered the pollard affair. the justice department did not dispute that
pollard was sentenced last year to life in prison for giving reams of secrets to israeli agents. but justice officials still pursued the case, in part, because sella had fled to israel and has not been brought to trial here
so there was surprise and consternation when the post reported feb. 19: ``after being briefed on the case last month, ... meese ordered that the pollard case be kept officially open so investigators can pursue their inquiry.''
asked by the associated press last monday for an explanation, justice department spokesman john russell said, ``i have problems with that account because meese is recused in pollard.''
russell bucked the question to deputy chief spokesman pat korten. citing the same problem, korten bucked it to eastland, who was with meese in california until wednesday
on tuesday, lewin said he'd never discussed pollard with meese because ``i think he certainly has recused himself because i am representing sella.'' expressing surprise at the post account, lewin said, ``at the department, they have known all along that it has been very much up front that he is not involved in pollard.''
while eastland sought an answer, a senior department official, demanding anonymity, said wednesday there was no problem because meese merely was briefed and made no decisions
some former department lawyers dispute that view. one, who once worked in the attorney general's office, said, ``a recusal has always meant a chinese wall. you are not even kept up to date.''
a former justice career lawyer said that, to avoid making a decision by ``a wink or a nod,'' briefings were restricted to situations where the information was essential to decisions in other areas
but friday afternoon, eastland provided an official explanation that did not claim an exception for briefings
he said the client lists regularly provided by lewin's firm ``have not included the pollard case, and so the attorney general is not recused from pollard.''
the lists do include the sella case, and the attorney general has been very careful to avoid taking any action in that case or in any other related case where his action might at all affect the sella case.''
eastland denied meese kept the pollard case open. ``he didn't have to, because it has been open for some time.'' 4th graf pvs ``dealers said...''</note>
stock prices declined moderately in quiet trading on the tokyo stock exchange today, ending 13 consecutive days of gains in the market's key index, while the dollar remained steady after opening lower against the japanese yen
the 225-issue nikkei stock average, which rose 119.69 points during saturday's half-day session, closed at 25,242.81, down 42.06 points or 0.2 percent
on the foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at 128.08 yen, down 0.27 yen from friday's close of 128.35 yen. after declining at one point in morning trading to 127.95 yen, its first trip below the 128-yen level in about three weeks, the dollar ended the day at 128.12 yen, down 0.23 yen
dealers said many stock market participants were staying on the sidelines in anticipation of a slight correction in prices following the recent gains
during the 13 previous trading days, the nikkei index rose a total of 1,622.60 points or 7 percent
the market is taking a respite, which many participants had expected for some time,'' said an analyst at nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage, who spoke on condition of anonymity
a record 14 consecutive days of gains in the nikkei average was set in early 1961
foreign exchange dealers said sentiment toward the dollar was relatively weak, with the market still searching for the currency's bottom level. but they said the dollar's decline was being tempered by fears of possible market intervention by japan's central bank below the 128-yen level, profit-taking by speculators and light activity by commercial dollar-sellers
despite the fears of dollar-buying by the bank of japan, a senior trader at a commercial bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the central bank was unlikely to intervene unless the dollar began falling at a faster pace below the 127.5-yen level. strong second</head>
new englanders michael dukakis and george bush claimed victories in the maine caucuses, but jesse jackson's unexpectedly strong second-place showing was the surprise of the evening
our message is winning,'' declared jackson, who finished with 1 percent of the democratic vote in maine's caucuses four years ago but gained 28 percent on sunday
anything but first place would have been a major setback for dukakis, the massachusetts governor who was winning 42 percent of the delegates to the state democratic convention in maine. twenty-one percent were uncommitted
the also-rans were paul simon with 4 percent, richard gephardt with 3 percent, and albert gore and gary hart with 1 percent each
`today our message shone through again ... (and that) gives our national campaign another push towards success on super tuesday,'' dukakis said sunday from cleveland
bush too needed the ``overwhelming victory'' he claimed sunday. with no official tally, the bush campaign cited its own reports from 259 caucuses and said the vice president had the non-binding support of 65 percent of the gop state convention delegates chosen over the weekend
that added up to a huge lead for bush in the state where he has a vacation home. robertson garnered 147 delegates, or 14 percent; senate majority leader bob dole 88, or 8 percent; and rep. jack kemp 14, or 1 percent, the bush campaign said, adding that 123 delegates, or 12 percent, were uncommitted
i am delighted with what appears to be an overwhelming victory in the maine caucuses, assuring my campaign of all 22 national delegates,'' bush said from washington
if the democratic results held up at the state convention, dukakis would win 10 of the state's 23 pledged delegates to the democratic national convention. jackson is in line for 8 delegates and the uncommitted group 5
the numbers were unquestionably on the side of dukakis, but the runner-up emerged with a victory no less sweet
maine has sent a message to america that we can win, that america wants bold leadership and a new director with sound ideas,'' jackson said from the campaign trail in texas
if it hadn't been for the strong grassroots organization that we had, we would have been in trouble,'' acknowledged david villarino, manager of dukakis' maine campaign. villarino asserted that jackson's victories in two of maine's largest cities, portland and bangor, reflected defections from the recently scaled-back campaign of illinois sen. paul simon
whatever the reason for their success, the jackson forces were ecstatic
what we're doing in maine is building an electoral victory, from the grass roots to the top of the blades,'' said scott nova of the jackson national campaign staff
bush aides had worried earlier in the week that robertson's ``invisible army'' of supporters would flood the caucuses here as they did in michigan, iowa and other states. but robertson's supporters did not total the numbers feared by bush aides, and deals with dole supporters diluted robertson's impact
with the state party planning no count of results, the various campaigns agreed in general that bush was running well ahead
jeff nelson, a spokesman for robertson in the state, said of the bush supporters: ``i don't think there's any question that they are going to be able to claim victory.''
a top dole organizer, state sen. pamela cahill, also conceded
this is bush country up in new england, up in maine and new hampshire,'' she said
in assessing the results in maine, dukakis and jackson both dutifully invoked super tuesday, the mega-primary next week in which 20 states and one territory will hold primaries or caucuses. at stake in the march 8 contests are 1,307 delegates to the national convention
we're right where we want to be, and we're heading into the final turn,'' said villarino
jackson spokesman mel king said, ``people across the country, when they find he came in second in maine, are going to dispel the notion that a person who is black can't do well.''
bush supporters acknowledged that they needed a big margin over robertson before the contests in the south, where the former television evangelist has a strong core of support
we couldn't afford to have the national story out of maine be that robertson comes in a close second,'' said gov. john r. mckernan jr., one of bush's strongest backers in the state
maine's conservative gop wing and fundamentalist churches were fertile recruiting grounds for robertson, and his forces mounted an energetic challenge. but outmaneuvered, if not outmuscled, by bush backers in caucus brokering, robertson's followers were unable to turn their raw numbers into a matching proportion of delegates
the party and the procedures'' favored bush over robertson, said jeff nelson, state spokesman for the robertson campaign
a strong earthquake in the bering sea shook the aleutian islands, but there were no immediate reports of damage
sunday night's quake struck about 100 miles east of bering island and had a preliminary magnitude of 6.6 on the richter scale, said the alaska tsunami warning center
paul whitmore of the tsunami center said the quake occurred at 8:32 p.m. sunday
he said no alerts were issued for a tsunami, a fast-moving ocean wave caused by sesimic action. ``it's too small for that area to potentially cause a tsunami,'' whitmore said
he said the center had no contact with the area and did not know if there had been any damage
bering island is part of the commander islands just west of attu in the aleutian chain
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion on a seismograph
a quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage
a rape-murder case nearly 13 years old will be the focus tuesday of a u.s. supreme court review that many inmates see as a ticket off death row
in my opinion, it will affect everybody,'' said jim vanderbilt, who has spent more than 11 years on texas' death row for the 1975 slaying of an amarillo teen-ager. ``we will have commutation of everybody.''
lawyers for the state and for donald gene franklin will present arguments to the high court on the constitutionality of a texas statute that limits consideration by a jury of mitigating circumstances that could benefit a defendant
since october, when the court agreed to hear the case, dozens of death-row inmates in texas, whose 27 executions in the last six years are the most in any state since executions resumed in 1977, have attached franklin's arguments to their own in efforts to win stays
it's an issue that could potentially affect everybody on death (row) in texas,'' said richard h. burr iii, coordinator of the death penalty project of the naacp legal defense and educational fund inc. in new york. ``i think probably everybody now is raising the issue and if they're not, they should be.''
franklin, 36, who has had three trials and four execution dates, blamed the abduction, rape and stabbing death of 27-year-old mary margaret moran on a friend who used his car
franklin was arrested hours after the july 1975 abduction but refused to say where the missing san antonio nurse was. search parties combed san antonio, but it took four days to find her bleeding in a bed of insects, suffering from loss of blood and irreversible shock. she died the next day
mark stevens, who is representing franklin before the high court, said jurors should have had doubt about franklin's guilt because of circumstantial evidence in the case
stevens also said franklin, at the time of the last trial, had caused no disciplinary problems while in prison, ``which goes to show among other things, he shouldn't be executed.''
stevens contends although such mitigating circumstances are presented at the punishment phase of a trial, the jury is given no guidance as to how heavily to weigh them
franklin's trial attorneys suggested a jury charge that spelled out ways to handle mitigating circumstances. the judge refused to include it in his instructions to the jury, which determined franklin should die. he has been on death row since 1982
the state is real confident it will prevail,'' said bob walt, an assistant state attorney general
a texas jury now has these questions to consider before deciding a person convicted of capital murder should be executed: whether the defendant's act was deliberate and with the expectation death would result; whether the defendant is likely to commit a future violent act; whether the victim may have provoked the attack and whether the response by the defendant was reasonable
what they're saying now is that the constitution requires a jury to consider mitigating evidence,'' walt said. ``i can't think of a case in texas that has less mitigating evidence than donald gene franklin's
he was in custody on a prior rape. ... there ain't no doubt in this case. they had the victim's clothes soaking in bloody water in his house. all the victim's property was at his house.''
stevens and walt agree one one thing: it is impossible to predict what the supreme court will do
if the court rules in franklin's favor, anyone who requested similar jury instructions could be entitled to a new trial, stevens said
even if you didn't request these instructions, you might be entitled to raise that fundamental constitutional right,'' stevens added
it's real tough to speculate,'' walt said. ``of course, hope springs eternal on death row.''
hope is indeed the prevailing word on death row, where more than 260 people await execution
there are a lot of options but (commutation) is the most likely,'' said james beathard, who arrived on death row in 1985 for killing a 14-year-old boy
what could they do _ hold new trials for 250 people? everybody's real hopeful about it and figure it's their best chance.''
friends and enemies of the confederate flag say they ain't just whistlin' dixie when they promise a fight over whether the rebel battle banner will keep waving from state flagpoles in the south
the confederate flag flies over the capitols of alabama and south carolina along with state flags. the state flags of georgia and mississippi incorporate the design
in georgia, a bill to redesign the state flag languishes in a legislative committee, and in alabama black lawmakers who hoped to remove the confederate banner from atop the capitol dome were arrested
this is a very emotional, controversial issue. we knew that when we took it on,'' said earl shinhoster, southeastern regional director of the national association for the advancement of colored people. ``we think we deserve a vote on the issue.''
south carolina state sen. glenn mcconnell said opponents are being intolerant of differing views
it does not breed good relations ... to pull (the flag) down and brand it as a symbol of racism and hate,'' mcconnell said. ``if we become a society that cannot bridge differences, then we ... become a society built on extremes.''
shinhoster said the flag ``represents the heart and soul of a defeated cause.''
it represents state sovereignty, state rights, a rejection or resistance to federal control, and it has an adverse effect on basic issues of human need,'' he said
georgia's legislature voted to include the confederate battle emblem on the state flag in 1956, as a reaction to federal school desegregation orders. a bill seeking to reinstate the former state flag has been sent to a house committee, where it will likely die quietly
judith damewood, president of the grass-roots lobbying group common cause georgia, said she is embarrassed whenever she looks at the georgia state flag
when the democratic national convention comes to atlanta this summer, this is not the flag i want those delegates to see,'' she said
in alabama, the battle flag has flown since 1961, when then-gov. john patterson had it put up in commemoration of the civil war's 100th anniversary
since there is no law allowing the flag to fly, gov. guy hunt has said he will allow the legislature to resolve the dispute
on feb. 2, the house turned down a resolution to remove the flag, so 13 black legislators, led by rep. thomas reed of tuskegee, tried climbing a fence surrounding the capitol to pull down the flag. the group was arrested on trespassing charges. a march 11 court date has been set
other states that made up the confederacy _ arkansas, florida, louisiana, north carolina, tennessee, texas and virginia _ do not fly the battle flag officially
the norfolk, va., city council, under pressure from the local naacp, recently voted to stop displaying the flag at meetings
while flag opponents hedge their bets on intense lobbying and public outcry for action, flag supporters are preparing to talk the issue down
if it takes a filibuster, i'm going to do it,'' mcconnell said. ``i hope we can reach a consensus where the naacp ... will decide that conciliation, rather than confrontation, is better for all of us on this.''
a jet that landed here slightly more than 36 hours after it took off unofficially broke the speed record for an eastbound, around-the-world voyage, company officials said
the 19-seat, gulfstream iv completed the route in 36 hours, 8 minutes and 34 seconds. the jet started and ended its flight at houston's hobby airport, taking off friday and landing saturday with stops in ireland, united arab emirates, taiwan and hawaii, said gulfstream aerospace co.'s chairman
the flight time remains unofficial until further review by the national aeronautics association, which sanctions such records. an naa representative was on the flight
allen e. paulson and his three co-pilots flew the jet 45 minutes, 41 seconds faster than a boeing 747-sp last month. that 747, piloted by clay lacy, flew around the world in 36 hours, 54 minutes and 15 seconds
paulson is chairman and chief executive officer of savannah, ga.-based gulfstream
paulson said he attempted the trip as a test performance for the new jet, which had logged just 12 hours flight time before its worldwide trip and weighs less than 77,000 pounds
the winds were cooperative, the airplane worked flawlessly and we had it red-lined all the way,'' paulson said
the average speed was 636 mph for the trip, which covered 19,988 nautical miles _ 22,986 statute miles
paulson, 65, established the westbound around-the-world speed record last year aboard another gulfstream aircraft
israel's state-run television and radio have been accused of playing down the extent of palestinian unrest in the occupied lands
since the violence in the west bank and gaza strip began, israeli viewers only once saw troops beat protesters and rarely see pictures of arabs wounded by gunfire. tv anchors often refer to the situation as ``relatively quiet.''
by contrast, tv viewers in the united states often see soldiers beating arab protesters and palestinians who have been wounded or killed by gunfire
after nearly three months of violence, u.n. figures show 74 arabs have died in rioting, mostly by israeli gunfire
there appear to be three reasons for the low-key coverage in israel: concerns that too much publicity will encourage arab protesters and spark more violence; ``patriotic journalism,'' or the reluctance to report stories that weaken the morale of soldiers, and, in some cases, official censorship
if i compare the reports we are getting from around the world to what the israeli people are watching, it looks like we are talking about two different places,'' said israel peleg, a former member of the israel broadcast authority's board of directors
the israel broadcast authority which runs television and radio barred this reporter from interviewing broadcast journalists
but yair stern, head of the tv's news division, said the coverage was considered too critical by many israelis. ``if the action is tough, we get up to 100 calls a night, most from people who say they don't want to see this or want us to be more favorable to the government,'' he said
stern rejected charges that tv intentionally soft-pedaled bad news. he acknowledged the station had only once shown soldiers beating palestinians, but cited as the reason lack of footage, not censorship
the footage of the only beating shown was provided by cbs television and showed soldiers kicking and hitting with rocks two bound arabs in the west bank city of nablus last week
but israeli editors cut the most gruesome scenes, including one in which a soldier who seemed to be breaking the arms of one of the arabs
israel radio quoted uri porat, the director-general of the israel broadcast authority, as saying the scenes were deleted because of a television ban on showing atrocities and because some viewers might not be mature enough to deal with such images
in defending the coverage, stern said israel tv tried to present longer background pieces, while american networks ``collect the highlight of action from here and there, and then wrap it up in 50 seconds. that's why the impression in america is of violence, and only violence.''
but several israeli print journalists rejected those explanations. israeli newspapers cover the arab protests much more aggressively than television and radio, and have broken several stories about army brutality, including an incident in which soldiers allegedly buried alive four arabs after a protest
the yediot ahronot newspaper described the television and radio coverage as ``vegetarian, sterile.''
they have this long-winded piece that there were disturbances, and then you hear five people were badly wounded,'' said ari rath, managing editor of the english-language jerusalem post
in an editorial, he complained of a ``new clean language by israel's radio and television that calls major clashes between civilians and troops ... mere `disturbances.'''
rath said he didn't know of widespread official censorship but said some broadcast journalists apparently held back on their own. ``in part, it could be a subconscious self-defense to an increasingly embarrassing and painful situation,'' rath said. ``you try not to call a spade a spade.''
peleg, a former director of the government press office, added: ``the self-restraint in israel tv has reached a point where there is no need for censorship or political interference.''
dr. henry heimlich, the physician who developed a maneuver to save choking victims, is trying to treat cancer patients in mexico by deliberately giving them malaria, a newspaper reported
heimlich has treated three people at a mexico city hospital since december by infecting them with a non-lethal strain of malaria on the belief that the 103- to 104-degree fever produced by the disease kills cancer cells, the (cleveland) plain dealer said sunday
heimlich, 67, believes that malaria, in addition to killing cancer through fever, can stimulate the body's natural immune system to fight cancer
malaria is an infection caused by parasitic microorganisms and is spread by mosquitoes. it causes high fevers, sweats and chills
some medical researchers say heimlich's procedures should be tested first on laboratory animals and tissue cultures. they also said they were skeptical about the quality of cancer research in mexico
u.s. food and drug administration officials said heimlich's so-called ``malariatherapy'' was ``not an acceptable treatment or therapy.''
george blatt, director of the health fraud unit in fda's drug evaluation and research center, said mexico was more lenient than the united states ``in what they allow in the practice of medicine.''
most of what we call quack clinics are not prohibited in mexico,'' blatt said
heimlich, contacted sunday at his home in cincinnati, said that describing his work as ``south-of-the-border research ... is despicable.'' he said cancer research regulations in mexico were more stringent than those in the united states
we had conferences with the very highest levels of (mexico's) government and very careful protocol was laid out to protect the rights, choice and selection of patients, much, much more than is required in this country,'' said heimlich, a professor at xavier university in cincinnati and head of the heimlich institute
the first patient was given the non-lethal strain of malaria, plasmodium vivax, on dec. 23. she was a 27-year-old woman dying of rectal cancer. two others, men in their 50s, were given malaria in january, the newspaper reported
heimlich said he developed his theories after he said studies showed that third world nations with high malaria rates had low incidences of cancer
officials of the american cancer society and the federal government's national cancer institute said they had never heard of the malaria therapy, according to the newspaper
friends and enemies of the confederate flag say they ain't just whistlin' dixie when they promise a fight over whether the rebel battle banner will keep waving from state flagpoles in the south
the confederate flag flies over the capitols of alabama and south carolina along with state flags. the state flags of georgia and mississippi incorporate the design
in georgia, a bill to redesign the state flag languishes in a legislative committee, and in alabama black lawmakers who hoped to remove the confederate banner from atop the capitol dome were arrested
this is a very emotional, controversial issue. we knew that when we took it on,'' said earl shinhoster, southeastern regional director of the national association for the advancement of colored people. ``we think we deserve a vote on the issue.''
south carolina state sen. glenn mcconnell said opponents are being intolerant of differing views
it does not breed good relations ... to pull (the flag) down and brand it as a symbol of racism and hate,'' mcconnell said. ``if we become a society that cannot bridge differences, then we ... become a society built on extremes.''
shinhoster said the flag ``represents the heart and soul of a defeated cause.''
it represents state sovereignty, state rights, a rejection or resistance to federal control, and it has an adverse effect on basic issues of human need,'' he said
georgia's legislature voted to include the confederate battle emblem on the state flag in 1956, as a reaction to federal school desegregation orders. a bill seeking to reinstate the former state flag has been sent to a house committee, where it will likely die quietly
judith damewood, president of the grass-roots lobbying group common cause georgia, said she is embarrassed whenever she looks at the georgia state flag
when the democratic national convention comes to atlanta this summer, this is not the flag i want those delegates to see,'' she said
in alabama, the battle flag has flown since 1961, when then-gov. john patterson had it put up in commemoration of the civil war's 100th anniversary
since there is no law allowing the flag to fly, gov. guy hunt has said he will allow the legislature to resolve the dispute
on feb. 2, the house turned down a resolution to remove the flag, so 13 black legislators, led by rep. thomas reed of tuskegee, tried climbing a fence surrounding the capitol to pull down the flag. the group was arrested on trespassing charges. a march 11 court date has been set
other states that made up the confederacy _ arkansas, florida, louisiana, north carolina, tennessee, texas and virginia _ do not fly the battle flag officially
the norfolk, va., city council, under pressure from the local naacp, recently voted to stop displaying the flag at meetings
while flag opponents hedge their bets on intense lobbying and public outcry for action, flag supporters are preparing to talk the issue down
if it takes a filibuster, i'm going to do it,'' mcconnell said. ``i hope we can reach a consensus where the naacp ... will decide that conciliation, rather than confrontation, is better for all of us on this.''
donald kaschalk has had fewer birthdays than any of his seven children
my youngest boy is 19, and i'm just going to celebrate my 14th birthday,'' says the east detroit milkman, who was born on leap day in 1932
like other folks born on feb. 29, kaschalk's actual birthday rolls around only once every four years. it's a studder step in time that compensates for the 365\ days it takes the earth to orbit the sun
the u.s. census bureau estimates about 9,600 babies were born in the united states on feb. 29, 1984, and a similar number of infants should be born today
it's truly delightful,'' said ypsilanti businessman peter fletcher, who was born the same day as kaschalk. ``the common reaction is one of sympathy and lament because you don't have a frequent natal commemoration
but that very streak of sympathy provokes people to make it even more memorable. when i was in my callow youth, people would try to compensate for it by having a veritable spate of shivarees and celebrations for me.''
jason weiner, who's celebrating birthday no. 3 though he turned 12 today, takes it all in stride
it's ok, i guess,'' said the sixth-grader at maple elementary school in walled lake
this is his third birthday,'' said jason's mom, joyce weiner. ``we used to celebrate it on the 28th (of february), but the last few years he's said he wants to celebrate it on march 1.''
the traditional observance of leap year began in 46 b.c. when julius caesar adopted the egyptian calendar and the western world began counting years with 365\ days each
the added day every fourth year keeps the earth's calendar in line with the sun's rotation
residents of the rural valley where arizona gov. evan mecham grew up find it hard to believe he has done anything wrong, no matter that he has been indicted and impeached
the dairy farmer's son who left the uintah basin when he joined the army air corps in 1943 was industrious and studious, kind of quiet and a model citizen, neighbors and relatives recall
we can't believe he isn't a good man and see no reason for impeachment. i've not found anybody who couldn't praise evan and his integrity,'' said birdie swasey, a retired teacher who has known the mecham family since the great depression
beverly fieldsted, who was one year behind evan in school and whose brother-in-law lives in the former mecham residence down the road in mount emmons, agrees
they were not a crooked family. evan didn't steal money,'' she said. ``he worked hard on the farm, he went to school, he minded his own business, he wasn't a smart-alecky, showy kid.''
while defending mecham's integrity, mrs. swasey acknowledged that the governor, whose impeachment trial was scheduled to begin today, may have spoken carelessly at times
i suppose he's not a politician. he may have spoken quickly. you have to learn the rules of society, be sophisticated ... you can't be naive like a child and say everything that pops into your head,'' she said
mecham and his family occasionally return to this expansive valley along the south slope of the uinta mountains to visit relatives, who remain supportive
i hate to see them treat him so badly,'' said edith burton, mecham's aunt. ``i just stopped listening to the news because it made me feel bad. i knew much of it wasn't true.''
mecham said recently that his home country was ``the greatest place to grow up. i always apologize to my children that i raised them in the city and not in a place like that.''
mecham's father, adelbert, settled in mountain home in 1908 and married ina hanberg there in 1916. evan, the fifth of six children, was born may 12, 1924
when evan was 12, the family moved to mount emmons, where they had a ``humble home,'' a dairy, ran a store and raised a few crops, the governor said. ``we didn't have much, but we weren't poor. i've never felt poor in my life.''
being a dairy farmer's son during the depression and early war years forged evan's character, including those traits responsible for his current problems, friends said
he's never been a quitter,'' said his cousin, ona rust. ``that's why he's hanging in there now to clear his name.''
in 1942, 18-year-old evan took over most farm duties when his father became incapacitated by rheumatoid arthritis. evan was forced to cut back on schoolwork, but kept up his grades and earned an agricultural scholarship to utah state university
he had a reputation of someone who always worked hard to get what he got, said former neighbor harry fieldsted, adding, ``i don't know if he was any smarter, but he seemed to apply himself more.''
mecham sang and danced at mormon church functions and was elected student body president his junior year at altamont high school, though he was kidded about his shyness in the 1941 yearbook
mecham's date at the altamont junior prom, florence lambert, became his wife, and they later had seven children. the couple settled in arizona after world war ii, when mecham studied business at arizona state university and became an auto dealer
smoke in the cockpit of a chicago-bound midway airlines jet forced its pilot to make an unscheduled landing here, officials said
no injuries were reported among the 119 passengers and five crew members aboard flight 793, which originated in tampa, authorities said
sunday's landing of the boeing-737 was a precautionary measure, said v.h. steed of the federal aviation administration in atlanta
the smoke was created by an electrical problem, said sandra allen, director of corporate communications for the chicago-based midway airlines
passenger jon klank, 24, of glen ellyn, ill., said he was sleeping when the plane started to descend to gainesville regional airport
i woke up when the ladies next to me started crying,'' he said
midway treated the passengers to lunch while they awaited another jet to take them to chicago
the tokyo stock exchange's key index ended 13 consecutive days of gains today, edging down in moderate trading, while the dollar stayed within a narrow range after opening lower against the japanese yen
dealers said many participants stayed away from the stock exchange in anticipation of a market correction following the string of gains. after rising 119.69 points during saturday's half-day session, the 225-share nikkei stock average closed at 25,242.81, down 42.06 points or 0.2 percent
such a small decline has almost no meaning,'' said kunihiro ono of nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage. ``it was just a reaction to 13 straight days of increases.''
the market is taking a respite which many participants had expected for some time,'' said another analyst who spoke on condtion of anonymity
during the previous 13 trading days, the nikkei index had risen a total of 1,622.60 points or 7 percent. it just missed matching a record 14 consecutive days of gains set in early 1961
on the tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at 128.08 yen, down 0.27 yen from friday's close of 128.35 yen. it edged down briefly to 127.95 yen, its first trip below the 128-yen level in about three weeks, before ending the day at 128.12, down 0.23 yen. spot volume was a light $4.1 billion
sentiment toward the dollar is bearish, and the market is still searching for its (the dollar's) down side,'' said a trader who spoke on condition of anonymity. he said speculators had tried to sell the u.s. currency lower, but had bought back some dollars in the afternoon to cover dollar-short positions
traders said the dollar's decline was being slowed by fears of possible market intervention by the bank of japan below the 128-yen level, profit-taking by speculators, and light activity by commercial dollar-sellers
but a senior trader at a commercial bank, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said the bank of japan was unlikely to intervene unless the dollar began falling at a faster pace below the 127.5-yen level
satoshi sumita, bank of japan governor, said today the central bank would continue to move ``flexibly'' in money markets
in a speech to businessmen, he cautioned against a further decline in the dollar, which he said would have negative effects on the u.s. economy, including possible inflation, stock market instability and a slowdown in foreign money flowing to the united states
carbon monoxide fumes apparently from a gas heater killed four children ranging from ages 6 to 12 and their teen-age baby sitter, police said
it's absolutely the worst multiple death case in one family that we've had in clay county,'' said sheriff's lt. tim martin
ultimately, what has happened was, we feel, a faulty exhaust on a gas furnace became clogged and the carbon monoxide fumes were allowed to back up and disperse through the house,'' he said saturday
ola weerts and a friend had left the children with a baby sitter and went to dinner. when they returned about midnight friday, the baby sitter and three of the children were dead, martin said
the only survivor was tanya weerts, 12, who was taken unconscious to shands hospital in nearby gainesville. she died saturday evening
pronounced dead at mrs. weerts' home here were two other children, 10-year-old james and 6-year-old sherri. mrs. weerts' friend's granddaughter, julie meador, 10, and baby sitter jennifer bias, 17, were also dead, martin said
they were all in their beds, apparently sleeping except for one 10-year-old on the kitchen floor,'' he said. ms. bias was found on a living room sofa
autopsies on the others showed they died of acute carbon monoxide poisoning, according to the medical examiner
reports that condoms were discovered in some milk products of steffen dairy foods co. were a hoax to defraud the company and not a case of tampering at the plant, police say
four people have been arrested on charges of felony theft and conspiracy to commit felony theft, police capt. john dotson said saturday. more suspects were being sought, he said
reports by four people of condoms in their milk was a hoax,'' dotson said. ``there is no tampering of products at steffen.''
steffen recalled about 10,000 quart and half-gallon cardboard milk cartons wednesday after four reports about unpackaged condoms in the milk. the company received a fifth report last week, but that was retracted, dotson said. highway</head>
a law school graduate out to celebrate after taking the florida bar examination was shot to death as he drove along interstate 95, police said
friends following irv ribler's sports car told police the single shot was fired from a van whose occupants had just thrown a small object at the car, but that was unconfirmed, broward county sheriff's spokesman jim leljedal said sunday
right now, we're just hoping someone will come forward who saw what happened. somebody had to. there was a lot of traffic out there,'' leljedal said of the shooting at dusk saturday in unincorporated broward county
after ribler, 26, was shot just below his left shoulder, his car sped across the median, three lanes of oncoming traffic and then plowed into a gully. he was pronounced dead within the hour at broward medical center
no other cars hit his and no other injuries were reported
zaida ribler, who cleaned houses and worked as a tailor seven days a week to put her only child through florida state university and the university of miami law school, said her son was going to a party in nearby delray beach
he left me a note before he left saturday,'' she said sunday from her home here, about 15 miles north of miami. ``it says, `mom, see you in the morning. i love you. irv
he was a good son. he studied so hard. he worked in the yard. he cleaned the house. he didn't drink,'' his mother said. ``now my life has ended. everything is over.''
ribler graduated from law school last may and had since failed the bar exam. since then, he had studied constantly. after taking the test in tampa on wednesday, he was elated _ certain he had passed, friends said
his whole life was centered on passing the bar and working as a public defender,'' said classmate manny fernandez, 24. ``he had some offers. he was almost there.''
a journalist for more than 45 years, newsday columnist murray kempton was given a special citation as long island university announced its george polk awards in journalism
kempton has represented the highest standards of the profession,'' said the university as awards in 14 categories were announced sunday
whether covering u.s. presidents, civil rights activists, or even gangland figures, he has demonstrated the tough-mindedness, courage, and sensitivity that are in the best tradition of the long island university polk awards,'' the statement said
kempton, 70, was given a career award, presented occasionally to honor a body of work
two wall street journal reporters, james b. stewart and daniel hertzberg, were chosen to receive a financial reporting award for coverage of the october stock market crash. a nominating committee member praised the ``rigor, depth and range'' of their reporting
the polk awards, among the nation's most coveted journalistic prizes, are presented each year at a luncheon at the hotel roosevelt in manhattan. this year's awards will be presented march 30
roger rosenblatt of time magazine won his second polk award for magazine reporting. rosenblatt's ```day in the life of the soviet union'' went beyond the commonplace accounts of the country's political and military politics, treatment of political leaders, and customary assessments of dissident movements, the university said
in a departure from the norm, the committee selected two major news organizations _ rather than an individual person or story _ as its winners in political reporting and network television reporting
knight-ridder's washington bureau received the political reporting award for what the university said was the general excellence of its political coverage and its particularly effective reporting on the iran-contra scandal
cable news network received the award for network television reporting for the ``excellence of its around-the-clock, seven-days-a-week, 52-weeks-a-year coverage of the news.''
other awards:
_foreign reporting: nora boustany of the washington post for coverage of the plight of palestinian refugees and the trauma of beirut
_national reporting: mike masterson, chuck cook and mark n. trahant of the arizona republic for a 30-story series, ``fraud in indian country,'' on mismanagement and corruption involving the federal bureau of indian affairs
_metropolitan reporting: the charlotte observer for more than 500 stories, with repeated revelations, on the jim bakker and ptl scandal
_local reporting: ron ridenhour of the new orleans citybusiness, a biweekly newspaper, for a yearlong investigation of a city tax scandal
_sports reporting: chris mortensen of the atlanta journal and constitution for ``ignoring the rules,'' a 110-story report on the subversion of amateurism by sports agents and college athletes
_science reporting: science news, published by science service inc., for comprehensive and reliable coverage of the latest research in all branches of science
_foreign television reporting: gordon manning of nbc for his role in bringing to the network and public two major projects, ``changing china'' and ``a conversation with mikhail gorbachev.''
_local television reporting: margie nichols of wsmv-tv, nashville, tenn., for ``a premium price'' and ``little assurance,'' an investigation of insurance fraud that preys on senior citizens
_radio reporting: larry bensky of pacifica radio for his multiple roles as organizer, anchor and commentator for pacifica's gavel-to-gavel coverage of the iran-contra hearings
the awards were established by liu in 1949, the year after polk, a cbs news correspondent, was slain while covering the greek civil war
the winter olympics' flame, which was lighted in greece and traversed some of the most rugged terrain by helicopter, dogsled, snowshoes and skis, was extinguished beneath a nearly full moon in calgary
with 60,000 people present, athletes from 57 countries marched in to mcmahon stadium for sunday night's closing ceremonies carrying miniature olympic torches. banners reading ``until we meet again'' in eight languages were draped along the top of the stands
about 250 skaters took to the world's largest temporary ice rink in period costumes depicting the history of figure skating as a high-tech array of thousands of lights glistened off sequined costumes, flags and flame
the skaters included past and present medal winners as well as young skaters from albertville, france, site of the 1992 winter games, and seoul, south korea, site of this year's summer games
these have been wonderful games,'' declared frank king, whose title is chief executive officer of calgary games' organizing committee
for the united states, however, the winter games was the worst showing in 52 years. two of the six u.s. medals were gold medals, won by brian boitano in figure skating and bonnie blair in speed skating. blair also won a bronze in speed skating, making her america's only double winner
the soviets finished first in number of gold medals, with 11, and total medals, with 29, a record. east germany's athletes won nine golds, 25 overall; while switzerland's team came in third in gold medals, five, and overall medals, 15
four other teams also did better than the united states in terms of overall medals: austria, west germany, finland and the netherlands
in 1936, the united states won just four medals, but only 51 were available then. this time, 138 medals were handed out
pulitzer-prize winning columnist jimmy breslin was cited for stories of ordinary new yorkers trying to live decent lives amid drugs and poverty as the american society of newspaper editors announced six recipients of its 1988 distinguished writing awards
the new york daily news columnist was honored for outstanding commentary, which also included columns he wrote on the howard beach racial attack
other recipients announced by the asne sunday are:
_ breslin's colleague at the daily news, columnist bob herbert. he was cited for deadline writing based on his account of the violence in the 1987 presidential elections in haiti
_ blaine harden, washington post africa correspondent, for non-deadline writing. he was chosen for a ``vivid account of a river journey through zaire'' and other stories
_ james m. klurfeld, associate editor of newsday, for editorial writing. klurfeld won for writing about president reagan and the iran-contra affair
_ carl schoettler, baltimore evening sun reporter, for obituary writing. his entries included accounts of the lives of three baltimore residents: a news dealer, a former mayor and a newspaper publisher
_ tom shales, chief television critic and tv editor of the washington post, for obituary writing. the committee noted his appreciations of ray bolger, david susskind, danny kaye and rita hayworth
winners of the national awards receive a $1,000 cash prize from the asne foundation at its annual convention in washington april 15
runners-up in the 1988 competition are henry allen, the washington post; graham s. dower, cleveland plain dealer; david finkel, st. petersburg (fla.) times; michael pakenham, new york daily news; and elizabeth rau, providence (r.i) journal-bulletin
the work of the national winners will be published in a book, ``best newspaper writing 1988,'' produced by the poynter institute for media studies in st. petersburg, fla
take note of today, monday _ there won't be another like it until 1992
it's leap year, when a day which seems to come from nowhere is added to february and the year is 366 days long instead of 365
the astronomers of julius caesar in 46 b.c. decided it
they said that as the solar year was 365 days and 6 hours, the hours made an extra day every four years
why leap?
the oxford english dictionary says _ and you may have to read this twice _ that the year probably got its name because any fixed festival after february in such a year ``falls on the next weekday but one to that on which it fell in the preceding year, not on the next weekday as usual.''
a leaping over day, you see
according to popular tradition in britain, a woman on this day has the right to ask a man to marry her, instead of the other way round
english folklore has it that any woman having her feb. 29 proposal rebuffed can claim a silk dress from the man
in 1288 a law was enacted in scotland to give women the right to propose on feb. 29. it said any maiden lady ``shall hae liberte to bespeke ye man she likes.''
if the man refused, he had to pay the lady a pound _ a lot of money in those days _ unless he could claim he was already betrothed
a few years later, france passed a simliar law and it was also legalized in the 15th century in the italian cities of genoa and florence
a british romantic fiction publisher named silhouette, seeking to find out modern manners of proposing, asked the gallup poll to include a leap year question in its survey
the poll found that women who propose to the man of their dreams on feb. 29 have a 92 percent chance of success
but only 12 percent of the women questioned for the survey _ it didn't say how many _ responded that they would seriously consider popping the question on this day
jane ellison, a columnist on a london daily, the independent, asked today: ``how many men are worth waiting four years to propose to these days?''
ms. ellison suggested using leap year ``sensibly'' by relocating those ``annual events you dread'' to feb. 29
among her choices: the university boat race, the next andrew lloyd webber musical and christmas
to the state, john gacy is a sex murderer many times over who deserves to die. to sue terry, he's ``a real nice person'' she'd like to marry
ms. terry came to this feeling by exchanging letters during the last 16 months and through repeated visits to gacy at menard correctional center, where he's on death row for murdering 33 young men and boys
most of the victims were buried in the crawl space under his home northwest of chicago
excerpts of some of gacy's 41 letters to the 43-year-old centralia woman from oct. 5, 1986, to feb. 16 were published sunday and today in the chicago sun-times
she said gacy, 45, expects to be paroled and she believes he's innocent of the sex killings
gacy is under 12 separate death sentences and 21 terms of natural life in prison with no hope of parole
we're real close,'' she said. ``i like john, and he trusts me. i guess i love him. yes.''
ms. terry, a divorced mother of eight children who is also helping to raise two grandchildren, said gacy has asked her to marry him. she said she would
i was gullible and trusted others. that's how i got where i am today,'' gacy wrote in one letter published today. ``i could lay back and say it's not my fault i am here, because i know i never killed anyone. the facts will back me up. but i am guilty of being gullible and trusting others, so i belong here for letting myself down.''
gacy also wrote of how he cried watching the olympics and the devotion of the athletes; he scolded ms. terry for not selling any of his oil paintings; and he told of how he was going to run a strict household for ms. terry's children when he gets out of prison and they all live together
however, attorney terry sullivan, who prosecuted gacy, said he ``is more likely to be executed than paroled.''
ms. terry said she first met gacy at menard in august 1986, seven months after she first wrote him a brief note
i decided to go back because, well, he's real nice. ... he's a real nice person and he seems to be really concerned about me and my kids.''
cardinal bernard f. law says the roman catholic church has been guilty of racism and has put `horrendous obstacles'' in the way of black catholics
at a special mass sunday where more than 1,000 black catholics celebrated the past and future of blacks in the boston archdiocese, the boston archbishop said the ``faith of black catholics has been tremendously tested by the church, which put such horrendous obstacles in their way. but the faith endured even under the most extraordinarily difficult circumstances.''
following the mass, which also marked black history month, law said, ``racism is not conquered, not here or anywhere else. but what we're seeing is a very positive sign
racism is a sin. it offends god. the church is made up of sinners, not saints, and one of the church's sins has been racism. for that we are repentant.''
there are an estimated 25,000 blacks among the 1.9 million catholics in the boston archdiocese
the mass at the cathedral of the holy cross featured the singing of hymns by soloists meyer chambers, philiss baker and denise graves
we're so accustomed to holding back in the catholic church, but today was a chance to live our own heritage, to open up,'' chambers said. ``it's been a long time coming.''
prices were mixed on the london stock exchange early today, although banking shares posted strong gains on news that brazil has agreed to resume interest payments on its foreign debt
at midmorning, the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index was down 1 point, or 0.06 percent, at 1,765.5. the index had opened at 1,769.1, up 2.6 points on friday's close
thirty-five of the 100 major companies comprising the index were showing gains in early trading, 19 were showing losses and the remainder were unchanged. contract expiration occurred late friday, adds two grafs of background.</note>
northwest airlines' 6,700 flight attendants continued to keep the carrier guessing today on whether they will strike, three days after a union deadline for reaching a new contract
both sides in the labor talks said just one issue divided them. but william genoese, international director of the teamsters union's airline division, said late sunday that no further negotiations were scheduled
at this moment we're in strike position. it can happen two minutes from now or any other time. under the law, we have that right,'' genoese said
he said absenteeism had increased among flight attendants
they are calling in sick. it's on the increase,'' genoese said. but he declined to categorize the absences as a negotiating tactic, saying, ``i'm not going to say that.''
representatives of the airline and the union met with a federal mediator for four hours sunday and agreed on all but one contract issue, said northwest spokesman william wren. wren and genoese said the issue is northwest's proposal to increase from five to nine years the period that newly hired workers stay on a lower pay scale
genoese said he sent a telegram to steven g. rothmeier, chairman and chief executive officer of nwa inc., the parent company of northwest, requesting a meeting. wren said late sunday he did not know if rothmeier knew of the request
northwest officials said sunday the airline continued to operate a normal flight schedule. no delays were reported at airports served by the carrier
if flight attendants do strike, the airline said it will keep flying, using about 2,000 managers trained as flight attendants were and 200 newly hired replacements
genoese said he planned to meet today with representatives of the pilots and machinists on whether they would honor flight attendant picket lines
a strike deadline late friday was extended as the two sides continued negotiations that began wednesday. genoese said saturday night that a request by the federal mediator to delay a strike helped avert a walkout earlier in the day
former republic airlines flight attendants have been working under their old contract since northwest acquired republic in 1986, and many of them are paid less than their northwest counterparts
the company, the nation's fifth-largest airline, is trying to bring the workers under one contract and offered to bring former republic employees up to the salary levels of northwest employees. but the union claimed the airline wanted too much in exchange, including cuts in vacation pay and retirement benefits
in a sun-dappled forest on the outskirts of geneva, a soviet negotiator and his american counterpart meet to discuss, among other things, the nuclear arms race and the fate of the world
they are a diplomatic odd couple. the russian, andrey botvinnik, is gregarious, impulsive and almost childlike in his enthusiasm for the frivolous. the american, john honeyman, is officious, humorless, a bit priggish and irritatingly sincere about his new job as the u.s. representative to the arms control talks
their one-on-one marathon conversations make up lee blessing's ``a walk in the woods,'' a wise and witty evening of theater that arrived sunday at broadway's booth theater
the russian wants to discuss country music, italian suits and making love to red-haired women. he wants a pal, not protocol. ``formality is simply anger with its hair combed,'' he coos
the earnest american wants to steer the talk back to the negotiations. he wants results. ``friendship,'' he says, ``takes you away from commitment to solving problems.''
the two-character play was inspired by a true incident in 1982 involving american arms adviser paul nitze and a soviet negotiator. blessing takes their real-life rustic ramble and embellishes on it, transforming their meeting into a theatrical situation laced with humor, grace and intelligence
some two-person plays are like tennis matches. they are made up of relentless back-and-forth banter that exhausts the audience without leading anywhere. ``a walk in the woods'' has its share of volleys and it dallies a bit, particularly in the second act. still, it manages to make its point about the need to keep trying for peace, with a minimum of preaching
in part, the play succeeds because blessing refrains from overloading the evening with technical jargon and anti-war sermons. there may be references to mx missiles, megadeaths, star wars, bargaining chips, lasers and afghanistan, but the emphasis is on the men, not specific ways of averting nuclear destruction
by the time the two diplomats have walked through these woods during four different seasons, they have grown to understand and even like each other. that knowledge comes at the same time they realize their two countries, while proclaiming interest in peace, have little desire to slow down the arms race
if that makes the play sound unusually somber, it isn't. ``a walk in the woods'' has its share of belly laughs, most of them supplied by robert prosky, best known as sgt. jablonski on television's ``hill street blues.'' he's a big, beefy actor who inhabits the very soul of the soviet diplomat and who even negotiates a convincing russian accent. but the character's joviality masks a cynicism fed by too many years at the bargaining table. ``if mankind hated war, there would be millions of us and only two soldiers,'' he says
sam waterston, as the somber american, plays straight man to prosky, except for one wonderful comic monologue in the second act when he explains what happened after he threw a gum wrapper on switzerland's spotless soil. but for much of the time, this reliable actor is left to deliver conventional, present-day attitudes on the horrors of the arms race. it's to waterston's credit that he makes them seem part of his character's idealistic beliefs rather than soapbox oratory
the play has been directed by des mcanuff in an understated manner with movement kept to a minimum. for a good deal of the evening, the two actors just sit on a park bench set squarely in the center of a woodsy glade designed by bill clarke and washed in a delicate light by richard riddell
rich-looking earth nearly spills into the first few rows of the theater and a forest of trees soars to the top of the proscenium arch. it's an inviting, tranquil setting, the perfect place to ruminate on what would be lost if the two superpowers didn't continue their walks in the woods
in other reviews:
the new york times' frank rich offered guarded praise for the actors' work and called the set _ with the trees changing with the seasons _ ``pretentious.'' rich said the play ``fudges the distinctions of actual international politics and arms negotiation, choosing instead to telescope the messy, life-or-death conflict into a sentimental relationship between two likable envoys.''
in the daily news, howard kissel roundly praised waterston and prosky. ``it is waterston's most moving work in years,'' he wrote. ``it is hard to imagine a more perfect actor to play the wily soviet.''
said kissel, ``a few times the play seems coy or tendentious, but the two are so powerful we never forget it's about frail men fighting quixotically against their awareness of futility.''
the protesters, marching four in a row, walked toward parliament from st. george's cathedral, where tutu and other clergymen had declared the churches would have to lead the protests against the government's anti-apartheid policies because 18 major opposition groups had been banned last week from all political activity
tutu marched in front of the procession, along with the rev. allan boesak, president of the world alliance of reformed churches, and the catholic bishop of cape town, stephen naidoo
at the end of each row were clergymen; lay people who had attended the service were in the middle. tutu had warned the protesters during the church service in the cathedral that they might be tear-gassed, sprayed with watter cannon or arrested
before starting the march, tutu told the service, ``we have gathered here as an active witness and out of protest against what the south african government did last week. we intend after this very short service to walk to parliament to present a petition.''
he said the intention was not to provoke police and if the march was stopped the participants should kneel down
the petition, addressed to president p.w. botha and parliament, said:
we leaders of a number of south african churches have come to parliament today to witness and pray in a time of crisis outside the buildings in which you make important decisions affecting the lives of millions of south africans who belong to our churches. in terms of the principles of non-violent direct action, we informed the government of our intention before coming here.''
the winter olympics' flame, which was lighted in greece and traversed some of the most rugged terrain by helicopter, dogsled, snowshoes and skis, was extinguished beneath a nearly full moon in calgary
with 60,000 people present, athletes from 57 countries marched in to mcmahon stadium for sunday night's closing ceremonies carrying miniature olympic torches. banners reading ``until we meet again'' in eight languages were draped along the top of the stands
about 250 skaters took to the world's largest temporary ice rink in period costumes depicting the history of figure skating as a high-tech array of thousands of lights glistened off sequined costumes, flags and flame
the skaters included past and present medal winners as well as young skaters from albertville, france, site of the 1992 winter games, and seoul, south korea, site of this year's summer games
these have been wonderful games,'' declared frank king, whose title is chief executive officer of calgary games' organizing committee
for the united states, however, the winter games was the worst showing in 52 years. two of the six u.s. medals were gold medals, won by brian boitano in figure skating and bonnie blair in speed skating. blair also won a bronze in speed skating, making her america's only double winner
the soviets finished first in number of gold medals, with 11, and total medals, with 29, a record. east germany's athletes won nine golds, 25 overall; while switzerland's team came in third in gold medals, five, and overall medals, 15
four other teams also did better than the united states in terms of overall medals: austria, west germany, finland and the netherlands
in 1936, the united states won just four medals, but only 51 were available then. this time, 138 medals were handed out
