why is there a three-story, $8,000 stained glass window 10 yards from the odor control tank at a sewage pumping station near fisherman's wharf?
the window is part of the $200,000 worth of art commissioned to decorate the city's sewage treatment plants
under a 1969 ordinance, san francisco requires contractors to set aside up to 2 percent of every public works construction dollar for art that is selected by the arts commission
just as we need air and water, we need art and culture in our lives. it doesn't cost any extra ... (and) it makes a facility more enjoyable and respected,'' jill manton, curator of san francisco's public art program, said recently
concrete totems, a colored geometric roof gravel design and mosaic tile walls are other completed sewer art projects
the sunnydale pump station near candlestick park is in line for a special design to help hide the station's rooftop air ducts while featuring a habitat for an endangered butterfly species
