a woman who thought she won enough in a million-dollar sweepstakes to pay off her debts is deeper in debt now after taking a celebratory trip and finding out she didn't win after all
but officials of united states purchasing exchange, the contest's sponsor, say debra long probably is the victim of a mixup, a misunderstanding or a bad joke. she won't be getting any money
long quit her $2.25-an-hour waitress job, took a trip to las vegas with her boyfriend and made plans to buy a house and pay off debts after thinking she won $1.7 million in a sweepstakes
they were convinced i was a winner. i got phone calls saying that,'' long said after learning last week that she wouldn't receive the money
a spokeswoman for the california-based mail-order company disputes long's story on several points. among other things, she says, no winner has been named because the sweepstakes is still in progress
long ordered a $9.98 canister set from uspe in november and entered its sweepstakes
in early february, she said, she received a letter from uspe saying she would receive a ``multimillion-dollar cash letter.'' another uspe letter arrived feb. 13 by certified mail, and long said she took it to mean she had won
uspe officials said the second letter was a promotion advising customers they're in the running for the prize
long said she called the company feb. 15 to confirm her windfall and was asked to read the letter over the phone
a secretary said ``if i heard two beeps, it meant i wasn't a winner,'' long said. ``i was sitting on the edge of my chair, waiting, but i didn't hear any beeps
and then she connected me with the manager. he said, `miss long, i pronounce you the grand prize winner of the uspe sweepstakes. you're $1,731,852.21 richer than you were 24 hours ago.'''
she said she was told the money would be deposited in her bank account within 60 days
uspe officials got word of long's claim last thursday, and cheryl mcgeary, the company's customer service supervisor, called long with the bad news
besides not confirming information via telephone, mcgeary said, uspe doesn't notify winners by certified mail and doesn't ask for bank account numbers
and while long said she called uspe on feb. 15 to verify her claim, mcgeary said company offices were closed that day for presidents' day
mayor edward i. koch called president reagan a wimp in the war on drugs today after taking out a full-page ad in the new york times urging the president to cut economic aid to drug-producing countries
the mayor's ad bore a black-bordered picture of a 22-year-old rookie policeman murdered last week in the drug-ravaged south jamaica section of queens
we are truly in a war with the drug pushers, but the president is not acting as the commander-in-chief. if anything, he's acting as a wimp,'' koch said today on ``cbs this morning.''
koch said the ad attempted to ``channel this rage that the whole city is feeling'' about the killing friday of officer edward byrne, who was shot three times while guarding the house of a threatened witness in a drug case
the $12,900 ad, paid for by koch's 1989 re-election committee, said byrne was killed ``by a gunman who, very probably, was acting on instructions from a new york drug kingpin.''
reagan is expected to sign an order tuesday exempting some countries from a law mandating cuts in economic and military aid for their failure to take adequate steps to combat drug trafficking
koch's ad asks readers to send reagan telegrams saying, ``do not sign the certifications for foreign aid to mexico, panama, the bahamas, haiti, paraguay, colombia, or any other drug source country.''
the mayor also urged readers to send telegrams to members of congress, asking them to vote against certificates of aid to drug source countries if reagan approves the aid. trafficking</head> yet made</note>
the united states will not impose maximum penalties against panama for failing to take steps to control drug trafficking, a newspaper reported today
under a 1986 anti-drug law, the president has until tuesday to certify whether countries in which major drug trafficking occurs are fully cooperating in efforts to fight the trafficking
the new york times, quoting senior reagan administration officials, said president reagan last weekend signed an order to decertify panama, but that he declined to use his discretionary powers to impose the maximum penalties
however, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the president has not made a decision. ``it hasn't gone to him yet. it's going today.''
the law requires the united states to vote against new loans by international development banks such as the world bank and the international monetary fund to decertified countries. in the case of panama, the united states also would be obliged to keep in place the military and economic sanctions imposed last year
other sanctions reagan has the power to impose include the barring of airline flights between panama and the united states; imposition of a 50 percent tax on all panamaniam imports; and the loss of preferential tariff treatment
some administration officials have said the president should impose full sanctions as a means of conveying disapproval to gen. manuel antonio noriega, panama's de facto leader. noriega was indicted in florida this month on drug-trafficking charges
it was not known why reagan chose not to use all the mechanisms under the law, but some officials speculated that the administration wants to wait until events become more stable in panama. panama's president, eric arturo delvalle, was ousted on friday by the country's assembly, which noriega controls
iran hanged two men sentenced to death for bombing a tehran square, iran's official islamic republic news agency reported today
the executions sunday raised to seven the number of people hanged in public in the iranian capital during the weekend for bombings. irna, monitored in nicosia, said five men were hanged saturday
a senior commander of tehran's revolutionary committees, which have largely taken over security from civilian police, announced saturday that 30 people responsible for recent bombings in tehran and western iran had been arrested
he said the suspects, described as ``paid iraqi agents,'' would be handed over to the revolutionary courts for trial
irna did not specify whether the seven men executed were part of the group of 30 reported arrested
irna identified the two men hanged sunday as mohammed kazimzadeh and rasoul rahmani. it said the islamic revolutionary court convicted them of planting bombs, spying for iraq and transporting explosives to tehran from iraq
they received ``a large amount of money'' from iraq for the bombings, the agency said
the two men were sentenced to death for bombings last year in a tehran square and were hanged ``at the scene of their crime,'' irna said
the latest reported bombing in tehran was feb. 18, when a car bomb exploded on a tehran expressway, wounding two people
another 10 people were wounded three days earlier by a blast in north tehran's martyr bahonar avenue, only a few hundred yards from the residence of iranian revolutionary patriarch ayatollah ruhollah khomeini
iran and iraq have been at war since september 1980. members of iranian resistance groups fighting against khomeini's fundamentist islamic regime are invariably branded iraqi agents by the iranian authorities
the supreme court today agreed to consider letting the federal government apply retroactively a formula that limits reimbursement paid to hospitals treating medicare patients
the court said it will hear reagan administration arguments that some hospitals could reap a windfall from the ban on retroactive application of the formula
the government in 1981 adopted a rule that excluded from the medicare reimbursement formula wages paid by hospitals owned by the federal government
the idea was to save money by not applying national pay scales to private hospitals in areas with lower wage levels
but the department of health and human services adopted the new rule without allowing a time for the public to comment on the proposal. the formula was challenged by private hospitals and thrown out by a federal judge as a violation of proper rule-making procedures
the federal agency adopted the rule again in 1984 using the correct procedure. but this time the department applied the rule retroactively to reimbursement sought by the hospitals beginning july 1, 1981
the u.s. circuit court of appeals here ruled last june that the formula may not be applied retroactively, and awarded more than $2 million in reimbursement money to seven hospitals
the appeals court said that if the government believes any hospital has received excess reimbursement, each case must be proved
the justice department, in its appeal to the supreme court, said the appeals court ruling ``would effectively eliminate the only realistic method available ... to make retroactive corrections to reimbursement decisions.''
the hospitals involved in the case are georgetown university hospital, howard university hospital and greater southeast community hospital, all in the district of columbia; tucson general and tucson medical center in arizona, st. cloud hospital in minnesota and community hospital of battle creek, mich
the case is bowen vs. georgetown university hospital, 87-1097
a reporter's attempt to force the state department to release documents from u.s. embassies around the world failed in the supreme court today
the justices, without comment, let stand rulings that threw out donald f. goldberg's lawsuit, which had been filed under the freedom of information act
goldberg, a reporter on the staff of syndicated columnist jack anderson, filed an foia request in 1984 seeking from the state department responses to an unclassified 1982 questionnaire on foreign governments' diplomatic practices
the foia was passed by congress in 1966 to help curtail government secrecy
state department officials told goldberg in 1985 that only four of 161 relevant documents could be released fully
of the remaining 157 documents, nine were not to be released at all and 148 were to be released with certain portions omitted
the government invoked an foia exemption that protects secrets of national defense or foreign policy
goldberg then sued, contending that the responses improperly were given a ``classified'' designation in washington by john eaves, director of the office of mandatory review in the state department's classification and declassification center
goldberg noted that most of the responses originally had been designated ``unclassified'' by responding ambassadors
a federal trial judge dismissed goldberg's suit before trial, and the u.s. circuit court of appeals for the district of columbia upheld that ruling
the appeals court said it rejected goldberg's argument that ``the affixing of conclusory `unclassified' labels on responses to an unclassified questionnaire by itself controverts a detailed review and explanation that some parts of those documents are properly classified.''
the case is goldberg vs. state department, 87-655
the supreme court today agreed to review a decision halving the fines and prison terms given to a dodge city, kan., business and its president for rigging highway-construction bids
the justices said they will hear federal prosecutors' arguments aimed at reinstating the original sentences received by broce construction co. inc. and ray c. broce
broce and the business pleaded guilty in 1982 to charges contained in two indictments, respectively alleging bid-rigging in highway-construction projects in meade and barton counties
broce was sentenced on march 15, 1982, to concurrent two-year prison terms and fined $101,000. the corporation he headed was fined $1.5 million
more than a year after the sentencing, broce and the corporation sought to set aside the judgment and sentence from the second indictment. they contended that the separate sentences meted out under the second indictment amounted to multiple punishment for the same crime
a federal trial judge threw out the appeal but the 10th u.s. circuit court of appeals reversed that ruling
the appeals court said that the constitution's protection against double jeopardy had been violated by the sentencing, and that broce and the corporation had not waived their double-jeopardy protections when agreeing to plead guilty
the appeals court set aside the sentences issued under the second indictment _ $750,000 in fines for the corporation and $50,000 in fines and a two-year prison term for broce
in seeking supreme court review, government lawyers noted that the two defendants pleaded guilty to two indictments alleging two different criminal conspiracies under a plea bargain in which the government agreed not to prosecute on other charges
under such circumstances, the government's appeal said, defendants should not be able later to attack the sentences on grounds that the two alleged conspiracies were actually a single conspiracy
the case is u.s. vs. broce, 87-1190. with quotes from news conference. picks up 6th graf, `the clergymen ...'</note>
police today arrested anglican archbishop desmond tutu and other church leaders as they marched toward parliament with a petition protesting the government's crackdown on anti-apartheid groups
the clergymen, wearing robes and crosses around their necks, stood with arms linked and bibles clutched in their hands as a policeman announced through a bullhorn that the gathering was illegal. police had been lining the street outside st. george's anglican cathedral, waiting for the marchers to emerge
after tutu, a nobel peace prize laureate, and other clergymen were placed in police vehicles, police fired water cannons at more than 100 demonstrators sitting on the sidewalk singing a hymn, local journalists said
the clergymen and demonstrators were taken to a police station and released with a warning that charges would be brought against them if they staged a similar protest, said the rev. allan boesak, president of the world alliance of reformed churches. he said they were told summonses might be issued against them for demonstrating near parliament and they might be called to court
police also took some journalists into custody
upon their release, the white, black, mixed-race and indian clergymen held a news conference in the cathedral, which was still surrounded by policemen with a water cannon nearby
we are not defying the law,'' tutu said, ``we are obeying god. we also obey god every day.''
in the past,'' tutu continued, ``it was possible for people to say it was the usual rabble rousers demonstrating. they can't say it any more. it's the church.''
boesak described today's protest as ``an act of subversion.''
we told the south african government that we had decided we would be obedient to god. that is a higher law to us,'' he said
the clergymen carried a petition, addressed to president p.w. botha and parliament, saying: ``we leaders of a number of south african churches have come to parliament today to witness and pray in a time of crisis outside the buildings in which you make important decisions affecting the lives of millions of south africans who belong to our churches.''
the protesters, marching five abreast, walked a few yards toward parliament from st. george's cathedral, the main anglican church in downtown cape town
in a service in the cathedral before the march, tutu and other ministers declared the churches would lead protests against the government's anti-apartheid policies because 18 major black opposition groups had been banned last week from all political activity
tutu marched in front of the procession, along with boesak and other prominent ministers
tutu warned those at the service that they might be tear-gassed, sprayed with water cannons or arrested. the church leaders said they had informed the government about the proposed march
the march proceeded with clergymen at the end of each row and lay people in the middle. as they reached government avenue, near the parliament buildings, they were met by about 50 policemen who linked arms to block the road
the police told the crowd they were gathering illegally, then began leading away the church leaders, starting with boesak
the rev. sid luckett, head of the anglican board of social responsibility, led the rest of the crowd to the police vehicles and they sat down on the sidewalk
police sprayed the seated protesters with water cannons, but they stayed in place, and were then put into police vans as they recited the lord's prayer
last wednesday, the government banned the united democratic front, the nation's largest anti-apartheid organization, and 17 other major black opposition groups from conducting any political activity
banning orders were also issued against 18 prominent black leaders, prohibiting them from taking part in anti-government activities, confining them to their hometowns, and ordering them not to speak to the press
church groups weren't included in the crackdown and theoretically still were free to engage in resistance campaigns, but most forms of peaceful protest are banned under existing regulations
tutu had called the new regulations ``a declaration of war against the people.'' he and other church leaders had pledged the churches would begin to conduct some of the protest campaigns that had been organized by the banned groups
in may 1980, tutu was one of 54 people, mostly priests, who were arrested in johannesburg under the riotous assemblies act for marching in protest against the detention of a congregational church minister. all were convicted and sentenced to pay a $45 fine or spend 50 days in jail. tutu's fine was paid
boesak was last arrested in august, 1985, when he was charged with subversion for, among other things, organizing a march to pollsmoor prison where african national congress leader nelson mandela is serving a life term. fourteen months later the charges were dropped
under south africa's apartheid policies of racial segregation, the nation's 5 million whites maintain political and economic control over 26 million blacks, who have no vote in national affairs. searches lose appeal</head>
illinois officials wanting to conduct warrantless searches of racetrack employees' on-grounds living quarters as one way of protecting the sport's integrity lost a supreme court appeal today
the justices, without comment, let stand rulings that such searches violate constitutionally protected privacy rights if conducted without first obtaining a court warrant
the illinois racing board for years had authorized state law enforcement officers to search, without warrants, the rooms of ``backstretchers'' _ those employees who feed, groom, exercise and generally take care of racehorses
the searches were aimed at discovering drugs or mechanical devices that could affect a race's outcome
while employed by horse trainers, many backstretchers live in small rooms located in the area where horses are stabled, the backstretch
the board also authorized warrantless searches of the employees themselves
at one time, backstretchers were required to consent to such searches as a condition to receiving their licenses
three backstretchers working at arlington park racetrack challenged the state board's policy and rules in 1982
don serpas, raymond johnson and carl waters sued the racing board in behalf of all backstretchers working at illinois tracks. the three had been subjected to searches that turned up no evidence of any crime
u.s. district judge charles p. kocoras ordered that the warrantless searches be halted temporarily in 1983, and then banned them permanently in 1985
the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals upheld the ban last july 17 after finding no explicit authority for the searches in illinois law
the appeals court said the backstretchers' living quarters, though temporary and humble, must be treated as their homes
the constitution's fourth amendment generally prohibits searches of someone's home unless a court warrant is obtained. courts generally will not issue a search warrant unless authorities show a likelihood that evidence of criminal conduct will be found as a result
there is no reason to doubt that drugs and mechanical devices pose major threats to the integrity of the horseracing industry,'' the appeals court said. but it added that the illinois racetrack searches ``without the safeguard of a warrant are unreasonable and violate the fourth amendment.''
in seeking supreme court review, illinois attorney general neil f. hartigan relied on past rulings by the justices that have allowed warrantless searches of heavily regulated industries
the case is schmidt vs. serpas, 87-644
the supreme court today refused to revive lawsuits charging the government and federal contractors with negligently causing deaths and disease among people exposed to open-air atomic tests
the court, without comment, let stand a federal law that effectively spared the government from having to defend itself against claims seeking billions of dollars
the atmospheric nuclear tests that gave rise to the case took place between the closing days of world war ii and the adoption of a treaty between the united states and the soviet union in 1963 banning open-air testing
suits were filed on behalf of 29 people _ civilians and members of the military _ including 26 who died from cancer or cancer-related causes. the suits alleged that the health problems were caused by radioactive fallout from the explosions
charged with negligence were the university of california, which operated the los alamos, n.m., project; lawrence livermore laboratories, which helped develop the atomic bomb; sandia corp., which provided engineering for the weapons program; and reynolds electric engineering co., which helped build and operate a test site in nevada
the suits accused the private contractors of failing to take adequate safety precautions at the test sites, and also said the government was responsible for failing to enforce its own safety standards
if the suits were successful, the government ultimately would pay the claims because it had insured the private contractors for any losses
but in 1984 congress passed a law supported by the reagan administration that says only the u.s. government may be sued for negligence allegedly caused by a private contractor in the atomic weapons testing program
the result was to bar the claims since the government is immune from such suits unless it surrenders immunity under the existing federal tort claims act
those who sued the companies said the 1984 law unconstitutionally deprived them of a remedy for the deaths and disease caused by the atomic explosions
the petitioners had a remedy against the original defendants. they have none against the united states,'' they said
the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals upheld the law last june. it rejected arguments that the law violates the constitution's required separation of powers by retroactively preventing the courts from considering pending claims
the administration, in urging the supreme court not to disturb the appeals court decision, said more than 3,000 people are seeking damages totalling more than $4.9 billion in all cases stemming from the weapons tests
the high court on jan. 11 refused to hear a related appeal by some 1,200 people in nevada, arizona and utah who sought to hold the government financially responsible for deaths and diseases allegedly caused by the tests in nevada
the case acted on today is konizeski vs. livermore labs, 87-953. case</head>
the supreme court asked the reagan administration today whether it thinks high-stakes bingo games run by indian tribes are subject to state sales taxes
the court said it wants to hear from justice department lawyers before it says whether it will review an attempt by oklahoma officials to tax revenue from a bingo game in tulsa run by the muscogee creek nation
the justice department's brief may not be filed for months
the 10th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled in september that the state could not force the tribe to collect and remit the state's 2.5 percent sales tax on the bingo operations
the appeals court said the state's interest in collecting the tax is minimal in this case
patrons do not travel onto creek lands to play bingo in order to avoid sales taxes,'' the appeals court said. ``creek nation bingo does not undermine the state economy or tax base. the state is not losing tax revenues it would otherwise obtain from sales made outside of tribal boundaries.''
the appeals court also based its ruling in part on a supreme court decision last year that said state and local governments may not regulate indian-run gambling unless congress gives them permission
the muscogee creek bingo game is conducted in tulsa on a 100-acre area known as the mackey site along the arkansas river
the 10th circuit court said the land is indian territory in the same way any reservation belongs to native americans
the appeals court also said the fact that the bingo game is managed by a non-tribal entity _ indian country, usa inc. _ hired by the tribe does not alter the exempt status of the gambling operation
forcing the tribe to collect and remit the sales tax would place a heavy burden on the indians even if the tax did not affect revenue for the creeks, the appeals court added
it said the tribe would be subject to fines and liens on its property if it were held responsible for collecting the tax and then failed to do so
the case is oklahoma tax commission vs. muscogee creek nation, 87-1068
former army football star peter dawkins today announced his candidacy for the gop senate nomination in a bid to unseat democratic frank lautenberg, saying new jersey needs to improve its environment, education, employment and trade
we've gone from being a state that was written off to a state being written up. and we're ready to climb even higher to become the very best,'' said dawkins, who was a rhodes scholar and vietnam war hero after he graduated from west point
he is the first candidate to announce his candidacy in the june 7 republican primary
we can't be satisfied until the opportunity and prosperity that has reached some, reaches all,'' dawkins said. ``we can't forget those people caught in the forgotten pockets of poverty in camden, in trenton, in newark, where too often the real growth industries have been drugs and crime and disappointment.''
both dawkins and lautenberg already have raised millions and are employing top national political strategists
republicans claim lautenberg, seeking his second six-year term, is among the most vulnerable incumbents in the senate. democrats counter that the millionaire businessman has compiled an impressive record
dawkins has never sought elected office, but has spent more than a year planting the seeds of his candidacy around the state
the supreme court today refused to reinstate a little rock, ark., man's criminal conviction thrown out because police did not tell him specifically about his right to free legal help
the justices, without comment, let stand a state supreme court ruling that so-called miranda warnings given before police question criminal suspects must mention that right
michael e. mayfield was convicted in 1985 of robbing a little rock store. when arrested and read his rights, mayfield had confessed
the standard warning then used by little rock police said a suspect has the right to remain silent or to talk with a lawyer ``either retained by me or appointed by the court'' before giving a statement
such police warnings have been given since 1966 when the supreme court ruled in a case called miranda vs. arizona that the fifth amendment protection against self-incrimination requires them
the arkansas supreme court, ruling last sept. 28 that mayfield is entitled to a new trial, said his confession should not have been used as evidence against him
the state court said an indigent criminal suspect must ``be informed that he has just as much right to representation by an attorney as a person who can afford one.''
earlier last year, the arkansas court upheld a police warning that stated, ``if you cannot afford a lawyer, one will be appointed for you, before any questioning if you wish.''
in the appeal acted on today, arkansas attorney general steve clark told the justices the state court ruling is inconsistent with their 1981 decision that the warnings given by police do not have to follow the miranda decision verbatim
the 1981 decision, however, involved a case in which a criminal suspect was told about his ``right to have a lawyer appointed to represent you at no cost to yourself.''
the case acted on today is arkansas vs. mayfield, 87-1105
jewish leaders have presented a 5,180-signature petition to the israeli consul general recommending a ban on television coverage of israeli-arab conflicts in the occupied territories
israeli consul general rahamim timor accepted the petition sunday at temple emeth near delray beach
good friends can give us advice,'' timor told the audience of 400. ``any recommendations, suggestions and advice will be studied and considered.''
rabbi leon fink and cantor david leon led the petition drive that blamed television coverage for sparking more violence on the west bank and gaza strip
graphic television footage of recent palestinian demonstrations against israeli rule has been shown around the world. the footage has shown stone-throwing by palestinians and israeli retaliation, including tear gas attacks, gunfire and brutal beatings
seventy-four palestianians have died in the protests since dec. 8, according to united nations figures
we're not against the press, but there's a major difference between the camera and the press,'' said leon, adding that television footage gives a distorted view of the entire conflict. ``you get a completely different picture from the print.''
if you think that stoning and firebombing in the middle east is a new thing, you are wrong,'' he said. ``we are concerned, we should not be excited.''
timor said that occasionally, excessive force is used, ``but this is war.''
we shall not commit suicide,'' he said. ``if the public relations is not nice, then they are not nice, but we shall survive.''
a tourist was in intensive care today after falling from a third-floor hotel balcony in the first such incident in the college spring-break season
david irwin and several friends stepped out onto the balcony after hearing a firecracker go off sunday night. irwin, 23, reached for a railing but missed, his friends told police. he fell to the pool deck
it was not known whether irwin was a college student. manager neal hughes of the hawaiian inn in daytona beach shores irwin had traveled alone from ontario
about 500,000 students are expected to visit area beaches this march and april for spring vacations. thirty people have fallen from daytona beach-area hotel and motel balconies in the past four years, mostly during spring break. six have died
heavy drinking has usually been the reason for the accidents, officials say
the hawaiian does not allow students on hotel balconies after 11 p.m
we have had students here for three weeks'' so far this year, said hughes. ``they have been real good. they have been real cooperative about keeping the curfew hours.'' sted lowdrick</note>
prince andrew and his wife, sarah, prayed with ordinary people in church then played with hollywood celebrities at a black-tie dinner, where the duchess joked with a male admirer in the audience
the duke and duchess of york ended a diverse day of activities sunday with the star-studded dinner organized by industrialist armand hammer and arco petroleum chief lodwrick cooke
among the 700 guests paying $1,000 apiece to dine with british royalty at the biltmore hotel were zsa zsa gabor, her husband prince frederick von anhalt, ``dynasty'' star joan collins, her date george hamilton, burt bacharach and his wife, carole bayer sager, actor michael york and astronaut buzz aldrin
british actor roger moore, the master of ceremonies, joked about the nature of the royals' trip, quipping that the highlight was today's visit to a supermarket
i couldn't help but notice the royal couple will be there on double coupon day. and just in case you want to do a little shopping, this one's for disposal diapers,'' moore said, holding up a coupon for the couple, whose first child is due this year
their fourth day in southern california was to start today with a visit to two british exhibits at the california museum of science and industry. in the afternoon, attention focuses on promoting british trade
they were to tour the bullocks wilshire clothing department store and visits a vons supermarket in arcadia
for sunday night's black-tie event, the duchess arrived in a strapless black evening gown with a shimmery, puffy orange wrap draped around her shoulders
allowed to give a few remarks after two lengthy introductions and a short speech by her husband, sarah drew applause and some cheers when she said: ``at last i have a turn to talk _ all these men.''
a man from the audience shouted, ``i love you.''
i'll see you later,'' she quipped to more applause and cheers
andrew had gotten in his dig a moment earlier when he acknowledged hammer's remark that the couple ``could fly duets'' as they are both licensed pilots
you mentioned being able to fly duets,'' the prince said. ``it is a little bit difficult because we would be fighting for the controls of the plane.''
money raised by the dinner benefits the three-month uk-la '88 art festival and a fund to salvage books damaged in disastrous 1986 fires at the los angeles central library. the guests dined on crepinette of salmon and white fish, with champagne chervil
on behalf of the british library board, andrew brought a gift, the book wonders of creation. sarah presented the couple's personal gift, two volumes of the book, ``royal heritage,'' bound at windsor castle
on sunday, the day began on a more common note. the couple attended services at st. luke's episcopal church in long beach
about 300 people lined the sidewalk across from the church to see the couple
we love them, we really do,'' said 48-year-old myrna dillon, perched on a stepladder to ctach a glimpse. ``we follow their every move.''
unknown to the royal retinue, officers sweeping the motorcade route detained a man carrying a .22-caliber rifle
john kasser, 30, of long beach, had retrieved the unloaded rifle from the police station and was headed to his car when los angeles city police officers spotted him, said long beach lt. rod mickelson. the gun had been held for safekeeping for several days after officers confiscated it during a domestic dispute, mickelson said
kasser was later freed and allowed to keep his gun, police said
there's absolutely no relation between him and the motorcade,'' mickelson said
every saturday morning at gene's cafe, over coffee, grits and country ham biscuits, elders of this small piedmont town discuss the weather, how to solve the nation's problems and lately, who should be nominated for president
unlike previous races, they've had plenty of firsthand looks at the candidates. and their republican primary votes on saturday, along with the rest of south carolina, will carry unprecedented weight
as george bush pointed out last week during one of many days spent in the state:
this state is going to be on the leading edge of the most significant political event in terms of selecting a president that we've had in this country in modern times,'' he said, in only a slight overstatement of the importance of the super tuesday collection of 20 primaries and caucuses three days after south carolina votes
you're going to see the darndest invasion of people who want to be president that you've ever seen.''
the republican candidates are blanketing the state ahead of saturday's balloting with an eye toward the state's 37 gop delegates, yes, but more importantly, with hopes of a boost going into super tuesday
south carolina's primary falls three days before 20 states, mostly in the south, choose more than one-third of the delegates to the national convention in new orleans
by going ahead of that, south carolina has a special place in the sun. you're going to send a signal, you see, all across the region. and that signal will reverberate across the country,'' bush said
heavy stuff for the boys at gene's
but claude crocker said no topic is too big for his crowd
we talk about international trade policy, the panama canal, the deficit. ... we handle all those high-level things,'' the vice president of clinton mills deadpanned
crocker thinks bush is the man to beat in his area and in the state. but charles ``buddy'' oakley said former television evangelist pat robertson can't be counted out
i think robertson appeals to a large group of religious-type people in south carolina,'' he said
their observations mirror more objective measurements
a survey published sunday by the state newspaper said bush was the choice of 48 percent of the voters likely to cast gop ballots, dole 25 percent, robertson 19 percent and jack kemp 3 percent. the poll, conducted last monday through wednesday, surveyed 319 likely gop voters
but lee atwater, a south carolina native and bush's national campaign manager, said robertson's strength has to be at least doubled because of the strong turnout of his supporters and the difficulty in measuring them. robertson has attracted new voters to the rolls, and many conservative democrats are expected to vote in the gop primary for him
university of south carolina political professor earl black said ``there is an enormous potential for a heavy cross-over vote'' because south carolina voters don't register by party and because, this being the second primary ever, there is no historical gauge
robertson has said for months that he is seeking a first-place finish in south carolina, where he has a large and fervent following of fundamentalist christians. one robertson stronghold is ptl's heritage usa, where more than 1,500 people live
south carolina is a do-or-die state for kemp, who has yet to finish better than third in any contest. the new york congressman is portraying himself here as the conservative alternative, saying robertson has no chance of winning the nomination
south carolina is george bush's to lose,'' said blease graham, an associate professor in governmental studies at the university of south carolina
one issue that could cost bush votes, graham said, is his opposition to legislation that would restrict the growth of textile imports, which the industry says is causing job losses
the industry is running advertisements across the state every day urging people indirectly to vote for candidates who back the legislation. robertson and dole announced last week that they support the bill now in the senate
bush's main strategy in south carolina has been to promote his close ties with president reagan, who remains popular here
turnout in 1980 was 145,000, and party officials estimate that between 175,000 and 200,000 people will vote saturday
a man sentenced to death in utah for his role in the 1974 killings of three people forced to swallow drain cleaner before they were shot lost a supreme court appeal today
the justices let stand william andrews' conviction and death sentence for the three murders committed during an aril 22, 1974 robbery of an ogden store
police said andrews and pierre dale selby, both stationed at hill air force base in utah, robbed the hi-fi shop. killed were stanley walker, the store's assistant manager; michelle ansley, a cashier; and carol naisbitt, a relative of the store's owner
andrews' lawyers said he was a ``non-triggerman'' participant in the crime, and that selby actually murdered the three
selby, from brooklyn, n.y., was executed last aug. 28
andrews, a former resident of jonesboro, la, contended that he was denied a fair trial because blacks were excluded from the trial jury. his appeal also challenged the validity of utah's death penalty law on several grounds
the 10th u.s. circuit court of appeals previously had rejected those arguments
the case is andrews vs. shulsen, 87-5449
the supreme court today agreed to decide whether states may block a man from trying to prove he fathered the child of a woman married to someone else
the court said it will study a challenge by a man identified in court records only as michael h., to a state evidentiary rule creating a conclusive presumption of fatherhood to a wife's husband
michael h. contends he is the father of a 6-year-old girl, victoria, born to a woman identified as carol d. at a time when carol d. was married to gerald d
michael h. filed in a state court in los angeles a ``reverse paternity'' lawsuit in 1982, seeking to have himself declared victoria's father
his lawsuit was thrown out because california law, as do laws in many other states, creates a conclusive presumption of paternity in favor of a woman's husband if a child is conceived and born during their marriage
in upholding the dismissal of michael h.'s lawsuit, a state appeals court said the conclusive presumption is based ``upon a determination by the legislature as a matter of overriding social policy that given a certain relationship between the husband and wife, the husband is to be held responsible for the child and the integrity of the family unit should not be impugned.''
the california supreme court had refused to hear michael h.'s appeal last july 30
the nation's highest court two years ago rejected, without comment, a similar appeal from a massachusetts man seeking to prove he fathered the child of another man's wife
in the appeal acted on today, lawyers for michael h. said he enjoyed ``an ongoing father-child relationship'' with victoria and that blood tests show a better than 98 percent chance that victoria is his biological daughter
the appeal said victoria was born as a result of an affair michael h. and carol d. had while she was married to gerald d
the appeal also said that carol d. and victoria moved to the virgin islands to live with michael h. for several months in 1982 when she and her husband were estranged
court records indicate that carol and gerald d. later resumed living together
the case is michael h. vs. gerald d., 87-746
a general strike started today to demand the resignation of gen. manuel antonio noriega but government intimidation, censorship and the fact that today is payday apparently hurt its effectiveness
the opposition asked the nation's businesses and industries to close today and remain shut indefinitely
deposed president eric arturo delvalle remained in hiding, defying noreiga, who ousted delvalle and ordered him out of the country
buses, by far the main mode of public transportation, circulated this morning like any other morning. most were full, taking people to work
about two-thirds of the stores were open at a commercial center of more than 100 enterprises on central avenue in panama city
many panamanian banks were closed by the strike, but international banks were open
several people consulted by the associated press as they stepped from buses on their way to work mentioned intimidation as a reason for not observing the strike
there's fear,'' said a middle-aged man, a bank employee. ``we lack unity to confront these people who have all the arms and are disposed to use them.''
the people don't have means to resist,'' said a woman, a domestic employee, walking with him. ``one has to live as they (the armed forces) say.''
the two also noted that today, being the last day of the month, is payday for many panamanians
police chief col. leonidas macias told journalists it would be understandale if hungry people looted a closed supermarket, and his forces would not try to prevent them
the strike call was supported by the industrial workers' union of panama, and its effectiveness appeared to be greater in industry than in commerce. most factories in panama city's industrial zone were closed
roberto brenes, a leader of the national civic crusade, predicted sunday that the strike would do well in manufacturing and construction, but would be less effective in the service industries
opposition figures also said they expected the strike to pick up in several days. they said government censorship had slowed word of the strike
indeed, la prensa, the leading opposition paper, has been closed by troops and the newspaper building surrounded by city police
delvalle's relatives would not disclose his whereabouts but they said he was in a ``safe and secure place'' in panama, in ``good spirits'' and determined to regain his job
i am going to stay here (and) stick it out,'' delvalle told abc television in a telephone interview saturday night. ``i'm going to fight it all the way.''
roderick esquivel, delvalle's vice president, also was in hiding. both men were ousted friday by the national legislative assembly in a move orchestrated by noriega, chief of panama's 17,000-member defense forces
on thursday, delvalle ignited the latest crisis in eight months of civil unrest in panama when he tried to fire noriega, charged in florida with corruption and narcotics trafficking. the united states also has urged noriega to step down as military chief
on friday, delvalle returned to his home in an upper-class neighborhood. police surrounded the house friday night and delvalle's telephones were cut, leaving him under an undeclared house arrest
sometime that night, he reportedly climbed over a patio wall at the rear of the house and escaped through a neighbor's yard
opposition leaders said a prolonged strike could create financial chaos in panama and force noriega to resign, paving the way for delvalle's return to office and an end to military domination of the government
the pro-government newspapr critica blared a red-ink banner headline ``a closed business is a taken-over business.''
osvaldo velasquez, president of the panama committee for human rights, predicted the government would ``use state terrorism'' to ``try to counteract the strike.''
he added: ``one of the means they will resort to is to stimulate the crowds to get into the stores, to break into the businesses that dare to close.''
he said that tactic had been used by the government in previous, unsuccessful strikes last summer
raul diaz, delvalle's brother-in-law, said sunday that the former president was telephoning world leaders from hiding to ask their support
delvalle, he said, was not with his wife and three children, but all of them were safe. ``they are in one place and he is alone in another,'' he said
the u.s. state department said on saturday that some of delvalle's children or grandchildren were at the u.s. embassy or the home of u.s. ambassador arthur davis. the embassy declined to comment sunday on that report
in an interview on cbs news' ``60 minutes'' program, noriega was asked where delvalle was and the general said, ``he's with the north americans, with the ambassador of the united states.'' when he was asked if delvalle was at the u.s. embassy, noriega said, ``at this point we don't know.''
delvalle's hopes of regaining his post were dealt a setback saturday when the permanent council of the organization of american states, meeting in washington, declined to impose trade sanctions on panama or approve a resolution condemning the president's ouster by the military
nancy reagan today called for a crackdown on casual drug users, saying they are ``an accomplice to murder'' in the deaths of judges, agents and others who have been killed by narcotics traffickers
i want to make it impossible for casual users to escape responsibility for any innocent deaths due to drugs,'' mrs. reagan said. ``i want to make them fully face the brutality of drug use.''
the first lady was joined by her husband, president reagan, at the white house conference for a drug free america, a meeting intended to showcase the fight against drugs
she said that when she moves back to california next year, ``i'm not going to give up my interest and concern about this.'' she said she will continue her efforts at the nancy reagan house in los angeles, which is to be run by the phoenix house
in his remarks, the president said that despite all the publicity about drugs, ``let's keep in mind the progress we've made.'' he said the number of users is leveling off and may even be falling
the tide of the battle has turned and we're beginning to win the crusade for a drug-free america,'' reagan said
mrs. reagan gave a more somber assessment, saying, ``drugs are tearing our community apart.'' she said drug traffickers and dealers will murder anyone who stands in their way
in particular, she cited the murder of colombia's chief prosecutor, attorney general carlos hoyos, and his two bodyguards who were abducted last month by a half-dozen gunmen who the government accused of working for local cocaine barons
hoyos' bullet-riddled body was dumped outside the center of the nation's drug trade. the body had been blindfolded and handcuffed
the government blamed his abduction and death on the medillin cartel, which u.s. officials say controls 80 percent of cocaine entering the united states
mrs. reagan said that ``the people who casually use cocaine are responsible beause their money bought those bullets.''
the casual user may think when he takes a line of cocaine or smokes a joint in the privacy of his nice condo, listening to his expensive stereo, that he's somehow not bothering anyone,'' she said
but there's a trail of death and destruction that leads directly to his door,'' mrs. reagan said. ``the casual user cannot morally escape responsibility for the action of drug traffickers and dealing
i'm saying that if you're a casual drug user, you're an accomplice to murder,'' the first lady said, prompting loud applause from the audience of anti-drug activists
the casual users ... also cannot morally escape association with those who use drugs and then endanger the public safety,'' she said. ``the message from casual use is that drugs are acceptable, that they can be handled, that somehow it's simply a matter of dosage
casual use sets the tone for tolerance and that tolerance can kill,'' she said, recalling a train crash in maryland last year that killed 16 people and injured 175 others. she noted that an investigation determined that a train engineer and brakeman had smoked marijuana. graf pvs, ``it's the entire xxx</note>
all five members of one family were found dead early today in their burning home, and authorities said investigators were treating the deaths as homicides
they were obviously not killed by the fire,'' said livingston county sheriff richard kane. he said that it might have been a murder-suicide, and that a 16-gauge shotgun was found near the father's body
obviously, two scenarios come to mind: murder-suicide is one, and the other is that another person was involved in committing these acts,'' said kane
the fire, discovered just before midnight by neighbors, was ``highly suspicious,'' kane said
kane identified the victims as lawrence delabarto, 32; his wife, linda, also 32; and their children, anthony, 12, danielle 10, and dominic, 6. he said the three young children and the father were found shot; mrs. delaberto was apparently strangled
it's the entire family,'' kane said. ``they were all dead.''
firefighters in this hamlet about 10 miles south of geneseo found the five bodies in their bedrooms, kane said
kevin niedermaier, chief of the groveland volunteer fire department, said it took two hours to bring the fire under control
the father of the family worked for a wholesale liquor company in the area, kane said
panama's ambassador to the united states said today that efforts by the newly installed government in panama to replace him will not succeed
following the ouster last friday of president eric arturo delvalle, the successor government appointed the second ranking official at panama's u.n. embassy, leonardo kam, to succeed ambassador juan b. sosa
the u.n. embassy said that kam was in washington today but sosa said he had heard nothing from the envoy
sosa said in a telephone interview that the ouster of delvalle by the national assembly, dominated by forces loyal to military strongman manuel noriega, was unconstitutional. sosa said he continues to regard delvalle as panama's president
i hope not to hear from mr. kam,'' sosa said. ``it would be a very embarrassing situation. he would be representing an unconstitutional government. he would be wasting his time.''
asked about the status of other embassy diplomats, sosa said, ``the panamanian embassy is loyal to its ambassador and the ambassador is loyal to president delvalle.''
he said the representative of panama's defense forces at the embassy, capt. jose s. motta, continues to serve at his post. he added that motta reports to the defense forces and not to the ambassador
an oceanographic research vessel will be renamed on tuesday in honor of the late secretary of commerce malcolm baldrige
the national oceanic and atmospheric administration ship researcher will be renamed the malcolm baldrige in recognition of the late official's public service. baldrige died last july following a rodeo accident
the 2,963-ton vessel, 278 feet long, is the largest ship in the noaa fleet of 23 research and survey vessels. it conducts climate research in the atlantic and caribbean for noaa, which is a part of the commerce department
the renaming ceremonies will be held at the washington navy yard
the u.s. naval observatory is looking for help in sighting the moon
while nearly anyone can see the huge full moon, the astronomers are trying to determine just how soon after a new moon the first faint crescent of moonlight becomes visible to observers
to help determine just how quickly that occurs, the observatory has scheduled an experiment for july 14
the new moon will occur at 7:53 p.m. edt july 13, and observers are being asked to look for the first visibility of the moon on the following night
the observatory wants residents of the united states, canada, the caribbean and central america to begin looking for the new moon about 40 minutes after sunset july 14 and to record and report their results
persons willing to take part can get details by writing to ``looking for the moon,'' u.s. naval observatory, washington, d.c., 20392-5100
first moon sightings have been reported as early as 18 hours after new moon _ that time each month when the moon is completely obscured bu the earth blocking the sun's light. but such early sightings are considered extremely difficult
being able to pinpoint first visibility of the moon is important in several foreign cultures, the observatory reports. in islam, for instance, the end of one month and the beginning of the next occurs when the moon is first visible, and being able to predict that moment will help in preparing calendars
one of three men arrested on capital murder warrants in the shooting death of an off-duty police officer had previously pleaded guilty to an assault on another police officer and was on parole, authorities said
another of the men arrested was on parole after a robbery conviction
this is rather indicative of how the criminal justice system is working,'' capt. john holt said sunday
the officer's death was the seventh in six shootings involving police this year. in addition to three dead police officers, four civilians have been killed by police this year
vincent edward cooks, 23, was arrested sunday in houston, and tony ray harvey, 23, and tracy dewayne stallworth, 27, were arrested saturday, holt said at a news conference sunday
holt and lt. ron waldrop told reporters that other details of the arrests were not available because the investigation into the death of officer gary d. mccarthy was continuing
cooks began serving a five-year sentence in december 1986 and was paroled on aug. 4, 1987. he initially was charged with attempted capital murder of a police officer, but houston police sgt. v.w. west said cooks pleaded no contest in september 1985 to a reduced charge of aggravated assault
harvey was paroled jan. 18 after serving 18 months of a six-year sentence for aggravated robbery and unauthorized use of a motor vehicle, holt said
harvey was being held in lieu of $500,000 bond while bond was set at $300,000 for stallworth. cooks was to be returned to dallas from houston, said an officer who refused to give his name
former secretary of defense caspar w. weinberger is joining the law firm of rogers &amp; wells as a washington-based specialist in international law and finance, it was announced monday
the 275-lawyer firm is headed by former secretary of state william p. rogers
the announcement, issued by rogers &amp; wells' new york headquarters, said weinberger will not engage in any work involving the federal government, defense contracts or any other matters connected with the defense department
weinberger served as secretary of health, education and welfare and as budget director during the nixon administration. he was senior vice president and general counsel of bechtel corp. from 1975 until 1980, and became secretary of defense in 1981. he resigned from president reagan's cabinet late last year
the government has some sweet news for candy-loving poles: the rationing of chocolate will be lifted on tuesday
newspapers on monday printed an official announcement on the end of the rationing, but no explanation was given for the decision
under the rationing system, parents could only buy 7 ounces of chocolate a month for each child under 16 _ about two candy bars a month
adult chocolate-lovers did not receive a monthly ration for themselves
until now, the only recourse was to buy chocolate on the black market, in private shops or in government-run western currency stores for prices several times higher than the government-set price for polish-made chocolate products
meat is the only food product still rationed in poland. since introducing widespread food rationing in 1980-81, the government has gradually lifted restrictions on purchases of grain products, butter and cooking fats, alcohol, cigarettes and sugar. gasoline is still rationed for private car owners
three vehicles packed with people crashed on a rain-slickened highway monday, killing 25 people and injuring 26 others, authorities said
many of the victims were supporters of political candidates going to nakuru to see the office-seekers present papers for the march 21 general election
according to witnesses, one overcrowded pickup truck tried to pass another, but rammed into an oncoming minibus
the injured were taken to nakuru provincial general hospital, where 11 were admitted and 15 were treated and released
the accident occurred about 8 a.m. on a road outside nakuru, which is 100 miles northwest of nairobi
small covered pickup trucks and minibuses or vans are the most popular form of public transportation in kenya. the brightly colored vehicles, known as ``matatus,'' are criticized as deathtraps because of their overcrowding and reckless drivers
james g. radakovich liked to dance with his wife at the local serbian club and take care of his cadillac and his yard, said those who knew him
no one knows what led to the shootings saturday that claimed the life of radakovich, his wife and their sons, both college students. police say radakovich shot them dead and then himself
you never know what goes on inside a family,'' said richard grilli, a neighbor
something happened. he just cracked up,'' said joseph bergamasco, a police officer in this working-class pittsburgh suburb
mary radakovich, 57, was found on the livingroom floor. one son, james l., 21, was in his bed, and paul, 19, was on the floor of their bedroom
radakovich, 54, a retired steelworker, died of a single gunshot wound in the head and was found beside his younger son, authorities said. he had two notes in a pocket of his pajamas, one a will, the other burial instructions
the note said he was sorry for what he is doing, but possibly they would all be better off wherever they were going. but it gave no reason,'' said bergamasco
investigators found no signs of struggle
whether he was depressed, i don't know, but he didn't show it,'' said samuel budich, mrs. radakovich's brother
he was always a good husband to my sister,'' budich said. ``two weeks ago he was dancing the `colo' down at the narodi dom.''
the deaths were discovered after james' girlfriend alerted her father that all three family cars were parked at the home but no one was answering the door. police found two .22-caliber pistols, a revolver and an automatic
radakovich was laid off from the homestead works of usx corp. two years ago, and had a good pension, relatives said. he caddied at the oakmont country club for extra money
he took up golf when he was laid off,'' said grilli. ``he'd have a beer now and then, but i never saw him drunk. he took care of his house and his lawn. he was nice, quiet.''
northern africa and the sahel region are facing the threat of an invasion by desert locusts that could cause widespread destruction of crops and pastures, a u.n. group reported monday
about 2.5 million acres have been infested in northern mauritania, said the u.n. food and agriculture organization, which issued an appeal to international donors for two spraying aircraft and 39,000 gallons of pesticide
successful control of infestations in northern mauritania would greatly reduce the risks of substantial invasion of morocco and algeria to the north and of the sahel zone to the south,'' the fao said in its appeal
major control efforts have been under way in morocco and several other countries in the past several months, the fao said
small infestations have also been detected in sudan, near the red sea coast, but these are under control, it added. picks up 2nd graf, `both the ...'</note>
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar, opening an emergency session of the general assembly today, urged the united states not to close the u.n. mission of the palestine liberation organization and to respect the united nations
this question has immediate and profound importance for the united nations,'' he said as the 159-member assembly reconvened a three-day session to condemn the u.s. plan to close the plo mission under a new anti-terrorist law
the plo is an invitee of the united nations and the united states is obliged by its u.n. headquarters agreement to permit accredited plo personnel to enter and remain in the u.s. and carry out their official functions,'' the u.n. chief said
perez de cuellar said he hoped the united states could reconcile its domestic legislation with its international obligations
both the state department and the united nations say the new anti-terrorism law that would close the mission by march 22 violates the 1947 headquarters agreement between the united states and the united nations. it allows all missions to operation
still, the justice department reportedly intends to go ahead and order the mission closed, although legal maneuvering is expected to keep the mission open for as long as a year
twenty-two speakers, including the plo ambassador and the envoys of the soviet union, jordan, egypt and syria, were to speak today before the assembly
in the unusual session, the united states, the largest u.n. contributor, was expected to be lectured and rebuked by the world body, which recognizes the plo
the head of the u.n. arab group said sunday that if the united states insists on closing the legal plo mission, operating under international treaty, then the general assembly should vote to leave new york and relocate in geneva
i don't exclude any idea of shifting the general assembly, the security council and other key bodies dealing with the middle east, if the u.s. goes ahead with closure,'' said ambassador karim ebrahim al-shakar of bahrain
i would hope it will not reach that point,'' he said. ``but that depends on the will and good intention of the host country, the united states.''
without the plo, recognized as the legitimate u.n. representative of the palestinian people, the united nations cannot hold discussions on the middle east, said the bahrain envoy, head of the 21-nation arab group
most other diplomats and the plo said it was unlikely that the united nations would leave new york
the three-day session is expected to approve resolutions calling on the united states to allow the 13-year-old plo mission to operate, as legally required by treaty with the united nations. it also may seek a ruling against the united states by the international court of justice
the state department and u.n. lawyers both say the plan to shut the plo mission under a new anti-terrorist law is illegal and violates the 1947 headquarters agreement between the united states and the united nations
u.s. prestige and influence at the united nations are at an all-time low over the reagan administration's withholding of more than $250 million in u.n. budget dues. the united states has also sided with israel and south africa on key issues
the united states is the largest u.n. contributor, paying about one-quarter of the annual budget of $800 million. but the united states has failed to pay its dues because congress has not appropriated full funding. american critics say the organization is inefficient and biased against the united states
matt and ben kearney did more homework, read more books and spent more time with their parents while facing the ultimate challenge, an entire year without television
it came to a festive end at a family party when their father, lawyer mike kearney, handed each boy a packet of 10 $50 bills tied up in a red ribbon and then turned the television set back on at 7:30 p.m. thursday
it feels real weird,'' said 9-year-old matt, flipping channels quickly between the olympics, ``jeopardy'' and ``magnum p.i.'' ``it feels like i'm not supposed to be doing it.''
kearney got the idea about the year without television when he read about a new jersey boy whose mother offered him $500 to turn off the set for a year
every day they'd get up in the morning and watch tv until they went to school,'' kearney said. ``then they'd come home and watch it the rest of the day. on weekends they'd watch it until their ... eyes bugged out.''
it took the two brothers about ``two seconds'' to take their father up on the challenge, ben, 11, said
the first days were the hardest. ``the first night we sort of played more and then went to bed,'' ben said. ``and then the next morning we got up and thought, `what are we going to watch?' and then we remembered we couldn't.''
their mother, shannon kearney, saw the project as an exercise in self control. the rest of the family, including 5-year-old patrick, had continued watching television
the boys plan to spend part of their money on a home video game and save the rest
a graduate of texas a&amp;m, whose alumni are dubbed aggies and are the butt of some farming jokes in texas, has some of his fields under water and dumps hay on them, leading some anonymous wag to proclaim it an ``aggie hay farm.''
but john gaulding, 41, is not trying to grow hay. he's feeding crawfish
gaulding farms about 1,200 acres about 60 miles east of houston and leases about 300 acres to people who raise the freshwater crustaceans, especially popular in cajun cuisine
he said he didn't appreciate it when a sign with the message ``aggie hay farm'' mysteriously appeared in front of his land in october
at first, it seemed like a harmless prank,'' gaulding said sunday. ``i had no idea who did it. i don't know if they really even knew that it was a crawfish farm.''
we left it up for a couple of days. people were asking us to leave it up, and there was so much talk, finally we decided we would,'' he said. ``i figured if a&amp;m could win the cotton bowl, i could put up with a little kidding about it.''
pain and punishment are more than mere agenda items to armando valladares, a human rights ambassador with a resume written by two decades of imprisonment
valladares is the chief u.s. delegate to the u.n. human rights commission. he is among the delegates from 43 nations who are meeting here to discuss human rights violations
but as a political prisoner in cuba for 22 years, he is far from a typical ambassador
when he talks about torture, he points to broken bones that never healed quite right. when he talks about prison life, he displays scars left on his hands by hungry rats
when he discusses desperation, he can recall being denied pens and pencils in prison, and writing a poem in his blood
when the topic is cruelty, he talks about forgiveness
i do not hate anyone,'' he said, ``not even those who tortured me, because i think that hatred kills the person who feels it. i would say ultimately that those years were a struggle between love and hatred and love always triumphs.''
valladares, 50, a u.s. citizen for slightly more than a year, is his country's latest weapon in a struggle to get the commission to discuss alleged human rights violations in cuba
in an interview with the associated press, valladares said the effort is a struggle ``against a selective sensitivity'' in the commission, which routinely condemns human rights violations in israeli-occupied territories, south africa and chile
but his appointment as chief u.s. delegate session has angered the cuban government, which denounces valladares as an impostor who never was tortured or paralyzed during his prison tenure
valladares is a slightly built man with intense eyes under a shock of dark hair just beginning to turn gray. he is the father of two boys, one 3 and one nearly 2, and the husband of a woman he met in prison when she came to visit her father. they were married behind bars
he was just 23 when he was sentenced to a 30-year term for what he says were anti-communist remarks. in a book about his experiences, ``against all hope,'' he said prisoners were systematically tortured and denied proper medical care
he said at one point, following a 46-day hunger strike in 1974, he developed polyneuropathy, a nervous system deterioration that confined him to a wheelchair for five years
at that time he began writing poetry and smuggling it out of prison to his wife, martha, then living in the united states, he said
he won his freedom in october 1982 after french president francois mitterrand intervened in his case. just a month after obtaining u.s. citizenship, he was added to the u.s. human rights delegation
the chief cuban delegate, raul roa kouri, told a news conference that valladares' book was ``full of lies.''
the cuban government held similar news conferences in washington and mexico city and distributed pamphlets rejecting what it said were lies by the state department about valladares' past
it is an attack against me, a man, because they cannot refute the violations of human rights that are happening in their country,'' responds valladares
although his mother and sister live in miami, his 77-year-old father remains in cuba
he lives in the center of the island and often the authorities tell him to pack all his things because he is leaving cuba. then he travels all the way to havana and they tell him it was an error,'' said valladares
he said his father also is denied treatment for an eye ailment that has left him nearly blind
i think that the cuban government is moving this way against him thinking perhaps that i will change my attitude. i will not do that,'' he said
what he does do is bring a dramatic air of realism to the commission
speaking recently on torture, valladares said: ``i remember when they had me in a punishment cell, naked, my leg fractured in several places _ fractures that were never treated and eventually fused into a mass of deformed bones
through the wire mesh that covered the cell, the guards would pour over me buckets of urine and excrement that they had collected earlier.''
international condemnation of such acts, he said ``is the only thing capable of pressuring the torturers.''
authorities said today that a small wooden boat carrying illegal aliens from the dominican republic sank in rough seas off the west coast of puerto rico. a survivor was quoted as saying more than 40 people were aboard
elmer hasker, deputy district director for the immigration and naturalization service in san juan, said one illegal alien was in ins custody, another hospitalized, two bodies had been recovered and another had been spotted but washed away before it could be retrieved
one of the two known survivors ``has stated that there were approximately 40 people on the boat,'' hasker said in a telephone interview in san juan. ``we don't know anything about their situation ... whether they drowned or made it to shore is unknown at this point.''
the boat sank during the weekend off aguada, about 85 miles west of the capital san juan. at the time, the seas were very rough and it was very windy
in a telephone interview from aguada, police spokeswoman evelyn crespo said a survivor told authorities there were 45 people on the boat, including 37 men and eight women
police said the two bodies were of two girls, one 14, the other 16
ms. crespo said one of the survivors reported the group left from the province of higuey, on the southeastern tip of the dominican republic, early saturday. the survivors were rescued around 10 p.m. sunday, she said
there was no information available on why the boat sank. hasker said the boat apparently sank sunday night
the boat has washed ashore so it was close enough that it didn't disintegrate,'' hasker said
estimates on the length of the boat ranged from 20 to 30 feet
this morning a vessel from the commonwealth maritime police searched the waters off aguada for survivors and bodies, and ins and local officials searched the land, ins border patrol agent luis garcia in a telephone interview from aguadilla, about five miles from aguada
garcia said some clothes had been found along the beach in aguada but there was no way of knowing whether they belonged to those aboard the boat that sank
in october, as many as 100 dominicans are believed to have died when their boat sank about three miles off the north east coast of the dominican republic as they started their journey to puerto rico
hundreds of dominicans leave their country each year in wooden boats to make the dangerous crossing to puerto rico, where they hope to find jobs and a better life
the supreme court today agreed to decide whether employees of a pentagon intelligence agency are entitled to administrative hearings when they are fired as security risks
the justices said they will hear reagan administration arguments that those who work for the national security agency are not entitled to such procedural protection
the case raises issues similar to those in a case decided tuesday by the high court
in that ruling, the court said the merit systems protection board _ which provides job protection to federal workers _ lacks authority to reinstate an employee fired for lacking a security clearance. the court upheld the firing of a laborer at a navy installation
in the case acted on today, the justices will review a ruling that granted an administrative hearing to an unidentified nsa employee who said he was fired because he engaged in homosexual activities
the employee, identified only as john doe, works with secret codes for the spy agency
he told his superiors in 1982 that he had homosexual relations with several foreigners during vacation travels abroad
after a psychiatric evaluation, the nsa _in a decision upheld by the defense secretary _ ordered him fired on grounds his ``indiscriminate'' sexual activities posed a security risk since he had access in his job to the most secret type of classified information. the agency said the fact the acts were homosexual was not the determining factor
doe then filed a federal court suit, claiming the department of defense violated a federal civil service law entitling him to an administrative hearing
the u.s. circuit court of appeals agreed with him in a ruling last june
the appeals court said, ``as the government acknowledges, in this case the (defense) secretary has not found that a hearing would itself contravene national security. accordingly, (doe) is entitled by law to that hearing.''
caspar weinberger was secretary of defense at the time of doe's firing. since then, he has been succeeded by frank carlucci
the case is carlucci vs. doe, 87-751
president p.w. botha suggested monday that his government might comply with a demand by some british lawmakers that the union jack be removed from the south african flag
members of all three main parties in britain's parliament, citing botha's latest crackdown on black oppositon, urged their government on saturday to request that a replica of the british flag be removed from the south african flag
the union jack and the flags of two south african provinces are displayed in the center of south africa's flag as symbols of the country's past
the flag of south africa not only relates to our history but is indeed a symbol of national unity and nationhood,'' botha said. ``it is surprising that the agitation against the south african flag from britain is not taking into consideration the feelings of the english-speaking south africans.''
but if the british government wishes to interfere with the composition of a south africa symbol on this basis, the question may be asked whether the south african parliament should not give this matter its serious attention.''
designed 60 years ago, the south african flag was intended to show how the country was formed by a merger of british-controlled territory and the former afrikaner republics of transvaal and the orange free state. the mainly dutch-descended afrikaners make up about 60 percent of the 5 million whites, while most of the others have british ancestry
the british and afrikaners battled each in the boer war that ended in 1902, and strains between the two still surface
former soviet dissident natan sharansky, who immigrated to israel in 1986 after serving nine years in a soviet prison, has begun basic military training, an associate said monday
sharansky reported sunday to a military base near tel aviv for three weeks of training, said yuri stern, a spokesman for the soviet jewry information center, a private lobbying group
sharansky, 40, will join israel's civil guard, rather than the regular army, because of his age and poor health, said stern
civil guard members serve in israel, and their duties include patrolling population centers and guarding holy sites, such as the western wall, the last remnant of the second jewish temple destroyed by the romans in 70 a.d
like all israeli men, sharansky will be called up for several weeks of reserve duty once a year, stern said
stern said sharansky was ``proud to fulfill his duty of defending the country.''
however, stern added, sharansky ``will be no more than a private in the army, while his true battlefield is the campaign for the release of soviet jews. that's where he is a general.''
since coming to israel, sharansky spent most of his time studying hebrew, lecturing on the plight of soviet jews and writing his memoirs, stern said
sharansky, one of the soviet union's most prominent dissidents, served nine years in a soviet jail on espionage charges. he was freed in february 1986 in an east-west spy swap after his wife, avital, campaigned for his release throughout the west
two nuns are suing the nephew of their mother superior, claiming he embezzled their community property and holy relics
the lawsuit was filed in el paso county district court on behalf of the carmelite monastery of the sacred hearts, an independent community no longer recognized by the roman catholic church. named as defendant was jose de la luz sanchez of albuquerque, n.m., who once was the nuns' legal conservator
i'm not worried because none of that is true,'' said sanchez, 65. ``every time they ran out of money they sure knew who to call. i never refused them because, frankly, my wife and i have no kids and they're all we have.''
the lawsuit filed last week accuses sanchez, who is retired from new mexico's highway department, of theft, fraud and breach of fiduciary duty
it says he transferred the sisters' community assets, including a $150,000 promissory note, to his own name; that he took items such as the nuns' car, wheelbarrow and organ; and that he told the nuns he was looking after them for free but ``billed the community thousands of dollars for his time.''
mr. sanchez has gone so far as to deprive the nuns of their chalices, monstrance and holy relics,'' according to the complaint filed by two denver lawyers, roger p. thomasch and mark wielga, who have never met the sisters in person
the nuns, who follow religious vows that permit little contact with outsiders, declined comment
sanchez is the nephew of mother helen chavez, 79, the leader of the community, and mother agnes chavez, 86, who live in albuquerque
the suit was filed by mother josephine florence, 76, and sister theresa schull, 79, who apparently have separated from sanchez's aunts and are struggling to establish themselves in colorado springs
since the late 1970s, the suit says, the nuns have lived in three states while searching for a permanent home. they left burnet, texas, in 1978 for bryan, texas. later they moved to gallup, n.m., and to albuquerque. then they moved to colorado springs
the two nuns living in albuquerque are in nursing homes and receive some social security
the nuns follow the rules of the larger discalced nuns of the order of our blessed lady of mount carmel, but their group is no longer affiliated with the larger order, said bishop jerome hastrich of gallup, n.m
he said they were ordered by the vatican to disband several years ago
they didn't have unity,'' said hastrich. ``the mother was about 80, and she was unable to control the group. about half were in their 70s and 80s, and half were quite young.''
he found other homes for about 16 nuns, but said the four elders refused to separate from the community
