a salvage crew continued pumping oil today from an upside-down barge that was raised one month after it sank in guemes channel and spilled about 70,000 gallons of heavy bunker oil into inland waters
after the delicate lifting procedure sunday, the inverted barge was held at the surface by cables strung from two cranes as crews began pumping the remaining 344,000 gallons of oil aboard into a second barge
coast guard officials said this morning that one compartment of the oil barge contained mostly water, raising the possibility that more oil leaked than previously thought
it appears the structural integrity of the tank may be breached,'' said coast guard lt. eldo delong
coast guard guard chief petty officer roy compton said that as oil was pumped out of the barge's six tanks, air would be pumped in until the barge floated on its own
as of 8:40 a.m., an estimated 68,976 gallons had been pumped out of the damaged barge
a small oil sheen marked the spot where the barge surfaced sunday morning. mark stewart of the state division of emergency management said roughly 500 to 1,000 gallons of lightweight oil had spilled
surface skimmer boats had cleaned up about 160 gallons, while absorbent pads collected more of the spill, he said
most of the barge's cargo is heavier-than-water bunker oil
state ecology department spokesman ats kiuchi said it appeared the fragile, inner coastal environment had avoided a disaster
we're dealing with a lot of unknowns here. it's like mount st. helens erupting; you use the best estimate you can get. but it (the lift) was smooth,'' he said
the barge, operated by olympic tug and barge of seattle, sank jan. 31 in about 130 feet of water four miles west of anacortes and about 100 yards off shannon point. it had been loaded at an oil refinery at anacortes and was being towed by to seattle when it began listing and capsized
after resting with its stern on the bottom and the bow breaking the surface for about a week, the vessel dropped all the way to the bottom
on thursday, the coast guard assumed financial responsibility for the salvage because olympic was unable to obtain pollution liability coverage. compton said harley franco, olympic president, would be billed for the salvage costs. picks up 3rd graf pvs ``tehran radio..</note>
iran said it fired three missiles into the iraqi capital of baghdad before dawn today and iraq said two missiles crashed into residential areas, killing many civilians
twelve hours later, iran's official media reported iraqi warplanes bombed residential districts of tehran and hit a hospital. iran's islamic republic news agency, monitored in nicosia, said 16 people were killed at the hospital and ``dozens wounded, including newborn babies.''
tehran radio, also monitored in nicosia, urged iranians to take refuge in recently built bomb shelters. it was the second time the iraqis have bombed tehran in three days
the turkish anatolia news agency said one bomb exploded 300 yards from a downtown hotel where state minister yusuf ozal of turkey was staying with an official delegation led by prime minister turgut ozal, his brother
there were no reports of turkish casualties
earlier today, baghdad's official iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, quoted a military spokesman as saying iranian artillery also shelled residential areas of the embattled southern port of basra and the border town of khanaqin, 80 miles northeast of baghdad during the night. he made no mention of casualties
it was the third straight day of attacks on cities and industrial centers by the two persian gulf war foes, beginning when iraqi warplanes bombed tehran on saturday for the first time in months
the attacks heightened fears that the two nations had begun another round of the so-called ``war of the cities'' that started in march 1985
in other action, iran claimed kurdish guerrillas and revolutionary guards killed or wounded 350 iraqis on sunday in fighting in northeast iraq
iran's official islamic republic news agency, quoting a military communique, said kurdish guerrillas beat back an assault by iraqi special forces on positions in erbil province, killing or wounding 250 men
the agency said iranian revolutionary guards killed or wounded another 100 iraqis in a bombardment of iraqi positions in the mountainous kurdistan region. irna, monitored in nicosia, said revolutionary guards gunners fired the three surface-to-surface missiles at the baghdad headquarters of iraq's state-run television and radio network and ``two military targets'' in baghdad
irna said the iranians fired the missiles in retaliation for iraqi air raids ``on non-military areas'' in tehran, the kurdish city of saqqez in northwest iran, dezful in southwest khuzestan province, and the western city of hamadan in recent days
it said 28 civilians were killed in those raids, with scores more wounded
the communique warned ``the iraqi government that its renewed attacks on civilian areas will not go unanswered,'' irna reported
baghdad radio did not identify the baghdad residential districts it said were hit by the missiles, believed to be soviet-made, scud-b weapons supplied to iran by libya and syria
the explosions were heard across the city of 5 million
many iraqis were killed, among them women, children and old people. many more were wounded and many houses were destroyed,'' the communique said. no exact casualty figures were given
the radio quoted an unidentified military spokesman as warning: ``all iranian cities are now targets for our air and missile forces until further notice. the losers in the end will be the rulers in tehran.''
the missiles were the first to hit the iraqi capital since nov. 8. the iranians have fired eight missiles into the city since the u.n. security council called for a cease-fire in the 7-year-old war on july 20 last year
altogether, iran has fired 37 missiles into baghdad since march 1985, when the two sides began the ``war of the cities.''
thousands of civilians on both sides have been killed or wounded in the intermittent campaigns involving air raids, missiles and long-range artillery bombardments. in one of the worst missile attacks, more than 30 children were killed and more than 100 wounded when their school was hit oct. 13
tehran's war information headquarters said iranian warplanes on sunday bombed a petrochemical plant in the southern iraqi port of basra, oil installations in abul khassib in the southeast and a bridge linking iraq with umm rassas island in the shatt al-arab waterway
baghdad said long-range iranian artillery shelled six border towns and cities saturday and sunday, killing and wounding an undisclosed number of civilians
baghdad radio said iraqi warplanes later sunday bombed hamadan in eastern iran and dezful in the southeast in retaliation for ``recent atrocities and crimes committed by the charlatans of iran.'' applicants</head>
here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken monday by the supreme court

drug tests

the court agreed to consider barring the u.s. customs service from conducting drug tests for people seeking drug-enforcement jobs, setting the stage for its first ruling on the constitutionality of mandatory drug-testing for public employees
the court said it will hear a challenge to the testing program by a federal workers labor union that says taking urine samples from employees violates their privacy rights
the case is national treasury employees union vs. von raab, 86-1879

atomic tests

the court refused to revive lawsuits charging the government and federal contrctors with negligently causing deaths and disease among people exposed to open-air atomic tests
the court, without comment, let stand a federal law that effectively spared the government from having to defend itself against claims seeking billions of dollars
the case is konizski vs. livermore labs, 87-953

medicare

the court agreed to consider letting the federal government apply retroactively a formula that limits reimbursement paid to hospitals treating medicare patients
the court said it will hear reagan administraion arguments that some hospitals could reap a windfall from the ban on retroactive application of the formula
the case is bowen vs. georgetown university hospital, 87-1097

embassy documents

the court let stand rulings that threw out a reporter's attempt to force the state department to release documents from u.s. embassies around the world
the lawsuit by donald f. goldberg, a reporter on the staff of syndicated columnist jack anderson, had been filed under the freedom of information act. he had sought from the state department responses to an unclassified 1982 questionnaire on foreign governments' diplomatic practices
the case is goldberg vs. state department, 87-655

bingo

the court asked the reagan administration whether it thinks high-stakes bingo games run by indian tribes are subject to state sales taxes
the court said it wants to hear from justice department lawyers before it says whether it will review an attempt by oklahoma officials to tax revenue from a bingo game in tulsa run by the muscogee creek nation
the case is oklahoma tax commission vs. muscogee creek nation, 87-1068

security risks

the court agreed to decide whether employees of a pentagon intelligence agency are entitled to administrative hearings when the government fires them as security risks
the justices said they will hear reagan administration arguments that those who work for the national security agency are not entitled to such procedural protection
the case is carlucci vs. doe, 87-751

paternity

the court agreed to decide whether states may block a man from trying to prove he fathered the child of a woman married to someone else
the court said it will study a challenge by a man identified in court records only as michael h., to a state evidentiary rule creating a conclusive presumption of fatherhood to a wife's husband
the case is michael h. vs. gerald d., 87-746

hi-fi killings

the court let stand the conviction of a man sentenced to death in utah for his role in the 1974 killings of three people forced to swallow drain cleaner before they were shot
the justices let stand william andrews' conviction and death sentence for the three murders committed during an aril 22, 1974 robbery of an ogden hi-fi store
the case is andrews vs. shulsen, 87-5449

racetrack searches

the court let stand rulings that warrantless searches of illinois racetrack employees' on-grounds living quarters violate constitutionally protected privacyrights
the illinois racing board for years had authorized state law enforcement officers to search, without warrants, the rooms of employees who feed, groom, exercise and generally take care of racehorses
the case is arkansas vs. mayfield, 87-1105
michael dukakis walked aboard his chartered jet with a smile on his face. ``they don't know what a frappe is here in texas,'' he said, ``but i got one.''
dukakis didn't come all the way from the gold-domed statehouse in boston to the heart of texas for the thick milkshake that every soda jerk in new england knows how to make
but if he can find one in the land where lyndon johnson once reigned, can the massachusetts liberal also find enough votes to establish himself as a democratic presidential candidate of nationwide appeal?
with 1,307 democratic national convention delegates at stake on march 8, a festival of 20 primaries and caucuses with a southern flavor known as super tuesday, his aides concede it's a challenge
outside south florida i wouldn't call it hostility, but there's a skepticism about mike dukakis,'' says s. stephen rosenfeld, who left his statehouse job in massachusetts to organize in florida for the governor
while dukakis periodically insists that he's competing ``in every state'' on super tuesday, he is targeting his appeal to liberals, labor workers and retirees, and reminding voters everywhere that he is the son of greek immigrants
dukakis and his aides carefully avoid saying that he must carry even a single southern state to succeed on march 8, and say they are concentrating on winning as many delegates as possible
much of his time and campaign budget is focused in areas of texas, florida, north carolina and georgia. like other democratic rivals, he is virtually conceding the region's large black vote to jesse jackson
dukakis has made subtle changes in the campaign message that earned him a respectable third place in iowa and victories in new hampshire and minnesota. he no longer emphasizes his opposition to president reagan's support for the contras in nicaragua. and to demonstrate toughness in an area that likes it, he is suggesting he might authorize strikes against terrorist base camps in an effort to deal with hostage problems in the middle east
he also showed a combative side in last saturday's debate, repeatedly challenging rep. richard gephardt to say whether he was proud of his vote in favor of the 1981 reaganomics tax bill and questioning sen. albert gore jr.'s credentials for the white house
he still trumpets his record of nine balanced budgets as governor of massachusetts as the centerpiece of his campaign and calls for ``real jobs at real wages.''
dukakis is ready to run commercials attacking gephardt if campaign officials decide it is necessary. ``one of the things that you can't do is to try to make yourself into something you're not,'' dukakis said in an interview. ``he's got a record, and the record is there for all to see.''
for the next week dukakis is targeting his time, money and resources in a hectic southern effort to prove his appeal outside his northern, liberal base. hundreds of delegates are at stake
the governor and his aides also hope he can win the maryland primary (67 delegates at stake) and the washington caucuses (65) on the same day, to go with a rousing victory at home in massachusetts (98) and rhode island (22)
dukakis' aides say they hope he can win delegates in 110 of the 171 congressional districts voting on march 8 and hope for 350 or so delegates overall
they believe that would put dukakis in the lead for nominating delegates just as the campaign heads for the industrial states where he should feel more at home
if we can move out of super tuesday with a good total of delegates i think we will be clearly established,'' he said in an interview as his jet carried him from austin to atlanta, ga
largely bypassing the conservative vote in deepest dixie, dukakis is concentrating on south florida, where the population has been swelled in recent years by droves of cold-weather refugees. he also will make an effort in central florida and campaign extensively in texas, whose 183 delegates make it the biggest single prize on march 8
this emphasis is seen by the decision of where to have dukakis campaign personally and where to advertise on television. the first wave of ads were aired in south florida and parts of texas, as well as baltimore
barring changes in the schedule, dukakis will campaign in areas around atlanta, competing for a fraction of georgia's 77 delegates, and in targeted areas of north carolina (82 delegates)
don't look for the man with the new england accent and the wing-tipped shoes to spend much time, if any, in alabama, mississippi, louisiana, oklahoma, virginia and kentucky. he'll leave tennessee and missouri to favorite sons gore and gephardt
we'll do well by winning delegates in a lot of congressional districts,'' says senior campaign aide leslie dach. since most delegates are awarded on the basis of the vote within congressional districts, a candidate can score by campaigning in one region of a state and ignoring another
thus, in a state like florida or texas, he might not pull enough votes statewide to be a winner, but he could leave with plenty of delegates
an eight-day-old baby girl born with almost no brain died one day after she was taken off a respirator used to preserve her organs for transplant, hospital officials said today
evelyn keys died peacefully sunday night, said dr. joyce peabody, chief of neonatology at loma linda university medical center
her heart valves, eyes and corneas have been donated. the parents are saddened, but still very pleased their daughter could give some gift of life,'' ms. peabody said in a statement
a previous statement released by the hospital during the early morning hours today had said the baby was still alive, but ms. peabody said the baby had died at 10:35 p.m. sunday
the infant with the usually fatal birth defect called anencephaly was part of a novel organ donor program at loma linda university medical center to use the hearts and livers of such babies once they are legally declared brain-dead
loma linda has developed the nation's first guidelines for using such infants as organ donors
the hospital, 65 miles east of los angeles, is known for its frequent infant heart transplants. thirteen babies have received new hearts at the center, with nine surviving
baby evelyn never met the hospital's critieria for brain death, however, and was taken off life-support systems with parental approval saturday, ms. peabody said
the infant continued to breath on her own and received feedings by mouth until she died, said hospital spokeswoman anita rockwell
on saturday, ms. peabody said the baby girl was breathing but was already showing ``signs of gradual deterioration.''
the hospital uses life support systems on until babies are brain dead in order to maintain organs until they can be used. anencephalic babies are connected to respirators soon after birth, and doctors then monitor their abilities to breathe on their own
if they can't breathe by themselves they are declared brain dead before any organ deterioration caused by oxygen loss occurs
if they continue to breathe on their own, slow deterioration eventually makes their organs unsuitable for transplants, ms. rockwell said
evelyn was born feb. 20 in san antonio, texas, to judy keys, 22, and airman todd keys, 21, of the 6993rd electronic security squad at lackland air force base. the infant was flown to loma linda that same day to be used in the donor program
colorado's first experiment with high-oxygen fuels ended monday, without the epidemic of clogged fuel injectors and stalled cars predicted by opponents of the smog-control program
we were very surprised _ we thought there'd be more consumer backlash,'' said jerry levine of amoco corp. in chicago. levine had opposed the mandatory program in hearings last year before colorado's air quality commission
it will be another month, however, before state officials know whether the experiment reduced levels of carbon monoxide along the eastern slope of the rockies
at the city's mile-high altitude, ordinary gasoline burns incompletely and the unexpended fuel emitted into the air adds to the pollution which frequently robs denverites of their mountain views
gasoline suppliers plan to switch back to traditional gasoline without oxygenated additives sometime in march, but oxygenated fuels will be back in the service stations nov. 1, when next season's four-month program begins
since jan. 1, colorado motorists have been able to buy only high-oxygen blended fuels, either ether-based mtbe or corn-based ethanol. state officials predicted the program would reduce carbon monoxide levels by at least 8 percent this year
oil company executives and car mechanics predicted highways would be littered with stalled cars and repair shops overflowing with clogged fuel injectors and other mechanical ailments
there have been no major problems,'' said state air pollution control specialist kim livo. ``the actual program probably has relieved a lot of concerns people might have had before it started.''
the more skeptical agree
the negative effects on our cars have been fairly minimal,'' said bmw service manager mike palmieri at ralph schomp oldsmobile, honda and bmw in littleton. mechanics at the dealership had predicted they would be flooded with complaints of vapor lock, and drying and cracking fuel lines and injector seals
i think everybody including us guys here are willing to put up with some minor inconveniences to clean up denver's air _ we live here too,'' palmieri said
he said he thought the fuels reduced mileage by about 5 percent; livo denied the fuels had any effect on mileage
oil companies also had predicted consumers would be stuck with the blended fuels all year, because it would be too expensive for suppliers to switch fuels twice a year
now, total petroleum, amoco and conoco say they plan to stop selling the oxy-fuels when the program ends and current supplies run out
levine said the blended fuels cost amoco about three cents extra per gallon, though the additional price was offset this year by a drop in gasoline prices overall
both levine and palmieri remained skeptical about next year's program. they said colorado's transition to oxygenated fuels was smooth only because mtbe still accounted for 95 percent to 98 percent of the market
that balance probably will change next year when the oxy-fuels program is expanded to four months, and the required oxygen level rises from 1.5 percent to 2 percent
oil companies favor mtbe because it has been used as an octane enhancer since the early 1980s, said levine
oil companies and many dealers have recommended mtbe as being safer than ethanol, although the big three u.s. auto makers and many import manufacturers have said their cars can be adjusted either to mtbe or ethanol blends at the 2 percent oxygen level
ethanol producers and state officials say the corn-based product got a bad rap in denver three summers ago when a batch of low-quality gasohol hit the area. since then, they say, state regulations have ensured a higher-quality blend
state officials have been adamant about securing ethanol a place in the air quality program and giving consumers a choice of oxy-fuels. livo said the air quality control commission will review the program this spring and make its final recommendations for next year
whatever the commission decides, levine said, ``we'll accept it. we'll live with it.''
the oxy fuels program targeted the 1.6 million people living in the front range from colorado springs north to fort collins. because oil companies could not deliver oxygenated fuels through their pipelines just to this area, however, nearly all of colorado and part of wyoming _ more than 2 million people _ wound up switching fuels
israelis in this communal farm expressed shock monday over the arrest of one young member in the beating of two arabs, but they said government policy in the occupied territories placed soldiers in an untenable position
sgt. saguy harpaz, a gesher resident, was detained in the communal dining hall friday night after a cbs news videotape showed that he and three other soldiers beat two bound arab protesters with rocks for more than half an hour in nablus
people who saw the film were shocked,'' said catherine gur, 38, who taught harpaz in elementary school. ``it was very brutal. he did not act according to the values we impart on our children.''
ms. gur and other kibbutz residents held defense minister yitzhak rabin responsible, saying his announced policy of beating arab rioters instead of shooting them has confused troops
ms. gur said harpaz, 20, joined the army because of ``an ideal to serve the country and to defend the country.'' but she said rabin's policy had taught him ``to beat up women and children.''
harpaz and the other three soldiers were arrested and their deputy unit commander, a captain, was suspended. the four will be tried by a military court. the two arabs were ordered released
on monday, harpaz was released into the custody of his parents. wearing his uniform, he sat in the small living room of his parents' garden apartment, drinking coffee. he was surrounded by a dozen relatives and friends
i'm happy he's out,'' said his mother, amalia. ``but i'm angry about what happened to him. he seems to have changed over the past few weeks. it was an unfair responsibility to have been placed on such young shoulders.''
they make my son into a murderer,'' his father, yossi, told the yediot ahronot newspaper. ``saguy isn't violent by nature. he grew up in this kibbutz and was educated with values.''
harpaz's arrest prompted intense soul-searching in gesher, where 600 israelis live within view of jordan 80 miles north of jerusalem, and in other kibbutzim, which are traditional bastions of liberalism and patriotism
kibbutzniks are considered the backbone of the army, with disproportionately large numbers volunteering for combat units and serving as officers
kibbutzim were founded on the ideas of equality, self-sacrifice and socialist principles. they have produced many of the country's left-wing leaders
how israel quells unrest in the occupied territories ``has become a question for the whole kibbutz society,'' absorption minister yacov tzur, himself a kibbutznik, said monday during a meeting of the united kibbutz movement
we know we are sending our children to do a very difficult task that cannot be compared to anything we did in the past,'' he said
former defense minister ariel sharon accused army leaders of responding to the case with hysteria. he criticized officers who arrested ``a soldier, a fighter, in his kibbutz, in the dinning hall, and took him from the bosom of his family.''
ms. gur said six gesher members serve in the army in the west bank and gaza strip. ``it's hard to speak to them about what they do because they are ashamed, just ashamed,'' she said
unlike in the past, many of gesher's young people are no longer eager to serve, she said
added harpaz's 19-year-old brother, chen, who will join the army thursday: ``i have zero motivation. if that's the way the country treats its soldiers, i don't want to be a part of it.''
ms. gur said kibbutz education stresses the values of tolerance and acceptance of other ethnic groups. however, she said, the only arabs most kibbutz children come in contact with are laborers building homes or picking up garbage
she described harpaz as an intelligent youth with a ``rough exterior. but underneath he's still quite sensitive, a child.'' she noted that he wrote his final essay in high school on democracy
gesher is nestled in rolling hills south of the sea of galilee. its members grow cotton, mine gypsum and produce magnets and ceramic wares. conflict between armenia, azerbaidzhan. picks up 7th graf pvs ``an official at... '' corrects soveit union to russian republic in next-to-the-last graf.</note>
rioting broke out in an industrial city in azerbaidzhan, the tass news agency reported today. a dissident said the violence was sparked by tensions between armenians and azerbaidzhan's dominant ethnic group, the azeris
the tass report said the disturbances sunday in sumgait, a city on the caspian sea, were provoked by ``a group of hooligans,'' and ``rampage and violence followed.'' the agency said measures were adopted ``to normalize the situation.''
the official soviet agency gave no indication what led to the violence
armenians in huge numbers took to the streets last week in their capital, yerevan, to demand that a region of azerbaidzhan that has a largely armenian population be made part of their republic
of sunday's violence in sumgait, a city some 1,500 miles from moscow, dissident sergei grigoryants said: ``thugs in sumgait went up to people and asked them if they were armenian or not. they started to beat people who said they were armenians. several people were knifed.''
grigoryants, who lives in moscow but is of armenian origin, said it appeared that no one was killed in sumgait. he said ``several dozen'' azeris were reportedly involved in the attacks
grigoryants said by telephone that he received his information on the unrest from sources in yerevan
tass said an investigation has been launched into the violence at sumgait
the four-paragraph tass dispatch gave only sketchy details of the violence and did not say whether there had been deaths or injuries. the report did not say who was involved in the unrest or say what caused the violence
an official at the azerbaidzhani government's offices in moscow contacted today by telephone refused to give any details of the unrest
everything will be printed in the central press and shown on television,'' said the official, who refused to give his name
telephone calls placed from moscow to baku, the azerbaidzhani capital 20 miles southeast of sumgait, did not immediately go through
sumgait, with a population of more than 160,000, is the second largest city in azerbaidzhan after the capital. sumgait is 150 miles from the autonomous region of nagorno-karabakh, which is at the center of a dispute between armenia and azerbaidzhan
the armenians want the nagorno-karabakh region, which has been part of azerbaidzhan for 65 years, returned to armenia. three quarters of the 157,000 residents are armenian
last week hundreds of thousands of armenians took to the streets in yerevan, armenia's capital, calling for the region's annexation
protests also occurred in nagorno-karabakh backing the call
on friday, soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev appealed for ``civil maturity and restraint'' in an address read on armenian television by a senior party official. in the address, gorbachev promised that the communist party central committee would review relations among the soviet union's more than 100 nationalities
that same day gorbachev also met with two prominent armenian writers to help work out a solution to the armenian problem
azerbaidzhan is the largest of three soviet republics in the caucasus. it is bounded on the west by the soviet republics of armenia and georgia, on the north by the russian republic. the caspian sea runs for nearly 800 miles along its eastern edge and to the south lies iran
the republic is predominately shiite moslem, expect for the armenian christians living in the nagorno-karbakh region
it has happened so many times over the past 25 years that ron burrows long ago lost count
a car drives toward burrows' house, the heads inside turning about, until it comes to a stop in his driveway at the end of the short road leading to craigville beach. the befuddled motorist either turns the car around or asks burrows for directions
the problem: the kennedy family compound is accessible only from irving avenue in hyannisport, a half mile from irving street, where burrows lives
i'm so used to directing cars to the kennedy compound that i've even thought of setting up an information booth and charging them 10 cents a piece,'' burrows joked monday
now, his days as an informal tour guide are coming to an end
he and the other residents of irving street last week persuaded town officials to change the name of the dead-end street to inwood lane. the name change became official thursday; burrows is just waiting for a public works crew to change the street sign
that might take a couple of months,'' he said
burrows, 80, doesn't blame tourists for seeking a peek at the kennedy compound
but it was a nuisance with all the cars coming up such a small street and sometimes it was a problem because big trucks trying to deliver merchandise to the compound would end up here.''
protestant fundamentalism is growing rapidly in this predominantly roman catholic nation, and american missionary don exley's yellow and white revival tent symbolizes the movement
one night last week, 63 people crossed a muddy field in a hard rain to hear exley, who represents the assemblies of god, preach a spirited sermon in spanish. he told them god would save their souls if they prayed hard enough and sang loud enough
before the two-hour revival ended in the tent in suburban martinez, many of the men, women and children, had ``spoken in tongues'' and eight bowed before exley to be saved. exley said his revival attract crowds of up to 200 people
the assemblies of god is trying to minister to felt needs,'' exley said in an interview. ``people come, and they're coming more and more, because they're hurting financially, physically or in their relations with family.''
sidney rooy of buenos aires, a historian of religion, said pentecostal churches are the fastest-growing religious movements among argentina's 31 million people. the assemblies of god arrived here 40 years ago, but its rapid growth began just five years ago
another historian, the rev. timothy hamilton of buenos aires, said the popularity of protestant evangelism has been growing for a decade. exley claims argentina now has about 2.8 million evangelical christians in a population that is 90 percent catholic
jimmy swaggart, the disgraced assemblies of god television evangelist, visited argentina in 1986 on a four-nation crusade that included brazil, chile and paraguay. a packed house of 60,000 heard him preach at the river plate stadium in buenos aires
carlos annacondia, a former salesman, probably is the most popular argentine evangelist. he preaches in quilmes, just outside the capital
in his magazine abundant life, he published pictures of a recent crusade in paraguay during which he met president alfredo stroessner, the general who has ruled that neighboring country since a coup in 1954. he features the meeting with stroessner in promotional material
exley attributes the popularity of his religious movement, in part, to years of high inflation and ``disillusionment with military government and democratic government.''
he holds revivals four to six nights a week in the tent. exley, 38, has been an assemblies of god missionary since 1976 in argentina and argentina
as an example of his denomination's growth, he cites cordoba, the northwestern industrial center and second-largest city of argentina. exley said he began the assemblies of god ministry there 12 years ago with 75 people in a small church, and cordoba now has 20 churches serving 3,000-4,000 members
the church claims up to 14 million members in brazil, one-tenth of the population, and 12,000 in paraguay
when asked how the movement will be affected by the swaggart sex scandal, exley said: ``for sure it affects his credibility, it affects his credibility a lot. i'm sure it'll affect his finances. but it's very early to know how far-reaching.''
swaggart's tearful confession of sin was was front-page news in argentina
exley said swaggart and the assemblies of god provided most of the money for the block-long lot where the tent stands, provide the swaggart television program dubbed in spanish and were expected to help build a church complex
other financial help from the swaggart group included financing an elementary school in the lower-class lomas de zamora section of buenos aires, he said
mayor federico pena has ordered an investigation into reports that street crews spend more time eating and reading than working
i am outraged by the information ... that a handful of city employees has been wasting taxpayers' dollars by intentionally neglecting their assigned responsibilities as members of the city's work crews,'' pena said in a statement
he commented after seeing a news series that kusa-tv of denver began broadcasting sunday. the station's news crews followed city crews for eight hours and videotaped them with a hidden camera
complaints about the city's public works department, including slow cleanup following a december blizzard, have fueled a recall effort against pena
the station taped several street crews leaving public works yards in the morning, then spending time at stores, restaurants and talking with other crews
in one case, kusa said, a crew drove 64 miles but did no work in its eight-hour shift while visiting five food stores
pena said disciplinary action would be taken against city workers who could be identified from the videotape
while the evidence appears to implicate less than 10 of the city's 11,000 employees, the type of intolerable and inexcusable behavior allegedly involved unjustly damages the reputation of the overwhelming number of city employees who have worked long and hard on behalf of the people of denver,'' pena said
pena also said earlier evidence had led him to begin a management review to improve supervision in the city's pothole repair operation
chuck mills, president of the city employee's union and a public works employee, said if there were problems with workers taking excessive time off, they were isolated. congress</head>
the reagan administration on monday urged a federal appeals court to stay out of a dispute over whether the war powers resolution should have been invoked when the navy began escorting oil tankers in the persian gulf
justice department attorney james spears urged a three-judge panel to uphold a lower court's dismissal of a lawsuit brought by 110 members of congress to force president reagan to report to congress that u.s. forces were sent into hostilities last summer in the persian gulf
our policy has begun to bear fruit,'' spears said of the navy's operation to protect reflagged kuwaiti oil tankers from attack by warring iraqi or iranian forces in the persian gulf. ``for a court to recharacterize the u.s. role threatens to undercut this progress.''
spears called the issue ``quintessentially a non-justiciable political question'' that courts cannot decide
this is a situation where a political decision has been made by the political branches, it is not one for the judicial branch to come in and second guess,'' spears said
the 1973 war powers resolution requires that in the absence of a declared war the president must notify congress within 48 hours of placing u.s. forces in hostilities
the lawsuit was filed by rep. michael lowery, d-wash., and other members of congress, after president reagan refused to file a report notifying congress that the navy ships escorting reflagged kuwaiti oil tankers had been sent into hosilities
the case was dismissed late last year by u.s. district judge george revercomb, who ruled that courts did not have jurisdiction to consider the claim
alan morrison, an attorney representing the lawmakers, argued that ``unless we are to say the statute is unenforceable... it seems to me the court has the power to at least require that the president file the report'' with congress
chief judge patricia wald questioned spears' assertion that courts are not qualified to decide what situation amounts to hostilities, which is essentially a military and diplomatic question
recalling vietnam, wald said that if ``people are in jungles fighting and dying ... you would say that is still a political question, if the president did not want to submit the report'' to congress
no matter what's going on overseas, that's a political question,'' spears said. he said congress has the power under the constitution to declare war. ``congress can't take the power that the constitution assigned it and assign it to a court'' to decide the question
judge stephen williams questioned why congress had not passed resolutions declaring that the persian gulf operation was covered by the war powers resolution
the fact that congress hasn't acted is not relevant'' to whether the president must obey the resolution's requirment that he notify congress that a military operation has begun, morrison said
the war powers resolution was enacted because congress was concerned that its role in deciding whether to send u.s. troops into armed conflict had been greatly diminished, morrison said
the whole purpose of the war powers resolution is not to have to pass a new law every time we have a vietnam or a cambodia,'' morrison said
but williams said the lawmakers who filed the suit were ``inviting courts to add a third voice to u.s. foreign policy where events found by a court fitted into the meaning of the resolution.''
the resolution provides that once he has reported that u.s. forces have entered hostilities, the president must withdraw troops in 60 days if congress doesn't formally declare war or the lawmakers take action to extend the deadline
for european leaders, this week's nato summit is a welcome chance to join president reagan in trumpeting alliance unity and highlighting its recent successes
privately, though, the europeans may add some words of worry
the most immediate concern to europeans is a lack of western consensus on how to balance the need to guard against a possible soviet attack with the hope for further reductions in east-west tensions
a more deeply rooted worry is that budgetary pressures may soon compel washington to pull some of its 326,000 troops out of western europe
the summit meeting wednesday and thursday is likely to declare the north atlantic treaty organization united on the need to keep some nuclear weapons in europe. the problem is deciding how many and which kinds
it also is expected to demand that the soviet-led warsaw pact alliance accept proportionally bigger conventional arms and troop cuts than the west, according to nato sources familiar with preparations for the summit
but the summit will sidestep, at least in public, the questions of whether and when to improve nato's very short-range atomic arms, most of which are deployed by the united states on west german soil. smaller numbers are in belgium, britain, the netherlands, italy and turkey
attention has been drawn to these weapons, which include ballistic nuclear missiles and artillery, since reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev signed a treaty in december eliminating more than 2,000 u.s. and soviet nuclear missiles which have ranges from 300 to 3,000 miles
moscow has suggested scrapping all short-range nuclear arms, of which the east bloc has more than a 10-1 numerical edge in europe, according to nato figures
but lord carrington, the nato secretary general, said in a recent interview that all 16 alliance members are steadfastly opposed to such a complete elimination. alliance members see the short-range weapons as vital to nato's strategy of responding to an attack with a full range of military options
the one thing that everybody is agreed on is that you can't have a third zero,'' carrington said, refering to the inf treaty which eliminates two categories of nuclear missile
west germany, however, wants nato to begin negotiations to bring the soviet total of short-range nuclear arms down to nato's level. but most of the other allies worry that such talks would eventually lead to a total ban on these weapons. they want to hold off until progress is made in reducing soviet advantages in conventional and chemical arms
a further complication is washington's desire, backed most strongly by britain, to upgrade nato's short-range nuclear arsenal, in part by deploying a new, longer-range version of the lance ballistic missile. key factions of the bonn government strongly oppose this, saying it would force west germany to bear too much of the nuclear risk
although bonn and washington appear to have agreed to play down the short-range nuclear issue, british prime minister margaret thatcher is expected to tell the brussels summit that nato must carry through with a commitment, first made in 1983, to upgrade these weapons
french president franoics mitterrand, however, has indicated that he is unhappy with the public focus on improving nato's remaining nuclear arsenal
it would be paradoxical and inopportune to overarm just now'' as washington and moscow are striving to further improve east-west relations, mitterrand said in an interview published monday by france's largest circulation newspaper, oeust-france
the presence of mitterrand at the nato meeting is significant. it demonstrates a growing desire by france to tighten its political links to the alliance
no french president has attended a nato summit since president charles de gaulle pulled french forces out of nato's joint command in 1966
beyond the immediate concerns about how to organize western arms control priorities, the european leaders view the brussels meeting as an opportunity to underscore their support for the u.s.-soviet missile treaty, which must receive a two-thirds vote of approval in the u.s. senate
the europeans also are eager to publicize their support for reagan in advance of his expected meeting with gorbachev in moscow in may or june
inflation has pulled the enforcement teeth from many government safety laws by reducing the impact of fines, a coalition of consumer groups said monday
penalties for violating various health and safety laws have remained essentially unchanged over the years, while inflation has reduced the value of the amounts involved, the consumer federation of america and the u.s. public interest research group said in a report
letting civil penalties be eroded by inflation operates as if there were a built-in depreciation schedule in our key health and safety statutes,'' said michael waldman of the group public citizen's congress watch, in a statement released with the study
examples cited in the study included:
_the occupational safety and health act of 1970 retains its original penalties of $1,000 per violation and $10,000 for failure to provide a safe workplace. to keep place with inflation these would have to increase to $2,970 and $29,700
_the federal aviation act has retained the same $1,000 fine for violations of safety rules since 1958. inflation has reduced its value to one-quarter of the original worth
_the consumer product safety commission act civil penalties of $2,000 per violation up to a maximum of $500,000 have not changed since 1972, with inflation reducing them to 36 percent of their original impact
the consumer groups submitted copies of the study to congress in support of a bill to adjust the civil penalties in federal laws to keep them up to date with inflation
the ability of the soviet union to wage an offensive land war is the ``most destabilizing factor'' in european security and is likely to be a key topic at this week's nato summit, the u.s. ambassador to west germany said monday
ambassador richard burt, in an interview with the associated press, also termed ``a publicity stunt'' last week's removal of some soviet missiles from east germany and czechoslovakia
he predicted that differences of opinion over modernizing short-range nuclear missiles and other points of dispute would not disrupt the atlantic alliance meeting in brussels wednesday and thursday
there is a growing consensus emerging within the alliance _ which i believe will be reflected in the summit _ on the importance now of negotiations on enhancing conventional arms stability,'' burt said
there has been a focus on the nuclear dimension of security in europe,'' he said. ``but there is a growing view that the time has come now to focus on the most destabilizing factor in european security, which is the soviet capability to wage an offensive war against western europe.''
their forces are deployed, structured and trained to fight an offensive war in europe,'' burt said, adding later that he meant an ``offensive land war.''
burt said it was mandatory to address this problem in arms control negotiations
military power casts a political shadow. the threat is not just one of outright invasion.''
there are about 990,000 active duty nato troops in central europe, most of them in west germany. western sources say they face about 1.2 million soviet-led warsaw pact troops in eastern europe
west german leaders already have begun calling on the soviet to reduce their superiority in conventional weapons and undertake other arms control measures
during the pre-summit preparations, washington officials had a highly publicized dispute with west german officials over u.s. insistence on the need to modernize short-range nuclear weapons in western europe
the reagan administration later promised not to insist on the modernization issue as a topic at this week's summit
there are no serious differences between bonn and washington on these subjects,'' added the 41-year-old ambassador, an expert on arms control and european security issues
burt has been speaking out against claims by some politicians in bonn that the intermediate-range missile treaty signed in december leaves west germany vulnerable to soviet nuclear attack
we will continue to be able to deter an attack in europe with u.s. nuclear weapons deployed in europe and at sea,'' he said. ``there is a sense that this agreement leads to the denuclearization of europe. that is not the case.''
in fact ... we should resist a trend towards the denuclearization of europe,'' he added
asked about the highly publicized removal of some soviet ss-12 rockets from warsaw pact members east germany and czechoslovakia last week, burt said: ``i tend to think this was basically a publicity stunt.''
i think they were mainly aiming to win points with western public opinion,'' burt said
the ambassador added that only when the soviets comply with the verification provisions of the treaty will there be certainty that the missiles have been destroyed. the treaty is awaiting ratification by the u.s. senate
a psychiatrist who failed to commit a mentally ill man can not be held negligent in the man's commission of murder three days later, the maine supreme court ruled monday
laurence d. herst was acting in an official capacity on behalf of the state and therefore immune from civil liability when he examined henry a. taylor and determined he did not need to be involuntarily committed to a mental institution, the high court ruled in a 6-0 decision
herst was employed by the maine medical center at the time. while that is not a state-owned facility, herst examined taylor at the request of the cumberland county sheriff's department
even though dr. herst is not employed by a state mental hospital, he is acting in an official capacity on behalf of the state when performing the task of determining, for involuntary commitment purposes, whether a `person is a mentally ill individual and because of his illness, poses a likelihood of serious harm,''' the court said
taylor was arrested nov. 14, 1978, after he drove through toll booths and onto a restricted area at the portland international jetport. he was taken to the cumberland county jail, where he began to show ``erratic and violent behavior,'' the court said
herst examined taylor and found that he did not exhibit tendencies that indicated he was a danger to himself or others. after taylor refused to voluntarily commit himself, he left the hospital
three days later taylor killed louise michaud, 84, during a shooting spree. he barricaded himself in his house but surrendered four hours later when tear gas was used to force him outside
in 1979, he was acquitted of murder by reason of insanity and sentenced to the augusta mental health institute. he was released shortly after a 1984 supreme court ruling that set aside a lower court's denial of taylor's petition that he be released from the institute as an outpatient
no suit had been filed. the supreme court issued its opinion at the request of a lower court with the consent of taylor and herst
taylor's attorney, eugene c. coughlin of bangor, said he had not received a copy of friday's decision and declined to comment. steven j. mogul, an attorney for herst, was in court and could not be immediately reached, his secretary said
protesters hurled bombs at a police jeep and burned other vehicles monday in a new wave of anti-government violence designed to disrupt this week's parliamentary elections, witnesses and police said
three people, including a policeman, were injured in two bomb blasts during a rally called to protest the deaths of three people reportedly killed during demonstrations the day before, witnesses said
meanwhile, an opposition leader called for continued protests to disrupt thursday's parliamentary balloting, charging that a fair election is impossible under the administration of president hussain mohammad ershad
obaidur rahman, general secretary for the anti-government bangladesh nationalist party, told supporters at the rally here to form ``resistance committees'' in the villages to disrupt ``this farcical election called to perpetuate the rule of ershad.''
mohammad ershad, a senior police official posted near the rally site, said ``people threw three bombs at a jeep carrying paramilitary troops. one bomb exploded inside, injuring a policeman.''
four cars were set ablaze by rioters in different parts of the city, police said
in downtown hazari bagh, protesters set fire to three election posts and damaged seven vehicles, witnesses said. they exploded several crude bombs before police dispersed them, the witnesses said
five vehicles were attacked and damaged near the dhaka university, a center of anti-government protests
the opposition has called for a nationwide strike on wednesday and thursday to disrupt the elections. the government has ordered all schools and colleges closed to enable teachers to work at polling places
at least 100 people were killed during local elections feb. 10 in clashes among rival political groups
but government officials said they already were beefing up security at polling places
information minister anis ul-islam said at least 9,000 soldiers would be deployed to help maintain peace on election day, forming part of a 300,000-member force that also includes village defense forces
they are moving out now. in some places they have already moved,'' he said
there are about 50 million voters but only a small percentage is expected to vote, according to political analysts
sheik hasina, leader of the opposition awami league, said three people were killed during a violent clash on sunday. the violence began shortly after hasina and opposition leader khaleda zia addressed separate rallies at the city's main square
the women have led a series of strikes and demonstrations since nov. 10 to try to oust ershad, a former army general who took power in a bloodless coup in 1982
ershad's jatiya party and several minor opposition parties are runningup candidates for the 300 elected seats of parliament, but the main opposition groups have boycotted the balloting
the military has been the driving force in bangladesh's politics. in the country's 17-year history, every change in government has been by coup. ershad, 58, seized power in 1982 and was elected president in a 1986 vote the opposition boycotted and contends was rigged
a 35-year-old white doctor who has worked in black townships since 1980 went on trial monday for refusing to report to a two-week military camp
dr. ivan toms, who opposes mandatory conscription of whites males, faces a jail term of up to three years if convicted
he has refused to apply for designation as a religious objector, the only legal avenue available for those wishing to avoid military service
instead, toms has called on the government to provide some form of alternative national service for young men who object to joining the army. he has urged that alternatives be found for those who do not want to serve in black townships or in the bush wars in angola and south-west africa
toms served as an army doctor for two years following graduation from medical school in 1978. however, he has decided to refuse participation in the annual two-week camps required of all white men who are physically fit
the government said monday it had sent emissaries to talk with exiled president ferdinand marcos, who has praised the aquino government and said he was ready to negotiate his return to the philippines
president corazon aquino said earlier monday she would not yet let marcos come home. but other officials hinted he may be allowed to return if he promises to behave and to return a some of the billions of dollars he allegedly stole during his 20-year rule
in honolulu, where marcos has lived since his ouster in february 1986, a spokesman for the former president read a statement. it said in part:
we must recognize the achievement of the present administration in being able to survive this long when many countries, especially those belonging to the third world, have floundered and gone under water. for this we must openly and candidly congratulate the aquino government.''
the statement said marcos was ready ``to negotiate the details and conditions under which my family and i shall return to the philippines for the salvation of the country from the bloody takeover by communist insurgents.''
marcos spokesman lonnie tan said marcos had held meetings recently in hawaii with philippine reps. francisco sumulong and egmidio tanjuatco, both relatives of mrs. aquino
indeed there were negotiations. they came over here to talk to the president to discuss the subject of him returning to the philippines,'' tan said
he would not say what marcos might offer to secure his return
tanjuatco, a cousin of mrs. aquino, told reporters monday that he met marcos on jan. 26
we met only once,'' tanjuatco said. ``the meeting was between him and myself only. during the meeting, mr. marcos reiterated to me his desire to return to the philippines at the earliest opportunity.''
sumulong, mrs. aquino's uncle and majority floor leader of the house of representatives, said he met marcos separately in february. sumulong said the former president's health was deteriorating and that he wanted to return home ``possibly because he believes he is near the end of his life on earth.''
in a statement issued through her spokesman teodoro benigno, mrs. aquino confirmed she had sent her relatives to honolulu
go there and listen,'' benigno quoted her as saying. ``if we can listen to other people, why can't we listen to mr. marcos.''
benigno revealed no details of the talks but said there was ``no official response to the message as far as i know.''
marcos fled the philippines during a civilian-military revolt in the wake of fraud-tainted feb. 7, 1986 presidential elections in which both he and mrs. aquino claimed victory
mrs. aquino canceled the passports of marcos and his immediate family and banned them from the country. asked by reporters monday if she would lift the ban, she replied, ``not yet.''
but sen. neptali gonzales, a former justice minister, told reporters marcos might be allowed to return if he swears allegiance to the aquino government and settles claims that he plundered billions of dollars from the treasury
emmanuel pelaez, the philippine ambassador to the united states, told reporters in manila that if marcos ``returns the stolen wealth, i think there are good chances for him to come home.''
meanwhile, officials said the name ``imelda marcos'' was on the passenger list of a flight to manila from australia. a marcos spokesman said the former first lady was still in hawaii
immigration supervisor rolando mancilla said the woman arrived saturday on a philippine airlines flight from sydney and gave a home address in ilocos norte, marcos' home province. he said a narcotics command agent found the name during a routine check of the manifest
in honolulu, a servant who answered the phone at the marcos residence said ``she's here, he's here, both of them.'' but he refused to give his name or put either marcos or his wife on the line. graf, ``twenty-nine xxx, to make clear whole senate is hearing impeachment trial</note>
evan mecham today became the first governor in almost 60 years to face an impeachment trial as the state's chief justice convened a jury of 30 state senators to decide whether to remove him from office
first on the agenda was a series of motions, including one to throw out the charges against mecham, a republican whose 13 months in office have also been scarred by a recall effort and a criminal indictment
the senate trial of evan mecham does not concern merely this one officeholder, but instead addresses the very essence of democracy in our state constitution,'' senate minority leader alan stephens, a democrat, said in a floor speech shortly before the court convened
we are really testing our form of government. will we stand up and do our duty amid calls from the public to intimidate us?''
senate leaders say they'll take up to two months to hear testimony and arguments before deciding whether the governor should be removed and possibly barred from holding elective office
mecham, 63, also faces a march 22 criminal trial on six felony charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, and a may 17 recall election
twenty-nine of the state's 30 senators were at desks in the brown-walled chamber as the presiding officer, arizona supreme court frank x. gordon jr., convened the senate as an impeachment court. a small gallery was packed with reporters and visitors, and the trial was being broadcast on radio and television
the state house was represented by a five member impeachment board of managers, or prosecutors, while mecham himself stayed at his temporary office in suburban glendale and was represented by several lawyers
after the trial began, the senate agreed on a voice vote to let the governor's original lawyer, murray miller, withdraw from the case. miller was replaced by washington attorney jerris leonard last week in a surprise move
a clerk read the impeachment articles, and the senate then considered and denied a defense motion seeking to have consideration of an article referring to the campaign loan delayed until after his criminal trial
the senate broke for lunch at noon while considering a motion to throw out all charges
mecham maintains he'll be acquitted in both trials, win the recall election and return to the office he gave up to democratic secretary of state rose mofford after he was impeached feb. 5 on a 46-14 house vote
the senator absent this morning was republican hal runyan, a republican who suffered a stroke in november
at a news conference saturday, mecham said winning acquittal in criminal court is more important than persuading the senate to keep him in office
i could have my freedom taken away and be sent to jail if i were guilty (in criminal court). doesn't that somehow seem to you ... a little more important than the job as governor? it does to me,'' mecham said
the state supreme court on friday refused an emergency request by mecham to intervene and delay the senate trial until after the criminal trial. the court planned to discuss tuesday whether to grant an injunction, although several justices already have said they believe the court lacks jurisdiction
mecham said he planned to take the issue to federal court. a new attorney hired by mecham last week, thomas crowe, said he would decide by wednesday where the appeal would be filed
the governor claims the impeachment trial threatens his right to a fair criminal trial because the senate proceedings will not be bound by the same rules of evidence as a criminal court but will be widely publicized to prospective jurors
as governor of this state, i ask nothing more than is accorded to every garden-variety criminal,'' he said. ``is this a star chamber or will we proceed under the time-tested constitutional mandate that i be afforded all of my basic constitutional rights?''
the house has leveled 23 charges against mecham accusing him of concealing the $350,000 loan, misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership and trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official against a witness before the grand jury that investigated mecham
senate majority leader bob usdane said the senate has decided to hear testimony on all charges even if it appears there could be a vote to convict him on the first charges heard
prosecutor paul eckstein said he and co-counsel william french planned to begin with testimony on the allegation that mecham ordered department of public safety director ralph milstead not to cooperate with a probe of the alleged death threat against former mecham aide donna carlson, who testified before the state grand jury investigating mecham
state official lee watkins, who has since resigned, has denied making the threat
two-thirds of the 30 senate votes are required to convict mecham, who is the first u.s. governor to be impeached since 1929, when huey long of louisiana and henry s. johnston of oklahoma were impeached. long was never tried, while johnston was removed
of the 16 governors in the nation's history to be impeached, six were convicted and removed from office
mecham, who never was considered part of the state's republican establishment, won the governorship in a three-way race 1986 on his fifth try
he immediately became embroiled in controversy when he canceled a martin luther king holiday for state workers, saying it was illegally declared by his predecessor, democratic gov. bruce babbitt
mecham has been criticized for defending the use of the word ``pickaninny'' in a book and for making remarks that angered women, jews, homosexuals and the japanese
nasa announced monday it will acquire a boeing 747-100 jetliner to use as a second space shuttle transporter
the 231-foot-long aircraft will be modified to carry shuttles piggyback from landing sites back to the launch center here. officials said the second vehicle would increase ferrying capability and eliminate a transportation problem that could result if there were only one carrier and it was grounded or suffered a mishap
the three remaining shuttles have not flown since the challenger accident two years ago. when flights resume, presently planned for august, nasa said that, for safety reasons, shuttles will land for the foreseeable future at the dry lakebed at edwards air force base, calif., instead of on the runway here, where there is little margin for error
a letter contract has been signed for the aircraft with boeing military airplane co., a division of the boeing co. of seattle. required modifications and cost are being negotiated, nasa said
police monday looked for suspects who apparently fired a shot from a van on interstate 95, killing a man on his way to a party after taking the florida bar exam
irv ribler, 26, was shot just below his left shoulder saturday. his car sped across the median, three lanes of oncoming traffic and plowed into a gully
friends following ribler's car told police the shot was fired from a van whose occupants had just thrown a small object at the victim's sportscar, but that was unconfirmed, broward county sheriff's spokesman jim leljedal said sunday
no other traffic hit ribler's car and no other injuries were reported
he left me a note before he left saturday,'' ribler's mother, zaida ribler, said sunday. ``it says, `mom, see you in the morning. i love you. irv
he was a good son. he studied so hard. he worked in the yard. he cleaned the house. he didn't drink,'' said his mother, who cleaned houses and worked as a tailor seven days a week to put her only child through florida state university and the university of miami law school. ``now my life has ended. everything is over.''
ribler was graduated from law school in may and initially failed the bar exam. since then, he had studied constantly. after taking the test wednesday, he was elated, certain he had passed, friends said
his whole life was centered on passing the bar and working as a public defender,'' said classmate manny fernandez, 24. ``he had some offers. he was almost there.''
town meeting day is as much a symbol of vermont as the maple sap that flows soon after, but this year's town meetings find vermonters fearful of their state's future because farms are going out of business and open land is sprouting vacation homes
we are losing our farms and we are losing rural vermont at an unbelievable rate,'' says jack starr, a dairy farmer from troy
the changing vermont is evident everywhere:
_ vermont has lost more than 300 dairy farms, 10 percent of its total, in just the last two years;
_ average housing values, fueled by competition from affluent out-of-staters, have increased 48 percent in two years;
_ the annual number of applications for development permits has almost doubled in the past six years;
_ the number of houses being bought by and built for out-of-staters seeking a vacation retreat is skyrocketing. in 1986, 52 percent of all new housing constructed in windham county alone was second homes
the reasons for the development pressure are simple: improved transportation networks have brought vermont closer to boston and new york; a booming economy has provided people with the cash; and vermont's ski resorts are expanding to become more attractive year-round
to help preserve farms, some towns are using the limited clout of their annual town meetings, a new england fixture in which residents vote directly on town expenditures and policy. in pawlet, voters are being asked to exempt farm silos from property taxes, a move that would mean a savings of $200 a year for each of the town's 17 farms
it's going to be a combination of these little things that keep the farmers going,'' said state rep. perry waite of pawlet. ``do you want new jersey or do you want a few farms left? i don't feel we can afford to lose one farm in pawlet.''
and the legislature is considering a controversial $40 million package that includes the first-in-the-nation state subsidy for dairy farmers, to offset cuts in federal milk price supports
it's a radical proposal, but these times demand it,'' said rep. paul poirier, the house democratic leader and chairman of a special house committee on growth
this has become the year of the farmer,'' said rep. michael bernhardt, the house republican leader. ``saving farms seems to be something people can identify with as a way to save vermont.''
the concerns over growth reached a boiling point last fall, prompting gov. madeleine kunin to appoint a special governor's commission on vermont's future
more than 2,000 people attended the commission's 11 public hearings, with several hundred voicing their fears
i don't see a lot of `rural' going on anymore,'' said peter saman of woodstock. ``if vermont is going to be here, i think rural has to exist or we're going to live in disneyland.''
victoria fraser of williston told the commission: ``i am afraid we will obscure the soul of vermont by covering her with parking lots, highways and condominiums.''
too many vermonters in towns near major ski areas and tourist centers are feeling like strangers in their own communities, hesitating to go to the grocery store or post office for fear of sitting in traffic or waiting in line,'' said mary mccallum of proctorsville
kunin, armed with the commission's report, devoted her entire state-of-the-state address in january to detailing ``today's unprecedented growth'' and describing her own fears about the changes
kunin said the only way to regain control is ``to inaugurate a new and tough planning process which will guide vermont into a future that we envision for ourselves.''
the special house growth committee has endorsed a far-reaching proposal that calls for $20 million to go into a special fund to buy up open land and help provide affordable housing. it also calls for stronger planning and would provide for regional tax sharing, under which property-rich resort towns would share some of their tax wealth with outlying communities
but the cornerstone of the legislative proposal is the dairy assistance, prompted by reports that between 10 percent and 40 percent of the state's farmers will be forced out of business in the next two years
the federal price support for 100 pounds of milk paid to farmers now stands at $10.60, almost $3 below what it was in 1980, and the decline has meant the difference to some farms. under the proposal, the state would pay farmers an extra 50 cents per 100 pounds
the october stock market crash will contribute to a significant slowdown in economic growth this year but the country should be able to avoid a recession, economists for top u.s. corporations predicted monday
the national association of business economists said its latest member survey found economists in a more upbeat mood than three months ago when more than half of them said the record fall in stock prices on oct. 19 would lead to a recession in 1988
in the latest survey, the number forecasting a recession this year had dropped to one-fourth, good news for republicans hoping to hold onto the white house. but an overwhelming 83 percent of the anlysts said a downturn was very likely before the end of the next president's first year in office
back in november there was a great deal of nervousness about what oct. 19 meant to the economy,'' said kathleen cooper, who briefed reporters on the new forecast. ``since that time, we have had good christmas sales, good employment growth and consumer confidence surveys have improved. these things make economists feel better about the future.''
while the next president will likely have to deal with a recession early in his first term, the economists said they expected the economy this year to expand at a modest pace of 2 percent, as measured by the gross national product
this would be about half of the 3.9 percent gnp growth turned in during 1987. the reagan administration, by contrast, is more optimistically forecasting 2.4 percent gnp growth this year, when measured from the fourth quarter of 1987
even though most of us don't expect a recession, we will have much slower growth than in 1987,'' said ms. cooper, who is chief economist for security pacific national bank of los angeles. she said the stock market decline had caused many economists to slash their gnp forecasts by between 0.5 percent and 1 percent
in other predictions, the survey results from 200 economists found:
_ unemployment will creep up this year because of the sluggish growth forecasts, rising from the current 5.8 percent level to 6.1 percent by the end of the year
_ inflation will remain under control with consumer prices rising 4.2 percent this year, a bit slower than the 4.4 percent consumer inflation recorded in 1987
_ the federal budget deficit will rise to $157 billion in the current fiscal year, but then resume falling, droping to $140 billion by 1990. this is more pessimistic than the reagan administration, which puts this year's deficit at $146.7 billion, a further improvement from the $150.4 billion 1987 deficit
_ the foreign trade deficit, which hit a record $171 billion last year, will finally start coming down, dipping to $150 billion this year and $130 billion in 1989. half of this year's overall growth will come from improvements in the trade deficit, the economists said
_ interest rates will hold steady, ending up the year about where they are currently. banks cut their prime rate, used to set interest rates on a variety of corporate and consumer loans, to 8.5 percent in early february and analysts forecast this would be the rate in effect at year's end
ms. cooper said that the optimistic outlook for interest rates stemmed in part from a belief that the federal reserve would be easing its grip on the money supply in the first half of the year in an effort to keep the recovery alive
she said over two-thirds of the economists believed the fed would be easing credit conditions in the coming six months with one-fourth of the analysts looking for a cut in the discount rate, the interest the fed charges to make bank loans
ms. cooper said that the economists believe that the dollar, which has at time fallen sharply on foreign currency exchanges, will stabilize this year with only one-fifth of the analysts expecting a decline of 10 percent or more. just three months ago, more than 40 percent of the economists were forecasting a decline in the dollar that was at least that large
southern democratic leaders are discussing the possibility of acting together on a pre-super tuesday endorsement of one of the six candidates pursuing their party's presidential nomination
former gov. charles robb of virginia and sen. sam nunn of georgia confirmed on monday such discussions have taken place but both cautioned against assuming that an endorsement would be forthcoming
it's only a possibility,'' said robb
nunn described it as ``a question that is in considerable doubt.''
robb and nunn discussed the endorsement in separate interviews during a meeting of the democratic leadership council, a group of elected officials who banded together in 1985 to halt what they considered the leftward drift of the national party
robb was chairman of the dlc the past two years and nunn succeeded him at this meeting
the agenda for the two-day meeting included discussions of the economy, but politics was the topic that dominated most conversation, particularly the impact of super tuesday march 8 when 20 states, most of them south of the mason-dixon line, and american samoa will hold democratic presidential primaries or caucuses
in a luncheon speech, nunn, who considered entering the democratic presidential race and decided against it, warned that ``political marketing seems to be replacing political leadership.''
the georgia senator said, ``first, campaign consultants tell the candidates what they think the public wants to hear _ usually more services and less taxes _ then the candidates deliver the message, usually avoiding any implication of short-term individual sacrifice for long-term national gain.''
the art of campaigning,'' he went on, ``is in danger of becoming divorced from the art of governing. the real question of the 1988 election is not who wins, but whether the winner can effectively govern america.''
members of the dlc took the lead in convincing southern legislatures to schedule their presidential primaries on the same day in an effort to give the region a stronger voice in selection of the democratic presidential nominee
robb told the group that super tuesday was important ``because democrats can't win the white house without winning the south _ it's that simple.''
robb noted that one-third of the delegates to the democratic national convention in atlanta in july would be selected on that day and that the 20 states also represented 207 electoral college votes, 76 percent of those needed to be elected president
the general election chances of the democratic party rest with these 20 states. the preliminaries are over and super tuesday is indisputably the main event of the primary season.''
four democratic presidential candidates are in a furious battle for support in the super tuesday states _ gov. michael dukakis of massachusetts, rep. richard gephardt of missouri, sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, and jesse jackson. dukakis, gephardt and gore are from super tuesday states, while jackson, a native of south carolina, has a powerful base in the region's black community
sen. bob graham of florida said that 30 days after super tuesday ``there are going to be three candidates left, there'll be dukakis, there'll be jackson and there will be either gephardt or gore.''
the former florida governor described gephardt, who has made trade the central issue of his campaign, as ``the only candidate who is running a message campaign. so he has the benefit of operating almost in a vacuum.''
graham said gore, who has been counting on his southern background to attract votes on super tuesday, ``has got to find some reason beyond geography to get people to vote for him.''
gov. bill clinton of arkansas summed up the debate between gore and gephardt this way:
gore's major argument was vote for me and i won't lose the general election for you because i'm tough on foreign policy. democrats get beat by being weak on foreign policy
gephardt's argument is i'll win the general election for you by having a good economic policy. democrats win on economic policy
both of them are telling the truth. both of them are right.''
clinton said he had not been involved in discussions of an endorsement and said, ``i doubt if we could all agree.''
a recent star wars space experiment has increased the confidence of pentagon scientists that they can defeat attempts to fool a missile defense by using decoy warheads, the head of the program said monday
lt. gen. james a. abrahamson, the air force general in charge of the strategic defense initiative organization, said the so-called delta 181 space experiment conducted three weeks ago had provided a ``tremendous amount of data'' that already was expanding scientific understanding of how objects look as they travel through space
that, in turn, will be crucial to devising infrared, radar, laser radar and other types of sensors that can tell the difference between a real nuclear warhead and a fake one traveling through space, abrahamson said at a pentagon briefing
while months if not years of research are still ahead, ``i think all of our evidence, so far ... is that, yes, we should be able to find effective ways to discriminate'' between decoy and real warheads, he said
the three-star general also acknowledged, however, that budget cuts imposed by congress this year have slowed the star wars program by at least a year and possibly more. the reagan administration had wanted to spend $5.2 billion on research this year, but received $3.5 billion
a future president probably will not be in a position to make a decision on deploying a rudimentary missile defense system until 1993 or 1994, abrahamson said, and actual deployment then could not begin until sometime after 1995
star wars _ known formally as the strategic defense initiative _ is a research program aimed at developing lasers and other types of exotic weapons that could be deployed in space and on the ground to automatically shoot down incoming nuclear missiles
abrahamson and a top program official, maj. andrew j. green, appeared at the pentagon on monday to discuss delta 181, which has been described as the most ambitious star wars experiment ever conducted in space
delta 181 was launched feb. 8 from the kennedy space center in florida. it boosted a special satellite into space that was used for 12 hours to conduct a series of tests
sensors on the 6,000-pound satellite were used to track how a variety of different-shaped objects appeared in space and against various backgrounds, such as the earth's surface and the portion of the atmosphere just above the ground called ``earth's limb.''
data from the tests are still being transmitted back to the ground but that process should be completed by the end of the week, green said
the data already in hand, however, show a laser radar sensor on board the satellite succeeded in highlighting ``vast differences'' in the way various objects looked in space, including contrasts based on the weight of the object, green said
sdi officials consistently have termed the mission a success, but the magazine aviation week and space technology reported on feb. 15 that the satellite had been unable to complete ``battle management fire control computations.''
the magazine blamed the problem on computers, but air force col. john otten, assistant director of the sdi kinetic energy office, said at the time that the problem was caused by an optical sensor trying to lock onto an object beyond its range
some test data were lost when the sensor gave false information to on-board computers. but otten said the losses were minor because the tracking exercise, in which the sensor was to look away from a target and then back to the target, was a secondary objective of the mission
the grass was being cut, the windows washed and the cactus garden weeded as employees hurried to work. just another monday morning at the arizona capitol
except for the governor, who went on trial
only a few of gov. evan mecham's supporters showed up as his trial began in the senate. seats were open in the gallery. three bus loads of schoolchildren made their annual field trip to learn about government, and the plaza in front of the senate was quiet
most of the people are working. i had to take a chance of losing my job to be here,'' said andy cosentino, a supporter of the governor who was carrying a bible and a placard. ``people are going to have to make a sacrifice to make sure justice prevails.''
while mecham's woes have drawn some large and loud rallies, the embattled republican's trial opened with little fanfare. mecham did not attend the opening sesion
by the 9 a.m. scheduled start of his trial, only a half-dozen protesters patrolled the plaza. ``more are due anytime now,'' said cosentino
by 10 a.m., their ranks had swelled to about 20
one woman placed a large radio by her signs so she could hear the proceedings in the senate, which must deliberate 23 charges made by the house
a few retirees milled about. one group laid a paper railroad across the courtyard with a drawing of the governor, gagged and bound on the tracks
he's being railroaded,'' said wilma harm of phoenix. ``the man has done nothing to be called upon like this.''
when the doors were opened to public seating in the gallery, only 15 people were in line. june reynolds, a retired government teacher who lives in scottsdale, arrived two hours early and was first
i'm concerned about what's happening to the state,'' she said
the loudest noises in the plaza came from the lawnmowers. even the air was calm, and the scent of orange blossom suffused the still air
the house impeached mecham on feb. 5, accusing him of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership and trying to thwart an investigation of an allegation that a state official threatened the life of a grand jury witness. two-thirds of the 30 senate votes are required to convict
scott mccartney is the ap southwest regional reporter, based in dallas
the federal government is expanding a program to allow more government services and non-tax debts to be paid for with credit cards, budget officials said monday
under the program, the government is expected to process 130 million credit-card transactions annually by next year, or $6.5 billion worth, said joseph wright, deputy director of the office of management and budget
it will make us the largest credit card user in the world,'' wright said
the government now accepts credit cards for some items, including publications of the government printing office
but wright and budget director james c. miller iii told a news conference this program would be expanded to include a wide array of new items _ from purchasing passports to paying some fines
credit cards will also be more widely used by the government itself, both to pay expenses of officials who are travelling and for some federal procurement, the officials said
everybody uses credit cards _ except for the federal government,'' miller said
the comments came as the white house released president reagan's report to congress on ``management of the united states government.''
the report noted that ``over half of u.s. households own one or more credit cards,'' and that the administration planned to begin making more use of them
for the government, credit cards make collections easier in an electronic environment, reduce delinquencies, cut down on bad checks, eliminate paperwork, and improve information received on collections,'' the report said
the report said that agencies that would start accepting credit cards by this april included:
_ the interstate commerce commission, for duties, fees and fines
_ the national archives, for sales of documents and publications
_ the u.s. courts, for filing fees, fines, opinions, and videotapes of proceedings
_ the federal trade commission, for fines and fees
_ the army corps of engineeers, for permits, fees and map sales
_ the federal emergency management agency, for sale of flood maps
wright said that omb is also working with the irs to develop guidelines that might be used later on to enable taxpayers pay their taxes with credit cards. however, he said to do so would require legislation from congress _ legislation the administration is not currently seeking
the management report also said the government is studying, for possible future use, a system under which ``smart cards'' would be issued by the government to those who receive federal payments and benefits, including social security recipients
these cards (would) have embedded on them information about the cardholder that can be accessed electronically. potentially (the) cards could make available funds for food stamps, social security payments, or grants and control their use electronically through central computers.''

democrats and republicans in 20 states and american samoa will vote in statewide elections or participate in presidential caucuses on march 8, super tuesday
we plan frequent transmission of at least 10 separate tables summarizing the popular vote and delegate allocation both by state and cumulatively for all participating states. in addition, separate formats will summarize activity in five states conducting precinct caucuses that night

all tables will be transmitted at least once an hour, and more frequently as circumstances warrant

our lineup includes the following:

_ primary vote state-by-state. summary packages displaying the latest popular vote, by state. separate packages will cover democratic and republican candidates. these tables are slugged bc-pp-dem-pres-all and bc-pp-gop-pres-all

_ caucus results state-by-state. identical in format to the primary vote state-by-state tables, with separate transmissions for democratic and republican caucuses. since caucus rules may differ from state to state, the numbers in each of the summaries may not mean exactly the same thing. these tables are slugged bc-pc-dem-pres-all and bc-pc-gop-pres-all

_ super tuesday delegates state-by-state. packages displaying the latest delegate allocation by state, with separate packages for the two parties. the formats are similar to the primary vote formats. these tables are slugged bc-pp-dem-deleg-all and bc-pp-gop-deleg-all

_ super tuesday delegate summary. cumulative summary of delegates allocated in all states holding elections and caucuses on super tuesday, with a separate summary for each party. these summaries are slugged bc-pp-dem-deleg-sum and bc-pp-gop-deleg-sum

_ super tuesday vote. cumulative summary of the vote in all states holding primary elections on super tuesday, with a single summary for both parties. these summaries are slugged bc-pp-pres-totvot-sum

_ national delegate table. an update of the overall delegate summary table that has been moving on national wires for several weeks. it gives the breakdown of the presidential preferences of all national convention delegates selected or allocated thus far, plus trend information. a single table contains totals for both parties. this table is slugged bc-us-deleg-sum

_ u.s. senate state-by-state. summary package displaying the latest popular vote in u.s. senate races in maryland, mississippi and texas, with a separate package for party. these tables are slugged bc-dem-senate-state-by-state and bc-gop-senate-state-by-state

depending on election-night developments, we may transmit single-state summaries on some presidential primaries

samples of the first four formats listed above will follow this advisory. sluglines contain the word ``sample'' but otherwise are as indicated above. for illustration only, the summaries and tables include mock votes and percentages rather than zeroes

the samples contain the candidate names in order and total precincts as they now exist for each state. that information may change before election day

please call tom jory at 212 621-1614 if you have questions

the ap
