jesse jackson's strong second-place finish in maine, following respectable showings elsewhere, proves he is attaining what he lacked throughout 1984 _ expansion beyond his black base of support
in a state with a 1 percent black population, jackson got 28 percent of the vote on sunday after campaigning for only two days in maine. winner michael dukakis, well known to maine voters as governor of nearby massachusetts, garnered 42 percent
on monday, addressing cheering students at pembroke state university in north carolina, jackson shouted, ``talk about mainstream; try the state of maine.''
political consultant ann lewis, who has informally advised the jackson campaign, called maine ``the most significant breakthrough state for him so far.''
in iowa and new hampshire he finished fourth out of seven contenders, she noted, after devoting considerable time and resources. in minnesota he was second with 20 percent in last week's caucuses, thanks to the state's liberal activists, she said
but in maine, where jackson's 28 percent contrasted to the 1 percent that he got when he ran in 1984, she said, ``the force of his message produced votes for him in a state in which he has been unable to make a major commitment of resources.''
in maine, jackson did buy $10,000 worth of tv ads in the days before the caucuses
bob beckel, a top political adviser to walter mondale's 1984 camapign, called jackson ``one of the best hidden political stories of the year.''
i would say it's a sign of a growing movement among non-black supporters of jackson, and for people to try to ignore it, they're making a great mistake,'' he said
people don't want to buy the notion that jesse jackson has got a message that people listen to and that has begun to rise above his blackness,'' he added. ``somebody in this party has to to recognize that this is a significant guy in the party.''
jackson carried two of maine's largest cities, portland and bangor, and won considerable support among the gay community and students. in his bid to expand his base, he has targeted those groups as well as poor people, blue-collar workers and farmers
he beat rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., handily in the mill town of jay. both candidates went to jay last fall to show solidarity with workers of international paper co. who have been on strike since last june. the company has hired replacements in the meantime
gary mcgrane, jay democratic chairman, commented that jackson ``said a scab is a scab. he didn't call them replacement workers. people understand plain talk.''
political analyst william schneider said that while jackson has gotten white votes, there is evidence the votes come not so much from the economically oppressed as from ``the radical chic.''
it could be the village voice crowd instead of the downtrodden,'' he said, citing exit polls from iowa and new hampshire that showed a good portion of jackson's white supporters were upscale well-educated liberals
but he and other analysts also said that besides being better known nationwide than the other candidates _ excepting former colorado sen. gary hart _ jackson has a clear, strong message that does not change from state to state
there is no other candidate in the race who really stands for the old politics ... what i would call democratic fundamentalism,'' as espoused by the late sen. hubert humphrey, sen. edward kennedy, d-mass., and new york gov. mario cuomo, said schneider
beckel added, ``i think people consistently underestimate him. they forget one important thing in politics. that is that message matters. he has got a message ... and it appeals to a lot of people.''
rick barton, democratic state chairman, who had predicted jackson would do as well in maine as he had a week earlier in minnesota's caucuses, contended that timing was a key to jackson's success
jackson's successful appearance at the university of maine in orono on feb. 11, just after iowa's caucuses and just before the new hampshire primary, was ``just the right time ... when maine democrats were starting to lock in,'' he said
barton said the scaling back of the paul simon and hart campaigns also helped jackson. he suggested that defections from those candidates inflated jackson's support by 5 percentage points
