hooligans'' went on a rampage in a city in azerbaidzhan, tass reported monday. an armenian dissident said ``thugs'' beat and knifed armenians as the ethnic hatred kindled by a territorial dispute spread in the caucasus republics
a soviet deputy prosecutor general said over the weekend that two people in another region of azerbaidzhan had been killed in ``disorders'' sparked by armenian demands that a part of azerbaidzhan be reattached to their republic
street demonstrations, in which some witnesses said more than 1 million people participated, took place in the armenian capital of yerevan last week to call for the annexation of the nagorno-karabakh region in azerbaidzhan, whose 157,000 inhabitants are mostly armenian
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev appealed friday to the people of armenia and azerbaidzhan for ``civic maturity,'' but state-run media reports and accounts reaching dissident circles in moscow on monday indicated he had failed to quell the dispute
the official tass news agency said a ``group of hooligans provoked disturbances'' sunday in the industrial city of sumgait, 1,150 miles south of moscow on the caspian sea. ``rampage and violence followed,'' it said
the tass dispatch on the unrest in sumgait was the first official report of civil disturbances in the soviet union since it reported that 3,000 people rioted in alma ata, capital of the central asian republic of kazakhstan, in december 1986. two people died and hundreds were injured in those riots
tass gave no indication what led to the violence in sumgait, a chemical and steelmaking center that is azerbaidzhan's most important industrial city after its capital, baku
a moscow-based dissident said the disturbance was sparked by tensions between azerbaidzhan's dominant ethnic group, the azeris, and armenians. azeris are predominantly moslem, while armenians are predominantly christian
thugs in sumgait went up to people and asked them if they were armenian or not,'' said sergei grigoyants, who is of armenian origin. ``they started to beat up people who said they were armenian. several people were knifed.''
grigoyants, who said he had received information on the unrest from sources in yerevan, said apparently no one was killed in the sunday fracas. he said ``several dozen'' azeris reportedly were involved in the attacks
tass indicated that authorities in sumgait, a city of more than 160,000 people, fear a resurgence of violence
measures have been taken to normalize the situation in the city and safeguard discipline and public order,'' tass said, adding that an investigation was under way
the watch officer at the ministry of internal affairs in baku, reached by telephone monday evening, said he had no information on the disturbances in the city 22 miles to the northwest. an azerbaidzhan government official in moscow refused comment
sumgait is 150 miles northeast of the disputed region of nagorno-karabakh, a region smaller than the u.s. state of delaware, which traditionally had been part of armenia until the soviet government put it under the jurisdiction of azerbaidzhan in 1923
deputy prosecutor general alexander katusev was dispatched from moscow last week to investigate reports that the clash over nagorno-karabakh had led to ethnic bloodshed between azeris and armenians
in a weekend report on baku state-run radio, katusev said two people in a district of azerbaidzhan that borders the contested region ``fell victim to murder'' in disorders linked to the territorial dispute
katusev identified the dead as bakhtiar uliyev, 16, and ali gadzhiyev, 23, both of the agdamsky district. several other people, he said, ``suffered bruises, beatings and injuries that do not threaten their life and health.''
the prosecutor spoke over baku radio on saturday, in a report that was monitored by the british broadcasting co. in london
there are no other victims or people who were maimed either in nagorno-karabakh or any other part of the republic (of azerbaidzhan),'' katusev said
however, valery senderov, another moscow-based dissident, said friday that there had been street scuffles in baku when armenians demonstrated outside three downtown movie theaters last week to demand that nagorno-karabakh be made part of armenia
blood was spilled,'' senderov said, citing telephone reports he received from sources in azerbaidzhan. he said no serious injuries were reported
gorbachev told the party leadership in a feb. 18 speech that relations among the more than 100 ethnic groups that make up the soviet population is the country's greatest problem. he said the party central committee would hold a meeting to discuss those relations
armenian broadcasts friday also said the central committee would reconsider whether it should reattach nagorno-karabakh to armenia. it refused such a request in january
an unsuspecting pilot wound up with his face in the dirt, m-16s pointed at his head and his ruined plane upside down on the runway after drug agents mistook him for a cocaine smuggler
gustavo viera, a miami accountant, has received an apology from vice president george bush's anti-drug task force, the drug enforcement admimistration and the u.s. customs service
however, he said monday he had received no compensation and plans to file a claim against the government
viera said he did not see or hear the customs service helicopter that followed him to the airport, and worries what would happen if the service's controversial proposal to shoot down suspected traffickers is adopted
had that been in effect, i wouldn't be here talking to you today,'' said viera. ``when you're in one of these airplanes and the engine is loud and they shoot a warning, you're not going to hear it.''
the incident occurred july 9 when viera flew his piper cherokee _ bought only three weeks before _ over biscayne bay. he then headed for a small airport south of miami
a subsequent letter from william rosenblatt, an assistant commissioner in the customs service enforcement office, explained what happened next
rosenblatt said customs service radar had lost a suspected trafficker in flight, then picked up viera's plane
it was incorrectly assumed that your aircraft was in fact the suspect,'' rosenblatt wrote
according to friends of viera who witnessed the incident, a customs service blackhawk helicopter followed viera's plane as it touched down at the kendall glider port, but stayed behind him. viera said it was impossible to see or hear the helicopter in that position
when (viera) was turning left to get out of the runway, presumably the pilot of the helicopter thought gus was trying to run away,'' said rene betancourt. ``he made a maneuver with a blast of the prop, and turned gus's plane upside down.''
viera first thought his nose gear had collapsed, then he realized the danger he was in
i'm upside down on my runway, fuel was pouring out and the thing was about to blow,'' said viera. then he saw the helicopter land beside him and several men rush toward his plane
i thought they were going to rescue me,'' he said. instead, as he pleaded with them to pull him out of the plane, someone smashed in his window and hit him in the back of the head, he said
the next thing he knew he was lying face down with a foot on his back. two bahamian agents who accompanied the customs team were pointing their m-16s at his head, said viera
they never identified themselves as customs agents, they never read me my rights and they illegally searched my plane,'' said viera
he was held for about 45 minutes until computer checks established the error
the viera wrote to customs and the dea, but only began to receive apologies when he finally wrote bush's task force
a letter from howard gehring, director of the task force's national narcotics border-interdiction system, said ``any inconvenience that this incident has caused is unfortunate.''
rosenblatt also apologized in a letter
as a resident of dade county, fla., you are in a position to view firsthand the drug-related violence that occurs almost on a daily basis,'' said rosenblatt, adding that the danger results in actions which ``might seem excessive.''
viera said the company which insured his plane paid off quickly and he has bought a new plane
roger garland, chief of the customs air branch at homestead, said as far as he knew, the viera incident was the first of its kind
normally, we wouldn't even do that to a bad guy,'' said garland. the''</note>
republican presidential candidate bob dole said monday that the reagan administration was sending mixed signals about panama's strong man manuel antonio noriega, and he suggested the united states ``may want to go back and take another look'' at treaties turning over the panama canal to panama
say no to drugs. say no to noriega, and no, maybe, to giving them the canal,'' dole said at a news conference
dole, the senate's gop leader, said that when he voted against the panama canal treaties 10 years ago in the senate ``we knew about'' drug trafficking by members of the panamanian military
he said that while the reagan administration has accused noriega of dealing in drugs it has also been sending a different signal to the panamanian leader. ``it seems to me we have one signal saying noriega ought to stay, noriega isn't such a bad guy,'' dole said
referring to the panama canal treaties, dole said, ``we may want to go back and take another look at that.''
sen. thad cochran, r-miss., appeared with dole at a news conference and offered his endorsement. ``the reason can be described in two words _ effective leadership,'' cochran said
earlier, in atlanta, dole jabbed at george bush and the other republican presidential contenders, declaring himself the tough candidate for president and calling toughness ``a quality that some may be lacking.''
trying to beat bush in the big southern presidential primaries, which are one week away, dole went before the predominantly democratic georgia state house and senate for separate addresses
dole, the republican leader in the u.s. senate, proclaimed an affinity with the georgia democrats through his rural kansas background, his start in rural politics and his legislative career. by comparison, that underscored the point he has often made that the vice president has had a more privileged background _ though he didn't mention bush by name
i got here just like you did. i got here the old fashioned way _ i earned it,'' dole said. ``nobody gave it to me.''
it was unmistakable who his target was as he stressed his ability to work with congress and said candidates shouldn't be judged on ``who has the longest resume and most impressive resume.'' bush often notes the high-level government posts he has held
there's one candidate and only one candidate with experience in dealing with congress and making tough decisions,'' dole told the georgia senate
i believe that i have a certain quality that some may be lacking,'' he told the house. ``i am tough. i understand you have to be tough to make tough choices
you have to be tough to deal with the legislature or to deal with congress or to deal with (mikhail) gorbachev or to deal with (daniel) ortega,'' he said, referring to the soviet and nicaraguan leaders
dole strongly criticized noriega, saying the united states should impose a ``full-scale embargo'' on panama if noriega doesn't give up power in 30 days. he said the united states should use ``whatever force is necessary'' to protect the panama canal and other u.s. interests there
we don't need noriega peddling drugs to our children,'' dole said. ``he's a bad influence and he has been a bad influence for 10 years.''
dole was making a series of campaign stops across the southeast on monday as he campaigned toward the southern primaries on super tuesday, march 8. from atlanta he flew to jackson, and was going on to florida and to north carolina
more than one-third of the gop nominating delegates are at stake in the contests on tuesday, including races in most of the south
bush leads dole in most of the super tuesday states, according to most polls. dole aides said they were planning to begin airing new television ads contrasting dole and bush's records in selected southern states
dole repeated his call for a one-year budget freeze to reduce the federal deficit, a proposal that he and bush tangled over in the republicans' debate on sunday. dole said ``there is a bipartisan majority for that kind of action.''
he was accompanied to the georgia legislature by his wife elizabeth
a former navy pilot testified monday that he made six cocaine flights for reputed colombian drug lord carlos lehder rivas in 1979
lehder, 38, reputed to be one of the leaders of colombia's violent medellin cartel, is on trial on charges he and others conspired to smuggle 3.3 tons of cocaine into the united states from colombia via norman's cay in the bahamas from 1978 to 1980
leverett francis, whose testimony opened the 14th week of the trial, is described in the indictment against lehder and co-defendant jack carlton reed as working with ed ward in flying cocaine for lehder
francis, 66, said he began working for ward, an admitted marijuana smuggler, and then switched to flying cocaine, making three trips from norman's cay in the bahamas to colombia and three flights from the island to astor park, fla
as a marijuana smuggler, francis said, he was paid $30,000 a flight. on his cocaine runs from colombia to norman's cay, he received $100,000 a flight, then $30,000 more to fly cocaine into the united states, he said
u.s. attorney robert w. merkle questioned francis about his contacts with defense attorneys and asked if he had wanted to testify against lehder
nobody does. it's distasteful,'' said francis
merkle asked francis if he had concealed illegal drug earnings from the government because he wanted to avoid paying taxes. the witness replied he had
did you say that if you didn't get a promise, you would take contempt instead of testifying?'' asked merkle
francis replied that his cooperation in the ed ward case had earned the government a lot of money and he felt that had discharged his obligation
when asked why he became a smuggler, francis replied, ``i was kind of wondering the same thing. it was the thrill of doing something, in addition to the money.''
francis was shown a photograph of a stack of money and replied that it was $88,000 given to him by ward
he had allowed federal agents to take a picture in 1980
i understood that mr. lehder was the gentleman for whom mr. ward was flying,'' he said
when asked to identify lehder in court, francis said he had developed vision problems over the past few months. he was allowed to leave the witness stand to get closer to the defendant
he walked up to attorney stephen weinbaum, who represents reed, and said, ``is that you, joe?'' joe is lehder's nickname
he also said he couldn't recognize reed
reed, 57, is charged only with being part of the alleged conspiracy
lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise
the chairman of president reagan's aids commission said monday he expects the panel to adopt his interim recommendations, including a $1 billion boost in federal spending on the disease, without substantive change
retired adm. james d. watkins outlined the commission's activities in an appearance at the national press club a day before the panel embarks on three days of hearings on some of the most controversial aspects of dealing with the disease
surgeon general c. everett koop is scheduled as the leadoff witness at tuesday's session, and education secretary william bennett will testify thursday morning
the two have differed on the best ways to combat the spread of the fatal disease, most notably in what emphasis to place on recommending use of condoms to prevent its transmission sexually
watkins, a former chief of naval operations, said he does not believe koop and bennett, or their followers, are as far apart as often perceived
my feeling is our job is to try to bring ... things together,'' watkins said during a question-and-answer session. ``i don't see that we have such obstacles ... we can't reach consensus. i wasn't so sure four months ago, but now i am.''
still, he said the commission is ``not going to shy away from anything'' such as touchy legal issues regarding confidentially of aids test results and discrimination protection for people with the virus
i think it's going to be a donnybrook in there, but i think something useful will come,'' he said
watkins' remarks about the commission's willingness to adopt his interim recommendations were limited to his call last week for spending an additional $1 billion a year in federal funds to fight the spread of aids among intravenous drug abusers and several other suggestions on developing drugs to treat the disease and revamping the system of caring for aids patients
the commission began considering those recommendations earlier monday _ with no hint of substantive differences _ and will meet thursday night to adopt the version that will go to the white house the following week
the panel's final report, which watkins said will address the more controversial issues, is due june 24
responding to a wide range of questions about aids in general, watkins said he agrees with those who do not foresee a dramatic spread of the disease into the general population in the immediate future
but he cautioned against complacency, particularly concerning the possibility that the virus could be spreading undetected among sexually active adolescents
we don't know what it is in adolescents,'' he said. ``there may be lurking on the horizon a real problem that has yet to unfold.''
he also renewed his call for those physicians who do not specialize in aids _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ to become more familiar with it
the medical education horse has got to get in front of the general education cart,'' he said
a dying boy who needs a bone marrow transplant will go to seattle for the treatment next week, even though a court battle still is being waged over his father's health insurance coverage, officials said monday
jim lacina sued nationwide life insurance co. of columbus, contending the company mistakenly canceled his health insurance policy without notifying him
attorneys had rushed to bring the lawsuit to trial monday because doctors said lacina's 11-year-old son, jamie, needed a bone marrow transplant by march 15 to survive more than a few months. the boy has leukemia
but the trial was postponed until june 27, visiting cuyahoga county common pleas judge george g. mcmonagle said, adding that lacina, of geneva, had found a way to pay for the treatment at the fred hutchinson cancer research center in seattle
i understand medicaid is taking care of the arrangements,'' the judge said
officials of the cuyahoga county department of health and human services declined comment, saying medicaid applications are confidential
there was no answer at lacina's home monday in geneva, and lacina's attorney, gerald jeppe, didn't return phone calls. but jeppe said last week that his client was applying for medicaid
edward e. duncan, attorney for nationwide life, also declined to comment
lacina was an agent for nationwide life until five years ago, when his job was terminated because of company cutbacks. because of his son's health, he paid to continue his health insurance after he left the firm, attorneys for both sides agree
however, the policy lapsed in late 1983. lacina said he never got a copy of his policy, a notice that his premium was due or a termination notice, jeppe said in court last week
lacina sued nationwide life on april 24, 1986. while the case has been pending, his son has received chemotherapy treatments at rainbow babies' and children's hospital in cleveland. court documents show lacina, who is unemployed, owes the hospital more than $24,000
the lawsuit became more urgent when doctors advised lacina to take his son to the fred hutchinson cancer research center by march 15 for a bone marrow transplant. the center requires patients to have $100,000 or proof of insurance coverage before it will treat them
susan edmonds, hutchinson spokeswoman, said jamie lacina is scheduled to arrive at the center on march 7. she said she hasn't received word from the boy's father that he has made arrangements to pay for the procedure
president abdou diouf declared a state of emergency monday and truncheon-wielding police battled rioting gangs of young people after news reports said diouf was winning re-election easily
opposition leaders denounced the early returns of sunday's voting, which had diouf getting 77 percent of the vote, as violence spread throughout the city
police arrested the presidential candidate of the major opposition party, abdoulaye wade of the senegalese democrafamily said monday night. the wife of ousmane ngom, a party press secretary, satic party, his id 20 men had come to her home, searched it and arrested her husband
diouf declared a state of emergency in the area around the capital ``in response to grave troubles this morning,'' according to a broadcast on national radio, which said all public meetings were now banned
a 2{-mile stretch of boulevard general de gaulle, one of the city's main thoroughfares, was littered with fire-gutted vehicles, spent tear gas canisters and shattered glass
young rioters burned a stack of tires at one traffic circle, windows were smashed in many houses and large granite stones that had been pulled from a monument lay in the street after they had been thrown at police
merchants in the downtown plateau districtains to senior citizens seated at long tables
at the school, robertson was met by students shouting ``go pat go!'' some students held signs passed out by campaign staffers
when a student asked if robertson would ever renew diplomatic relations with cuba, he replied: ``i don't think we should have diplomatic relations with a butcher and a tyrant!''
robertson began his florida tour in jacksonville monday and arranged a rally in miami monday night, followed by breakfast tuesday in fort lauderdale and stops in hollywood, fort myers, sarasota, gainesville and orlando
in jacksonville, robertson told about 500 supporters that ``along with texas, florida is one of the two most pivotal states.''
he added:
we've got one week to the most crucial election, i believe, in the history of america, certainly this century and maybe since its beginning
we're at a crossroads in america. we're either going to return to the ways that made this nation great, or we're going to go down the road.''
robertson mentioned a gun problem experienced this year in several florida schools
how can a child study when he's living in mortal fear of somebody shooting him with a handgun in the halls of the school? we owe our children an education in a crime-free, drug-free school environment,'' said robertson
if we want to see this country strong. there's only one way in my estimation to do it. we will restore the greatness of america through moral strength,'' he added
robertson also said that ``we've got to go back to a time in our educational system when once again we teach our kids moral values. we've got to bring god back into the public schools of america.''
on trade, he said: ``there isn't one country that is treating us fairly. ... as president of the united states, i'm not going to shut down american factories and put americans out of jobs to improve the standard of living in communist china and communist russia.''
at a news conference following his address, robertson called panama military strong man manuel antonio noriega ``a bandit,'' but added that ``i don't see us sending troops (to panama). i don't think it is necessary.''
on south africa, robertson said, ``i am totally opposed to apartheid ... but the thing i'm concerned about is turning south africa into a bloody battleground.''
i don't want to see a marxist state in south africa,'' robertson said
the flashing billboard broke down but at least two wedding offers still stood monday, a day that leap-year lore supposedly gives women the right to propose marriage
four women were scheduled to have their marriage proposals flashed on an electronic board in london, but british telecom's giant ``message master'' suffered an electrical glitch, said spokesman peter chandler
the couples, who stood on a street corner waiting for the proposals, were whisked to a nearby hotel for a consolation lunch
two couples walked away without announcing their intentions, but the other two said they would tie the knot
donna walker, 20, turned to her boyfriend, mark beva, 22, and said ``everything's gone wrong, but anyway will you marry me?''
a stunned beva blurted yes. aides; sub 6th-7th graf pvs with 4 grafs new to explain bgng ``dukakis and...</note>
george bush and pat robertson will skip next sunday's debate in tennessee, putting that pre-super tuesday confrontation in jeopardy, and richard gephardt has backed out of the democratic version the same day in rival albert gore jr.'s home state, aides said today
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis' staff debated the debate, with one aide saying he would not go and another saying the decision on the league of women voters' forum in nashville was still under consideration
word of candidates no-debate decisions tumbled out as the presidential contenders themselves plunged into their final week of campaigning before the biggest delegate day of the primary season
meanwhile, dukakis was celebrating another new england victory, in maine, saying he will ``surprise some people in the south'' next week on super tuesday. vice president bush claimed victory in maine on the gop side
the gop presidential hopefuls split up today after criticizing each other on taxes and trade in a debate sunday in atlanta
robertson, in jacksonville, fla., told about 500 people today, ``i've got a feeling we're going to win in florida and we're going to win in the south. ... we've got one week to the most crucial election, i believe, in the history of america, certainly this century and maybe since its beginning.''
dukakis and gephardt, the winners of the major democratic contests so far, skipped a democratic debate in houston on sunday. gephardt aides said today that he wouldn't show up for a debate in opponent albert gore jr.'s home state
gephardt, who had said last october he would participate in the debate, sent word last week that he would not, noting that it was to be in gore's home state, said janice kaplan, a spokeswoman for the league of women voters' presidential debates
dukakis aides passed out conflicting word on his intentions. political director paul jensen said he would not attend the debate; communications director leslie dach said ``no official decision had been made'' on whether or not to attend the sunday debate
league officials said dukakis had told them last fall he would participate and they have heard of no change in that stance
she said robertson _ as well as bush, who announced his plans earlier _ would not take part in the gop debate the same day. bob dole has not formally agreed to attend, and the republican debate will be called off if he decides against debating, she said
it was a son of the south, jesse jackson, who pulled the weekend's surprise, finishing a strong second to dukakis in the maine democratic caucuses on sunday
with super tuesday looming barely a week away, republican jack kemp sought to pump up his fading campaign with direct attacks on bush and senate gop leader dole, saying they will not be true to ronald reagan's legacy
they sound alike. they talk alike. they've supported every single tax increase over the last eight years,'' kemp said in a testy gop debate sunday in atlanta. ``if they're nominated, the reagan revolution is over, gone, dead.''
harsh rhetoric did not dim the good news from maine for bush and dukakis
bush's campaign claimed victory in the gop caucuses on sunday. with no official count available, his campaign gave out figures saying he more than doubled his rivals' totals in the city and town meetings
on the democratic side, dukakis won the maine caucuses easily, relying on a strong organization and his neighborly ties. he took better than 40 percent of the delegates to the state convention and at least 10 national convention delegates
today's victory gives our national campaign another push towards success on super tuesday,'' dukakis said
earlier, he told a crowd in maryland _ where he hopes to do well on march 8: ``you're an important super tuesday state. ... i think we're going to surprise some people in the south.''
dukakis' win was expected. jackson's strong second-place showing was not
the black civil rights leader campaigned relatively little in the state, but showed strength in many parts of the new england countryside to win nearly a third of the vote. a block of uncommitted delegates was in third place with the rest of the democratic field trailing
both dukakis and bush hoped to put another victory in their column on tuesday, when the non-binding vermont primaries are scheduled
the democratic candidates gather for another pre-march 8 debate tonight in williamsburg, va., before the members of the democratic leadership council. it was dlc members who put together the idea of a southern regional primary and then pushed state legislatures across the region to move their primaries to the early march date
the republicans' debate sunday in atlanta may be their last full-scale confrontation before super tuesday
bush, who is skipping the league of women voters' debate next sunday in nashville, told his three rivals that intra-party sniping is not useful
there's no point in republicans going around criticizing each other or certainly criticizing the president of the united states. what we want to do is go after the people you had here yesterday,'' bush said, referring to the democratic candidates who debated in the same hall on saturday. ``that's easy. that's slow-motion, slow targets to go for.''
kemp attacked hardest during the debate sponsored by the atlanta newspapers, accusing his opponents of sounding like democratic hopeful gephardt on trade
pat robertson and bob dole sound like dick gephardt to me on trade, and george bush and bob dole say the budget deficit is public enemy no. 1. i want to say i believe the soviet union is public enemy no. 1,'' kemp said
for his part, dole attacked bush for the reagan administration's decision to trade arms for hostages in the iran-contra affair
we never should trade arms for hostages. we shouldn't issue these reports and say we shouldn't trade arms for hostages _ the vice president's report _ and then later go to a meeting and say it's all right. we shouldn't do those things,'' dole said, holding up a report on terrorism that was written by a commission headed by bush
bush did not respond directly, but did say ``mistakes were made'' in the iran-contra affair. he has maintained throughout the affair that he did not know the arrangement was an arms-for-hostage deal
saudi arabia said monday it would not bar iranians from making a pilgrimage to mecca, islam's holiest shrine and scene of violent rioting last year
there is no trend ... to bar any moslem from performing the pilgrimage rites,'' a government official was quoted by the saudi press agency as saying
dates will be announced soon by the responsible authorities regarding the commencement of entry formalities, said the official, a representative the ministry of pilgrimage and wakf, religious endowments
the agency did not provide the official's name, but said he made the statement in response to ``recent claims by some iranian responsible officials regarding a trend to bar iranians from this year's pilgrimage.''
the saudi cities of mecca and medina harbor islam's most sacred shrines, and moslems from all over the world converge on the kingdom for the annual pilgrimage, falling this year in the latter part of july, according to the lunar calendar
thousands of iranian pilgrims staged a political demonstrations last year and more than 400, most of them iranians, were killed in subsequent clashes with saudi riot police
saudi interior minister prince nayef has issued stern warnings that no political activity would be allowed during pilgrimage
iranian minister of culture and islamic guidance hojatoleslam mohammed khatami challenged the saudi statements recently, insisting that iranian pilgrims were planning political rallies again this year
iran is persian and shiite, while the sunni sect generally dominates in persian gulf arab nations. the deep division between shiites and sunnis began with a split in islam centuries ago
prices farmers got for raw products in february declined an average of 0.8 percent from january but still were 6.6 percent above those a year earlier, the agriculture department said monday
the department's agricultural statistics board said lower prices for lettuce, tomatoes, cotton and milk contributed most to the february decrease. higher prices for cattle, hogs, corn and soybeans helped soften the declines for the other commodities, however
most commercial vegetable prices dropped sharply from a month earlier as supplies became plentiful,'' the report said. ``warm weather in the southwest pushed vegetable crops to maturity.''
but cattle and calf prices ``were the highest since may 1979'' and hog prices rose for the second month in a row, the report said. corn prices at the farm were the highest since july 1986, while soybean were the highest in more than three years
department economists say net cash income of farmers set a record in 1987 of about $57 billion. this year's net _ the difference between cash receipts and cash expenses _ may be in the range of $50 billion to $55 billion
consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987
according to the preliminary february figures, based mostly on mid-month averages, the index for crop prices was down 4.3 percent from january but averaged 11 percent more than a year ago
commercial vegetable prices dropped 33 percent from january and were down 2.2 percent from february 1987. sweet-corn prices rose from january, while all other vegetables declined. lettuce prices dropped to $11.90 per 100 pounds from $35.60 in january
feed grains and hay, collectively, showed a 3.2 percent price gain from january, averaging 23 percent more than a year earlier. corn, sorghum, oats and hay were up, while barley prices declined from january levels. cotton prices were down 6 percent from january but averaged 22 percent more than a year earlier
the index for livestock and livestock products was up 2 percent from january and 4.2 percent above februrary 1987. prices were higher for beef cattle, calves and hogs, which more than offset declines in milk, poultry and egg prices
prices of beef cattle averaged $67.90 per hundredweight, up $2.50 from january. calf prices, at $93.10, were up $4.90 per hundredweight. market hog prices rose $3.60 from january to $47.50 in february but were still below a year earlier
february farm commodity prices averaged 130 percent of a 1977 base used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures, down from a revised january reading of 131 percent. a year ago, the february index was 122 percent
no new figures for farm production costs were included in the report. those have been confined to quarterly averages because of budget cutbacks
in january, however, farm expenses were up 0.6 percent from last fall but averaged 1.4 percent below a year earlier. the next quarterly figures will be reported in april
the report said:
_cattle averaged $67.90 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally, up from $65.40 in january and the $58.80 reported for february 1987. those are averages for all types of cattle sold as beef
_hogs averaged $46.70 per 100 pounds, compared with $43 in january and $48.20 a year earlier
_corn, at $1.83 a bushel, was up from $1.77 in january and the average of $1.42 per bushel a year earlier
_wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures, averaged $2.83 per bushel, compared with $2.75 in january and $2.58 a year earlier
_rice averaged $7.85 per 100 pounds, compared with $7.70 in january and $3.83 a year earlier
_soybeans were $5.90 per bushel, compared with $5.73 in january and $4.69 a year earlier
_upland cotton was reported at 57.1 cents per pound, compared with 60.6 in january and 46.4 cents in february 1987
_eggs were 46.9 cents per dozen, compared with 49.3 cents in january and 58.3 cents a year earlier
_milk was $12.30 per 100 pounds, compared with $12.50 in january and $12.90 a year earlier
_broilers were 25.7 cents per pound, live weight, compared with 27.1 cents in january and 30.1 cents a year ago
edna brown turned 25 on monday, according to leap year standards, but lots of relatives gathered to help her celebrate her 100 years on the planet
but mrs. brown can't claim the distinction of being the only person in her family born on feb. 29, which comes around only once every four years
her great-great grandson, david jacobs, 20, is celebrating the date of his birth for only the fifth time. and her nephew, rex napier of visalia, was having his 19th leap year birthday, although he's really 76
eula jones, one of mrs. brown's 10 children, said her mother has been resting up for her party. she just had a cast removed from an arm that was broken around christmas
mother's real spunky, real sharp,'' mrs. jones said. ``we're going to take her down and get her hair done and get her ready.''
a driver whose vehicle struck a bicyclist has been sentenced to community service, most of which could be waived with a bicycle ride on a narrow highway near crested butte
it might be a real eye-opener for you,'' gunnison county court judge gerry reese told bruce hartel at his sentencing last week. ``riding a bicycle along the highway while three-ton vehicles hurl by can only be appreciated by experiencing it.''
reese decided that if hartel, 59, of littleton, rides a bicycle on a section of the highway between crested butte and crested butte south within 90 days, 100 hours out of 124 hours of court-ordered community service will be waived
reese told hartel he can walk part of the way if he gets tired, as long as he has a bicycle with him. colorado 135 is a two-lane, narrow, winding mountain highway with no shoulders
in a plea bargain, hartel pleaded no contest to careless driving and driving too fast for conditions
the charges stemmed from a sept. 22 collision with bicyclist eliane wiscocq of crested butte. she was knocked off her bike and suffered facial lacerations, a broken wrist and whiplash
hartel apologized in court and presented his driving record, which was clean
he was sentenced to 90 days of unsupervised probation and fined $561, and said his insurance company has agreed to pay wissocq's lost wages, property damage and medical expenses up to $50,000
hartel left court without commenting on the sentence
president reagan is taking a decongestant for a cold that left him with a hoarse voice for a speech monday to the annual convention of the american legion
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said reagan's physician, col. john hutton, said, ``it wasn't a flu, just a cold.'' he said reagan did not have any fever
the cold comes as reagan prepares to depart tuesday for brussels, belgium, and a two-day summit beginning wednesday with nato allies
two sisters' homes burned within a day of each other, bringing to six the number of residences they have lost to fire
pat rader and her family have lost four trailers, the most recent on wednesday
the first three burned on the same spot,'' she said. ``the one that burned (wednesday) was on the same property, but not on the same place. ``i don't know if i'll ever live in another trailer, but i won't go back there.''
on thursday, fire hit a frame home owned by her sister, wanda pratt, and her family. mrs. pratt said the house may be salvageable
the house stands near the spot where the pratts lost a mobile home to fire about three years ago
my uncle was living with us then,'' mrs. pratt said. ``he was 85. the fire started in his room, but we never knew what started it.''
mrs. rader, her husband and three children are staying with her parents in kingfield for now
i'm going to try to get me a house,'' she said. ``my stepfather and my mother own the property my trailers have been on. they're giving us a couple of acres, and we're going to try to build on it.''
capt. keith crowell of the williamson county rescue squad said monday authorities don't know what caused either fire
the streets were awash with dress blues and angry tears monday as 10,000 police officers attended last rites for edward byrne, a 22-year-old policeman killed while protecting a witness in a drug case
it was the largest police turnout for a fallen colleague in the history of the new york city police, authorities said. they came from texas and ohio, maryland and rhode island, and they lined the eight blocks approaching st. james church
eddie's murderers need to be pitied and also prayed for,'' the rev. thomas devita said in his homily during mass. ``they do not know about the sanctity of life. they cannot really know or understand what they have done, even though this is such a terrible sin.''
byrne was slain early friday as he guarded a witness who had complained to police about crack dealers working in the south jamaica section of the borough of queens. there have been no arrests. byrne, eight months on the force, was struck by three shotgun blasts
eight officers carried the coffin, draped in the green-and-white flag of the department, into the church as a police bagpiper played ``when the battle is over.'' the family followed; his father, a former city police lieutenant, carried a color photograph of his son
today we commit eddie back to our god and father, to god who gave us ed 22 years ago. ... if only it could have been longer,'' the priest said
he remembered byrne as a smiling storyteller, an enthusiastic friend, relative and police officer. byrne turned 22 nine days ago
maybe eddie has done more in eight short months than other people will do in a lifetime,'' devita said. ``he sacrificed his life trying to protect the lives of others.''
six police helicopters followed overhead as the body was taken to st. charles cemetery for interment
after the mass, the rev. charles norris of bethesda missionary baptism church, located in the 103rd precinct where byrne served, climbed to the altar to speak in support of police who are fighting drugs _ ``this venom.''
mayor edward i. koch also spoke from the altar after the service. he said he felt the same sadness he felt upon the deaths of franklin d. roosevelt, john f. kennedy and martin luther king jr
in a strange way, edward byrne's death has the same importance,'' koch said. ``if drug trafficking has become so bold that they can engage in the assassination of a police officer, then our whole society is at risk. ... that is why his death is so important.''
all four republicans and at least one democrat appear to be passing up sunday's presidential debates in nashville, a league of women voters spokeswoman said monday
republicans george bush and pat robertson sent word they would not participate, nashville president carole bucy said. jack kemp had never accepted the debate invitation, she said
the fourth epublican, bob dole, said he was willing to attend, but only if robertson and bush participated. ``i'm not sure i want to spend an hour with jack kemp,'' he said in jackson, miss
democrat richard gephardt advised the league he would not attend the nashville debate
aides to michael dukakis were sending out conflicting signals. political director paul jensen said he would not attend the debate; communications director leslie dach said ``no official decision had been made'' on whether or not to attend the sunday debate
gephardt and dukakis skipped a democratic debate in houston on sunday, leaving the forum to sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, jesse jackson, sen. paul simon of illinois and gary hart. problems</head>
as a general rule, the agriculture department is making progress but still lags in expanding jobs and services to black americans, a special review panel said monday
in 1986, agriculture secretary richard e. lyng directed all agencies in the department to carry out new guidelines to improve usda compliance with civil rights and equal opportunity standards
as part of the department's february observance of black history month, five study groups looked at how usda has performed since then
black employees continue a modest but upward movement in all occupational categories,'' the report said. ``some increases have been realized both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of total usda employment. this is especially important because the increases have occurred at a time when overall employment in usda was declining.''
the usda employs the equivalent of approximately 102,000 full time employees, according to recent budget documents. the task force report said blacks comprise 8.4 percent of the department's employees, up from 8.1 percent in 1986. but that ``is low compared with other federal agencies,'' it added
to continue to improve its equal opportunity posture, usda must realize larger increases in the number of blacks hired, promoted and trained,'' the report said. ``and such increases mus be realized at a faster pace. additionally the department must place emphasis on retention strategies once black employees are recruited at hired.''
the task force report said there are ``encouraging signs'' that usda agencies are beginning to address the complex problems of black farmers and their declining numbers
coordinated efforts between the soil conservation service, farmers home administration and extension service are just beginning to show limited success at eliminating the historical factors militating against small and economically disadvantaged farmers,'' the report said
the mediator of peace talks between the government and the contra rebels said the sandinistas' insistence on a limited agenda for the discussions is a step backward
cardinal miguel obando y bravo, the mediator, broke off the last round of meetings in guatemala on feb. 19, saying the two sides remained far apart on ways to end the 7-year-old war
since then, the roman catholic prelate has charged the leftist sandinista government with failing to compromise and president daniel ortega has criticized the ``abrupt'' end to the second set of direct talks
ortega, in a speech sunday, reiterated that the discussions should be limited to how to arrange a truce. the u.s.-backed contras and obando y bravo are seeking to discuss political reforms as well as a cease-fire
earlier sunday, the cardinal said the government's position represented ``a step backward'' for his plan. the cardinal declined to say whether further talks would be held, saying, ``we'll have to reflect on that.''
agreement on details of a cease-fire could deter congress from voting for non-lethal aid for the rebels
the democrat-controlled house on feb. 3 narrowly voted down president reagan's proposal for $36.2 million in funding, including $3.6 million in military financing
in the recent talks, obando y bravo expanded his role by offering his own peace plan. in addition to cease-fire proposals, it calls for complete press freedom, renewed talks with internal opposition parties, a revision of the military draft law and a total amnesty, reforms long sought by the contras
the sandinistas agreed to discuss the sections of the cardinal's proposal that had to do with a cease-fire, but they have refused to enter into what they call a ``political dialogue'' with the rebels
in a peace plan signed aug. 7, the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, guatemala, costa rica and honduras committed themselves to implementing cease-fires, amnesties and greater democracy and called for an end to outside aid to insurgencies
nicaragua has permitted the reopening of some newspapers and radio stations it had closed. the government maintains that a full amnesty will be granted when there is a cease-fire
talks with the internal political opposition parties _ also mandated by the peace plan _ broke down in december when the government refused to discuss a new constitution
the sandinistas accuse the cardinal, often harshly critical of the government, of siding with the contras
the cardinal called on those attending his sunday mass to pray for peace. he estimates that 15 nicaraguans die each day because of the war
nicaragua's internal problems have been increasing. opposition parties, taking advantage of new freedoms since the state of emergency was lifted in january, have staged several demonstrations against the sandinistas
the sandinistas have held their own marches to show their strength and at times have quelled opposition demonstrations
the sandinistas came to power in a 1979 revolution that ousted pro-american dictator anastasio somoza
only three applicants for concealed weapon permits under florida's new gun law have been turned down because of previous crimes, but officials said monday many convictions don't show up because of loopholes
as of thursday, 20,393 floridians had received concealed weapons permits under the law effective oct. 1, state records show. a total of 26,086 applications have been received, and of those only 20 have been denied, said marilyn thompson, chief of the bureau of concealed weapons
thirteen were rejected because of documentation problems, four for other reasons and three because of a criminal history, ms. thompson said
under certain circumstances, the state cannot deny permits to admitted felons, people with a history of violent crimes and those with drinking and psychological problems, said ms. thompson
unless a judge formally hands down a guilty verdict, a defendant who pleads guilty or no contest to either a felony or a misdemeanor has not been formally convicted, she said. such withholding of adjudication, which does not create a criminal record, is usually part of a plea bargain on first offenses or lesser offenses and often is accompanied by probation
i can only deny a permit under the law if they have been formally convicted of a felony by a judge,'' ms. thompson said
unadjudicated cases are not entered into the florida department of law enforcement computer system, which the bureau uses to check criminal backgrounds
no adjudication means there is no guilt,'' marion hammer, a lobbyist for unified sportsmen of florida, a group backed by the national rifle association. ``and if there is no guilt, you can't take a person's rights away _ whether that's the right to vote or the right to bear arms
stewart schurr of the fdle said he doubted that unadjudicated defendants receiving concealed weapon permits would lead to a murder increase
the sort of people who do these crimes don't go get a permit so that they can conceal the gun and sneak up on someone,'' he said. ``in other words, i wouldn't be comfortable saying the law has had any kind of effect.''
but some people, including tourism officials, fear florida could develop a ``wild west'' image
here in canada, anything to do with florida makes front page _ especially bad news,'' said ellis webber, the florida tourism department's marketing director for canada, which ships the sunshine state 1.5 million tourists yearly
before lawmakers closed a legal loophole allowing open carrying of firearms, ``we got telephone calls from people concerned about going to florida and seeing people strolling down the shopping mall with guns on their hips,'' he said
president reagan, who is of irish ancestry, paid tribute to the irish monday in a st. patrick's day message
two and a half weeks ahead of time, reagan took note of the commemoration of st. patrick's day on march 17, saying ``i seek to remind america and the world of the debt we owe to the irish people.''
through the ages, he said, the irish people ``have created and perpetuated a unique heritage of faith and freedom, of humor and hope, of scholarship and sanctity and sacrifice.''
with faith and fearlessness, st. patrick brought christianity to ireland a millennium and a half ago,'' reagan's message said. ``the annals reveals the irish people's eagerness to embrace the faith and to keep it; that trait remains to this day, a tribute to the apostle of ireland and to his flock in every generation.''
may america and ireland always cherish each other and the kinship in which we hold st. patrick's day,'' he said
rain was scattered over parts of the west on monday, with some snow around the great lakes, and record high temperatures were reported on the northern plains
rain was scattered over west-central california and western washington state during the morning. rain and thundershowers also extended over northwestern utah
santa maria, calif., got 1.01 inches of rain in the six hours up to 1 p.m. est
snow fell along lake superior, over northwestern lower michigan and across much of northern new york state, but no measurable snowfall was reported in that same six-hour period
elsewhere, showers were scattered over east-central texas
on the northern plains, aberdeen, s.d., reached a record 45 degrees under a sunny sky, and bismarck, n.d., posted a record 46 degrees
advisories for strong, gusty wind were posted over the mountains of central california, where gusts to 40 mph were measured at sandberg
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 11 degrees at sault ste. marie, mich., to 86 at alice, laredo and mcallen, texas. the low for the day was 9 degrees below zero at houlton, maine
for tuesday, scattered showers were forecast from southern idaho across arizona and western colorado
highs in the teens and 20s were predicted over the great lakes and northern new england; in the 30s and 40s from central new england across the virginias, the ohio valley, from southern minnesota across northern iowa, over the northern plains and the upper missouri basin, and from southern colorado into central arizona; in the 70s over much of florida and the desert southwest, and the southern plains; near 80 across southern texas; and in the 50s and 60s over the remainder of the nation
gov. evan mecham faces charges detailed in 23 counts in his impeachment trial before the arizona senate
the articles of impeachment brought against him by the house are the equivalent of an indictment in criminal court. the specifics center on three alleged violations of law _ misuse of $80,000 in state funds, concealment of a campaign loan and obstruction of justice in trying to thwart investigation of an alleged death threat
briefly, these are the accusations:
_ misuse of state funds
in may 1987, a governor's protocol fund was created from funds raised by the governor's inaugural ball. the funds had been earmarked to pay off mecham's campaign debts, but a state law limiting campaign contributions precluded that use. two months after the protocol fund was established to promote interests of the state, $80,000 from it was loaned to mecham's automobile agency. the loan has been repaid, but prosecutors contend mecham, with his son, dennis, tried to conceal an illegal loan of state funds
mecham says the protocol fund was private, not state money, and that he broke no law by loaning it to his dealership
_ concealment of a $350,000 campaign loan
in october 1986, tempe developer barry wolfson loaned $350,000 to the mecham for governor campaign. the loan, which has been repaid, was not reported properly on required disclosure statements
mecham says he didn't try to conceal the loan but contends his brother, willard, who was his campaign treasurer, tried to save time by lumping it in with other funds on the financial statements without including wolfson's name
_ obstruction of justice by thwarting investigation of a death threat
on nov. 12, 1987, lee watkins, an assistant director of the department of administation, allegedly threatened to harm donna carlson, the governor's former legislative liaison who then was expected to testify in a grand jury investigation of mecham's reporting of the $350,000 campaign loan
watkins is alleged to have said if ms. carlson did not keep her mouth shut, she would ``take a long boat ride'' from which she wouldn't return. ralph milstead, director of the department of public safety, says mecham ordered him not to cooperate with the arizona attorney general's office in its investigation of the death threat allegation
mecham says he had already checked out the alleged death threat and considered it ``a lot of hot air.''
the new york board of elections ruled monday that former sen. gary hart, d-colo., failed to qualify for the state's april 19 democratic presidential primary ballot
petitions meant to put hart on the ballot contained only 6,864 signatures, more than 3,000 under the required number, said board spokesman steven lafever
to get on the ballot, democratic candidates must file petitions bearing signatures of at least 10,000 registered democrats and at least 100 of those must come from each of 17 of the state's 34 congressional districts
he has 14 days to go into court with an appeal,'' lafever said. ``but it's really difficult (to win in court) if you don't even have the 10,000'' signatures, he added
among other democratic candidates, jesse jackson has collected more than 64,000 signatures, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis got 42,615, rep. richard gephardt of missouri collected 22,477, sen. paul simon of illinois had 22,076, and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee had 21,759
a group of democratic county clerks filed petitions containing more than 18,000 signatures to get a spot on the ballot for ``uncommitted.'' most of those clerks want new york gov. mario cuomo to run
while cuomo has said he is not a presidential candidate, he has refused to rul out accepting a draft for the nomination if there is a deadlocked national convention when the democrats meet in atlanta in july
political extremist lyndon larouche filed petitions containing 23,061 signatures. those petitions may be challenged by mainstream democrats
georgia's law banning exit polls within 250 feet of voting places violates the constitution's free-speech guarantee, an attorney representing three major television networks argued in court monday
the 1985 law does not define exit poll and therefore ``allows certain types of speech but not others,'' said floyd abrams
reporters ``can ask questions and take notes as long as they don't do it in a systematic way,'' abrams told u.s. district judge robert hall in a hearing on a lawsuit filed by abc, nbc and cbs against georgia and fulton county election officials
but patrick mckee, an assistant attorney general representing state elections officials, said poll workers have interpreted the law as disallowing anyone from questioning voters about their vote within 250 feet of the polling place
former state rep. claude bray, d-manchester, who headed the house state governmental affairs committee when it considered the exit poll bill, said election officials mostly in metropolitan atlanta complained that voters were being intimidated by exit poll takers
this was a bill to help the voters keep their privacy so they could vote and leave without being harassed,'' he said
supporters
supporters of rep. richard gephardt attended news conferences around his home state monday to give endorsements to the democratic presidential candidate
simultaneous news conferences at court houses, public meeting places and campaign headquarters in at least 50 counties brought hundreds of local officials out to show support for gephardt's campaign, members of his campaign staff said
supporters held rallies at campaign headquarters in springfield, kansas city and columbia, while in some rural counties, supporters joined forces to hold combined rallies on what they called ``dick gephardt endorsement day in missouri.''
in st. louis, lt. gov. harriett woods told supporters who gathered at the foot of the gateway arch that missourians should be proud of gephardt and could expect him to serve their country well. fired at tehran, acknowleding late-night explosions.</note>
iraq said it retaliated for pre-dawn missile attacks on baghdad by firing long-range rockets into the heart of tehran monday. iran reported 16 people killed in the bombing of a hospital
the official iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, said its gunners fired five surface-to-surface missiles into tehran after two similar projectiles had exploded in baghdad, killing and wounding ``many civilians.''
iran's islamic republic news agency irna, also monitored in nicosia, said in urgent dispatches that ``two loud explosions'' were heard after nightfall in tehran and ``there may have been casualties and damage.''
it said the blasts, 10 minutes apart, were ``from fresh iraqi attacks'' but gave no other details
earlier, irna said tehran was bombed twice in iraqi air raids but made no mention of missile attacks on the city
it said in one of the raids, 16 people were killed and ``dozens wounded, including newborn babies,'' at a tehran hospital
irna did not identify the hospital but said several people were buried under the debris. tehran radio urged iranians to take refuge in bomb shelters
the later communique carried by irna indicated there was confusion over the iraqi attacks, possibly because iraq had not previously used surface-to-surface missiles against tehran in the war that began in september 1980. instead it had relied on its warplanes to strike deep inside iranian territory
the iraqi rockets will reduce the iranian capital to rubble,'' the iraqi news agency said, quoting an unidentified military spokesman. ``the iraqi rockets will fall on tehran all night until the city is demolished on the heads of its rulers.''
it said three missiles were fired at 5:45 p.m., 5:55 p.m. and 6:08 p.m., followed by two more at 11:10 p.m. and 11:20 p.m
iraq was not known to have any surface-to-surface missiles capable of reaching the iranian capital about 200 miles east of the iraqi border
the iraqi news agency quoted a military spokesman as saying the missiles fired monday ``had been designed by iraqi minds and put together by iraqi hands as a gift to the leader of iraq (president saddam hussein) and the people of iraq.''
iraq's attacks began about 12 hours after iranian missiles hit baghdad
irna quoted a revolutionary guards communique as saying the iranian missiles were aimed at the headquarters of iraq's state-run television and radio network and two military targets in baghdad
state-run baghdad radio said two missiles exploded in the city of 5 million people. it reported a military communique said: ``many iraqis were killed, among them women, children and old people. many more were wounded and many houses were destroyed.'' no casualty figures were given
the iraqi news agency also reported that iranian artillery shelled residential areas in the southern port of basra, the border town of khanaqin and sirwan in northeast iraq throughout the night. it made no mention of casualties
it was the third day of attacks on population and industrial centers. the attacks began saturday when iraqi warplanes bombed tehran for the first time since january 1987
on sunday, iran said its forces fired three surface-to-surface missiles in 40 minutes in retaliation for the iraqi air raids on ``non-military areas.'' it said 28 civilians were killed and scores were wounded in the iraqi raids
the exchange of attacks and reported use by iraq of long-range missiles heightened fears that the persian gulf foes are locked in a fresh round of the ``war of the cities.''
iran has fired 37 missiles into baghdad since that phase of the war began in march 1985, but had not targeted baghdad since nov. 8
meanwhile, president ali khamenei of iran warned the u.n. security council not to approve any resolution imposing an arms embargo on iran for failing to agree to cease-fire calls
irna quoted khamenei as saying such a move would mean ``the end of all political solutions to the war, imposed by iraq.''
the united states and its allies have been lobbying for an arms embargo against iran because of its refusal to agree to security council resolution 598 adopted in july. iraq has said it would agree to the resolution, which calls for a cease-fire, if iran did
khamenei said again that iran would not accept any settlement until iraq has been condmned as the aggressor and punished by the international community, according to irna. schools</head>
about one non-school building in seven contains potentially dangerous asbestos that's been damaged and one in 11 has significant damage, the environmental protection agency told congress on monday
however, administrator lee m. thomas said it might do more harm than good to begin a major regulatory program affecting such buildings while epa, states and communities are trying to deal with asbestos in schools
the asbestos in question is ``friable'' _ it can be crumbled by slight pressure, such as a hand squeeze, and release fibers to the air. though asbestos has not been permitted in new buildings since 1978, it was used in millions of structures from the 1920s on
the fibers, if breathed, can cause lung cancer and other illness. the cancer may not show up for 40 years, and the danger increases the earlier the exposure _ which is why school children are such a concern
thomas did call for increased grants to states to improve enforcement of existing regulations and funds to advise building owners, to increase the supply of inspectors and to develop guidance for dealing with pipe and boiler insulation. his estimates totalled $6.6 million a year for the next three years
rep. james florio, d-n.j., whose pressure has helped win passage of existing asbestos-in-schools programs, said in a statement, ``everything in this report points toward aggressive federal intervention except epa's recommendations, which amount to nothing more than sweeping this alarming problem under the rug.''
congress required the report on the status of asbestos in non-school buildings in 1986. in partial response, epa subjected a 1984 building survey to more detailed analysis, reporting for the first time the condition of asbestos it found
the agency had reported that about 20 percent of the buildings contained friable asbestos. about 35 percent of schools, however, already were known to have such asbestos, and congress has required tighter school regulations
by october 1988, all schools must adopt asbestos management plans to take effect in july 1989. ``the successulf implementation of this school program should remain our first concern, and we all have much to learn from it,'' wrote thomas. ``i fear a major initiative in other buildings could do more harm that good.''
john a. moore, assistant administrator for pesticides and toxic substances, ``we've got finite resources ... a finite number of people who are experts.''
the report said carrying out the school regulations will cost about $3 billion and a similar program for other buildings could cost $51 billion
epa's 1984 survey did not cover elementary and secondary schools, state and local government buildings or apartment buildings of fewer than 10 units, leaving 3.6 million buildings to be sampled. an estimated 14 percent of the buildings, 501,000, contained damaged friable asbestos, and 9 percent, or 317,000, contained significantly damaged friable asbestos
since only 231 buildings were tested, the range of uncertainty in the results was wide. epa said there was a 95 percent chance the figure reported as 20 percent was somewhere between 14 percent and 27 percent; the 14 percent damage figure was between 6 percent and 22 percent and the 9 percent significant damage could be anywhere from zero percent to 19 percent
this and other statistical points were criticized by the safe buildings alliance, a trade association of former asbestos product manufacturers, which said, for example, that epa's surveyors disagreed with each other 95 percent of the time on the condition of the asbestos they were looking at
moore, however, said the agency's methods had been approved by outside experts
bill borwegen, health and safety director of the service employees international union, said, ``the gut level issue here is the right to know. it's federal policy that workers have the right to know what dangerous chemicals they're dealing with. ... we want to inform building occupants if there's a hazard.''
jean-bedel bokassa, a village chief's son who made himself president for life and then emperor, was spared the death penalty monday for murders committed during his 14-year reign
president andre kolingba commuted bokassa's sentence in an order announced on the national radio
bokassa was convicted june 12, 1987, of ordering the murders of at least 20 political opponents. he also was convicted of diverting huge sums from the state treasury
the former leader, who had changed the name of his country to the central african empire and proclaimed himself bokassa i, unsuccessfully appealed the verdict to the supreme court
during the course of this trial i discovered crimes of which i know nothing,'' he said. ``i assume the moral responsibility. i affirm my innocence of the facts against me. i was motivated only by the desire to serve my country. today, i only want to live in peace as a simple citizen.''
western governments and some african leaders had asked gen. kolingba to spare bokassa. kolingba previously commuted other death sentences imposed in this former french colony, and is said to oppose capital punishment
bokassa went into exile after he was overthrown in september 1979 in a french-backed coup after the deaths in custody of 100 schoolchildren who protested a government order to wear expensive uniforms produced at a factory run by the emperor's wife. bokassa was alleged to have personally beaten 17 of them to death
a court in this nation of 3 million people, which he had ruled since 1966, convicted him in absentia and sentenced him to death in 1980
in late 1986, he returned from france unexpectedly ``to be judged'' by his countrymen. he was tried for offenses ranging from corruption to murder and cannibalism
during the six-month trial, prosecutor gabriel mbodou said: ``there were no extenuating circumstances whatever in the odious acts committed by the accused, his atrocities and his greed which plunged the entire country into a nightmare throughout the 14 years of his bloody reign.''
the french legal system used in the central african republic obliged the government to try bokassa again
officials and western diplomats said privately last year that kolingba probably would commute a death sentence for fear execution would stir unrest among bokassa's minority m'baka tribe in the southwest corner of the landlocked nation
bokassa, 67, was educated in roman catholic mission schools. he joined the french army, won a dozen combat medals in indochina and achieved the rank of captain
when the country became independent in 1960, president david dacko asked bokassa to form an army. he led a coup against dacko in december 1965
after bokassa proclaimed himself emperor, he was crowned in a 1977 ceremony that cost more than $200 million, one-quarter of the nation's annual revenue
president reagan says he hopes the summer olympics in seoul, south korea, will be incident-free and that he has confidence in newly inaugurated president roh tae woo
in responses to questions submitted by the south korean newspaper, dong-a ilbo, reagan said a smoothly run olympics competition in september ``is in everyone's interests.''
the prospect of north korea, or anyone else's, attempts to disrupt the games through violence is a danger that we and the soviets can agree to work against.''
the key problem in korea is north korea's proclivity to use violence,'' reagan said, noting the bombing last november of a south korean airliner off the coast of burma. ``the world was shocked again by the recent murder of 115 innocent people aboard kal-858 by north korea.''
we hope that moscow will use its close relations with pyongyang to urge moderation and to encourage the resumption of direct north-south contacts on practical ways to reduce tension,'' the president said. ``it is time for the north to eschew violence and get down to the serious business of resuming dialogue with seoul.''
reagan, in response to a question about whether he will meet soon with roh, replied that ``talk now of the details of summits and such seems a bit premature.''
as you know, i met president-elect roh in washington last year,'' he said. ``he impressed me as a man committed to the democratization of your country because he knew that was what koreans, including himself, wanted.''
north korea has been demanding to be a co-host of the olympics, but the international olympic committee and south korea have rejected the demand
a woman who claimed she was a north korean agent, kim hyon hui, made a televised confession in seoul last month in which she said she destroyed the kal flight to disrupt the olympics
north korea has denied it had anything to do with the bombing. shore</head>
a small boat said to be carrying about 40 illegal aliens from the dominican republic sank in rough seas just off the west coast, but a survivor said monday he believed most made it to shore
one person was in custody, another hospitalized, two bodies were recovered and a third was spotted but washed away before it could be retrieved, said luis garcia, an agent of the u.s. immigration and naturalization service
garcia spoke in a telephone interview from aguadilla, about five miles from aguada
hundreds of dominicans leave in wooden boats each year on the dangerous, 90-mile journey to puerto rico in search of a better life. estimates by u.s. officials of the number of dominicans living illegally in puerto rico range from 40,000 to 160,000
the bodies were of two girls, one 14 and the other 16, police in aguada said. the boat, estimated at 20-30 feet long, sank sunday evening off aguada, about 85 miles west of san juan
garcia said miguel bigay, a survivor who was with him during the interview, reported seeing most of the passengers scramble ashore and flee
he said most were able to get to shore with him,'' garcia said. ``the people who got to shore ran off and hid in the brush.''
bigay, who gave his age as about 30 and said he was a part-time truck driver, said the boat left a beach saturday night in the southeastern dominican province of higuey with 40-45 passengers, including eight women
it crossed the 90-mile mona passage between the dominican republic and puerto rico in good weather, but then the see became rough and a big wave overturned the boat about one-eighth of a mile from aguada, bigay said
garcia quoted him as saying: ``people were screaming and calling for help.''
bigay said he managed to swim ashore but ``thought he was going to drown because the waves pushed him down every time they passed over him,'' garcia said
those in the boat were from different towns and did not appear to know each other, bigay said. police caught him on shore and garcia said he would be returned to the dominican republic
officials continued searching, but garcia said he doubted more survivors would be found because they ``managed to get somewhere else ... and escaped detention.''
pieces of boards believed to be from the boat were on the beach, along with articles of clothing and a plastic bag labeled ``dominican republic.''
at least 16 dominicans drowned in december 1986 off rincon, a few miles away, when their boat capsized near shore. last october, 50 or more dominicans are believed to have died when their boat sank about three miles off the northeast coast of the dominican republic
sen. albert gore jr.'s presidential campaign on monday took out a loan to pay for media saturation going into next week's super tuesday primaries, a campaign spokesman said
we have borrowed some money,'' said press spokesman mike kopp. but he declined to say how much, saying that was confidential campaign strategy information
we're gong to saturate super tuesday ... we want to pour it on,'' before the march 8 series of 20 primaries and caucuses on which gore has staked his democratic campaign, kopp said
he insisted, however that the campaign is not in financial trouble and only borrowed the money as ``icing on the cake'' for the extensive media buy the tennessee senator already has in place
in tennessee, his state campaign treasurer johnny hayes said monday that gore has taken a $1 million line of credit against which money will be borrowed for a tv blitz in 20 states
he said part of the credit line was established with tennessee banks
kopp reiterated gore's pledge to spend more money on the super tuesday contests than any other candidate
gore's public financial statement through jan. 31 showed that he had just over $2 million in the bank at that point, considerably less than the $4 million that money leader michael dukakis had on hand. kopp said gore has raised about $1.2 million in february
the campaign has declined to give any specifics on its spending, saying it does not want to tip off its rivals
kopp said new commercials will go on the air tuesday, following on the biographical spots that have been running on cable tv nationwide and on local markets in 14 southern and border states for the past three weeks
the ads are produced both by the campaign group, gore's initial media consultants, and by raymond strother, a media consultant hired last week
kopp said the new ads will be message-oriented, touting gore's record. he said they do not include attacks on other candidates
strother traveled with gore last tuesday, and the candidate has been giving a new emphasis in recent days to his congressional record being one of championing ``the average working man and woman.''
kopp would not rule out the possibility of such ads, which was essentially the same stance he took last week when asked to comment on the $1 million loan
television advertising is seen as a major factor to reach the voters across the vast super tuesday spread of states
dukakis, the massachussetts governor, was advertising on prime time television during the olympics in miami last week. it was also a biographical commercial
dukakis aides said commercials were also running in texas and maryland
aides for u.s. rep. richard gephardt of missouri said his commercial promising trade retaliation to open up foreign markets was going on the air in the south over the weekend
hundreds of vatican lay employees pledged to donate part of their day's salary monday to pope john paul ii in a labor protest which a vatican official denounced as ``completely unacceptable.''
mario cerullo, president of the association of lay vatican workers, said preliminary counts showed more than 90 percent of the 1,800 lay employees took part. the employees work at vatican museums, the post office, main library, the daily newspaper l'osservatore romano, vatican radio and many offices
workers performed their jobs as usual but signed a special form promising to donate their first three hours' pay to the pope to help feed the poor, cerullo said. he estimated donations would total about $40,000
the labor action _ called by the association an ``active strike'' _ was called to protest plans to change the vatican workers' pay schedule and to demand creation of a special office to resolve labor disputes in the world's smallest city-state
the vatican employees want dignity and respect,'' cerullo said in an interview. ``we hate to bother the holy father but we had to do something to show our unhappiness. i hope this is the first and last time.''
archbishop jan schotte, a belgian who handles labor relations for the vatican, said in letters to cerullo and vatican-based cardinals that the protest was unjustified, extreme and ``completely unacceptable.''
he said salary and work conditions were ``superior to those existing in comparable work places'' and that negotiations could lead shortly to creation of a special labor office
cerullo said vatican employees' salaries range from $927 a month to $1,370. the workers are exempt from italian taxes, work a 36-hour week and have one month of vacation and 26 paid holidays
the strike was triggered by the vatican's recent decision to pay workers at the end of each month instead of at the beginning
people in other countries are becoming less willing to lend money to the united states, the head of the international monetary fund said monday
the congressional joint economic committee has predicted that u.s. debt would reach about $400 billion at the end of last year. it is growing at about $150 billion annually
i have looked at a very long historical set of figures,'' said michel camdessus, the fund's managing director. ``and i have to tell you that there are no precedents. each time similar imbalances have been... reduced, it was through recession ..
our latest projections suggest that, on present policies and exchange rates, the imbalances would still continue to be very large over the medium term,'' he told a conference sponsored by the overseas development council, a private study group concerned with problems of the third world
for some time, the growth of u.s. debt has not been matched by the willingness of business people in other countries to lend more, he said
the risks that this portends for renewed disturbances in financial markets, for increased protectionist pressures, and for a weakening in global economic activity need no elaboration here,'' said camdessus, who is french
he said the job of the fund is to help all 152 member countries in setting strategy that will make them grow
he suggested that for a long time u.s. output must grow faster than spending and that countries with surpluses have to do the reverse. the process, camdessus said, should take place without either a slow-down in business or increased inflation
he did not name the surplus countries, but japan and west germany are the major nations which in recent years have been selling more goods than they buy. surpluses have also been mounting in taiwan, south korea and other newly industrializing areas
camdessus went on to say that nothing can be done without reducing the u.s. budget deficit
no reasonable policy instrument that can contribute to this end should be ignored,'' he said
the u.s. treasury must borrow to meet the deficit, and much of the money it borrows comes from abroad. for the year ending last sept. 30, the deficit was about $149 billion
camdessus called for new proposals that would help cut the debt of third world countries
any ... proposal that would be market-based and would share in a mutually agreed fashion between debtors and creditors the discount on debt and the benefits of adjustment ... could only be welcome,'' he said
also addressing the conference was american express chairman james d. robinson iii, who suggested creation of a new international financial organization to help ease the debt crisis of developing nations by buying their loans
robinson said the organization, which he named ``the institute of international debt and development,'' would buy outstanding third world loans at a discount
one possibility, he suggested, would be for the loans to be acquired at about 60 percent of face value
the organization would then offer the banks which had held the loans ``new, long-term, high-quality obligations,'' including bonds and certain forms of stock, robinson said. to update with reagan to issue no new sanctions against panama; picks up 10th graf pvs, bgng: over the; adds 1 graf to include embassy plans to announce legal action against noriega government</note>
panama's ambassador the united states, proclaiming his loyalty to president eric arturo delvalle, refused to relinquish the embassy on monday to an envoy designated by the military controlled government to replace him
the second-ranking panamanian official at the country's united nations mission, leonardo kam, showed up at the embassy to assume his duties, but ambassador juan b. sosa refused to turn the mission over to him
kam was appointed last friday by the new government that was formed after delvalle was ousted by the national assembly, which is dominated by supporters of military strong man gen. manuel antonio noriega
after what kam described as a ``frank'' discussion monday, he departed the embassy. since friday, sosa has maintained that the vote to oust delvalle was unconstitutional and he has refused to step down
delvalle's dismissal was touched off by his bid thursday to fire noriega, who ignored the order and then rallied his followers in the assembly to replace delvalle with the former education minister, manuel solis palma
before his encounter with kam, sosa was asked by a reporter about the position of other embassy diplomats. ``the panamanian embassy is loyal to its ambassador and the ambassador is loyal to president delvalle,'' he said
reagan administration officials, meanwhile, said delvalle's attempt to reinstate himself as president has been strengthened by going into hiding and refusing to flee the country. he has been at an undisclosed location in panama since the weekend
delvalle is viewed in washington as a more effective symbol for opposition forces by being inside panama than he would if he had left the country
the administration has been pursuing other means to restore delvalle to office and to end noriega's five-year domination of the country's political life. a number of economic sanctions, including a trade embargo, are under consideration, and high-level meetings on that subject were held monday
a u.s. official said monday that president reagan planned no new economic sanctions against panama, even though he has determined that panama has not been cooperating in curbing drug trafficking to the united states
the official, speaking only on condition of anonymity, said penalties to be announced tuesday already have been applied against panama and thus will have no material impact on that country
under a 1986 law, countries which do not take steps to halt drug trafficking to the united states are no longer eligible for u.s. aid and are not entitled to u.s. support for their assistance requests to international lending institutions
noriega was indicted by two u.s. grand juries on feb. 5 on charges that he is a major figure in an international drug smuggling conspiracy
over the weekend, noriega won a credentials skirmish at the organization of american states when his oas ambassador, ricardo leyton, was permitted to occupy panama's seat for a meeting on the panamanian crisis
the united states had supported the seating of lawrence chewing fabrega, a panamanian diplomat who broke with noriega two weeks ago
although the oas refused to take a stand on the panamanian situation, a number of latin american governments have backed delvalle. they include el salvador, argentina, venezuela, uruguay, the dominican republic, bolivia and ecuador
some officials have been anxious about the safety of the 10,000 u.s. military personnel in panama and the thousands of other americans there in civilian capacities but noriega has said all americans in panama will be safe
meanwhile, panamanian opposition leaders in washington have been stepping up their activities against noriega. they have been telephoning panamanian diplomatic missions around the world asking them to withhold the fees they receive for consular services and other activities instead of sending the money back to panama for use by the new government
embassy officials said that on tuesday they would reveal ``legal steps that have been taken against the dictatorship of noriega.'' crime</head> samford in alabama, sted south carolina</note>
nancy reagan said monday that casual users of drugs are an ``accomplice to murder'' because they help finance traffickers willing to commit brutal crimes to keep supply lines open
kicking off a white house conference for a drug-free america at which the federal government's anti-drug efforts were criticized, mrs. reagan dramatized her ``just-say-no'' campaign with a speech focusing on those whose lives have been ruined by drugs
with president reagan serving in the unusual role of warm-up speaker, the first couple talked about the drug problem from both the supply and demand vantage points
with all the headlines about how we're losing the drug war, let's keep in mind the progress we've made,'' the president told conference participants at a local hotel. he ticked off statistics he said show the united states is making headway, saying ``drug seizures are at an all-time high.''
but as significant as stopping smugglers and pushers is, ending the demand for drugs is how, in the end, we'll win,'' the president said
mrs. reagan picked up the subject there, saying that while progress has been made, ``many ignorant ideas persist. and one of the worst is the casual user's justification that drug use is a victimless crime, that drugs don't hurt anyone except the person who's using them.''
she called attention to several people in the audience who lost loved ones because of drug abuse and cited the murder of colombia's chief prosecutor, attorney general carlos hoyos, who was abducted by a half-dozen gunmen whom the government accused of working for local cocaine barons
hoyos' bullet-riddled body was was found blindfolded and handcuffed
the government blamed his abduction and death on the medillin cartel, which u.s. officials say controls 80 percent of cocaine entering the united states
the people who casually use cocaine are responsible,'' mrs. reagan said, ``because their money bought those bullets. they provided the high stakes that murdered those men, plus hundreds of others in colombia.''
she dismissed ``the notion that the mellow marijuana user doesn't hurt anyone,'' pointing to the murder of american drug agent enrique camarena salazar in the aftermath of the eradication of a 10,000-acre plantation in mexico
the casual user may think when he takes a line of cocaine or smokes a joint in the privacy of his nice condo, listening to his expensive stereo, that he's somehow not bothering anyone,'' she said. ``but there is a trail of death and destruction that leads directly to his door.''
the casual drug user cannot morally escape responsibility for the action of drug traffickers and dealings,'' she said. ``i'm saying that if you're a casual drug user, you're an accomplice to murder.''
while the reagans helped kick off the drug conference, the administration came in for some criticism on its anti-drug abuse efforts, with marion barry, the mayor of the district of columbia, complaining that not enough was being done
barry, facing a record murder rate in nation's capital fueled by warring drug dealers, said the problem in cities has reached ``catastrophic dimensions.''
we're beginning to lose the war on drug and alcohol abuse,'' barry said in his welcoming remarks, telling the conference his was the ``view from the cities. the united states government has not done enough to stop drugs from coming into this country.''
we must say to colombia, peru and mexico, we're not going to take it anymore. heroin and cocaine does not grow here, it's brought here. we must stop it, stop it, stop it from coming here,'' barry said
a private study released last week said the washington area's drug problem is almost unrivaled among large cities and that drug abuse has grown in the area's suburbs more than in any other suburban area in the nation
in her address, mrs. reagan alluded to this problem, saying that ``in saturday's washington post, there was one page in which every article was a local drug story _ and there was another local drug story on the front page.''
we must face the fact that drugs are tearing our communities apart.''
rep. charles rangel, d-n.y., chairman of the house select committee on narcotics abuse and drug control, said in advance of monday's conference: ``advances in stopping drugs _ we haven't made any.''
if we didn't have nancy reagan, we wouldn't have anything,'' he said in an interview with the post
attorney general edwin meese iii, during an appearance at samford university in birmingham, ala., said drugs are the nation's no. 1 social problem, but said some progress is being made, particularly in high schools
but, he acknowleged, ``we still have a long way to go.''
cocaine seizures by u.s. authorities have risen by 1,822 percent in the past seven years, according to the drug enforcement administration
in fiscal 1981, 1,872 kilograms was seized, compared with 35,970 kilograms in fiscal 1987, the dea said on feb. 4. a kilogram is equal to 2.2 pounds
during the same period, marijuana seizures went down 42 percent, from about 1 million kilograms in fiscal 1981 to 632,000 kilograms last year. it peaked at 1.4 million kilograms seized in fiscal 1984, the dea said
the dea increased the number of its agents 34 percent, from less than 1,500 to about 2,000, from fiscal 1981 to fiscal 1987, the agency said
the world bank, largest source of aid loans to the third world, announced monday that it made a profit of $679 million for the last six months of 1987, up from $655 million for the same period the year before
the bank's profits come largely from its ability to borrow money at low rates of interest, because its funds are guaranteed by the 152 member governments. the bank lends money at varying rates, depending on how poor the country is
in the period, the bank borrowed the equivalent of $7.7 billion in 17 currencies at an average cost of 6.92 percent. its rate of return on $20.8 billion worth of investments at the end of the year was 8.88 percent
the profit helped it make $3.6 billion worth of new loans to third world countries, reducing the interest rate it charges them to an annual 7.72 percent for the first six months of this year from a previous 7.76 percent
gov. evan mecham, absent from the opening day of his impeachment trial in the state senate, blasted his former attorney for remarks to lawmakers on monday, and vowed he will be found innocent
the governor said he had a falling-out with murray miller, his lead attorney until last week, when washington attorney jerris leonard was brought in to lead the defense
miller, who appeared at mecham's senate trial to formally withdraw from the case, monday told senators that he was pushed aside by leonard, calling his arrival in phoenix last week ``a one-man coup.''
responding to question by sen. tony west, r-phoenix, miller hinted that the sudden change in legal counsel could weaken mecham's defense
responding to miller's comments from his suburban headquarters, mecham said, ``i'd both disappointed and disgusted by the prejudicial and unnecessary grandstanding by murray miller before the arizona state senate today.''
i deeply resent the possible prejudice to me by mr. miller's remarks to the state senate and do not believe his actions were in my best interest. ... i don't feel too good about what he did.''
the governor said he began a search for more attorneys when it appeared trials in the senate and state court might overlap. when leonard was hired as chief counsel because ``i felt we have to have a lot more horsepower,'' miller decided to leave, mecham said
i suggested if he did not want to work in a cohesive group then let's part as friends,'' mecham said
mecham said he will not attend the impeachment trial until his attorneys tell him to. he said he hasn't spent much time tracking the proceedings
he did say he expects to be acquitted
i remain convinced that if i receive a fair trial, the truth will prevail and i will be acquitted,'' the governor said
mecham said miller has been paid in full, but he declined to say how much the attorney received
the governor also denied a published report that top fund-raisers were promised jobs
one of the things we can prove was that at every finance meeting, everyone was told, `you get nothing but better government,'' mecham said. ``it was the cleanest campaign this state has ever seen.''
mecham said he had had no recent direct contact with acting gov. rose mofford
britain said monday a special commission will investigate complaints against the royal ulster constabulary, the predominantly protestant police force in northern ireland
the announcement was made by tom king, northern ireland secretary. it prompted speculation that the commission might supervise a disciplinary inquiry about officers involved in the killings of six unarmed roman catholics in 1982
britain's top official for the province said in a written reply in the house of commons the independent commission for police complaints will make ``a material contribution to strengthening good relations between the ruc and the whole community in northern ireland.''
king and the northern ireland police authority, a police-civilian watchdog body, will be able to have the commission supervise investigations of any complaints against police involving death or serious injury
according to the northern ireland office, the province's administrative authority, cases that are not the subject of formal complaints but ``indicate that a member of the police force may have committed a criminal or disciplinary offense'' could be included
on feb. 17, northern ireland police announced an inquiry into police shootings of six catholics in three separate incidents in late 1982
the investigation led by charles kelly, chief constable of staffordshire, will look into a controversy that has been revived this year and seriously damaged relations between britain and the irish republic
john stalker, then assistant chief constable of manchester, investigated the shootings for two years. he published a book in february claiming he was removed because his findings threatened senior officers of the royal ulster constabulary
on jan. 25, the government disclosed that evidence had emerged of perjury and subversion of justice in an alleged coverup related to the shootings, but said no officers would be prosecuted
two men have been hanged in a tehran square where they planted bombs last year, iran's official news agency reported monday
the executions occurred sunday, the day after five people were hanged in another square, also for terrorist bombings, the islamic republic news agency said
hojatoleslam serajeddin musavi, commander of neighborhood islamic revolutionary committees, announced saturday that 30 people responsible for recent bomb attacks in tehran and western iran had been arrested
neighborhood committees are vigilante groups that handle some security duties
according to irna, musavi told a news conference those arrested were ``paid iraqi agents,'' who were promised 30 million rials ($470,000) for each bomb exploded in a busy area of tehran and 6-10 million rials ($94,000-$156,000) for each one that went off in an area less densely populated
he said they arrived in the capital feb.1 to plant bombs during the 10-day celebration surrounding the anniverary of the fundamentalist moslem revolution that ousted the late shah mohammad reza pahlavi in 1979
irna said the bombers were found and arrested by musavi's organization soon after a booby-trapped car exploded feb. 13 and wounded 10 people on martyr bahonar avenue a few hundred yards from the residence of revolutionary patriarch ayatollah ruhollah khomeini
the last bombing reported in tehran was a car that exploded on an expressway on feb. 16, wounding two people
in its dispatches monday, irna did not say whether the five people hanged saturday were among the 30 musavi said were arrested that day
iran and iraq have been at war since september 1980 and iranian authorities refer to members of iranian resistance groups fighting the khomeini regime as iraqi agents. mujahedeen khalq, the main iranian resistance group, has its headquarters and bases in iraq
opposition leaders said the government arrested more than 150 activists who were organizing a strike monday to protest suspension of six local officials, all of them members of the outlawed nepali congress party
only a few shops were closed in this capital city on monday despite the general strike called by the opposition
all political parties were banned in 1960 following nepal's dissolution of a western-style parliamentary system. the congress party, led by krishna prashad bhattarai, has for years sought to change the present system of government through a disobedience movement
the government said monday it arrested about 60 strike organizers
bhattarai, however, told reporters more than 150 of his party's members were arrested monday. congress party leaders said 35 other members were arrested in recent days, including the man elected mayor of katmandu in elections last march
the mayor, his deputy, and four presidents of district and town assemblies were suspended indefinitely from their offices for boycotting constitution day observances last dec. 16
the government said the six had pledged to work under the non-party system when they filed nomination papers
nepal, a constitutional monarchy, is governed by a complex system of district councils and a national legislature.  
more than 300 winners in bulgaria's first election with multiple candidates did not receive the majority needed to gain office, the official bulgarian news agency bta said monday
it said 99.15 percent of bulgaria's 6,652,792 registered voters participated in sunday's election of mayors and local and regional councils. they were the first elections held since the law was changed in december to allow more than one candidate for each post
the agency report said 66,048 candidates were registered in 55,539 electoral districts. it said up to 1.47 percent of the electorate voted against candidates who were elected, but was not clear on whether those voters cast their ballots for alternative candidates
in 302 electoral districts ``the candidates did not collect the necessary number of votes,'' bta said
to win, a candidate must have more than 50 percent of the vote if more than half of the electorate has taken part in the election. the new law does not require bulgarians to vote
bta said 13 seats in regional councils and sofia were among those not filled, along with 31 mayors' offices. elections were not held in five districts because ``the candidates died after they were registered,'' it said without elaboration
by-elections will be held to fill all the vacant posts, the agency said, but did not give a date. graf pvs bgng ``robertson campaigning...</note>
republican presidential candidate pat robertson revived his charge that there are soviet missiles in cuba on monday, producing a cuban refugee who said he had seen the weapons
since robertson first raised his claim two weeks ago, denials have been issued by the white house, congressional experts on u.s.-soviet affairs and cuban president fidel castro, who robertson called ``a butcher and a tyrant.''
robertson visited privately with the refugee, who identified himself only as e. rodriguez, saying he feared family members still in cuba would suffer retribution if he gave his full name
robertson has yet to offer documentation to back up his claim other than a miami cuban-american newspaper, diario libre, which has printed copies of maps drawn by rodriguez to pinpoint missile sites
ninety-five percent of the cuban-americans in miami believe there are missiles in cuba,'' robertson said at a news conference where he held up a copy of the newspaper
rodriguez, speaking through an interpreter, said his job in cuba as an agricultural planner gave him access to aerial photographs and to areas where the missiles were based. he said he saw 60 long-range surface-to-surface missiles as well as air defense and anti-ship missiles. he said he did not know if the missiles had nuclear warheads. rodriguez left cuba three years ago
robertson, campaigning for support in the balloting on super tuesday, was on a two-day swing through florida, one of the biggest prizes in the 16-state round of republican primaries and caucuses march 8
he was greeted by about 400 mostly cuban-american senior citizens at the allapattah community center and about the same number of students at heavily hispanic la salle high school
i will work with you to see cuba independent and democratic,'' robertson said at the community center. ``today i say it, tomorrow i say it, the next day i say it, viva cuba libre!'' _ long live a free cuba
he put on an apron and passed trays of chicken, rice and fried plantains to senior citizens seated at long tables
at the school, robertson was met by students shouting ``go pat go!'' some students held signs passed out by campaign staffers
when a student asked if robertson would ever renew diplomatic relations with cuba, he replied: ``i don't think we should have diplomatic relations with a butcher and a tyrant!''
robertson began his florida tour in jacksonville monday and arranged a rally in miami monday night, followed by breakfast tuesday in fort lauderdale and stops in hollywood, fort myers, sarasota, gainesville and orlando
in jacksonville, robertson told about 500 supporters that ``along with texas, florida is one of the two most pivotal states.''
he added:
we've got one week to the most crucial election, i believe, in the history of america, certainly this century and maybe since its beginning
we're at a crossroads in america. we're either going to return to the ways that made this nation great, or we're going to go down the road.''
robertson mentioned a gun problem experienced this year in several florida schools
how can a child study when he's living in mortal fear of somebody shooting him with a handgun in the halls of the school? we owe our children an education in a crime-free, drug-free school environment,'' said robertson
if we want to see this country strong. there's only one way in my estimation to do it. we will restore the greatness of america through moral strength,'' he added
robertson also said that ``we've got to go back to a time in our educational system when once again we teach our kids moral values. we've got to bring god back into the public schools of america.''
on trade, he said: ``there isn't one country that is treating us fairly. ... as president of the united states, i'm not going to shut down american factories and put americans out of jobs to improve the standard of living in communist china and communist russia.''
at a news conference following his address, robertson called panama military strong man manuel antonio noriega ``a bandit,'' but added that ``i don't see us sending troops (to panama). i don't think it is necessary.''
on south africa, robertson said, ``i am totally opposed to apartheid ... but the thing i'm concerned about is turning south africa into a bloody battleground.''
i don't want to see a marxist state in south africa,'' robertson said. war ii</head>
an official monthly acknowledged about 500,000 poles were deported to the soviet union from territories occupied by the red army at the outbreak of world war ii, and said many died as a result of harsh conditions
the unusual account of the fate of the poles came in an article in the february issue of konfrontacje (confrontation). it is published by the patriotic movement for national rebirth, a national front organization
the article said much was written about the wartime deportations of poles to nazi germany
but it said ``the fate of polish people in the east has been unnecessarily covered in a mist of secrecy, although it was known that there were hundreds of thousands of witnesses of those events living who probably haven't concealed them from relatives.''
it was the first time a widely circulated official publication offered a detailed breakdown of the number of poles deported to the soviet union in world war ii, although polish underground and western publications have described the large-scale suffering of poles at soviet hands
last year, polish leader gen. wojciech jaruzelski criticized abuses against poles committed by soviet dictator josef stalin in an article in the soviet communist party journal kommunist. he said thousands of poles suffered deportation and repression in territories occupied by the soviets
after the germans attacked poland in september 1939, soviet troops invaded from the east and occupied eastern polish territories under provisions of the nazi-soviet non-aggression pact
konfrontacje said poles in the soviet-occupied territories ``found themselves in a difficult situation'' suffering from police harassment and restrictions on civic rights
about 4 million poles lived in the eastern territories before the war, along with millions of ukrainians, byelorussians and jews
the article said a ``safe'' estimate indicates the soviets deported 500,000 poles from the eastern territories in four mass transports from february 1940 to june 1941, when the nazis launched a surprise attack on the soviet union
those deported included state clerks, farmers and their families, refugees who fled nazi-occupied poland, intellectuals and workers, both leftists and right-wingers, the monthly said
it said an additional 200,000 poles were recruited into the soviet army and later evacuated to the soviet union
about 270,000 of the poles deported or evacuated ``died in different circumstances _ in fighting with the red army, during long and exhausting transports, as the result of difficult conditions in siberia and in other areas'' or else ``did not come back to poland'' after the war, it said
the monthly said that overall, about 600,000 to 800,000 poles from the eastern territories died during the war, almost half of them killed in a terror campaign launched by nazi-collaborating ukrainian nationalists in 1943
polish and soviet historians began a weeklong meeting in warsaw on monday, a follow-up to a moscow session last year devoted to ``blank spots'' in polish-soviet relations, referring to topics so controversial they are unmentioned or distorted in official histories
participants told polish television they would discuss the fate of poles in the soviet union during the war, including the deportations, and would have at their disposal ``valuable and important documents'' previously kept secret
the meeting is an outgrowth of an agreement signed last year by jaruzelski and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev on ideological and cultural cooperation which discussed the necessity for a more truthful history of polish-soviet relations
gorbachev has encouraged greater examination of history through his policy of glasnost, or openness
spokesmen for solidarity said management promised to consider pay increases for employees of a railroad car repair plant who stopped work to protest price increases
solidarity's national executive commission accused the communist government of ``alarming ineptness in the economic realm.''
spokesmen for the outlawed independent labor federation in wroclaw, a southwestern industrial city, said about 1,500 people joined the job action at the railway rolling stock repair plant _ about half the work force. plant officials declined comment
a government spokesman denied such a large number of people participated, and said the stoppage ended when managers dispelled a misunderstanding about how the annual profit bonus would be paid
it appeared to be the biggest work stoppage in poland since the government imposed major price increases earlier in february
government spokesman zbigniew augustynowicz said plant workers were disturbed over profit-sharing. he said distribution of the annual bonus based on profits began last week but many workers found it too small
about a third of the staff stopped work at various times monday morning but resumed after plant officials explained how the bonus was calculated, he said
jozef pinior, a wroclaw leader of solidarity, said about half the plant's 3,000 workers downed tools at 9 a.m. in response to a solidarity call
pinior said plant director wojciech zmyslony pleaded with workers to return to their jobs and said management would consider increasing monthly pay by the equivalent of $8 to $11
union members said sunday plant workers were in a ``combative mood'' because of price increases imposed feb. 1
besides claiming too much bonus money was going to managers, they said raises given to offset price increases were inadequate
prices of staple goods were increased 40 percent, with increases in school tuitions and energy prices set for march 1 and april 1, as part of an economic reform program aimed at reviving the economy
in its statement monday, the solidarity national executive commission said: ``drastic price increases have lowered the living standards of all society, pushing low-income groups to the level of subsistence.''
union adviser jacek kuron read the statement, which accused police of tightening surveillance of commission members and said the number of activists jailed, ``often under criminal pretext,'' is growing. with police describing intended target. pick up 4th graf pvs, the ira ...</note>
a huge explosion in the south armagh border area killed two irish republican army guerrillas monday in ``an unfortunate accident,'' the ira said
the blast destroyed a van and a barn about two miles outside crossmaglen village, badly damaged two cars and left a crater
police said four armed and masked men hijacked the van and a car shortly before the blast. authorities speculated that ira guerrillas were installing explosives in the van when the explosives accidentally detonated
a police officer, speaking anonymously in keeping with british practice, said it was believed the ira's intended target was an army observation post near the border with irish republic
the ira later issued a statement saying two of its men died in the blast, which it described as ``an unfortunate accident.'' the group gave no details, and said names and ira ranks of the dead men would be released after families are notified
police said human remains were found at the site and walkie-talkies and a notebook were among the debris
helicopters brought security forces into the surrounding fields to seal off the area overnight. police said they would not move in until tuesday, after army bomb disposal experts made sure no booby-trap bombs were around
the mostly roman catholic ira often uses explosives in its violent campaign to drive the british out of the predominantly protestant province and unite it with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic. after 15th graf pvs, ``lobbyists would</note>
democratic presidential contender richard gephardt came under attack from rivals in a debate monday night for taking contributions from special interest groups, with michael dukakis saying gephardt had accepted the money and raced ``around the country beating up on the establishment.''
when gephardt replied that he had often voted against the policies advocated by people who had given him contributions, dukakis scoffed
`this isn't a fairy tale; this isn't kindergarten; you're talking politics,'' he said
gephardt fought back. ``to suggest that ... you're going to take direction on how to vote is an affront,'' he said
he said he was sure that dukakis, as governor of massachusetts, had taken contributions from firms doing business with the state. ``does that make you less of a public servant?''
yes, said dukakis, but ``i am not running around the country beating up on the establishment.''
gephardt accepted $341,000 in contributions from political action committees last year
the exchange during the debate at the college of william and mary, came eight days before voters in 20 states, most of them in the south, make their decisions in primaries and caucuses on super tuesday. the debate, the democrats' third in three days, was, by the count of moderator judy woodruff, the 24th time the democrats had met in debate
the candidates, at jesse jackson's suggestion, wore yellow ribbons on their jackets in protest of the arrest of anglican archbishop desmond tutu in capetown, south africa, on monday
to gary hart, who joined in the criticism of gephardt for taking money from political action committees, the missourian retorted: ``you took contributions for your senate campaign.''
nonetheless, hart said, reform is needed: ``the system is out of control.''
gephardt, on the defensive, said, ``we all understand the need for reform, but to suggest that people have voted according to the wishes of people who have given them money, i just think is out of touch with reality. i haven't done that and i know you haven't done that.''
hart said he hadn't and hoped gephardt hadn't
but jackson said gephardt's contention that he ignored the wishes of his contributors was unrealistic
lobbyists would lose their jobs if they gave money continuously against the interests of who they were working for,'' jackson said
at another point, jackson seized an opportunity to say he was being treated differently than the other candidates because he is a black
he cited a poll which he said nbc took after the new hampshire primary. in it potential voters were asked if they could support a black for president
i said did you ask how many would vote for a greek?'' said jackson, a reference to dukakis, whose parents were greek immigrants
they said no. i said why even bring race into it. my race is self-evident and my leadership is obvious. let's take the issues to the people.''
for the most part, the candidates wrangled over familiar issues, with gephardt belittling dukakis' plans for increasing government revenues without a tax increase and dukakis saying gephardt has changed his positions
in iowa, dick was telling us i'm sorry for that vote,'' dukakis said of gephardt's vote for the 1981 tax cut proposed by president reagan _ a bill that other democrats say led to the huge deficits that followed. ``that was the iowa gephardt. now we have another one here,'' dukakis added
i'm trying to figure out which one i'm debating.''
gephardt defended his vote for reagan's tax cuts, saying they had reduced taxes for the average american
and he said the dukakis plan to collect taxes now evaded by many americans _ the new englander says billions of dollars are involved _ won't do much to combat deficits
sure we want revenue agents but that is not going to solve the problem,'' gephardt said
dukakis attacked gephardt on another front, saying the oil import fee that gephardt advocates would damage mexico
you're going to kill mexico,'' dukakis said
asked gephardt: ``are you running for president of mexico or president of america?''
that drew a gasp from the audience and then applause. but more applause came when dukakis replied: ``if i'm president of the united states, i'm going to pay attention to that country.''
gore, stressing the harder line he takes on defense issues in comparison with his rivals, defended the decision by the reagan administration to send american ships to protect kuwaiti tankers
when the ayatollah said he was going to shut down our access to 70 percent of the oil available to the free world, no one else (among the candidates) was willing to say we had a right to keep the sea lanes open,'' he said
the only democratic candidate who didn't take part in the debate was sen. paul simon of illinois
the affair's sponsor was the democratic leadership council, an organization of moderate democrats who decided after walter mondale's 49-state loss in 1984 to seek to move the party somewhat toward the right. rejected</head> optimistic, senator's comments; picks up 10th graf, `mecham, a ...'; inserts 1 graf after 13th graf, `mecham also ...' with supreme court decision expected; subs penultimate graf with 3 grafs to add response of mecham to miller comments.</note>
the arizona senate on monday opened the first impeachment trial of a u.s. governor in six decades, and within hours an attorney for gov. evan mecham lost a plea for dismissal of the charges against the first-term republican
this man hasn't dipped his hands into public funds,'' attorney jerris leonard said. ``he hasn't ripped off the treasury. he hasn't committed high crimes in office, and i urge you to dismiss these articles of impeachment.''
but the 29 voting senators gave mecham an overwhelming rejection. on 11 different motions to dismiss portions of the charges, the largest number voting for mecham was seven and the smallest was two
the rest answered firmly, ``no,'' when asked if they would drop the challenged articles of impeachment. they also refused to recess early at leonard's request and continued to address motions brought by the governor's laywer
attorney paul eckstein, one of the prosecutors, had responded to leonard that even if it turned out that mecham didn't violate state laws, his conduct would be ``grossly offensive to the people of this state.''
the articles of impeachment ... cry out for conviction,'' eckstein said. he urged speedy resolution of a raft of pending motions to allow testimony to begin
at the conclusion of monday's session, senators said they expected opening statements and testimony to begin tuesday
mecham, who was not required to be present when the senators convened, stayed at the suburban glendale offices of his ``government in exile,'' and said he was too busy to watch the proceedings on television. he told reporters that he remained optimistic
i remain convinced that if i receive a fair trial, the truth will prevail and i will be acquitted,'' mecham said
of his absence from the trial, he said, ``when my attorneys tell me to be there i'll be there.''
his absence was not mentioned during the proceedings on the senate floor
following monday's session, sen. jeff hill, a republican who once strongly backed mecham, said that judging from the heavy vote against him on dismissal, things looked bad for the governor
i think it's not likely he's going to prevail,'' he said
mecham, a 63-year-old auto dealer who won election after five tries, is accused of ``high crimes, misdemeanors and malfeasance in office.''
twenty-three articles of impeachment approved by the state house alleged three broad areas of misdeeds. the articles said mecham concealed a $350,000 campaign loan, wrongly loaned $80,000 from his protocol fund to his car dealership and obstructed justice by discouraging a public official not to cooperate in the investigation of an alleged death threat to a grand jury witness
if convicted by the senate, mecham would be removed from office and could be permanently barred from holding elective office. he is the first u.s. governor to be impeached since 1929, when huey long of louisiana and henry s. johnston of oklahoma were impeached. long was never tried; johnston was removed
mecham also faces a march 22 criminal trial on six felony charges of concealing the campaign loan, and a may 17 recall election
meanwhile, the arizona supreme court was expected to rule tuesday on a defense claim that the impeachment trial should be delayed until after mecham's criminal trial
mecham, a political outsider, has drawn criticism for comments which critics considered slurs against blacks, homosexuals, jews and the japanese. he spurred controversy by eliminating the state's martin luther king holiday on his second day in office and defending an author's use of the word ``pickaninny'' in a history book
leonard, who took over mecham's defense only last week, addressed his major concern to mecham's failure to report the $350,000 loan. he challenged the senators to recall whether they themselves hadn't committed similar acts and accused them of putting the governor to a stricter test than other officials
the rules of the game have been changed overnight,'' leonard said. he contended mecham should have been given a second chance to amend his disclosure forms
i think you're applying a legal standard here to an act i'm not going to condone but is commonplace,'' leonard said. ``if there are members of this senate who haven't had to file an amendment, god love you
you are applying a standard to one public official that has not been applied to others.''
eckstein responded that he was ``in no small amount of shock'' at such an argument
that's commonplace?'' he said. ``god save us all. and if it is commonplace, that conduct must be offensive to the people as a whole.''
the impeachment proceeding opened with an air of high solemnity after senate democratic minority leader alan stephens told the 29 other senators who sit as judges and jury: ``we are about to embark on an arduous duty
the senate trial of evan mecham does not concern merely this one officeholder,'' stephens said, ``but instead addresses the very essence of democracy in our state constitution
we are really testing our form of government,'' he said. ``will we stand up and do our duty amid calls from the public to intimidate us?''
the first action taken by the senate as the impeachment court convened was to accept the substitution of leonard for murray miller, mecham's original attorney. miller, who left the case last week, made a brief speech saying he had not willingly abandoned it
mecham criticized miller for making the remarks before the senate
i'm both disappointed and disgusted by the prejudicial and unnecessary grandstanding by murray miller before the arizona state senate today,'' mecham said
during the impeachment proceedings, a handful of mecham supporters gathered outside the senate building. some carried placards demanding justice. others laid a paper railroad track across the courtyard with a drawing of the governor, bound and gagged on the tracks
he's being railroaded,'' said mecham supporter wilma harm of phoenix. ``the man has done nothing to be called upon like this.''
the irish republican army is equipped with soviet-made sam-7 anti-aircraft missiles, irish and british authorities acknowledged in a tv program broadcast monday
the surface-to-air missiles were contained in more than 100 tons of weaponry sent by libya to ireland for the ira in four shiploads in 1985 and 1986, according to the british broadcasting corp.'s ``panorama'' program
the program said british army helicopters operating along northern ireland's border with the irish republic would be the most likely targets. the helicopters are the army's main mode of transport in ira-plagued border regions
the irish justice minister, gerry collins, said some of the missiles ``may very well be'' in northern ireland already. the ira, outlawed in britain and ireland, is fighting to drive the british out of the province
john hermon, chief constable of the royal ulster constabulary, northern ireland's police force, said he had ``no reason to doubt'' the sam-7s are hidden somewhere in ireland
as to where they are precisely, there's an element of doubt,'' he said. asked how many there were, he replied, ``that's not a question i'd be prepared to answer directly, but i'm satisfied that they exist.''
collins said he was puzzled over how the ira apparently was able to unload in one night in october 1986 an estimated 105 tons of libyan-supplied arms using an isolated jetty near arklow, 40 miles south of dublin
that is something that is causing us concern, putting it very bluntly,'' collins said. ``at the particular time we did not have any intelligence that this was about to happen nor indeed did we know that it did happen.''
the october shipment contained an unknown number of sam-7s, the program said, quoting unidentified british and irish security sources. a shipment in july 1986 included four sam-7s, it said
gen. sir james glover, british army commander of land forces in northern ireland in 1979-80, said army countermeasures against sam-7s have been prepared but have not yet had to be tested
three shipments that reached ireland were loaded off the mediterranean island of malta and one 15 miles off libya, the program said
last oct. 30, authorities seized a ship, the eksund, and its five irish crewmen in french waters. the ship was carrying about 150 tons of weapons, including 20 sam-7 missiles, apparently destined for the ira, the program said. the first of the four shipments to reach ireland was delivered in august 1985 and contained seven tons of arms, including pistols and 70 soviet-made ak-47 assault rifles, the program said
a shipment in october 1985 contained 10 tons of arms, including 100 ak-47s and 10 machine guns, and a third in july 1986 contained 14 tons and included four sam-7s
the three shiploads were landed using inflatable dinghies at clogga strand, an isolated beach near arklow
in august 1986, apparently in response to the u.s. bombing raid on libya the previous april, libyan leader col. moammar gadhafi bought a ship that in october that year was used to deliver an estimated 105 tons of weaponry to the ira, the program said
the arms apparently were trucked inland and hidden in already prepared bunkers. police have uncovered some of the weapons recently in both the irish republic and northern ireland, but no sam-7s have been found
on monday, a huge explosion in the south armagh border area in northern ireland killed two ira guerrillas in ``an unfortunate accident,'' the ira said
police believe the ira men were installing explosives in a stolen van about two miles outside crossmaglen village, intending to attack an army observation post, when the explosives accidentally detonated. sted ophrah</note>
oprah winfrey bought a mercedes and a jaguar when a syndicated television deal made her a millionaire, but the talk-show host laughs at the notion that fame and fortune may spoil her
my feet are still planted firmly on the ground,'' winfrey said in an interview published in tv guide. ``they're just wearing more expensive shoes.''
winfrey's lifestyle reflects her success. she lives in a luxury apartment with a wraparound view of lake michigan, and owns a mercedes-benz 560 sel and a jaguar
gayle king bumpus, an anchorwoman in connecticut, does not think wealth and fame have gone to her friend's head. as a fifth anniversary present, winfrey sent bumpus and her husband to paris, rome and venice
i remember once she came to visit us in connecticut in a stretch limo,'' bumpus said. ``she was wearing one of her five fur coats, probably a $25,000 number, and white tennis shoes with rhinestones on them and a red sweat shirt that said `husbands can be temporary but best friends last forever.'''
sikh gunmen killed seven members of a family in the bloodiest attack on christians in punjab state since sikh militants began a campaign for autonomy in 1982, police reported monday
it is a gruesome killing, the assailants systematically wiped out the entire family of kulwant massiha,'' said j.p. virdi, police chief of gurdaspur district where the attack occured late sunday. gurdaspur is 40 miles south of the sikhs' holy city of amritsar
virdi said the motive for the killings was not known. there have been several cases in recent years of sikh extremists killing the entire families of hindus or sikhs suspected of being police informers
four gummen entered the massiha house and opened fire with automatic rifles on the victims who were sitting in one room, according to virdi
he said the seven killed were massiha, three brothers, one sister, their 70-year-old mother and massiha's 7-year-old son
massiha's wife was away in the village of kalibramnia when the terrorists struck, virdi added
he said that as the killers fled they wounded seven people in kalibramnia
sikhs, who make up about 2 percent of india's 780 million people, claim they are discriminated against by hindus who form about 82 percent of the population. punjab state is predominantly sikh, and separatists are demanding an independent homeland there
christians compose 2.5 percent of india's population, and most of the few who live in punjab are in the gurdaspur district that borders pakistan. many of the christians in punjab are immigrants from predominantly moslem pakistan
police say sikh extremists have killed at least 313 people in punjab this year. last year they were blamed for more than 1,000 killings in the state
sikhism is an offshoot of the hindu religion
