a key nazi document made public monday shows that kurt waldheim signed a german letter seeking approval for mass deportation of greek civilians in 1943 in a ``cleansing operation.''
the document, found in u.s. national archives, was vital in the justice department's decision to place waldheim, now austria's president and formerly u.n. secretary-general, on a ``watchlist'' barring him from the united states
the document was one of those used in making the watchlist decision,'' justice department spokesman john russell told the associated press by telephone from washington monday
that u.s. government decision said in part that waldheim ``assisted or otherwise participated'' in ``mass deportation of civilians.''
the document, dated aug. 15, 1943, was made available to the ap by the world jewish congress and its authenticity was confirmed by justice department sources
waldheim says he was innocent of war crimes. he was serving as deputy operations officer of the german general staff attached to the 11th italian army in athens at the time the document was sent
the document shows waldheim, while not authorizing the deportations, received the communication via radio, transcribed it and forwarded it, the world jewish congress said
in the message, a german army officer in the field was seeking authorization from headquarters to deport all the male civilians in northern greece where the division was operating. the request was sent to a gen. gyldenfeldt who subsequently approved the deportation, the world jewish congress said
however, the order was countermanded before it could be used to deport any greek civilians, the world jewish congress said
the communication mentions ``heavy bandit concentrations'' and says, ``bridgehead formations by groups seem particularly promising, for which reason scheduled cleansing operations in this area are deemed necessary
(there is) hope of success only if all male civilians are seized and deported.''
the nazis often used the term ``cleansing operations'' to refer to destruction of towns and mass execution of inhabitants as a warning to others to report partisans to german authorities. deported greek civilians were generally sent to german labor camps
the document also says the ``jewish committee'' operating in the town of joannina, greece, ``must be regarded as a center of preparations for a resistance movement.''
the following march, the nazis deported 1,860 jews, virtually the entire jewish population of joannina, to auschwitz death camp in poland, the world jewish congress said. the document signed by waldheim did not seek authorization to deport the jews
the austrian government has complained that the justice department has not turned over all information on which it based its decision to prohibit waldheim's entry into the united states
the u.s. government said it is not up to the united states to do austria's investigation. it said the documents are available to the austrian government and that waldheim can appeal the watchlist decision if he wishes
he has not done so
a commission of six international historians appointed by the austrian government found in february that as a german army officer, waldheim knew about nazi war crimes and could have done more to prevent atrocities. it said it did not have evidence he actually committed atrocities, but left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime
waldheim said he was vindicated by the commission
under the nuremberg charter, the deportation of civilians is both a war crime and a crime against humanity, the world jewish congress said in a statement
elan steinberg, executive director of the world jewish congress, said monday his organization provided the document to the justice department in 1986
the translation of sections of the document from german into english was done by the world jewish congress. it was not questioned by the justice department
in london, the british defense ministry appealed to the public monday for information about waldheim's wartime activities that might help its investigation into the nazi executions of six british commandos in 1944
the commandos, a raiding party captured in the balkans off alimina island in april 1944, were handed over for interrogation to the unit in which waldheim served
they refused to talk and were executed by the nazis _ a war crime under the geneva convention on prisoners of war
the conservative government ordered an investigation two weeks ago to try to pin down whether waldheim interrogated the six men
