the american intention to close the plo mission by march 21 jeopardizes u.n. independence, arab and western diplomats told a special general assembly session monday
representatives of the 21-nation arab group, the plo and the 45-nation islamic conference urged the united states to submit the dispute to binding arbitration, and asked the assembly to request an advisory opinion from the world court in the hague
u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar also recommended arbitration and said the integrity of the world organization was at stake
even close u.s. allies such as canada, members of the european community and the scandinavian countries urged the united states not to close the plo mission and joined in the call for arbitration
at stake at this point are the effective functioning of the united nations and the right of the organization to hear the views of those invited to attend as observers,'' canadian ambassador stephen lewis said, speaking also on behalf of australia and new zealand
later this week, the 159-nation general assembly is expected to approve resolutions echoing all those recommendations. a resolution passed in december asked the united states not to close the mission of the palestine liberation organization, which has non-voting, observer status
the confrontation over the plo mission, which congress has ordered closed by march 21, has become the bitterest argument ever between the united nations and the host country
several speakers said monday the dispute could hurt u.s. peace efforts in the middle east, where secretary of state george p. shultz has been on a shuttle mission
u.s. prestige at the united nations already was waning when the plo issue arose, primarily because washington's failure to pay its full share of u.s. expenses for the several years has contributed to the worst financial crisis in the organization's 42-year history
peter florin of east germany, president of the general assembly, opened the monday session with a reminder by citing a charter provision saying a member can lose its vote if arrears grow too large
the united states, which is assessed a quarter of the u.n. budget, now owes more than $535 million in dues and contributions to peacekeeping forces. at the current rate of funding by congress, the united states could face losing its vote in 1990
last week, u.s. ambassador vernon walters said: ``we cannot continue to neglect our financial commitments to the united nations and then expect that our opinions, policies and positions will carry their former weight in the world body.''
arab diplomats said monday the credibility of the united states and the independence of the united nations are at issue, not just the fate of the 13-year-old plo mission
the united nations and u.s. state department both say the anti-terrorism bill ordering the plo mission closed violates the 1947 u.s.-u.n. headquarters agreement, but attorney general edwin meese iii is said to be planning to implement the legislation
walters told a news conference monday he didn't know what meese was going to do
he said a ``series of discussions is going on within the u.s. government as to what is the appropriate action to take under the circumstances and i am not aware the various agencies in the u.s. government have reached some decision in this matter.''
zehdi labib terzi, plo representative at the united nations, said monday: ``will the u.n. headquarters in new york be in a position to continue operating in the absence of a respected and adhered-to headquarters agreement?''
karim ebrahim al-shakar, ambassador of bahrain and chairman of the arab group, said the decision to close the mission was ``part of a feverish zionist campaign against the palestinian people.''
the belgrade district court on monday banned another book by dissident sociologist vojislav seselj, saying it could ``imperil public peace,'' the state's tanjug news agency reported
the book, titled ``the books for the pyre,'' deals with court documents and proceedings from several previous trials involving seselj's works
yugoslav courts have banned at least five of the sociologist's books
seselj was convicted in july 1984 of counter-revolutionary activity, largely on the basis of an unpublished manuscript that took a critical look at yugoslavia's economic and social problems. he served nearly two years of an eight-year prison sentence
tanjug said seselj's latest work slandered josip broz tito, founder and leader of communist yugoslavia who died in 1980. by law, anyone publicly denigrating tito is liable to criminal prosecution
tanjug did not say if further action might be taken against seselj
a violent white supremacist group targeted several prominent people for assassination, including henry kissinger and top television executives, a witness testified monday in a federal sedition trial
denver parmenter, who is serving a 10-year prison sentence after pleading guilty in 1985 to racketeering, testified that members of the order planned robberies, guerrilla warfare and murders to further their goal
our purpose was to kill important people in government or other important institutions in this country to create havoc, disorder, destruction,'' parmenter said. order members took an oath which included the words, ``i have no fear of death.''
ten of the 14 men on trial are accused of sedition, or plotting to overthrow the government by illegal means; two are charged with interstate transportation of stolen money; and five are charged with conspiring to kill a federal judge and an fbi agent. neither the judge, the fbi agent nor any of the celebrities mentioned in the trial monday were harmed
parmenter said he was a former member of the church of jesus christ christian (aryan nations) at hayden lake, idaho, which is run by defendant richard butler
parmenter said butler frequently spoke of his racial and political viewpoints in sermons. he said butler said the u.s. government was ``basically a government that wasn't supporting its race.''
parmenter said he and eight others, including defendants david lane and bruce pierce, formed the order in september 1983 in metalline falls, wash., home of the late robert mathews
mathews outlined six goals for order members, including developing a war chest through illegal means such as robbery and counterfeiting, parmenter said. each member was given a target to kill, parmenter said, including david rockefeller, television producer norman lear, kissinger and the three major network tv presidents
parmenter previously outlined the assassination plots during the 1985 trial of order members in seattle. union</head>
hungary's official trade unions on monday denounced a proposal by a group of academics to consider establishing the country's first independent union
in a statement carried by the government news agency mti, the central council of hungarian trade unions said the group seeks ``to destroy the unity of trade unions and set up organizations outside the movement.''
on feb. 19, some members of the hungarian academy of sciences met to discuss the possibility of establishing an independent union, well-informed sources in budapest said monday
several hundred people attended the meeting to consider creating the tudosz union of scientific workers, said the sources who spoke with the condition they not be identified. they were contacted by telephone from vienna
the sources said after the meeting, academics from several universities, including the karl marx economics university, expressed in university newspapers their support and their intention to join the new union if it were completely independent
some academics have criticized the official unions in communist hungary for not protesting a government decision to cut the nation's scientific budget by 15 percent
according to the sources, a committee of about 30 people was set up at the feb. 19 meeting to determine under what conditions the union could operate
the scientists currently belong to the union of public employees, which is under the umbrella of the central union council
the sources said the preparatory committee has sent a report to scientific insititutions across the country asking them to recommend delegates to the committee to ensure broad representation
there are no independent trade unions in hungary
the first independent union in the soviet bloc was solidarity, formed in poland in august 1980 during nationwide strikes. it was chartered by the government but then suspended in december 1981 and subsequently outlawed
mti reported the union council statement did not directly mention the academics, but referred to ``a limited group'' that it said was ``motivated by ill-willed political considerations.''
the agency quoted the statement as saying the council rejects ``the intentions of those who make an attempt to set up organizations opposing the trade union movement.'' with meeting ending, official saying national headquarters also represented at meeting. picks up 5th graf, `leaders of...'.</note>
