a police officer guarded the parking lot of the assemblies' state headquarters, and officials issued a statement saying the denomination would have no comment
decisions made by the louisiana district presbytery today will be returned to the executive presbytery. there will be no further announcement or comment from the louisiana district counsel,'' district superintendent cecil janway said in the statement
there was no indication swaggart, who confessed a week ago to committing a sin, was present
the meeting broke up at 7 p.m. seen leaving the office building were the rev. jim rentz, who is substituting for swaggart at the family worship center in baton rouge, and forrest hall, secretary-treasurer of the assemblies of god louisiana district council
rentz had no comment, but hall acknowledged that the meeting had ended and that executive officials from springfield, mo., where the church is based, had attended at the meeting
leaders of the pentecostal denomination are considering a rehabilitation plan that will suspend swaggart from preaching, reportedly because he paid a prostitute to pose naked and tried to make a deal with a minister who confronted him about it
last week, louisiana church officials recommended barring swaggart from preaching for three months, but national denomination officials asked for reconsideration after receiving hundreds of calls protesting the penalty as too lenient
the state denomination also was criticized for publicizing its recommendation before it was reviewed by the national office
during a brief appearance sunday at the jimmy swaggart world ministries center, swaggart thanked about 4,000 worshipers for their backing
i'll never have the words to express to you how much that i care, my concern, for you and my thanksgiving. if it hadn't been for you, we would not have made it. it's just that plain and simple,'' said swaggart
swaggart again was not specific about his wrongdoing, but said he had received support and sympathy from members of various denominations
the founder of an evangelical empire worth an estimated $150 million said his worldwide ministry would continue
first of all, this ministry belongs to god. secondly, this ministry will continue. and last, but certainly not least, this ministry will be what he wants it to be,'' swaggart said
marvin gorman, the defrocked assemblies of god minister who reportedly confronted swaggart with photographs of him entering and leaving a new orleans motel room with a prostitute, asked his own congregation sunday for prayers for swaggart
i want you all to pray for jimmy swaggart and his family because we know that they're going through a lot right now. and i want you to know that i know that a lot of miracles will come out of this,'' gorman, who now preaches independently, said at his metropolitan christian centre in new orleans
in a $90 million lawsuit filed last year, gorman alleged that swaggart and 13 others had destroyed his ministry by spreading false rumors of adulterous affairs
guenther tschanun, former head of the city building inspector's office, was sentenced monday to 17 years in jail for fatally shooting four of his colleagues in 1986 at his office
a zurich court convicted tschanun, a 47-year-old austrian-born architect, of voluntary homicide and attempted voluntary homicide
tschanun told the court he committed the april 16, 1986, slayings during a psychological breakdown and without premeditation
state prosecutor marcel bertschi had demanded a life sentence for murder, saying tschanun deliberately set out to kill after becoming embroiled in conflicts with his co-workers
tschanun fled after the killings. he was arrested in france three weeks later
presidential hopeful gary hart, mired in the back of the democratic pack, failed to qualify for new york's democratic primary ballot, the state board of elections ruled monday
board spokesman steven lafever said petitions meant to get the former colorado senator a spot on new york's april 19 primary ballot contained only 6,864 signatures, more than 3,000 less than required
to qualify for the statewide primary ballot, democratic candidates must file petitions containing the signatures of at least 10,000 registered democrats and at least 100 of those signatures must come from each of 17 of the state's 34 congressional districts
the other five announced major candidates and political extremist lyndon larouche all filed petitions last week with more than enough signatures to qualify for the ballot
jon kaiman, new york coordinator for the hart campaign, said a court appeal of the board's ruling would be considered
we don't know what to make of it,'' said kaiman of the board's finding. ``we were under the impression we had them (enough signatures).''
lafever said the hart petitions were received in the mail monday morning. the deadline for getting a postmark on the petitions was midnight thursday
hart dropped out of the presidential race in may amid reports of his relationship with a miami model and rejoined the race in december. he has been running well behind the rest of the field in early contest states
remember the '70s?,'' asks one of the three rapidly aging young men who dominate the action in ``boys' life,'' a brittle, boorish and unappealing comedy that stumbled into the mitzi newhouse theater at lincoln center on monday night
all that another member of this troubled trio can recall about the decade is watergate and the sex pistols, but then he's not having such a great time in the 1980s either
all three guys have women problems, and playwright howard korder examines their woes in numbing detail. phil (steven goldstein) is a good-natured schmo, still trying to score with a girl who already has dumped him. don (jordan lage) is equally dim-witted, but he manages to find a woman who will put up with his jock mentality
the most interesting _ and sarcastic _ character in the play is jack (clark gregg) who already is married but willing to fool around. his mean-spiritedness gets a workout during the evening at the expense of the other characters
some of jack's comments are funny, but he's really a nasty fellow. the playwright finally gives him his due in the last scene, a wedding reception. between sips of champagne, jack gets to confront the emptiness of his own life. by then, the audience doesn't care. they have had to confront the emptiness of korder's play for some 90 minutes
the large cast _ some 13 actors, in all _ works hard and undoubtedly will go on to better things. so will director w.h. macy who at least keeps the actors in motion on james wolk's mobile set. it's the play that never goes anywhere at all
a man accused of killing 16 people, including 14 members of his own family, is competent to stand trial, a judge ruled monday before setting a may 9 trial date
circuit judge john patterson accepted a state mental hospital finding that r. gene simmons was competent to aid in his own defense
the state hospital in little rock also found that simmons, 47, was sane at the time of the slayings, but that ultimately will be decided by a jury, defense attorney john harris noted
simmons was transferred monday to the pope county jail at russellville from the state hospital, where he has undergone a psychiatric examination since late december
on dec. 28, simmons surrendered to police in russellville after a 45-minute shooting spree in which two former co-workers were killed and four people were wounded
police then searched simmons' rural home near dover where, over a two-day period, they found 14 bodies _ simmons' wife, four daughters, three sons, two spouses of his children, three grandchilden, and a child who officials say simmons fathered by his oldest daughter
dr. roy ragsdill, director of the hospital, said the agency answered yes to both questions asked by the judge: first, whether simmons was competent to stand trial and, second, whether he had an ability to appreciate his actions and conform his behavior within legal limits
but simmons may still plead innocent by reason of insanity, harris said. simmons could contend either he was unable to tell right from wrong at the time of the killings or if he was, he was nonetheless unable to conform his behavior to the law
they said he was responsible; that means he's not legally insane,'' prosecutor john bynum said. ``we thought all along he was competent to stand trial. ... we're real pleased with the ruling.''
harris said he visited simmons monday and that he seemed in good spirits. harris said more psychiatric tests are needed, and that it could take a couple of months to get the results back
psychiatrists are like lawyers,'' harris said. ``you get a different one, you get a different opinion.''
simmons has not been arraigned. lt. jay winters of the pope county sheriff's office said the arraignment may occur tuesday. bynum said it should be soon, but said he didn't know if it would be tuesday
two tamil women ended their 10-day fast for peace monday by taking water mixed with salt and sugar, witnesses said
the hunger strikers, anama david, 58, and nesamma vadival, 50, are members of the tamil mothers front and had vowed not to eat until indian troops ceased anti-rebel operations and tamil separatist guerrillas agreed to negotiations
the witnesses spoke on condition of not being identified
there was no indication the women's demands had been met
an official at the indian high commission, or embassy, in colombo said indian troops had reduced operations in northern and eastern sri lanka, zones where the tamil minority form a majority
but the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the move was not related to appeals from the two women and he insisted the scaling down did not amount to a cease-fire
in new delhi, foreign ministry spokesman gopalaswami parthasarthy said operations against the tamil rebels were continuing. he said india would agree to talks with the rebels only after they surrendered their weapons
a senior sri lankan military official, who also spoke on condition that he not be identified,, said, however, that indian soldiers suspended operations in eastern batticaloa district in a bid to save the lives of the women, who were reported in poor condition before abandoning their fast
officials at the sri lankan military headquarters in colombo said there was no fighting between indian troops and tamil rebels for the previous 24 hours. the officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules, said indian soldiers were continuing search operations and patrols, however
more than 45,000 indian soldiers are in sri lanka to enforce an indian-sponsored peace accord signed last july 29 with the sri lankan government to try to end the rebels' four-year war for an independent tamil homeland in the northern zone of this island off india's southern coast
a spokesman for the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the largest rebel group, said sunday the tigers were prepared for unconditional talks with the indian government
more than 8,000 people have been killed in sri lanka since the tamil insurrection began. tamils, most of whom are hindus, comprise 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people. they claim the sinhalese buddhist majority discriminate against them
moses gunn is such a good actor that when he's speaking, as the blues singer-musician in the new play ``tapman,'' he makes the character credible
however, the play, which opened sunday at the off-broadway hudson guild theater, holds together about as well as a cookie that has been stepped on
the plot focuses on tapman, who's nearing 50, thinks of himself as old, ruminates about death and worries because he never has made a recording
tapman recently has married a chic, well-dressed woman (kim hamilton), after his first wife died. his daughter (seret scott) from his first marriage dislikes the new wife and has a chip on her shoulder. it's an awkwardly written part awkwardly acted
tapman gets drunk when it's time to go on stage, so the other three members of his band perform without him and they lose jobs. he then misses three dates entirely. his musicians, dean irby, helmar augustus cooper and guy davis, venerate him but resolve to work without him
the band finally gets a chance to play at the opening of a huge blues club in houston, and tapman rejoins them for the night. but the play drifts pointlessly, as tapman begins drinking again and sends his daughter, who hates blues, on to sing with the band. he says she is his legacy
author karen jones-meadows has had one other play produced off-broadway. samuel p. barton directed. bail</head>
