an off-duty policeman shot during an attempted robbery was remembered monday as a ``hero in the strictest sense'' at a memorial service for the third dallas officer slain in six weeks
hundreds of officers, some weeping and others with their badges taped in black, filled the eagle's nest cathedral at a memorial service for gary d. mccarthy, a former missionary who joined the force 14 months ago
at least 2,200 people attended, police spokesman ed spencer said
he left the foreign mission field but he found another mission field,'' said the rev. clyde box, pastor of brook hollow baptist church in desoto where mccarthy, a husband and father of two children, attended church
while gary was a policeman, the streets became his mission field. last friday he gave his life on that field.''
mccarthy's funeral will be tuesday in his hometown of amarillo
police were holding three men in connection with mccarthy's death friday, but the district attorney's office said none had been formally charged by monday afternoon. the three were arrested on capital murder warrants
one of them, vincent edward cooks, 23, was paroled aug. 4 from the texas department of corrections less than a year after he began serving a five-year sentence for aggravated assault of a police officer
cooks had originally been charged with attempted capital murder after apparently shooting at an off-duty police officer outside a club in houston
houston police sgt. v.w. west said cooks pleaded no contest to the reduced aggravated assault charge and began serving his sentence in december 1986
cooks was arrested sunday at a houston apartment where he tried to escape from a second-story window, said dallas police lt. ron waldrop
another man arrested in the case, tony ray harvey, 23, of houston, was paroled jan. 18 after serving 18 months of a six-year sentence for aggravated robbery and unauthorized use of a motor vehicle, police said
the third man, tracy dewayne stallworth, 27, of irving, has no prior convictions
police would release few details in the case
we'd rather not get into specifics about what we're going to allege that any of the participants did because, obviously, this case is coming back to dallas for trial and we want to protect as much of the investigation as we can,'' waldrop said
harvey was held monday on $500,000 bond, while stallworth's bond was set at $100,000, plus an additional $200 bond for possession of a controlled substance. cooks was moved from houston to dallas on monday but bond was not immediately set, a jail spokeswoman said
mccarthy was escorting a grocery store manager back from a bank visit when a man jumped out of a car to rob the manager, police said
the off-duty officer was shot three times, including once in the heart, but was able to return fire, police said. he died several hours later
mccarthy's death was the seventh in six shootings involving police this year. in addition to the three dead police officers, four civilians have been killed by police
two former lebanese students of hostage professor thomas sutherland said monday that the u.s. government has failed to provide leadership in solving the hostage problem and lebanon's civil war
farij el-awar and basil hamdan, who studied under the colorado state university professor when he was agriculture dean at american university in beirut, spoke at a news conference announcing csu activities planned this week to mark sutherland's 1,000th day of captivity friday
both el-awar and hamdan are graduate students at csu
hamdan said sutherland believed his role as a professor extended beyond the classroom to helping underdeveloped countries
but, hamdan said, ``the u.s., as a government, is not providing the leadership it needs to solve the problem. ... they have chosen to ignore it because of political reasons.''
sutherland, 56, was abducted in beirut on june 9, 1985. he was working at the beirut university while on leave from csu
el-awar said sutherland ``introduced a new spirit to the school'' and obtained a new computer for the university in beirut
csu has planned a number of activities in honor of sutherland this week, including the distribution of yellow ribbons wednesday, thursday and friday; a video with statements by former hostages friday; and a ceremony and reception friday to include appearances by two of sutherland's daughters and the rev. lawrence martin jenco, a former beirut hostage held captive with sutherland
csu president philip austin has proclaimed thursday as ``tom sutherland awareness day'' on campus
hamdan said he thinks the reagan administration is too afraid of risking small setbacks in the middle east to begin the complex strategy required to solve the region's problems
there is no easy answer to the lebanese problem. it would be really childish to say the u.s. could solve the problem tomorrow ... but the government has to have some large vision. if it built one thing at a time, it would come to a solution,'' hamdan said
