thought for today: ``my life needs editing.'' _ mort sahl, american comedian
with february's cold and snow past, gardeners are turning their thoughts to home-grown vegetables. while it may not be time to plant yet in most areas, some projects can be started right away
right now, the first thing they ought to do is decide what to grow and order the seeds,'' says charles a. mcclurg, a vegetable specialist with the university of maryland
while family preferences dictate most decisions, ``many people like to grow something new they've never tried,'' he said
there are always new varieties coming out. ones that have received the all-american selection award are those best adapted, and most commercial seed companies have them in their catalogs,'' he said. ``most people have better success with hybrids, even though they cost more.''
besides armchair gardening with catalogs, folks anxious to get to work can start soil preparation in their gardens as soon as the ground is dry enough. many still have plant supports and trellises in place, and this is the time to clean up and get the ground ready
about six weeks before the last frost is a good time to start seedlings indoors, mcclurg says, and cold weather vegetables like broccoli, cabbage and cauliflower can be started even sooner
any prepared starting mix with a combination of perlite and vermiculite plus peat moss is better than soil for starting seedlings,'' mcclurg said. ``you may need supplemental fertilizer a few weeks after plants start to grow.''
the biggest problem we have with people is light. they tend not to have adequate light in the house for transplants,'' he added
give the transplants full sun from the time that the seeds emerge. if you don't have a sunny window available, provide supplemental lighting with a grow lamp.''
avoid overwatering by allowing the soil surface to dry out between waterings
a temperature of 70 degrees to 75 degrees is best for germination and growth
a cold frame can be useful, mcclurg said, but you have to be careful not to let it get too hot on a sunny day. and make sure the plants are not subjected to freezing temperatures
container gardening is losing its popularity somewhat, he noted, but is ``still an excellent way to grow a few things for people without space. we suggest they make the containers as large as practical. they need adequate drainage, and should try to select plant types that are fairly small,'' he said
cool-season crops that can go in quite early include such vegetables as asparagus, broccoli, brussels sprouts, cabbage, cauliflower, celery, chives, endive, garlic, horseradish, rhubarb, kale, leek, lettuce, onions, garlic, parsley, parsnips, peas, potatoes, radishes, shallots, spinach and turnips
cabbage and head lettuce are best handled as transplants, mcclurg says, but never try to transplant peas
peas and radishes are very good short season crops, and should be seeded in successive groups to help assure a steady crop. later the same garden space can be used for a late season item
the first-run situation comedy may have peaked in the television syndication market, and ``reality'' programming _ talk and information shows _ seems to be the trend for the fall
the national association of television program executives has just concluded its 25th-anniversary convention in houston, and a number of the new programs being offered are reality based, such as ``usa today,'' a news show designed to be a tv version of the newspaper
an estimated 8,000 people attended the five-day meeting at the george r. brown convention center. the convention is the major arena for producers to show off their new programs and for station program executives to pick and choose syndicated shows for the next television season
altogether, between 300 and 400 shows are being offered to the program executives. the shows include reruns of network shows and packages of motion pictures
what i see is a movement toward reality programming,'' a. philip corvo, executive director of natpe said in an interview before leaving for the convention. ``it seems to be bigger than any move in that direction we've had in the past.''
other ``reality'' shows being offered include ``group one medical,'' from mgm, ``public people, private lives,'' from orbis communications, ``the howard cosell show,'' from casablanca, and ``on trial,'' from republic. ``usa today'' is from gtg entertainment
i think this trend will pick up speed if any of these shows are successful,'' said corvo. ``another trend i see is that some shows are leaning toward horror and science fiction.''
lorimar has ``nightmare on elm street'' and mca has ``the munsters,'' a revival of the horror spoof from the 1960s. already o the market are paramount's ``star trek'' and ``friday the 13th.'' another new show will be paramount's `war of the worlds,'' based on the novel by h.g. wells and the award-winning 1953 movie by george pal
mgm has 30 new episodes of ``the twilight zone,'' in addition to 64 vintage shows from the rod serling classic series
by far the most successful of the distributors is king world, which has ``wheel of fortune,'' ``jeopardy'' and ``the oprah winfrey show.''
there doesn't seem to be a dent in the popularity of those shows,'' said corvo. ``stations are buying them three or four years in advance. in the old days you never bought a game show more than a year in advance. most didn't last that long
the popularity of the original situation comedies has leveled off and may even be going into a decline. `the munsters' is the only new comedy show. stations tried a checkerboard arrangement with the comedies, with a different show each night, but they seem to be getting away from that. i think they'll go back to stripping game and reality shows (running them each night of the week). i think that's what grant tinker's looking for with `usa today.'''
that doesn't mean reruns of network comedies aren't selling, however
bill cosby is going into syndication in 1988 or '89 with the highest-priced off-network show in the history of television,'' said corvo. ```who's the boss?' is also going into syndication and that is getting some very high prices. in fact, the off-network stuff is so expensive that it's helping the sale of first-run syndicated shows. it's making them more attractive economically.''
corvo said he also sees renewed interest in hourlong, off-network shows, which have not done well in syndicated sales in recent years
the usa network has picked up `miami vice' and `murder, she wrote,''' he said. ``this is a cable network, but it programs just like an independent station and sells commercial time. it's just like a superstation.''
elsewhere in television:
for kids _ fourteen-year-old tina yothers of nbc's ``family ties'' is the host of the pbs special ``it shouldn't hurt to be a kid,'' which will be telecast on march 25. the show will look at the various problems teen-agers face growing up, from family troubles to alcohol to drugs to sex
presenters _ among the presenters announced for the 14th annual people's choice awards are danny devito, kirk douglas, howard hesseman, bronson pinchot and james stewart. the show will be presented live on sunday, march 13, on cbs
women in film _ the arts &amp; entertainment cable network is providing funding for the american film institute's directing workshop for women, a 14-year-old program whose alumni include dyan cannon, lee grant, marsha mason and joanne woodward. the program provides women directors with backing for videotape projects that may then get an airing on a&amp;e. ^by john cunniff</byline>
wherever it exists, rent control is an issue that splits public opinion, penetrating deep beneath individuals' mere political instincts into their philosophical marrow
it is viewed as the most effective protection the poor have against greedy landlords. it is seen by others as a violation of private property rights by governments that should, constitutionally, be protecting them
the issue attracts as much emotion as reason. in every city where it exists, it is defended as needed to protect the poor _ and simultaenously damned as the cause of inferior housing, and too little housing, for the poor
never dormant, the issue has been heated to a boil again by a feb. 24 supreme court ruling that seems to reaffirm a municipality's right to consider a tenant's finances before allowing or disallowing a rent increase
in the specific case, pennel v. city of san jose, calif., the court upheld the constitutionality of an ordinance in which a city official would deem whether or not a tenant could afford an increase of more than 8 percent
under the ordinance, if the city hearing officer so ruled, the allowable rent increase could be rolled back to 5 percent, plus an amount needed for improvements, maintenance and rehabilitation
landlords boiled over, since most have for years contended that their industry has been singled out for exceptional treatment, that treatment being an unconstitutional taking of private property _ that is, theirs
but, as usual, even the institution of the surpeme court couldn't deal with the issue without splitting sharply. chief justice william rehnquist wrote the majority opinion, but justice antonin scalia wrote a scathing critique
said rehnquist: ``we have long recognized that a legitimate and rational goal of price or rate regulation is the protection of consumer welfare.'' but in scalia's view, such regulation permits unfair transfers of wealth
moreover, said scalia, these wealth transfers have added dimensions that make them cause for additional concern
they are, for instance, relatively invisible, he said. they have ``relative immunity from normal democratic processes.'' and as a consequence, they allow government to subsidize a social group ``off budget.''
the national association of realtors filed a brief that added a practical dimension. rent control, it said, it inherently irrational, since it exacerbates rather than relieves a shortage of affordable housing
the nar can support its contentions with independent studies; it is no secret to anyone familiar with rent control that it scares apartment builders away and can cause landlords to abandon properties
those who defend rent control contend that theirs is the best way since, as they see it, those members of society who need protection are granted it, while landlord interests are secured by regular and fair, albeit limited, increases
but william north, nar executive vice president, states that the court has ``created the ultimate oxymoron: compulsory charity.'' rental hardship cases, he argues, are a responsibility of the community, not just of landlords
danny the red, leader of student revolts in france and west germany in the 1960s, jokingly says he was never quite as leftist as his nickname implied
they only meant my hair color,'' said daniel cohn-bendit, referring to his rust-colored hair during an interview in his frankfurt office. ``i've always been an anti-communist, more of one than reagan.''
he's now 42 years old and an active member of west germany's anti-establishment, environmentalist greens party _ the moderate wing _ and publishes a left-leaning regional magazine in frankfurt
he ran unsuccessfully for mayor of frankfurt in 1986 in a purely symbolic move, he said. but he is considering seriously running for frankfurt's city council next year
cohn-bendit has also become an author. a collection of interviews with other 1960s activists around the world was published in west germany in september
american activists featured in the book include jerry rubin and abbie hoffmann, leading yippies of the era, and the black panther activist, bobby seale
the book, ``we loved it so, the revolution,'' portrays rubin as a yippie-turned-yuppie and seale as hoping for commercial success as a cookbook author
his book isn't the only look back: west germany's news media have carried numerous articles on the tumultuous times of 1968
cohn-bendit said that he has basically remained true to many views he had 20 years ago
i believe that i can still legitimize everything i do from my standpoint in 1968,'' cohn-bendit said
as a moderate member of the greens, cohn-bendit favors forming coalitions with west germany's liberal social democratic party, which the greens' radical wing opposes. nor does cohn-bendit favor a west german withdrawal from nato, as some of the radicals do
west german militarization is more dangerous on its own than embedded in a larger context,'' he said. ``that's the lesson of world war ii.''
cohn-bendit has always been a figure who defied traditional national, political, and religious labels. he was born in montauban, france, on april 4, 1945, the son of german jews who fled hitler's persecution in the 1930s
his parents moved to west germany when cohn-bendit was 13. in 1961 cohn-bendit became a west german citizen
i did it only for pragmatical reasons,'' he said. ``i didn't want to serve in the military.''
jews whose parents or siblings were persecuted under the nazis are by west german law exempted from the country's mandatory military service
cohn-bendit, who speaks french and german fluently, said he doesn't assign his national identify to either country. as a french citizen, he would have been subject to the military draft in france
i'm just me. i'm not german or french,'' he added. ``i don't need a national definition.''
cohn-bendit's views have led to occasional flaps with frankfurt's jewish community. in a highly publicized dispute in 1985 he publicly supported the city playhouse in presenting a play by rainer werner fassbinder, which many jews wanted banned as anti-semitic
in the feb. 18 issue of his magazine ``pflasterstrand,'' cohn-bendit described himself as a ``convinced anti-zionist.''
in the interview, he said he favored the existence of israel but also a separate palestinian state and ``a limitation of zionism.''
tenants' housing rights and terrorist amnesty are among other issues that have made cohn-bendit a household name
but the era that propelled the activist to world fame, the 1960s, is a topic cohn-bendit said he no longer wants to talk a lot about
in his book, originally published in france, he writes that people have used him ``like a machine that turns back time.''
cohn-bendit captured world attention as a university student in france, at a time when youth protests were rocking the globe
he was a spokesman for students whose demands included greater social equality and an end to war, in vietnam and elsewhere. danny the red became the leader of paris' tumultuous _ and occasionally bloody _ student revolts
we had the will to change our lives, to participate in history right at the moment it happened,'' cohn-bendit writes of his revolutionary days
in may 1968 french authorities expelled him from the country on grounds of disturbing the peace. the ban was not officially lifted until 1978, cohn-bendit wrote in his book
cohn-bendit lives with his girl friend, but he said he doesn't intend to get married
it was 4 a.m., and the line of brazilians seeking tourist visas had already formed outside the u.s. consulate in rio de janeiro. it started near the front door and before long wound around the corner
ever since the brazilian government on jan. 1 rescinded a 25-percent surtax on overseas airplane tickets and on u.s. dollars purchased for foreign travel, the consulate has been besieged with visa requests
on this particulary morning, one man in the line _ he refused to give his name _ had no intention of going to disneyworld or looking out over new york city from the top of the empire state building. he was there, he said, because he can sell his place in line later for 10,000 cruzados _ about $100
the desire of brazilians to travel to the united states is growing, not only because it is cheaper nowadays, but because at least some hope to stay there, even if illegally
in 1987 the number of those seeking u.s. visas averaged 300 a day. now it is 450, sometimes more than 600
there has been an increased demand for services, but our resources have not expanded accordingly,'' clyde bishop, the head of the consular section, said in an interview
the consulate has just one u.s.foreign service officer to handle non-immigrant visas
me,'' bishop said
the result is delay, and grumbling and dissatisfaction on both sides
our people are working 10 to 12 hours a day processing visas,'' bishop said. ``often they go without lunch.''
the consulate's air conditioning broke down recently, and the temperature inside reached 100 degrees
the situation is serious,'' said oscar dalsenter, president of the brazilian association of travel agencies. ``we have people with reserved flights and booked hotels who miss their trips because of the visa delay,''
most of the visa seekers are legitimate travelers, happy about the repeal of the tax and hoping to take advantage of cheap charter flights to the united states
a brazilian can fly to disneyworld in florida and back in a charter group for $650. the normal round-trip economy fare from rio de janeiro to miami is $1,600
the price drops even more if a tourist _ ticket and visa in hand _ decides to buy the permitted $1,000 for foreign travel at the official government exchange rate. near the end of february, for example, a traveler could have bought the $1,000 for 97,000 brazilian cruzados and immediately sold the dollars back in rio's loosely controlled black market for 121,000 cruzados. the profit then goes to offset the cost of the plane ticket
but some in the lines are brazilians hoping to use tourist visas to stay in the united states as illegal aliens. the u.s. state department has reported that the number of illegal brazilians in the united states recently has been on the rise
according to newspaper polls, a growing number of brazilians want to leave the country for good because of serious economic and political problems
among the measures the u.s. consulate has taken is to require potential tourists to show proof of income to pay for an american vacation. it also has stopped issuing visas assigned just to ``the bearer'' and requires photographs with each application. all this has slowed the process
the prime duty of a consular officer is to make sure foreigners do not get into the united states under fraudulent pretenses,'' bishop said. ``on the other hand, u.s. policy is to facilitate matters for legitimate tourists who want to visit our country. so we have to carefully go over each request.''
the travel agents have proposed, and the consulate is considering, separate visa handling, en masse, two days a week for brazilian passports submitted by registered travel agencies
the travel agents association has promised to police its own ranks
dalsenter, the association's president, maintained the travel agencies' proposal would reduce the confusion in the visa lines and discourage the selling of places
bishop said, ``we have heard reports of money changing hands out there, but we have no concrete proof.''
it goes on every day,'' dalsenter said. ``everybody knows it.''
on the day an associated press reporter and photographer arrived at the consulate at 4 a.m., no one on line would agree to be interviewed or give his or her name. many turned their backs or covered up documents they were holding
a brazilian policeman then came by and chased away the photographer, citing reasons of ``security.'' photo, 1 drawing. colorfoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</note>

editor's note _ with civilization encroaching on the amazon rain forest at the rate of 80,000 square miles a year, ap special correspondent hugh a. mulligan decided he'd better go see the world's longest river before it's too late. here's his journal of a recent cruise 1,200 miles up the amazon on a small passenger ship
aaaah-yeeee-haaaaa.'' tarzan cries upstage the incessant caw of birds, the chatter of monkeys and peeping of frogs in the vine-tangled rain forest
in the morning mist on the amazon river, dozens of dugout canoes dart out from a thatched village hugging the muddy bank, where a scrawny pig and a few frazzled chickens scurry beneath the banana trees
the cries of the canoeists, paddling furiously toward us with what seemed to be long-handled, gaily painted pingpong paddles, brought out more boats from houses on stilts farther upstream and in the side creeks
they come to greet us but also to keep their boats from being smashed against those little wooden docks by our bow wave,'' says capt. harry biehl, looking down from the bridge wing of the 10,000-ton mv berlin, a small west german passenger ship
most of the 270 passengers desert morning bouillon on the lido deck to hug the rails with their cameras and shower down chocolate bars, fruit from the dining room, soap from their cabins, cigarettes and ball point pens in plastic bags on the indian families, from toothless grandmothers down to the tiniest infants, bobbing about in the mini-armada that soon slid by in our churning wake
around the next bend, where a generator throbs and a tv antenna rises improbably above the flame and rubber trees, the excited yells of a small boy out on the landing empties out the clapboard casa de sao jeronimo mission, leaving the preacher waiting at the altar on a steamy sunday morning, as his parishoners took to their boats
what next?
first came the conquistadors, dropouts from francisco pizarro's expedition against the incas. then the bandeirantes, the slave traders, followed by the diamond hunters and the garimpeiros, the gold prospectors. next the rubber barons, who were crueler and greedier than the slavers, then the loggers and ranchers, soon joined by the industrialists and power dam builders, chewing up the rain forest with their voracious machines at the rate of 80,000 square miles a year
and now tourists
the amazing amazon, the widest, wettest and, so national geographic now affirms, the longest river in the world (4,007 miles, 51 longer than the nile), boasts the longest snake, the most venomous viper, the biggest rat, beetle and ant, along with razor-toothed piranhas that can reduce a brahman steer to raw bones in minutes and electric eels delivering 640 volts, enough to drive a metro-north commuter train. this surging, swarming stream, veined by 1,000 tributaries, that on its majestic march from the andes to the atlantic carries one-fifth of the fresh water discharged into the sea by all rivers of the world, now has seen it all
tourists, yet. no wonder the crocodiles stared with jaws agape from the seclusion of gigantic victoria regia lily pads, and the pumas and jaguars fled into the forest fastness
the strange thing is that our mini-liner, small enough to navigate the amazon's side channels, avoiding the freighter and barge traffic in the broad mainstream, was as much a novelty to the natives unencumbered by cameras as they were to us
smiling and wide-eyed, they swarmed about with blowguns, javelins, bows and arrows to sell for only a few dollars or barter for the clothes off your back. mask makers, a declining skill, offered replicas of the palm fiber yagua headdress, framed with shoulder-length blonde braids, that erroneously gave the amazon its name. gaspar de caravaj, a dominican friar who accompanied the conquistadores in 1541, mistook the local tribesmen in their shoulder-length headdresses for women warriors. in his journal he gave the name amazon to the river, after the lady legionnaires of greek legend, writing of ``battling warrior women who fought as 10 indian men.''
the tourist incentive is to see it all before it is too late
the forest is all gone south of here. who knows what will be left by the end of the century?'' lamented serafim bastedo, a dock crane operator at belem, 90 miles from the mouth, the largest city on the amazon
now a city of l.2 million, with 24-story high-rise apartments, a huge manganese plant, open-pit iron mines, modern hospitals and a six-lane highway to brasilia 1,000 miles to the south, belem is a boom town of jarring contrasts
the luxurious hilton hotel is flanked by side streets of narrow portuguese houses, a door and two windows wide, out of the l7th century. its shopping district pulsates to a samba beat broadcast at top volume from municipal loudspeakers
brazilians can't live without noise,'' serafim shouts over the din
the yacht club shares the riverfront with a rickety fishing fleet out of another century, jungle medicine stalls selling dried snakeskins filled with herbs, bones and feathers, and a sprawling outdoor market with hundreds of tarpaulin-covered restaurants redolent of roasting cassava and pato no tucupi, duck stewed in a tangy yellow soup. on the far shore lies marajo island, bigger than denmark, rangeland for 400,000 brahman cattle
belem's excellent goeldi nature preserve keeps alive in a jungle setting the amazon's more bizarre residents: the 38-foot-long anaconda, the deadly bushmaster, the endangered manatee, the 4-foot-long rat called the capybara, exotically plumed and beaked parrots and toucans, long-tailed squirrel monkeys and lumbering, leathery tapirs, the brazilian mammal that looks like the love child of dumbo and miss piggie
a few miles upstream the street lights vanish and the rain forest resumes
two brazilian pilots, sharing four-hour shifts, keep watch for shifting sandbars, sudden current shifts where tributaries enter and the writhing limbs of partially submerged trees toppled from the eroding red clay banks as we negotiate the narrow breves-macacos channel
like the mississippi, the river is always changing,'' observed first officer andreas jungblut, who has taken freighters up to baton rouge, la. ``but in the amazon there are no buoys or channel markers, except for a rare light marking a sharp bend.''
at least,'' adds capt. biehl, ``there are no bridges to worry about all the way to peru.''
flocks of yellow-bellied birds called bem-ti-vi, ``i see you,'' dart along the shore, and baldheaded vultures with enormous wingspreads glide lazily overhead in the faint equatorial air currents. the sailor on bow watch spots a trio of red freshwater dolphins frisking just ahead
night brings the telegraph-wire whine of cicadas, the shrieking of nocturnal dourcouli monkeys, a sudden boom of thunder or another falling tree, a solitary silver nighthawk soaring beneath the southern cross and, so the first mate insists, the mating yowl of a jaguar
sunrise finds some passengers down on all fours photographing the huge moths, fat beetles and slant-faced grasshoopers attracted to our decks. a barman shimmies up the radio mast to pin a mammoth purple and gold butterfly for his collection
before noon, the city of santarem, 700 miles from the sea, breaks the monotony of forest and savanna. settled by confederate veterans of the civil war, this gateway to the gold fields has false-front cafes right out of the american west, signboarded with names like higgins, jackson and macdonald
a torrential downpour cancels a barbecue at alter do chao, a nearby pink ribbon of beach. then a rainbow arches over the river, and the berlin lowers her motor launches so passengers can swim in the amazon and walk out for nearly a mile on a narrow, curling sandbar
where have all the piranhas gone?'' an elderly lady inquires
fled for their lives,'' answers ship's surgeon heinz wehselau
next morning the boats are lowered again for a visit to boca de valeria, a native village of thatched huts on stilts and a red mud trail through tangled wetlands teeming with exotic flowers, brilliantly plumed birds and strange insects, like a 4-inch-long crawling something brightly banded in black and yellow with a red head and tail. the landing party returns with bows and arrows, spears and a variety of tick and mosquito bites
some 1,200 miles up river, just below manaus, nature stages a spectacular for the film buffs on board. on our left, the coffee-brown solimoes river, flowing a mile wide out of lush lowlands, meets the broad black rio negro, fed far upstream by the snows of the andes
for a dozen miles they flow side by side without mingling, like competing oil slicks. the banks of the solimoes swarm with leeches and insects, while the rio negro is almost pest free
even the fish swim aloof in their different colored currents,'' the brazilian pilot informs us
the two eventual mix at the ``wedding of the waters'' to form the amazon's final surge to the sea
at manaus, the berlin ties up to the floating dock built by british engineers at the turn of the century and assembled piece by piece to accommodate the 45-foot rise and fall of the river
the custom house and ``little ben,'' the clock chiming in the plaza before the cathedral, also were prefabricated in europe in the days when rubber was king and manaus glittered like the el dorado dreamed of by the conquistadors
workmen were busy restoring the italian frescoes in the gold-domed teatro amazonas, the 1,000-seat opera house that showcased jenny lind, the ballet russe and string quartets playing liszt for the rubber barons, whose decaying mansions are now subdivided into tenements. in 1910, manaus boasted french modistes, british tailors, 15 miles of streetcar track and cafes with fountains gushing champagne
such luxury in the middle of a rain forest was purchased at a terrible price in human suffering. the indians who tapped the white latex from the wild rubber trees were kept in virtual peonage by their white and mestizo patrones
penned up at night, underpaid for their labor, overcharged at the company store, often sick with malaria and dengue fever, the tappers were kept to a quota by guards armed with clubs and guns. the first failure to meet the quota resulted in a beating. the tapper lost an ear for the second failure, his other ear for the third and was killed for the fourth
international commissions met to protest the brutality. then henry wickham, a british biologist, solved the problem by smuggling out seeds of the wild rubber tree to the royal botanical gardens at kew for cultivation as a plantation crop in the malaysian states
by 1915, the boom was over. cheaper, asian rubber dominated the market. manaus receded to a town on stilts at the water's edge with suburbs of ``flutuantes,'' floating houses, as the rain forest reclaimed the cobblestone streets leading to the candy-colored villas on the cliffs
but now with an oil refinery, a 60,000-ton steel plant, huge sawmills and government-decreed duty-free shops to bolster its economy, manaus is making a comeback. jumbo jets fly in daily from miami and rio
the sprawling tropical hotel, cleared from the jungles along the rio negro, is attracting conventions from around the world, along with jet setters and antwerp diamond dealers to its arcade of boutiques and jewelry stores
at the height of the rubber boom, 400 passenger ships a year left liverpool for manaus
two or three cruise ships a month call here now, but we are hoping for many more,'' says godfrey springer from tooting bec outside of london who settled in the amazon with his brazilian wife. he makes his living taking tourists up the side creeks of the solimoes in a frail putt-putt boat to view crocodiles lurking among the victoria regia lily pads, broad enough for a small, brave child to use as a float for sun bathing
one would think that like joseph conrad's hero, mr. kurtz, the natives would cry, ``the horror, the horror,'' at the first sight of tourists invading the heart of their dark rain forest. instead they smile and offer snakeskin handbags and masks made of turtle shells that will certainly be confiscated by u.s. customs agents
the amazon indeed has seen it all
belem, brazil _ some droll, delightful or deadly denizens of the amazon rain forest:
anaconda _ the world's super snake, a 38-foot constrictor that suffocates rather than crushes its prey, the distinction usually being lost on the victim
bushmaster _ twelve feet of vicious, venomous viper
capybara _ king rat, 4 feet from pointy nose to lack of a tail
crested toucan _ birdland's pinocchio, the perennial cover star of nature magazines and travel folders
dinoponera gigantea _ world's biggest ant at 1{ inches long
electric eel _ it's a carp, not an eel, delivering 640 volts, enough to power a commuter train. indians believe its most jarring jolt is saved for fishermen who catch more than they need
fer-de-lance _ hissing cousin of the copperhead, but faster and fiercer with the fang
jaguar _ this loud-mouthed cat out-roars and out-runs the larger lion and tiger
manatee _ harmless, hapless and hunted, a flippered, whale-tailed mammal that grazes on waterlilies; known locally as the sea cow
morpho didius _ monarch of all the butterflies with a 7-inch wingspread
peccary _ a red-eared distant relation of the wild hog, cute but pugnacious
paiche _ a 400-pound catfish, succulent but seldom pan-ready
piranha _ only 4 to 15 inches, these ravenous, razor-toothed fish, with a school enrollment into the thousands, can skeletonize a cow or a cowhand in a matter of minutes
tapir _ a lumbering, leathery mixture of hog and rhino that's got to be seen, but not up too closely, to be believed
three-toed sloth _ upside down tree-snoozing quadruped of legendary lethargy; may be self-endangered for preferring siesta to sex
titanus giganteus _ a half-foot long, hard-shelled beetle, the global giant of its genus
vampire bat _ count dracula's late-night drinking buddy with a thirst for blood light; its dagger-sharp central incisors spread rabies throughout the amazon. photos. colorfoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</note>

editor's note _ when it comes to finding homes for orphaned pets, the north shore animal league is big league indeed. a combination of operational savvy, a gift for fund raising, and large doses of affection for its charges enable the league to place more than 40,000 cats and dogs each year, including animals regularly rescued from the pound
mehitabel, a calico cat, arrived by taxi from new york city with a $100 bill around her neck. the note asked the north shore animal league to find her a good home
the anonymous owner knew that this non-profit organization, totally supported by voluntary contributions, never destroys an animal
others do not arrive in such style. they are simply tied outside in the cold of night. no note, no donation, just a trusting dog waiting for an owner's return, a return that will never happen. that final pat, if there was one, was goodbye
and if that's not enough to handle, north shore has five vans that daily go to dog pounds to rescue animals on ``death row.'' the league spends $60,000 a year in pound fees alone gathering the doomed. some of them, anyway
what sets the north shore animal league apart from other equally noble operations throughout the country is sheer volume. its directors say it places more animals in homes than any other shelter in the world. consider these statistics:
_it placed more than 43,000 animals in 1987, although it can only kennel 400 animals at a time, with another 100 in its foster home system
_an animal's average stay at the league is less than three days
_the kennel operation runs a $3.5 million deficit each year, but its creative fund raising and direct-mail campaigns pull in $5 million
_the league spends half a million dollars a year placing ads and mails out over 30 million pleadings to potential donors each year
_it is open 12 hours a day, seven days a week
_the average contribution by adopters is $17
despite the good work, the league's animal-loving staff is quick to point out that their effort scarcely makes a dent in the slaughter of unwanted pets in this country
the american humane society, based in denver, estimates that about 20 million unwanted dogs and cats are put to death each year
the league works hard to educate people to neuter their pets and its credo is that there is no such thing as an unadoptable animal. it's their job to match the right animal with the right person. they matched a deaf dog with a deaf woman who was not only able to teach it tricks by hand signals, she also taught it to bark, just as she had been taught to talk
while the great majority of their animals are perfectly healthy, the league has managed to place three-legged dogs, a 12-year-old newfoundland, a giant pyrennees that couldn't walk and a cat with a bladder problem. on one freezing day recently, a cat lover named donna taffen of queens came in and asked for the least adoptable cat. she took home a 7-month old calico with a prolapsed eye
when an animal has been here for a while, the associates ask me to help. if i can get its picture in the paper or call it `pet of the week,' that usually works,'' says betty rosenzweig, the director of adoptions who has worked at the shelter for nearly 20 years
she's also a born saleswoman as she roams the compound, with praise for this dog or that cat
we are all salesmen in a sense, except that our commission is the satisfaction that up to 300 dogs and cats are adopted on some days,'' says michael arms, director of operations
some big hound and shepherd mixes, all-americans as the league calls the non-breed, have been waiting five or six months. but, the league knows eventually someone will fall for one of these big mongrels
some breeds, like yorkshire terriers and poodles, move so fast they often never see the inside of a cage. ditto purebred persian and siamese cats
alan cooper, 24-year-old graduate student in psychology and currently kennel manager, says that when he walked in the league five years ago, it was the best thing he ever did
he has seen cruelty and animal abuse, but also nobility he never expected
one man came in one day and asked for the ugliest dog we had. he wanted to adopt it and he did,'' recalls cooper. ``actually, was a 5- or 6-year-old terrier mix and it was so ugly, it was almost cute.''
another asked for the dog that had been there the longest. another requested the fattest cat. a blind man specified he wanted the dog with the most beautiful eyes.   
when cooper began here, he drove one of the vans that rescue doomed dogs from the pounds. workers on that duty usually burn out quickly, he said
they're told they can only bring 10 dogs back and the pound might have 40 dogs that are going to be put to sleep. it's awful to make that choice,'' he says. ``they usually bring back 14 instead of 10, but they know there is no room for all 40.''
the north shore animal league is truly a national organization. contributions and animals come in from many parts of the country, and because of the league's reputation, people often adopt their pets here while on vacation
the not-so-secret ingredients behind its success are alex and babette lewyt, a well-to-do couple who came to port washington to retire in the late '60s. lewyt made his fortune as an inventor, with 200 patents to his credit, including the lewyt vacuum cleaner. babette lewyt took one look at the old north shore league, a down-at-the-heels operation that was about to go under, and set out to transform it
both of them would work here from dawn to dusk, cleaning out cages, and doing everyting that needed to be done,'' says ms. rosenzweig. ``he took out the first ad in the new york times under the adoption columns, advertising a free golden retriever and some other purebreds. the ad cleared out the shelter
in business since 1944, the physical plant is not much to look at _ a gerrymandered hodgepodge of rooms with cages stacked atop each other. it's on a side street in a long island bedroom community some 20 miles from manhattan. the original building was donated by a san francisco woman. one individual left the league $200,000 in a will
the league has strict guidelines. one out of five potential adopters are turned down. it is no coincidence that the man working the parking lot is an off-duty policeman. punches have been thrown when someone was rejected
besides precautions, there is a ``dowry,'' including a leash, collar, id tag, starting food, a training book and a 30-day health insurance policy. but they also check references right there on the spot, making one area resemble a bookie operation. on occasion, they make on-site follow-up calls. this accounts for a return rate of only 6 percent
arms, partial to newfoundlands, worried when his favorite was adopted by a queens couple. he drove by the house and found the dog chained outside on cement with the new owners at work. an 8-foot cyclone fence enclosed the area
arms telephoned the pair, fibbing about a faulty blood test, and asked the couple to bring the dog in for further checking. then he snatched the newfie back and delivered a lecture to the highly displeased couple
arms can be a tough guy when it comes to rescuing dogs. when he worked for the american society for the prevention of cruelty to animals in the bronx, he was stabbed by three men who were betting on how long a wounded dog would live. they objected to arms' interference with the outcome
the league also backs their orphans. for $15 you can bring your dog back for obedience training for as long as it needs it. such training can cost as much as $50 an hour elsewhere
the league will also neuter your animal for a token fee _ $30 for a female, $20 for a male. ``and if you can't afford that, it gets even cheaper,'' says arms. ``free.''
once in a while, workers let instinct replace checking
such was the case with bruce and monsita abramski and their three children of central islip, n.y
both adults were experienced dog owners, the children all loved grandma's dog, and they were about to move into a larger and more secluded home where mrs. abramski would be all alone with the kids. they wanted a puppy to grow up with the kids, but mature into a big watchdog
they settled on a chubby, big-boned, mostly black pup, about 6 weeks old, with telltale big paws, and to judge by looking, lots of shepherd genes
jessica, the eldest at 8, took over as family spokesperson and declared the puppy would be named ``tramp.''
we will all vote on the name,'' her father corrected as six little hands all reached in unison to pet the new addition, whose sad brown eyes looked a bit overwhelmed
monsita abramski shook her head
do you think the puppy is up to these kids?''
if puppies are puppies and kids are kids, mrs. abramski, it's a sure thing. illustration.)</note>

editor's note _ there are still a lot of lakes and mountains and such in alaska without proper names, but not because no one has any ideas. naming geographic features simply gets bogged down in red tape, with both state and federal agencies to satisfy. and some of the suggestions seem frivolous at best
a fisherman's pet dog dies, dead blackfish are found floating on a lake, a college student loses his a skiff in a storm, british paratroopers scale an alaskan peak
those are some of the events that inspired requests from people who want the state of alaska to name a lake, stream, creek, island, mountain or some other landmark in honor of someone or something
don lallemand from the state of washington buried his dog mitzi on an unnamed southeast alaska island 12 years ago. he wrote the state geographic board in 1986 asking that the two-acre island be named in honor of mitzi
we buried a small dog who had traveled with us for years aboard the boat and loved the area as much as we do,'' he wrote
lallemand included a picture showing the sign he posted on the island, naming it for mitzi. he plants flowers and trees near the grave site every year
but lallemand has not heard anything from the state board in the two years since he submitted his request. ``we're very disappointed,'' he says
he is not alone
the board has almost 100 requests on file, waiting for action
the board last met in august. before that, it met in march 1985
we are swamped,'' says gladyce williamson, secretary to the board
williamson serves as secretary to the state community and regional affairs commissioner, who chairs the geographic board. she said there is no extra staff for the board, and she must process the applications while also handling her regular duties for the commissioner
the eight-member board, comprised of state officials and one public appointee, reviewed 10 requests at the august meeting. ``the federal people had really been pushing and really wanted some action on the oldest cases,'' williamson says
the oldest cases date back six or seven years, she says
all recommendations from the state board go to the u.s. domestic geographic names board for final approval
one of the priority cases was a request from the u.s. army corps of engineers to name a mountain near the interior brooks range for a federal geologist. his name is reuben kachadoorian. for ease of pronunciation, williamson said, the corps proposed reuben's peak
most requests come from individuals, not government agencies. some landowners get upset when the board refuses to allow them to name features on their own property
a home-site owner had asked that a lake be named for dead blackfish found floating on the surface. his nomination of deadfish lake southwest of fairbanks was deferred by the board
homesteaders north of anchorage want to pick their own name for a small lake on their property. ``we felt it was not only our responsibility to the community, but also our privilege to name a feature on our property,'' they wrote in their nominating letter
the backlog of nominations includes the expected personal requests such as otto's lake and moore's mountain, and also some unexpected ones
in 1985 a 24-year-old college student from the lower 48 wrote a sad tale of losing _ and finding _ a skiff while crab fishing in the aleutian islands
his crew lost their skiff in a storm and then recovered it. ``now, when we happen to anchor at this cove, we affectionately refer to it as skiff cove.''
the board also deferred action on skiff cove
williamson said nominations must meet certain criteria to win the board's approval. commemorative names get the most thorough review
_the person for whom the feature is to be named must be dead at least one year
_the application must include a biography and the person's length of stay in alaska
_the nomination must have local support and the native corporation in the area must be consulted
the person must have made a substantial contribution to a city or the state or their rural area,'' williamson says
some commemorative requests appear to fall a little short of that criterion
a small creek northeast of fairbanks has been nominated as pete bloom pup, after a trapper who killed himself in 1937
according to the nominating letter and a 1937 newspaper article accompanying the request, pete bloom had fallen into the ice and knew that even if he lived he would lose his hands and feet to frostbite. ``he took a snare and put it around his neck and then attached it to his dog sled. he then told his dogs to mush, thereby choking himself to a fast death.''
a kenai peninsula resident wants the board to name a lake in the kenai national moose range as dangerous lake. the person had once found a cow moose near the lake, killed by a bear, and must have figured it was a dangerous spot to be
a fairbanks resident wants a waterway near the dalton highway named solitude creek
this wayward wandering hall of wonder does not entertain the aspects of fear, only unpolluted silence. this is a fitting name as it will no doubt draw others who will be searching for that very avenue of adventure.''
an anchorage resident nominated tranquility lake northwest of town
a kenai resident likes the name of the greek goddess of the sea
giving a lesson in mythology the person wrote, ``thetis, the mother of achilles, saved him by hanging onto his foot and the lake is shaped like a foot.'' therefore, he proposes the name lake thetis
never mind that thetis is also the kenai man's first name
a 12,060-foot peak in denali national park was scaled in 1956 by members of a british parachute regiment. the regiment's symbol is pegasus, the flying horse
although the regiment may have named the peak in their honor, the federal review board in 1985 rejected pegasus peak. the state geographic board still has the file open
tired of butterfly lake and butterfly creek, of which there are several in the state, one nominee suggested the french name for the insect _ papillon pond
even children get into the act. ``my daughter thought of the name after my mustache and a moose,'' said a proud parent in asking that the state name a small lake moosestache lake. illustration.)</note>

editor's note _ it's the southernmost inhabited point in canada, an island on lake erie virtually isolated in the winter. but the island's population has dwindled as farms become more mechanized and today local officials are looking for ways to keep the young folks at home
they sometimes call it canada's key west, but until the spring thaw comes, the 195 year-round residents of pelee island on ice-crusted lake erie are virtually cut off from the outside world
from mid-december, when the last tourist boats head home, until the ice pack breaks up in late march, commuter flights to windsor, ontario, and sandusky, ohio, are the only direct link with the mainland
pelee island, 16 miles south of the canadian mainland and 22 miles north of sandusky, is the southernmost inhabited point in canada
the only problem with pelee island is you either love it or hate it,'' says donna olsen, who runs a bait and tackle shop with her husband, svend. the olsens are among the year-round residents of the island, 11,000 acres of farmland, scrub and beaches
about 300 people consider it their primary residence and up to 1,500 people crowd its 17 square miles during the summer, when the ferries mv pelee islander and mv upper canada ply their regular routes between the island, kingsville and leamington, ontario, and sandusky
visitors are few in the winter months, mostly small groups of hunters who want to make use of one of the few decent spots within hundreds of miles for shooting pheasant
i don't have an attitude that it's an isolated place,'' says helen mccormick, owner of the pelee passage restaurant, which offers the island's only year-round food service
the island's hotel, motel, bar and other two restaurants close for the winter
the pelee passage restaurant is the site of a tuesday night card game and the canadian legion hall hosts a friday night gathering
seated at the restaurant one recent afternoon were four pheasant hunters who had flown over that morning on the six-passenger piper navajo that makes twice-daily flights to the island
we're friends and we go up north every fall, moose hunting and bear hunting,'' says dudley sparks of merlin, ontario
if you want to hunt pheasant, you have to go to pelee,'' said one of his companions, gary ryckman of muirkirk, ontario
farming has dominated the economy of pelee island since the first european settlers arrived in the 1820s. while fields of soy beans, wheat and corn still cover about 7,000 acres, the population has dropped sharply as mechanization has increased the acreage one farmer can plant and harvest
there were close to 1,000 people here when i was growing up,'' says don gow, a retired postmaster born on the island in 1902. ``if you had 50 acres and a team of horses, you were pretty busy all summer. if you work it with a tractor, that's a day's work.''
more typical today is the 540-acre spread farmed by bill krestel, the ``reeve'' or supervisor of the township of pelee island. krestel was born on the island to a farm family that emigrated from romania before world war ii
as is common among farmers everywhere, he holds several jobs to supplement his income, working as a telephone repairman for bell canada, deputy game warden and occasional hunting guide
his post as the island's top elected official brings him about $1,200 a year
krestel says lack of employment opportunity drove most of his classmates off the island. he wants that to end
when i went to school, there were 13 kids in my class and about 130 in the school,'' he says. now there are 25 in kindergarten through eighth grade at the two-room pelee island public school
five young people from the island attend high school in kingsville on the canadian mainland, boarding with local families and flying home on weekends
what you've got to have is a job that a kid who has gone to school can be proud to do,'' krestel said. ``you can look at a million things and it always comes back to tourism.''
he and other island officials and merchants are at work on a number of projects to boost pelee's tourist trade
key to the expansion is the introduction of a larger, 400-passenger ferry, with space for 45 cars, to replace the mv upper canada, which can carry a maximum of 100 people and 10 vehicles
the mv pelee islander, with capacity for 267 people and 15 cars, will continue to run
we'll almost double our capacity,'' he says
getting tourists to the island is only half the battle. krestel and others are trying to drum up more things to keep visitors busy while they're here
a pelee heritage center, featuring exhibits on the island's history and economy, is to open on may 1. the town council will experiment with a third pheasant hunt, importing adult birds to supplement the 20,000 raised each year on the island's pheasant farm
the 1,600 permits for the two hunts sell out within days
recently, krestel and peter pfeifer, vineyard manager for the pelee island winery, sat at pfeifer's kitchen table and discussed plans for a tasting center that would allow visitors to sample products of the island's grapes and tour the nearby pheasant farm
pfeifer took the job in february 1986 after answering an advertisement in a west german wine magazine, bringing his wife, inge, and their two daughters from heppenheim, a city of 36,000, to the island community
the moderating effect of lake erie gives pelee island an average of 19 more frost-free days than the mainland and its rich dark soil yields hearty, sweet grapes that are shipped to the winery in kingsville for processing
while pfeifer talks, daughter alice, 4, wanders in from the living room where she is watching cartoons on television, clutching a stuffed bear
daddy, i'm thirsty and baby bear is thirsty,'' she said. pfeifer gets them a drink
island life has been good for alice and her big sister, denise, 7, a second-grader at the island's two-room school. other children live just across the road
the remoteness has been harder on his wife, who had stayed on in windsor after a family trip to the mainland earlier in the week
it's a little more difficult for the women out here,'' pfeifer said. ``there is no shopping. it can be isolating out here.''
occasionally, if the lake freezes hard and deep enough, snowmobilers will trek from pelee south to put-in-bay on south bass island, a part of ohio
lisa nageleisen came to pelee island to teach in 1981, met and married a ferry worker. she teaches 11 children in grades four through eight while in the next room, debbie janzen teaches 14 children from kindergarten through third grade
it's a juggling act,'' nageleisen said as she and janzen watched from a classroom window as the children frolicked outside. ``the kids learn to work a little more independently. the older ones will sometimes help the younger ones
they're not as segregated in terms of grades. at lunch, the whole school was playing soccer.''
because the children spend years with the same teachers, they often become very close
nageleisen says she stays in contact with former students who have gone away to college on the mainland
i hope that they come back and find something here and remain pelee islanders,'' she says. photo. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>

editor's note _ over the past two decades he has written some of america's most popular songs, starting with ``up, up and away'' in 1967. but jimmy webb has not been able to get off the ground on broadway, even while working with some of the top names in the theater. he's still trying, with three productions in the works
ace songwriter jimmy webb, who has returned to performing, is still trying to crack broadway after several frustrating years of trying
so many of these things, you can work on them for years and you don't get to see anything,'' he says. ``someone told me it took eight years to get `annie' on broadway. it's a tough business.''
webb is also not forgetting the record market, his bread and butter. he alternates, writing one song for records, one for a broadway show
nobody pays anybody to write broadway shows,'' he says. ``there's nothing up front. and i think it's dangerous to work 15 months on a musical and not write one song for the record market. record people say, `is he still alive?'''
after 1967, when his ``up, up and away'' became the first big hit for the fifth dimension and his ``by the time i get to phoenix'' put glen campbell on the charts, webb concentrated on the record market. campbell scored again with webb's ``wichita lineman'' and ``galveston.'' actor richard harris had record hits with webb's ``macarthur park'' and ``didn't we?''
but in the 1980s, webb has concentrated on writing for broadway. three productions are planned for next season _ on broadway, off-broadway and in dublin, ireland
so far, nothing webb has written has been performed on broadway. the shows he worked on, with some of the top names in the theater, never opened
webb composes in a studio in a manhattan building that was owned by the late michael bennett, the master director of ``a chorus line'' and ``dreamgirls.''
the first musical i did with michael, `scandal,' i spent 14 months in this room writing, almost every day,'' webb recalls. to no avail. 
i got kind of uncomfortable with that. i feel i have to get back to these individual songs. but they're harder. i think it's easier to write songs when you know the plot than sitting down with a blank piece of paper and going, `let's write a hit, here.'''
webb accomplished the latter this winter with ``still within the sound of my voice,'' glen campbell's first hit record in 10 years. it was campbell, a friend for 20 years, who in 1985 suggested webb's four-verse ``the highwayman'' to waylon jennings, willie nelson, johnny cash and kris kristofferson
at 41, webb also is singing in cabarets, accompanying himself on the piano. during january and february he performed at jan wallman's and the ballroom in new york and at the hollywood roosevelt hotel's ``cinegrill.''
i'm just not ready to pack it up yet,'' webb says
he performed with a rock band in the early 1970s, but stopped after a second tour as opening act for the group america. he made six record albums in the 1970s but none sold exceptionally well
amy grant sings webb's ``if these walls could speak'' on her next album. webb co-wrote ``home of the brave'' with david paich of toto for that group's new album. ``his father, marty paich, arranged `up, up and away.''' webb says. david was about 12 then
in 1980, webb moved to tuxedo park, n.y., and began writing ``tuxedo,'' a show based on the history of the once-fashionable suburb of new york city where the dinner jacket that bears its name was introduced. ``i was wasting time,'' webb says. ``i knew nothing about what i was doing.''
then recording mogul david geffen introduced webb to michael bennett and webb started working on ``scandal.''
but bennett announced the postponement of ``scandal'' two weeks before scheduled rehearsals in broadway's mark hellinger theater
we call it black monday,'' webb recalls. ``we had treat williams and swoosie kurtz and most of the great dancers and singers from the original `chorus line' and some others from `dreamgirls.'''
webb says that bennett probably decided the times were not right for a show about infidelity
next they started working on another musical together called ``children's crusade.''
there was a mass uprising of children in france and germany, twice, 40 years apart in the 13th century. huge groups of children left their homes and banded together and declared their intention to go to the holy land. and did it. people would ask where they were going. they'd say they were going to heaven, to see jesus. there were hundreds of thousands of them, white-robed children carrying little wooden crosses with this light in their eyes
one of the last conversations i ever had with michael, he wanted me to go ahead with it. he still thought it was the best idea he'd ever had for a broadway show.''
webb hopes it'll arrive on broadway next season
last summer webb wrote the music and he and ray bradbury collaborated on lyrics for a musical, based on bradbury's novel, ``dandelion wine.'' it's planned for off-broadway next season
it's about learning as an adult to face yourself as a child,'' webb says. ``that way you find out a lot about why you are the way you are and maybe you can become happier with yourself
ray and i have a song, `kangaroo tennis shoes,' in which this 11-year-old has his first pair of tennies and all the things he is going to do in them.''
and, webb is working with dale wasserman, librettist of ``man of la mancha,'' on a george bernard shaw play, ``the shewing up of blanco bosnet.''
it's a one-act play about the old west, about which shaw knew absolutely nothing, which makes it hilarious,'' webb says. ``we have a commitment from the abbey theater in dublin.''
webb says he has also written eight chapters of a novel about a boy of 12 growing up in southwest oklahoma. ``it is about me, quite a lot about my grandfather and my sons are woven in there, as well,'' he says
webb and his wife patsy got married under a big oak tree, on musician jimmy messina's ranch in ojai, calif. the composer of ``up, up and away'' had a balloon for guests to ride in at the wedding reception
they now have five sons, chris, 15, justin, 12, james, 9, corey, 5, and charles, 9 months. photos.)</note>

editor's note _ early this century, railroads looking for cheap labor brought mexicans to an illinois town where they lived first in boxcars and later in cramped bungalows along a narrow street. but that winding lane has earned the name hero street for the patriotism of its residents, and some think it should be made a national monument
for more than 40 years, scores of mexican-americans have gone off to war from a winding drive of tiny wood-frame houses perched on a hillside rising from an old rail yard in this illinois town
eight have returned in caskets
and since 1968, the street has been named hero street u.s.a. in honor of the 110 young warriors who have left it for the armed forces since 1941. now a move is under way to get congress to name the former dirt path a national monument
for joe munos and his family, life on hero street always meant serving their country. not only did munos and his three brothers all fight for the united states _ his younger brother johnny died in korea _ but his three sons and his daughter joined the armed forces, as well as his grandson
that's the tradition of hero street,'' munos says. ``it must be in our blood. it's an honor for me to be a veteran of foreign wars.''
for georgia sandoval herrera, growing up on hero street meant watching a half-dozen brothers leave during world war ii and seeing two return in caskets. brothers joe and frank died 10 months apart and portraits of them in uniform still hang on her living room wall
it seemed like a ghost town during the war because so many of our boys were gone,'' she recalls. ``but we were one big family on hero street. the losses pulled us together. we're still a very close community
my son says, `why don't we move?' and i say the only place i'd want to live is hero street. there's no place like hero street.''
another sandoval family sent seven boys into world war ii and suffered one death
those kinds of statistics are common on hero street
no other single block in america has made so great a sacrifice, according to local officials. although the defense department can't confirm the claim, it's never been disputed in 20 years
a memorial park was built on the site in 1971 and now a city alderman is leading the drive to have congress declare hero street a national monument as a tribute to all who died in service _ especially immigrant soldiers
these men walked into this country and picked up arms without a complaint,'' says alderman joe terronez, 58. ``some weren't even citizens when they joined the armed forces. this is a great story about great heroes and it should be a national monument.''
located between billy goat bluff and honey creek, hero street is a small mexican barrio that winds its way back up a dead-end hollow near the rail yard in this town of 7,200
some of its 36 tiny bungalows sit precariously on the steep terrace of the bluff while others are perched just above the creek and appear to be sinking into the gully
many of the wood-frame homes are long and narrow, like the railroad boxcars they replaced. until a few years ago, the street was a dirt path that turned to mud and trapped hearses as they brought home dead soldiers
when terronez was growing up, hero street was simply 2nd street and a ``tough neighborhood.'' living conditions were poor for the large mexican families crowded into the cramped houses
the mexicans were brought to silvis early this century by the railroads who were looking for cheap labor. originally, they lived in boxcars in the nearby rail yard but were moved to 2nd street when townspeople complained about the growing mexican population in the yard
this is a story of our parents coming to the united states and adopting it,'' terronez says. ``although we were all viewed as aliens, the boys of hero street proved this was their country.''
the fight for national monument status is more than just a battle for recognition of the contribution made by eight dead soldiers or even 110 men and women who joined the armed forces
for terronez, it epitomizes the struggle of hispanic americans everywhere for appreciation and respect as first-class citizens. he's enlisted the help of u.s. rep. lane evans, a democrat from nearby rock island, in achieving national recognition in congress
hero street's residents hope for tangible benefits from elevating the street to a national monument
federal money would be available for maintaining the memorial, built on a bluff to resemble a mayan temple. residents also hope it would become a tourist attraction after placement on national parks system maps
steve vetzner, an aide in evans' washington office, said the congressman plans to work with the illinois delegation to get some sort of designation for hero street, such as a national monument, historic site or historic landmark
let's be honest _ naturally this would be a shot in the arm to hispanics,'' terronez says. ``sometimes, we feel we are second-class citizens. but when you look at the blood shed by hispanics on that one street you know we are real americans. it would be a source of great pride for all mexican-americans.'' photo.)</note>
actor kirk douglas says he learned just how controversial ``inherit the wind'' is when the movie company was turned away from filming at a private school in oregon
this is a play about the scopes monkey trial in 1925, but the issue is as relevant today as it was then,'' he says
the best example of that came when we planned to shoot a scene in a schoolhouse in a small town in oregon. we had made arrangements with the school's board to film scenes of the young teacher teaching darwin's theory of evolution. but when they found out what we were going to film they threw us out. they said they only teach biblical creationism.''
douglas, jason robards, jean simmons and darren mcgavin star in the new two-hour production of ``inherit the wind.'' david greene directed from a screenplay by john gay, based on the play by jerome lawrence and robert e. lee
douglas plays matthew harrison brady, a brilliant orator and fundamentalist politician invited to prosecute a teacher for bringing darwin's theory into the classroom. robards is henry drummond, a liberal lawyer who defends the teacher. simmons is brady's wife and mcgavin is a cynical reporter named e.k. hornbeck
the play, of course, is based on the trial of john scopes in tennessee. brady is really william jennings bryan, the three-time democratic presidential nominee. drummond is clarence darrow and hornbeck is h.l. mencken. it was made into a movie in 1960 with spencer tracy as drummond, frederic march as brady and gene kelly as hornbeck
it's interesting for an actor to play a role with a point of view you don't believe in,'' douglas says. ``i think he was very sincere. he wasn't a charlatan, he wasn't a buffoon. he believed every word in the bible should be accepted as it was written
that's what creates the dramatic friction between my character and jason robards'. they were both sincere in their beliefs. the pathetic quality which we develop is that these two men had been friends. clarence darrow had backed bryan in his first run for the presidency. it's touching because these two men are now bitter enemies.''
douglas says he wasn't interested when his son, peter, the executive producer, first brought the idea to him. he didn't want to do a remake of the movie, in which brady was more buffoonish
i never thought he should be played as a fool,'' he says. ``i played him as a mixture of pat robertson, billy graham and jimmy swaggart. brady wasn't gluttonous and eating all the time, the way he was in the movie.''
he also began to see how relevant the subject was because of the ongoing debate, evolution vs. creationism
the time of the trial was also moved to the fall
in the movie you see a hundred extras fanning away because of the summer heat,'' douglas says. ``we didn't want that. we also went back to the original trial transcript and picked up a few things. brady dies in the courtroom, but in reality bryan died five days after the trial ended. the play was never an attempt to be exact history.''
inherit the wind'' is douglas' second movie with son peter. the first was called ``amos,'' which was set in a home for the elderly
that's the exciting thing about doing movies for television,'' he says. ``you can deal with subjects you can't do for theatrical films. theatrical films seem to fall into certain formulas _ wild comedies, violence or young kids finding out about sex
on television you can do something with substance. this is the first program in the new `at&amp;t presents' series. what i like about that is that we have fewer commercial breaks.''
douglas' last theatrical film was ``tough guys,'' which also starred burt lancaster
i've got several projects pending, but i've been devoting my time to my autobiography,'' he says. ``i've just finished it and simon &amp; schuster will publish it. it was interesting to write, like taking a self-inventory. it was hard work. i found it painful. i wrote it by myself
one of my motivations for the book is that i have four sons. i'll say something and one of them will say, `gee, dad, i didn't know that.' i think this book is my chance to say who i am.''
douglas believes that the public has a different image than the one he has of himself
before `champion' in 1949 i'd played an intellectual schoolteacher, a weak schoolteacher and an alcoholic. after `champion,' i was a tough guy. i did things like playing van gogh, but the image lingers. that's one of the things i loved about `inherit the wind.' it was a battle of ideas rather than of physical violence.'' photo. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>
second stage has devoted an entire theater season to the plays of michael weller, a rare honor for playwrights these days
since november, the enterprising off-broadway company has presented ``moonchildren'' and ``loose ends,'' two of weller's best-known efforts. in april, it will offer the world premiere of his latest drama, ``spoils of war,'' at the troupe's small theater in what was once an old gymnasium on the upper west side
and in between there will be staged readings of other weller plays, panel discussions about weller and his work and viewings of ``ragtime'' and ``hair,'' two movies for which weller wrote the screenplays
for weller, the second stage celebration is a homecoming of sorts. since its start nine years ago, the company, which specializes in second looks at plays that may not have been successful the first time around, has been receptive to the playwright's writing
mike is one of the people who started the theater with us,'' remembers robyn goodman, one of the company's two artistic directors. ``he was one of the first people to write a play for us.''
and he's doing it again this year. ``spoils of war,'' the story of a mother and son in the 1950s, was commissioned by goodman and her second stage partner, carole rothman. kate nelligan plays the mother
one of the enticements in writing a new play was that mike would be cushioned to a certain extent by having his other plays done during the same season,'' rothman says. ``new york has kind of a hit-or-miss mentality. with our current season, people will be able to see a body of work. it's not as frightening for a playwright to premiere a new play when it's surrounded by plays that have been done before.''
the object of these theatrical festivities is a boyish, 45-year-old writer who does his writing out of an east village studio
the man is surprisingly low-keyed, considering he is under deadline to get ``spoils of war'' finished before it goes into rehearsal and considering he is juggling phone calls from texas where his latest screenplay actually has gone into production. it's a movie _ as yet untitled _ directed by hugh hudson and starring donald sutherland and adam horovitz of beastie boys fame
the film is about kids whose parents don't supervise them too much,'' weller says. ``the movie follows one boy through his adventures with a gang and getting into trouble with the law.''
he had no problem taking a new look at his old plays and was closely involved with the casting and directing of each revival. weller found the experience a pleasant one and didn't feel compelled to rewrite what he had written years ago
it's like going into your old neighborhood again,'' weller says. ``i usually work out of a real emotional knot and once that's untied, i don't feel much inclination to go back to a play.''
moonchildren,'' a look at college students in the 1960s at the beginning of the vietnam war protests, was his biggest success. it flopped on broadway in 1972 but had a successful off-broadway run the following year and has been a staple of regional theaters and acting classes ever since
loose ends'' examined the same generation 10 years later, when they were struggling to sort out their lives and loves. it was a harder play to write, weller says
for one thing, i knew more,'' weller says. ``the more deliberate you are in your writing, the harder it is. when you're a kid, you think no one's ever done this before. but the next time, you realize it's been done a million times.''
weller didn't start out to be a writer. he wanted to be a composer and studied music composition at brandeis
i wasn't a good musician,'' he admits, but when an opportunity came up to write a college musical, he enrolled in a playwriting course. writing eventually took precedence over composing and weller went off to england to study playwriting before eventually coming back to the united states
a handwritten copy of ``spoils of war'' lies on the desk in weller's study. the penmanship is small and precise
i write quite a bit every day but i hardly use any of it,'' the playwright says. ``i keep going back and poring over it, pulling things out. in that way, i am very slow to select what i'm finally going to use.''
weller's parents were both painters, so artistic discipline was in his blood. and success wasn't what counted the most
i saw people who went off to their workshop every day and painted,'' he recalls. ``for some of them, the glory train came in and for others, it didn't. you couldn't allow that to hinder your daily output. you couldn't allow yourself to get thrown by it.''
for that reason, weller, when he isn't helping take care of his young son, keeps to a rigid writing schedule. he jots down in notebooks ideas and notes for projects he will get to when he has time
i think the only hard lesson is not to have any big expectations,'' he says. ``just concentrate on what you are doing and get it right.''
the nazi occupation in world war ii and a lingering anti-semitism left the jews of france in disorder and disarray _ so much so that many renounced their heritage and took french names. but more recent years have seen a rebirth of jewry in a nation that is largely roman catholic, and a new era for jews has set in
friday is a busy day on the rue des rosiers, a narrow street in the heart of paris' oldest jewish quarter. it is there that shoppers preparing for the sabbath find everything from kosher chickens to prayer books and sacramental wines
this colorful neighborhood, and many others like it throughout predominantly roman catholic france, have come alive again as the jewish community revels in a new era of jewish pride and an upsurge of judaism
traumatized by world war ii, which saw the virtual dismantling of french jewry and the deportation of some 117,000 jews to nazi gas chambers, the community of guilt-ridden survivors lived in fear of anti-semitism and new persecutions
many renounced their jewish identities, changing their names, refusing to circumcize newborn boys as prescribed by their faith or to give their children jewish educations
today, those are just bad memories
jews again are playing major roles in the upper levels of french life _ government, industry, the intelligentsia, entertainment and the media
the change is largely due to the 150,000 sephardic jews from algeria, morocco and tunisia who poured in during the 1950s and 1960s as the french colonies in north africa gained independence
the sephardim are jews who originated in spain in the middle ages and who migrated to north africa after the spanish inquisition in 1492. many also moved to the middle east and the term now refers to all jews who are not of askenazic, or eastern european, origin
the sephardim make up more than 60 percent of france's population of 650,000 jews, the world's fourth-largest jewish community after the united states, israel and the soviet union
no one was as startled as today's sephardic jewish community when word came from washington earlier this year that they were considered wretched enough to warrant $8 million in emergency relief from the united states
sen. daniel k. inouye, d-hawaii, one of the measure's congressional backers, said the money for schools for north african jews in paris was earmarked for ``these unfortunates, these jews . .. who have not been absorbed or assimilated.''
the american funding, later cancelled by congress, was to build schools for ozar hatorah, a non-profit organization that promotes education, assistance and charity in 20 countries
globally, you can say that the integration of north african jews into french society has been a real success story,'' said emile touati, director of consistoire, the religious governing body for french jews
besides their own folklore, culinary habits, tight-knit family stucture and so-called ``mediterranean mentality,'' north african jews brought their unconditional devotion to judaism and a demand for jewish culture
in the past 15 years, the number of synagogues in the paris region has increased from 30 to 70. in 1950, paris had just three kosher butchers; today they number more than 100
touati says it has become virtually impossible to keep track of the dozens of restaurants, grocery stores, professional caterers, supermarkets and fast-food outlets serving kosher fare. before the coming of the sephardim, there were virtually none
there was a time when you couldn't even find a bottle of kosher wine for the sabbath meal,'' touati said in an interview. ``now, the finest chateaux in burgundy, bordeaux and champagne produce kosher wines which we export all over the world.''
the ``pletzl'' in the marais, a ghetto-like haven for poor askenazic jews since the middle ages, has seen an influx of sephardim too, and the shops that once sold chopped liver and gefilte fish have been joined by fast-food joints serving falafel and kosher couscous
these places are filled with young people looking for their jewish identity and a sense of community,'' said eric ghebeli, fomer president of france's jewish student union. ``they are mini-cultural centers where people get together to enjoy a dish their mothers once made. but there is also a thirst for knowledge.''
enrollment in jewish schools is higher than ever, with 10 percent of school-age children, about 15,000 enrolled full-time in one of france's 33 jewish schools. an equal number attend sunday school
a century ago the watchword was assimilation. today, it is the preservation of jewishness among france's 55.5 million people. the lucien de hirch school, founded in the early 1900s to help new immigrants adapt to french life, has done an about face: today it teaches the principles of judaism to its 850 students, 75 percent of whom are north african sephardim
since the arrival of the sephardim, more than 6,000 study groups, with different goals and religious tendencies, have sprung up around the country, along with countless adult education courses teaching hebrew and yiddish
in a country where jews have long believed that flaunting their jewishness was asking for trouble, the lubavitch, ultra-orthodox hasidic jews originating in 18th century poland, have seen their memberships swell, thanks to new sephardic recruits
dressed in long black coats, wearing beards and earlocks, some have even learned yiddish to read in the original the works of rabbi menachem mendel schneerson, head of the sect who lives in the brownsville section of brooklyn, n.y. in december they plastered billboards around paris with posters telling jews to light hanukkah candles and installed a giant menorah at the place de la concorde
jews around france can tune in to any of 13 radio stations playing hebrew and yiddish songs and broadcasting cultural programs and news commentaries. the three paris stations claim a daily audience of 37,000
jewish publications also have more readers than ever. numerous weeklies are distributed free in jewish centers and shops. the monthly ``l'arche,'' geared to france's educated middle class, reaches 10,000 subscribers. it was joined in december by ``passages,'' a magazine offering what it calls a jewish point of view on the news
the jewish community as a whole has been deeply troubled by the recent events on the israeli-occupied west bank in the middle east
we deplore the violence, but our support of israel is unconditional,'' said roger pinto, president of siona, a zionist group made up of north african sephardim. ``unlike many askenazim, we support israel first, and then ask questions.''
in a recent statement, an umbrella organization of jewish institutions known as crif, reiterated its support of israel and condemned its arab neighbors for ``refusing a real and useful dialogue ... to solve the problems of the region.''
in an editorial in the monthly ``information juive,'' the consistoire's touati asked, ``under the circumstances, what army in the world would have behaved better than tsahal (the israeli army)?''
nonetheless, nearly a dozen jewish groups have publicly called for a peaceful and political solution to the violence
(the french government strives for even-handedness in relations with israel and the arab nations of the middle east, where historical ties translate today into what france considers ``special relationships'' with several of the arab nations. france supports the convening of an international conference with all parties represented to resolve the middle east conflict
many french intellectuals of jewish origin have begun identifying with judaism, some for the first time
benny levy, militant founder of the proletarian left and close friend and secretary of the author-philosopher jean-paul sartre in the years before his death, has abandoned politics completely and embraced a life of piety and study of the torah, judaism's holy scriptures
philosopher jacques derrida, the father of deconstruction, a textual analysis based on the theory that language refers to itself, has been discussing jewish and biblical themes in seminars at the elite ecole normale superieure and at yale university in new haven, conn., for several years
intellectuals bernard-henri levy, andre gluckmann and alain finkielkraut, once committed leftists and later the major force behind the new philosophy movement of the mid-1970s, are among france's most visible jews, publicly rediscovering their jewish roots, writing on jewish issues and supporting jewish causes
but for joseph sitruk, france's newly installed grand rabbi, they are hardly examples of what he calls in hebrew ``teshuva,'' or return
many of them are interested in judaism the same way they would be interested in buddhism or leninism,'' he said in an interview. ``they may be going through an identity crisis, and that's respectable, but they're not calling themselves into question and going all the way.''
rabbi michael williams, of the ``liberal'' copernic synagogue, said he understands the cyncism of the religious establishment
how can the so-called return be anything but superficial when its standard-bearers don't respect the very basic rules of judaism, and marry out?''
williams maintains that french jews are ``going through an intense crisis of love.'' he says he regularly meets with observant young people planning to marry gentiles
indeed, studies show that intermarriage is on the rise, at about 50 percent. among the sephardim, the figures are only slightly lower
the family structure among north african jews is still quite strong, and plays an important role in influencing decisions made by family members,'' touati said. ``the increase in intermarriage is one of the consequences of rapid assimilation and integration into french society.''
yet sitruk maintains the current upsurge in judaism is not superficial but profound, touching all classes and backrounds, rich and poor
it comes in the wake of the holocaust, the birth of the state of israel, the new positions of power held by jews worldwide and the profound and far-reaching need to identify with the jewish biblical message,'' sitruk said
reform jews too, have been swept up in the trend towards orthodoxy. five years ago, friday night services at copernic, france's largest reform community, were mostly in french. today, three-quarters of the service is in hebrew
there is definitely an unspoken demand for a return to jewish knowledge and values,'' williams said. ``but we must be careful that it doesn't come at the expense of a new ghetto-like mentality.''
from the conviction of the army officer alfred dreyfus nearly 100 years ago to the french police zealously rounding up jews during world war ii, france has a long and sordid history of anti-semitism
today, however, jewish leaders say it is on the wane
the bombing of the copernic synagogue in 1980 and a terrorist attack on a kosher-style delicatessen two years later were not the work of frenchmen, but of palestinian terrorists, who are still at large
according to the b'nai brith anti-defamation league office in paris, the number of anti-semitic acts of violence has dropped considerably in recent years. in 1986, it recorded two, though the desecration and vandalism of jewish tombstones remains frequent
recent polls indicate that jews are better accepted than ever before in france. in 1946, 37 percent of the population thought jews were like any other french citizens. in 1987, that figure rose to 94 percent
i certainly look jewish when i walk down the street,'' said joseph sitruk, france's grand rabbi. ``i've been in marseilles for the past 12 years and have heard only two remarks. that's two too many, of course, but not very much.''
nevertheless, french jews remain vigilant and many express concern over the growing popularity of jean-marie le pen, leader of the extreme right-wing national front that rallies roughly 10 percent of french voters around an anti-immigrant ``france-for-frenchmen'' platform
le pen prides himself on ``saying out loud what everybody thinks to himself.'' he caused a storm of controversy last year by referring to the nazi gas chambers as ``a detail,'' adding their existence was still being ``debated by historians.''
for decades french jews didn't like themselves much either
anatole france summed up a whole mentality when he said that if alfred dreyfus had been on his jury, he would have convicted himself,'' said rabbi michael williams of the copernic synagogue
robert goldman, spokesman for the b'nai brith anti-defamation league, says the age-old cliches of the jew as the dangerous, money-hungry foreigner with the long noses are dead, but they have been replaced by anti-zionism
he called french press coverage of violence in the israeli-occupied west bank biased and said israel has taken an ``excessive drubbing.''
being harsher in judging israel than other western countries is a new form of discrimination,'' goldman said. ``it deeply affects jews in the diaspora, given the role israel plays in the minds of jews after the holocaust.''
wheel a baby down any street in italy and you'll never walk alone
fussing over children seems like a national pasttime, but if present trends continue italians will have fewer and fewer toddlers to dote on
to the concern of politicians and sociologists, the italian family is steadily shrinking. the latest statistics say each family has an average of 1.27 children, the lowest in europe
children are still king in italy. but, these days, one king is enough, not two or three,'' said renato tagliani, a father who has just one little emperor in his household, 11-year-old, chubby-cheeked gianbattista
family is practically a sacred institution in italy. it's certainly the most enduring one in a country that has seen invaders conquer and crumple and governments rise and fall
the value of family as an institution hasn't changed,'' said lorella spinelli, a 30-year-old roman, who had her first child in the fall. ``but to create a world for children these days is very difficult.''
fingers point to the slow but steady changing of women's roles, the difficulty of finding jobs and housing and the irritations of daily life that are particularly italian and particularly frustrating if you want to have children
to have more children signifies being penalized, suffering the lack of services, inadequate salaries,'' said demographer antonio golini, who directs a national center for population research
what's especially intriguing is that surveys show the practice of birth control is low in italy compared to other western european countries
less than 12 percent of women use the pill, more than 60 percent don't use any contraceptive,'' said panorama, an italian news weekly, in a recent issue
are italians not making love any more? have they all become sterile?''
studies are under way here to see if italians are indeed becoming infertile
for laura spinelli, just starting out as a parent, and renato tagliani, with more than a decade of experience, the reluctance of so many italians to be parents once, let alone more than once, seems understandable
having children once was the goal of an italian woman's life. you married, had kids, stayed at home,'' said mrs. spinelli
now the role of women is more like men's. you go to university and finish when you're 25 or 26. then it's usually a year or so before you find a job. once you find one, you're reluctant to leave it to have a child.''
her husband's success in business allowed her to give up her job after childbirth, but he's on the road a lot
i'm lucky to have my mother at home,'' mrs. spinelli said
her 67-year-old mother helps with the care of grandson luca
i have a friend whose mother lives on the opposite end of the city,'' mrs. spinelli said. ``she leaves her 7-month-old baby with her mother all week because with all the traffic it would take her too long to get there and back.''
such daily trials mean ``nonna'' (grandmother) is rapidly replacing ``mama'' as the anchor of the italian household
nonna is in special demand because babysitters are hard to find and can be expensive
many italians won't let their teen-agers work because they are obsessed with ``brutta figura'' _ making a bad impression _ and neighbors might gossip that your children have to work because you don't earn enough
with no grandma handy, the taglianis, a two-career couple with their own business, a media agency, feel the shortage of babysitters daily
italian schools close at 1:30 p.m. so where do you put your child when he gets out?'' said clemenzia tagliani
in italy, stores are closed at lunchtime, in the evening and on sundays and public schools are open saturday mornings
so if you have to buy a pair of shoes for your son you drag him out of school on saturday, when you're off, and make a mad dash to the store before they pull down their shutters at 1 p.m.,'' mrs. tagliani said
miriam mafai, a journalist who has written extensively on italian women, finds it curious that an overwhelmingly roman catholic country, where the pill was illegal until the early 1970s and where christian democrats are the dominant party, doesn't have a policy to make it easier to raise a family
some political debate has begun about what to do, but so far no legislation has been adopted
among suggestions are financial incentives, but none so ambitious as the family program in neighboring france. gen. charles de gaulle, after becoming president in 1959, used monthly allowances to encourage the french to have more children. the result is that a french couple with two children today collects more than 1,200 francs (about $200) a month from the government
ms. mafai said such ideas invoke the ``stigma'' of benito mussolini, italy's fascist dictator who tried to swell the population for his glory, his army and his dreamed-of imperial colonies
war is to man what motherhood is to woman,'' mussolini once said. he introduced family allowances in the 1930s and made bachelors pay a heavy tax. but the birth rate actually fell for several years under his rule
golini, the demographer, predicts italy's child population will swell in the next few years, but that will be only a consequence of the 1960s economics boom babies reaching child-bearing age
in the first six months of '86, the average number of children per family was 1.33; at the end of the year, we went down to 1.32. in '87, in the same period, the average was 1.29; in december, 1.27. you see, we're always going down.''
but remove the cause and italy will grow again,'' golini said
it's the kind of place englishmen left to join mad dogs in the noonday sun or perhaps strike out on the road to mandalay. the more sensible sat around sipping singapore slings
it's raffles hotel, which has survived for 102 years _ ceiling fans still whirring, grillwork elevator clanking up and down, dark paneling and long corridors with creaking floors, wide verandas and elderly waiters shuffling around the palm court garden
dear as it was to the hearts of many, raffles in recent times has become a bit seedy, and the talk was that it would come down because the land on which it sits is extremely valuable. one plan to renovate it was scrapped in 1983 because tourism had slumped and thousands of rooms in singapore's more modern hotels stood empty
but another chance has come for the legendary raffles, with the announcement by its owners that it will be restored to some semblance of its old self in a two-year, $27.3-million face lift
a tourist industry study two years ago had suggested that the ``national asset'' might make it if turned into a suites-only establishment for state guests and vips
the 127-room hotel will remain open during the renovation, which will be done in phases, according to the bankers that now own it
the central block will remain but the old ballroom and courtyard wing are to be demolished to make way for a basement parking garage, function rooms and a bedroom wing
raffles is in many respects the antithesis of a standard modern hotel, with its french renaissance architecture and palm trees all around
the atmosphere is still tropically relaxed, but with a residual whiff of stiff-upper-lip british colonial
raffles dates to the early 1800s, when it was founded as a ``tiffin house,'' or lunchroom in a private home. the actual hotel in beach road was started in 1886 by three armenian brothers and named for the founder of singapore, sir stamford raffles
by the turn of the century it was the social center in a key outpost of the british empire. rubber planters, merchants, military officers, ships' captains, remittance men and other colonials stayed there. the years have left legends
one says that c.m. phillips, the principal of a nearby school, was summoned in 1902 to shoot a tiger that had taken refuge under the billiard table at the hotel. a stuffed tiger on the premises keep that legend alive today. then, there's the hotel's tiger tavern, which serves the locally brewed tiger beer
bartender ngian tong doon is credited with mixing the first singapore sling 73 years ago. the hotel sells more than 1,000 glasses of the gin-based cocktail each day
lounge lizards who kept their elbows on the bar gave cad's alley its name. it was later changed to gin's alley to honor bartender ngian and his concoction
another legend has it that joseph conrad got the idea for ``lord jim'' while on the veranda reading a newspaper story about a british crew that abandoned ship and left 200 passengers to die
feed at raffles when visiting singapore,'' was rudyard kipling`s advice. but he found the beds less than comfortable and suggested sleeping elsewhere
those were the days of awesome appetites and massive meals. one dinner menu surviving from 1900 lists 18 courses
a typical breakfast of that period: porridge, fish, mutton chops, deviled fowl, cold beef, salad, boiled eggs, cheese, toast, tea or coffee and benedictine
when japanese bombers attacked at the start of world war ii, raffles' band played on in the ballroom behind blackout curtains. singapore surrendered to the japanese on feb. 15, 1942, and with occupation imminent the staff buried the hotel's silver in the palm court garden
hotel records show high-ranking officers of japan's occupation army lived there. when the war ended in 1945, former inmates of changi prison and other japanese internment camps were taken in by the hotel. the silver was dug up and raffles reopened for business again in 1946
somerset maugham, the late british novelist and short-story writer, once had said raffles ``stands for all the fables of the exotic east.''
the hotel uses that as its motto today and has a plaque outside one of its rooms in maugham's his honor
here's a switch: the two-hour movie pilot for nbc's ``aaron's way'' is set in pennsylvania and california, but it was filmed in australia
we had to have a grape harvest when we filmed it last march,'' said merlin olsen, who stars in the new series as aaron miller
we were able to duplicate parts of california and pennsylvania in southeastern australia. we shot the entire pilot there. we did all the episodes at the lorimar studios and in the santa ynez valley near solvang. we have our own grape vineyard and home there.''
olsen stars in ``aaron's way'' as an amish farmer who is suddenly forced to leave his sect and confront the modern world. miller leaves his peaceful pennsylvania amish village to run a california vineyard, yet tries as much as possible to cling to his religion and his traditions
the series also stars belinda montgomery (early ``miami vice''), jessica walter (``play misty for me'') and kathleen york. the series is from william blinn and jerry thorpe, producers of nbc's ``our house.'' blinn, who wrote ``brian's song'' and co-wrote ``roots,'' wrote the pilot with reno down
the series is in the tradition of ``little house on the prairie,'' ``the waltons'' and ``our house,'' although olsen said it's probably slanted more toward adults
the pilot premiered last week. the hour-long series begins a spring tryout on wednesday
it's the fourth series for the 6-foot-5 olsen, selected to the pro football hall of fame after being an all-pro defensive tackle for the los angeles rams. for several years he has been an nbc football analyst, and is probably best known as the spokesman for the ftd florists group
immediately after retiring from pro football, olsen became jonathan garvey on ``little house on the prairie'' in 1977 and stayed for four years. he then starred for a year in ``father murphy,'' a spinoff series. another series, ``fathers and sons,'' ran briefly in 1986
in the pilot, miller goes to california after his son noah, who has left the amish ways, is drowned in a surfing accident. there he learns that noah had a common-law wife who is pregnant and owns a vineyard that needs to be harvested
aaron feels that he must help her and the whole family shows up on her doorstep one day,'' he said. ``i say that we just happen to be in the neighborhood. although he's amish, aaron is a man who's looked over the fence and accepted some things that are not amish if they suit the needs and lifestyle of his family.''
olsen said he knows that the amish want to be left alone and were unhappy about how they were portrayed in the movie ``witness.''
we did some research because it's our desire and our responsibility to present the amish as honest and as respectfully as we can,'' he said. ``but the amish, like any other faith, have members with different levels of adherence. aaron miller was in danger of being `shunned' because he kept in contact with his son.''
olsen said the show would deal with many contemporary and adult problems. many of the problems will arise from miller trying to hold onto his traditions, yet having to make concessions to survive. ``it will ask very serious questions about the values and morals of an old world family suddenly brought face to face with the modern world,'' he said
he concedes that his role as aaron miller is not that different from jonathan garvey on ``little house'' or john murphy on ``father murphy.''
it's deliberate in a way,'' he said. ``there are some things i'm not eager to do. on the other hand, these are roles that came looking for me. partly because of my size. it reminds me of what happened when i first went out for football. the coach asked me what position i wanted to play. i said quarterback. the coach took one look at me and told me to play tackle
i don't think i'm being stereotyped. each role is different, but there is a thread of similarity. i want to do roles that i can sit down and watch with my children. i want to be able to point to the screen and say, `that's your father.' i'm afraid there's a lot of things on tv i wouldn't want to watch.''
olsen said he filmed 13 episodes of ``aaron's way'' while continuing his full schedule of sportscasting for nbc's pro football coverage. ``that was a tough fall,'' he said. ``i don't want to do that again. if the show is picked up i'm going to have some conversations with nbc sports about cutting back,'' he said. ``i love doing this show. i look forward to getting up in the morning and going to work. i love working with belinda montgomery and jessica walter.''
western banks and brazil have reached agreement on important elements of a loan restructuring package for the third world's most indebted country, providing it with more money at lower interest rates
banking sources familiar with the agreement say the negotiations reflected a surprising level of cooperation from brazil, which last year toughened its position over loan repayment terms and aroused considerable concern in the banking industry
fernando milliet, president of brazil's central bank, and william r. rhodes, chairman of the bank advisory committee for brazil, said sunday that under the agreement reached in new york, brazil will get more than $6 billion in new financing to help make debt payments through the first half of 1989
the u.s. economy has shrugged off the worst effects of the october stock market collapse and should be able to escape a recession this election year, economists for top u.s. corporations predicted today
the national association of business economists said optimism among its members has risen appreciably since the last survey conducted in the month following the oct. 19 plunge in stock prices
consumer prices rose a moderate 0.3 percent in january, but a decline in energy costs cloaked increases in many other areas, the government said
the january increase reported friday in the labor department's consumer price index followed a revised december increase of 0.2 percent. the december rise initially been reported as 0.1 percent
the advance equaled an annual inflation rate of 4.2 percent. that compares with the 4.4 percent rate of inflation in 1987 and with the reagan administration's projection of 4.3 percent inflation for 1988
sales of existing single-family homes suffered their third consecutive monthly decline in january, a 3.6 percent drop which pushed activity to its slowest level in 2{ years, according to a real estate trade group
the national association of realtors said friday that sales dropped to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 3.21 million units last month, following declines of 1.2 percent in december and 2.9 percent in november
the association said consumer fears raised by the collapse of the stock market in october partly caused the slowdown
americans' incomes rose 0.3 percent in january, matching the gain in consumer spending during the month, the government has reported
the commerce department said friday the 0.3 percent rises in incomes and spending followed identical 0.7 percent advances in both categories during december
the gains were taken as positive signs that consumer spending will grow enough this year to prevent a recession
the value of newly started construction fell 8 percent in january from the previous month, led by a steep drop in non-residential buildings, according to a report by a construction research concern
the f.w. dodge division of mcgraw-hill information systems co. said sunday the latest decline continued a downward drift from highs reached last august
the report said the annualized value of new construction contracts fell to $228 billion in january from $247.3 billion in december 1987
former stockbroker peter brant has been sentenced to 120 weekends in jail and fined $10,000 for his role in the insider-trading scandal involving a former wall street journal reporter
u.s. district judge charles e. stewart on friday also put brant on probation for five years and ordered him to do 750 hours of community service. brant, 35, a former broker at kidder peabody &amp; co., pleaded guilty july 12, 1984 to conspiracy and securities fraud. he admitted his part in a scheme to trade stock based on information to appear in the journal's influential ``heard on the street'' column
u.s. companies surveyed by the government reported a loss of $23.8 billion in 1986 because of foreign piracy of u.s. patents, trademarks and copyrights, according to a u.s. international trade commission study
the itc said friday that actual losses are much greater because not all companies filled out questionnaires on the subject
the commission said it received responses from 431 companies. the questionnaire was sent to 736 u.s. companies, including all those on the fortune 500 list
champion spark plug co. plans to lay off nearly 20 percent of its 1,700 production workers nationwide because of overcapacity in the auto parts industry
the bulk of the cuts announced friday, which will begin march 22 and will be phased in over the next four months, are being made at the plant here
the layoffs come just one month after workers at four u.s. champion plants approved a new four-year contract that includes a provision that the company try to increase production at two of its domestic plants
metromedia co. has agreed to acquire the ponderosa inc. restaurant chain for an undisclosed amount
metromedia, a privately-held telecommunications and technology holding company, said friday it planned to keep ponderosa management in place and anticipated no changes in the company's operation
ponderosa, which was taken private in a $331 million buyout led by new york investor asher b. edelman in january 1987, is one of the nation's largest steakhouse chains, with annual sales of $500 million
three companies accused of selling thousands of pounds of non-kosher poultry as kosher to customers in up to 22 states have agreed in a legal settlement to get out of the kosher business
we wanted to make sure something like this never happened again,'' said rabbi victor segal, president of goldman-segal kosher caterers of chicago, which had accused the three companies of fraud in a federal lawsuit
segal said friday it was the largest case of fraud involving mislabeling of kosher foods, and potentially affected jewish families in 22 states where the companies' kosher poultry products were sold
the stock market closed a choppy week with a small gain in quiet trading friday. the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.64 points to 2,023.21, finishing the week with a net gain of 8.62 points
bond prices rose in thin trading
the dollar slipped against most major currencies in quiet trading. gold prices declined
cocoa futures prices dropped sharply, energy futures mostly were lower, soybeans rose while grains were mixed, and cattle and pork futures were mixed
western banks and brazil have reached agreement on important elements of a loan restructuring package for the third world's most indebted country, providing it with more money at lower interest rates
banking sources familiar with the agreement, who spoke on the condition they not be identified by name, said the negotiations reflected a surprising level of cooperation from brazil, which last year toughened its position over loan repayment terms and aroused considerable concern in the banking industry
fernando milliet, president of brazil's central bank, and william r. rhodes, chairman of the bank advisory committee for brazil, said sunday that under the agreement reached in new york, brazil will get more than $6 billion in new financing to help make debt payments through the first half of 1989
both sides also agreed that the interest rate for repaying that money will be 13-16ths of 1 percent over the london interbank offered rate, a commonly used benchmark for determining foreign debt payments. brazil has been paying 1[ percent above the so-called libor rate because of its high-risk status
under the agreement, brazil also will make a payment next week of about $700 million from its reserves to cover unpaid interest on foreign bank loans for january and february, milliet and rhodes said in a press statement
the amount of (delinquent) interest they're paying is considerably more than the market had expected,'' said one source knowledgable about the negotiations. ``the market had expected they would wrap up the month of january, but they're adding the month of february. they're starting to make interest payments more often and in larger amounts than we'd foreseen.''
concerned about its deteriorating economy and reliance on outside money, brazil hasn't repaid any principal on its $114 billion foreign debt since 1983. in february 1987 it decreed a moratorium on interest payments but late last year agreed to resume them
with the agreement announced sunday, the country's interest payments will be current for all 1988 and the last quarter of 1987. brazil still owes back-interest from feb. 20, 1987, when it first declared the moratorium, up to sept. 30, 1987
plans for repaying the remaining delinquent interest are still under negotiation as part of a broad plan to restructure a foreign bank financing package for brazil
the banking sources said the package should be ready by the time a meeting of foreign bank creditors and latin debtor nations convenes march 20 in caracas, venezuela
this accord marks the end of a period of great uncertainty,'' brazil's finance minister mailson de nobrega told a news conference in brasilia. ``we should have all the details smoothed out by the end of march.''
the agreement also is expected to help brazil in negotiations with the international monetary fund that were scheduled to begin monday in washington. brazil was expected to ask the imf for $1.7 billion in standby loans
rhodes said in the statement that the negotiations and the $700 million interest payment represent ``significant progress in restoring brazil's traditionally good relations with its commercial bank creditors.''
about 25 perent of brazil's foreign bank debt is held by u.s. lenders. concern about the country's ability or willingness to repay has caused many u.s. banks to reclassify some loans as possibly uncollectable and raised concern about the health of banks with large brazilian loan portfolios
negotiations over restructuring brazil's loan repayments began in october between brazilian finance officials and the 14-member bank advisory committee, which represents 700 creditor banks
one of alpine county's main industries is a silver mine, but neither silver ore nor a gold mine of ski business are enough to keep the county's only bank from checking out
bank of america will close its markleeville branch tonight, 30 years after the county tax collector cajoled the banking giant to set up shop in california's least populated county
the bank says the closure is a cost-cutting move forced by keen competition following deregulation of the banking industry. it promises to continue serving alpine county customers at its south lake tahoe branch, about 35 miles away
the move angers many customers, who lament bygone days when resident bank managers would open the bank and approve loans after hours, attend neighborhood potlucks and host an annual holiday buffet in this sierra nevada community
they claim the bank would have done well in the county had it made efforts to secure accounts such as the kirkwood ski resort and the washoe indian tribe. now, alpine is the only one of california's 58 counties without a bank
it's not the community failing the bank,'' said don jardine, one of five members of the alpine county board of supervisors. ``it's the bank failing to aggressively go out and just provide basic services.''
corporate spokesman richard beebe said ``it's not our intention to abandon anyone.''
beebe said alpine county clients won't see any interruption in their accounts and will be able to do much of their banking, including loan applications, by telephone
although some customers are grumbling they'll bank in nevada, 20 minutes away by car, the county doesn't have that option
state law requires that local governments bank in california. alpine county, which has cash assets of $3 million and an annual budget of $5 million, is considering hiring an armed transport service for $70 a trip to deposit its money at south lake tahoe
dee rudden, who moved here two years ago from san jose with her husband, bob, and bought the markleeville general store, said the bank's closing ``is really going to be a problem for everyone
i guess what we're going to do is buy a safe,'' rudden said. ``we're going to have to do something.''
in markleeville, the economy seems as slow as the pace of life. welcome signs on the edge of town boast a population of 165 in a county of 1,200 people. work is seasonal at the silver mine, four miles south of town
doranna tognotti, deputy treasurer-tax collector, said the estimated $755,00 it would cost to start a new bank in alpine county may be prohibitive
you can't help but wonder if we're going to end up being a ghost town,'' she said
the mexican government said it would raise by 3 percent the minimum daily wage in march and freeze officially regulated prices under its inflation-fighting program
it also said the value of the peso currency against the dollar would be maintained in march at the level reached today. the government had been paring the currency's value by 3 pesos per trading day
the national motto is no increase in prices in the month of march,'' president miguel de la madrid said sunday, in announcing that the government was stepping up the pace of its anti-inflation program
he said the decision was made after fresh inflation figures showed ``an important de-acceleration'' in february
the inflation tally for february, he said, will be about half the record 15.5 percent posted in january. consumer prices rose 8.7 percent in the first half of this month, the government reported last wednesday
in outlining inflation-fighting steps for march, the presidential office said the prices of government-produced and -controlled goods and services, such as gasoline, telephones and electricity, will be frozen
private companies, it said, will be urged to absorb the increase in the minimum wage and not pass it along to consumers in the form of higher prices
moreover, it said, the government will push ahead with plans to reduce the government's red-ink spending
the government had been expected to announce over the weekend a target for boosting wages and prices in march, under an indexation plan scheduled to go into effect on tuesday
under that plan, wages and prices of government-regulated goods and services were to be increased by a set amount, based on projected inflation
but officials decided instead to raise only the minimum wage, which will move from 7,765 pesos a day to just under 8,000 pesos, or about $3.50 at the current exchange rate. the higher pay will go into effect tuesday
the small increase dealt a setback to labor. labor officials had called for a gain of at least 10 percent to help workers keep pace with the sharp rise in prices in recent months
but during a meeting at the presidential office, labor chief fidel velazquez said he believed the fresh steps would help ``attack inflation.'' he said workers had, once again, ``placed the interests of the country ahead of their own interests.''
the inflation rate in all of last year was a record 159.2 percent, up sharply from the 105.7 percent of 1986
de la madrid unveiled the anti-inflation program, called the economic solidarity pact, in mid-december in an effort to prevent the nation from spinning into hyper-inflation. officials have predicted that the plan will reduce the monthly inflation rate to just 1 percent to 2 percent by year's end
as part of the solidarity pact, the government authorized sharp increases in the prices of a variety of officially controlled goods and services, which kicked up costs throughout the economy
the exchange rate on friday was 2,270 pesos to the dollar in the controlled market, which is regulated by the government and used in about 75 percent of commercial transactions
the rate in free-market trading, used in tourism and transactions along the u.s.-mexico border, was 2,327 pesos to the dollar
in february, the bank of mexico, the central bank, sliced the currency's value by an average of 3 pesos per working day. the rate had held fairly steady from mid-december to february
japanese automakers exported 9.1 percent fewer cars, trucks and buses in january, largely because the yen's rise against the dollar shrank shipments to the united states, an industry association announced monday
exports to the united states dropped 19.4 percent from a year earlier to 199,904 units, according to the japan automobile manufacturers association
japanese companies exported a total 524,785 units in january
an association spokesman, who requested anonymity, said there was no single reason for the drop in shipments to the u.s. market. he added that the higher value of the yen, which makes cars exported from japan more costly to american buyers, was an important factor
the united states is the largest market for japanese car exports
exports to the united states in the first 10 months of fiscal 1987, which ends in march, were down 5.4 percent compared with a year earlier, to 1.978 million units
total exports to the u.s. market for fiscal 1987 will probably not exceed the 2.3 million unit quota set in japan's voluntary export restrictions, the spokesman said
the stock market staged a broad advance today, making another run toward new highs for the year
the dow jones average of 30 industrials climbed 11.27 to 2,034.48 in the first half hour of trading
gainers outnumbered losers by about 2 to 1 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 699 up, 340 down and 490 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 61.56 million shares as of 10 a.m. on wall street. but more than half of that activity came in a few high-yielding stocks, representing plays on their impending dividends
analysts said optimistic traders still had their sights set on the 2,051.89 level in the dow jones industrial average, where it closed jan. 7 for its highest closing reading since the crash last october
the average failed in a bid to surpass that point last week, but brokers argued that it might be ready to make another try
one concern facing the market is the report due tuesday from the commerce department on the index of leading economic indicators for january
analysts generally expect the figure to show a decline. but the firm of smith barney, harris upham &amp; co. said the 0.2 percent drop originally reported for december might be revised to show a gain
that would mean that the index would no longer have a string of three consecutive monthly declines, a phenomenon which is traditionally regarded as a potential recession warning
gainers among the blue chips included general electric, up { at 44[; eastman kodak, up ] at 42~; international business machines, up ] at 116[, and american telephone &amp; telegraph, up \ at 29\
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose .89 to 148.59. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up .43 at 284.75
on friday the dow jones industrial average rose 5.64 to 2,023.21, finishing the week with a net gain of 8.62 points
advancing issues outpaced declines by about 5 to 4 on the nyse, with 804 up, 655 down and 483 unchanged. big board volume totaled 158.06 million shares, down from 213.89 million in the previous session
continental airlines is seeking to open a hub in west berlin to serve destinations in west germany and others parts of europe
an application has been filed with air attaches in west berlin for permission to serve several west german cities, including frankfurt, stuttgart, cologne and dusseldorf, and flights to london and paris, said c.w. ``pete'' runnette, vice president of continental's international division
the proposal was filed 10 days ago and is expected to be acted on in several months, the houston chronicle reported today
we feel there is a lot of opportunity in west berlin right now,'' runnette said. ``continental is considering expansion in europe, and west berlin seems like a suitable entree. we will bring low-cost, high-quality service to the european market.''
under the proposal, continental would use airbus 300s and 737-300s in west berlin, with four flights a day to munich, seven to frankfurt, and five to dusseldorf, stuttgart and cologne
two flights a day to london's gatwick would also be scheduled, in addition to service from west berlin to paris
the west berlin-london route would connect with the carrier's non-stop london service from houston, miami, denver and newark, n.j., as well as its newark to paris flight
under an agreement signed at the close of world war ii, only american, french and british airlines can land in west berlin, which is the non-communist part of the divided city in east germany
the air attaches for the united states, britain and france control the west half of the divided city and regulate air routes and fares, and those three will make a decision on who obtains west berlin service, runnette said
pan american, the major american carrier in and out of west berlin, is developing a hub at west berlin's tegel airport. trans world airlines and american airlines have sought permission for flights in west berlin, and delta air lines and northwest airlines are also reported to be interested in gaining rights to fly from west berlin, the chronicle reported
the supreme court today asked the reagan administration for its opinion of a ruling that states indirectly may tax interest paid to financial institutions from investments in federal home loan bank (fhlb) bonds
the court said it wants to hear from justice department lawyers before saying whether it will review fully a challenge to a maryland bank franchise tax
the maryland national bank challenged the tax, seeking a refund of $197,310 it paid under protest to the state for the years 1979 through 1982
during that period, the bank reported $2.82 million in interest from fhlb bonds
the sum was included in the bank's net earnings that were subject to maryland's franchise tax, which is imposed on financial institutions for the privilege of doing business in maryland
the difficulty over whether earnings from fhlb bonds are taxable arises because of two apparently conflicting federal laws
the 1932 law that created the fhlb generally exempts the bonds from taxes
but a law enacted in 1862 permits states to levy a ``non-discriminatory franchise tax'' on ``stocks and obligations of the united states government'' that generally are exempt from state and local taxes
the maryland court of appeals upheld the state franchise tax, ruling in october that the 1862 law takes precedence
the state court based its ruling in part on a 1975 opinion by the general counsel's office of the federal home loan bank board
the state court said a franchise tax paid for the privilege of doing business in the state is not the same as a direct tax on a bank's income
the state court also said the tax does not violate the constitution's supremacy clause, which binds states to adhere to federal law
the case is maryland national bank vs. state department of assessments, 87-1080.   
fidelity investments, the nation's largest mutual fund firm, today announced plans to lay off about 800 workers, with more than 70 percent of the cuts in its boston area offices
the company attributed the 10.5 percent workforce reduction to a slump in new stock transactions and slower money management business since the oct. 19 stock market crash
the layoffs, to take effect immediately, include 530 workers in greater boston, about 150 in dallas and about 50 in new york, said fidelity spokeswoman karen ernst
the remainder of the cuts will come from other offices around the country, she said
the action reduces fidelity's nationwide staff to approximately 6,850, about the same number of workers employed by the firm in mid-1987. since the early 1980s, fidelity experienced significant growth as the economy improved
most of the layoffs were from corporate staff department and ``volume-sensitive'' areas, such as telephone representatives and order takers, said the corporate announcement. no investment personnel were effected
fidelity, which operates 54 offices in the united states, presently manages about $80 billion in assets, down from a peak of about $85 billion in mid-1987
the company dismissed about 300 part-time and 50 fill-time workers feb. 11, including 50 in boston and 125 each in dallas and salt lake city
earlier this year, fidelity laid off 32 workers at investment centers nationwide
among fidelity's other services include discount stock brokerage and institutional pension management
eric kobern, a former fidelity employee who publishes an independent newsletter that monitors the company, predicts future layoffs if business does not accelerate
this is a first step,'' said kobern. ``i would not be surprised if we see further cuts after the ira season if business stays at the same pace. this may be the first round of cuts, and they will digest it and see how they are doing then proceed with others.''
stop &amp; shop cos. inc. announced today it would go private in a $1.23 billion leveraged buyout by kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co. the deal could thwart dart group inc.'s attempt to take over the supermarket and department store chain
the buyout agreement, signed after several days of negotiations between stop &amp; shop directors and several interested firms, calls for a kohlberg kravis subsidiary, ssc holdings corp., to purchase all 28 million outstanding stop &amp; shop shares at $44 each, stop &amp; shop said in a statement
kohlberg kravis is an investment company specializing in management-led acquisitions, including the $6.2 billion leveraged buyout of beatrice cos. in 1986. in a leveraged buyout, investors borrow heavily to buy out a company and then pay off the debt with the target company's cash flow or the sale of its assets
stop &amp; shop's board had rejected as inadequate dart's offer of $37 a share, or a total of $1.03 billion
officials of dart could not be reached for comment today, but a spokesman had said they would likely make a counter offer
other companies reportedly interested in stop &amp; shop were thomas h. lee co. of boston, and riordan, freeman &amp; spogli inc. of los angeles
stop &amp; shop has 113 supermarkets and 169 bradlees in 12 states in the northeast
the company's stock has gone up more than $25 a share since dart first announced its takeover intent in january. in early new york stock exchange trading today, it was up another 75 cents to $43.37{ a share
the sale, which must be approved by a majority of stop &amp; shop shareholders, is expected to commence on or before march 4, stop &amp; shop said. kohlberg kravis has received a financing commitment from manufacturers hanover trust co., the retailer said
stop &amp; shop said it will retain its present management and remain based in braintree
on friday, dart said it would launch a proxy fight and called for a special meeting of stop &amp; shop shareholders at which it would move to replace the directors
dart, based in landover, md., is known for a series of unsuccessful but profitable bids to gain control of other companies, and its chairman, herbert haft, and president, robert haft, have acquired reputations as corporate raiders
their most recent targets include supermarkets general corp. and dayton hudson corp
the stock market gained ground today in a session enlivened by heavy takeover activity
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.95 to 2,032.16 by 11 a.m. on wall street
