the supreme court agreed today to consider barring the u.s. customs service from conducting drug tests for people seeking drug-enforcement jobs, setting the stage for its first ruling on the constitutionality of mandatory drug-testing for public employees
the court said it will hear a challenge to the testing program by a federal workers labor union that says taking urine samples from employees violates their privacy rights
the outcome will carry no direct effect on such tests conducted by private, non-governmental employers
president reagan signed an executive order in 1986 calling for drug testing of government employees
the transportation department, with 30,000 employees, became the first cabinet-level department to adopt random testing for civilian workers. the program covers those in safety-related jobs such as air traffic controllers, federal aviation administration pilots and workers with high-rated security clearance
the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last year that the customs service tests, which are not administered randomly, are lawful
the appeals court said the tests may be considered searches but do not intrude unnecessarily on the privacy rights of workers
because of the strong governmental interest in employing individuals for key positions in drug enforcement who themselves are not drug users and the limited intrusiveness of this partricular program, it is reasonable and, therefore, is not unconstitutional,'' the appeals court said
the national treasury employees union challenged the testing program, which requires some workers to provide urine samples in restroom stalls as a person overseeing the test waits outside the stall. the tests are conducted by an independent company hired by the customs service
the union said the tests are a ``humiliation'' for workers, and are being administered indiscriminately to employees who otherwise are thought worthy of promotion and are not suspected of drug use
the tests are given to those in the customs service applying for promotion to drug-enforcement jobs, and for outside applicants for those jobs
the union president, robert m. tobias, praised the high court's decision to hear the case, saying its ruling ``should clarify the constiutional boundaries of drug testing for federal employees and, we hope, destroy reagan's plans for wholesale testing of the federal work force.''
in other action today, the court:
_ refused to revive lawsuits charging the government and federal contrctors with negligently causing deaths and disease among people exposed to open-air atomic tests
the court, without comment, let stand a federal law that effectively spared the government from having to defend itself against claims seeking billions of dollars
_ agreed to consider letting the federal government apply retroactively a formula that limits reimbursement paid to hospitals treating medicare patients
the court said it will hear reagan administration arguments that some hospitals could reap a windfall from the ban on retroactive application of the formula
_ let stand rulings that threw out a reporter's attempt to force the state department to release documents from u.s. embassies around the world
the lawsuit by donald f. goldberg, a reporter on the staff of syndicated columnist jack anderson, had been filed under the freedom of information act. he had sought from the state department responses to an unclassified 1982 questionnaire on foreign governments' diplomatic practices
_ asked the reagan administration whether it thinks high-stakes bingo games run by indian tribes are subject to state sales taxes
the court said it wants to hear from justice department lawyers before it says whether it will review an attempt by oklahoma officials to tax revenue from a bingo game in tulsa run by the muscogee creek nation
the reagan administration said the drug tests are needed to prevent drug enforcement agents who used drugs from being bribed or blackmailed
justice department lawyers said, ``any affront to privacy felt by those applying for the affected positions is outweighed by the service's interest in ensuring that officials responsible for the interdiction of drug smuggling are not themselves drug users.''
customs employees are not ``immune from a problem that is ravaging the society at large,'' the government lawyers said in urging the court to reject the union's appeal
they said the tests are particularly important now because the customs services plans to recruit some 3,000 new employees, including many in the 18-to-25 age range in which use of illegal drugs is most prevalent
the tests were halted in 1986 after a federal judge ruled they are unconstitutional and ordered them stopped
the 5th circuit court then overruled the judge, and the supreme court last may permitted the tests to resume
drug testing policies also have come under legal attacks led by the american civil liberties union
the case is national treasury employees union vs. von raab, 86-1879
the number of local businesses bankruptcies reached an all-time high in 1987, and increased for the fifth consecutive year, according to an accounting firm's report
there were a record 1,688 bankruptcies in houston last year, a 4 percent increase from the previous year, a price waterhouse-houston study showed. the small percentage increase indicates a stabilization of the business climate, the company said
price waterhouse said the number of bankruptcies increased by 17 percent in 1986 and 33 percent in 1985
we expect bankruptcies in houston to decline in 1988,'' said carol bennett, senior manager and economist with price waterhouse. ``such a decline would be the first we have reported since we began these bankruptcy analyses in 1982.''
in its survey last year, the company predicted houston bankruptcies had peaked in 1986
retail businesses represented the largest industry segment in the bankruptcy figures with a 41.5 percent share, the study said
but the beleaguered oil and gas industry improved dramatically in its survival statistics, showing a 53 pecent decrease in business failures and bankruptcy filings last year compared with 1986. the 59 filings in the energy sector last year were the fewest since 1982
the possibility of a bidding war for federated department stores inc. arose today after the nation's fifth-largest retailer announced that another party in addition to campeau corp. was presenting an acquisition proposal to the federated board
federated did not identify the new bidder, but said it had been advised that the party planned to submit a proposal that appeared competitive with campeau's $6.1 billion, $68-per-share bid to buy federated
federated's board of directors, meeting today to consider campeau's proposal, was to consider the rival bid as well, the retailer said
the cincinnati-based federated, which owns chains including bloomingdale's, filene's and burdine's, declined to say where the board was meeting, or when it would announce a decision
representatives of federated and campeau negotiated over the weekend on a merger plan. however, the retailer said last week there was no guarantee its directors would agree to a merger with campeau, which owns store chains including jordan marsh, ann taylor and stern's
federated stock was up $1.50 to $66.25 a share in late morning trading on the new york stock exchange today
federated ended weeks of fending off campeau's takeover attempts by announcing friday that its board of directors authorized merger negotiations after the toronto-based development company offered $68 per share
the directors previously rejected lower campeau offers and ordered managers to study alternatives to a takeover
analysts speculated that federated decided to negotiate with campeau because it could not find a favored buyer to acquire the company or develop a restructuring plan that would pay shareholders what campeau was offering
most analysts said that if an agreement was reached, campeau probably would sell some federated divisions to help pay off the $4.5 billion in debt it would incur to make the acquisition
campeau took similar steps after acquiring allied stores corp. in december 1986 and sold off 16 of 24 store units
campeau has already indicated it would sell federated's non-department store operations, which include gold circle discount stores based in columbus and ralph's supermarkets in los angeles. it indicated it would combine headquarters operations of federated and allied stores
some analysts said the cincinnati-based lazarus department store chain is considered among federated's weaker performing units and could be sold
there have been rumors that a number of other retailers, such as may department stores, would step in and buy federated. william smith, a retail analyst with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co., said st. louis-based may would be interested in acquiring some of federated's stores, ``but they don't have to buy the whole company to do that.''
federated had $11 billion in sales last year. it operates 650 stores nationwide. its holdings also include abraham &amp; straus, rich's, bullock's and bullocks wilshire and i. magnin
campeau said last week it would raise a substantial amount of equity for its proposed buyout of federated by selling the brooks brothers division of allied stores to britain's marks and spencer plc for $770 million. the brooks brothers sale was conditioned on campeau acquiring federated
britain's merchandise trade deficit soared 33 percent to a record 1.5 billion pounds in january as exports fell more sharply than imports, the government said monday
the latest seasonally adjusted figure, equal to about $2.7 billion, compared with a deficit of 1.01 billion pounds in the previous month and 597 million pounds in january 1987, the department of trade and industry said
britain's current account deficit, which includes invisible trade such as services and overseas investment earnings, more than doubled to a record 905 million pounds, or $1.6 billion, in january from a deficit of 410 million pounds in december
the current account deficit was 28 million pounds in january 1987
the invisible trade in janaury was estimated to be in a surplus of 600 million pounds
exports fell 9 percent to 6.2 billion pounds, or $11 billion, in january from 6.8 billion pounds, or $12 billion, in december
imports fell 1.3 percent to 7.7 billion pounds, or $13.6 billion, from 7.8 billion pounds, or $13.8 billion, in december
