in early trading, live cattle were unchanged to .50 cent a pound with the contract for delivery in april at 72.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent higher to .52 cent lower with march at 80.30 cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged to .60 cent lower with april at 43.85 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .07 cent lower to .25 cent higher with match at 52.20 cents a pound
on friday, futures prices for frozen pork bellies were lower while cattle and hogs were mixed
officials from leading cocoa producers and consuming countries began two weeks of talks monday on measures to support world prices against the background of a renewed slump in the market
cocoa bean prices have declined by more than seven per cent since the start of the year, with contracts for may delivery dropping the equivalent of $26.40 to touch a five-year year low of 995 pounds, or $1,751, per metric ton, dealers said
cocoa prices have been undermined by a world surplus following four seasons of overproduction, and the ending of intervention buying to support the market
intervention buying of cocoa by the 37-nation international cocoa organization was halted indefinitely last week because purchases had reached the maximum 250,000 tons permitted under the price-stabilization treaty
dealers said that the market's weakness also reflected doubts whether cocoa organization members can agree on supplementary measures to support the market at the talks that opened monday
the cocoa treaty allows the introduction of a stock withholding process to restrict supplies when intervention purchases have been halted
under the procedure, the organization's leading producers _ the ivory coast, brazil, ghana, nigeria and cameroon _ can hold back up to 120,000 tons of cocoa. the beans would be put into storage and only released when prices were rising strongly
industry sources said that although it was likely to come into force this week or next, there were doubts whether all producers would operate it
holding back cocoa will mean lost export revenue and that is something that some countries may not be able to afford,'' said one analyst
he noted that most of the producers are massively in debt and making huge interest repayments
the talks will be complicated by a call from cocoa organization consumers for a cut in the support price, said delegates to the meeting who spoke on condition of anonymity
norway's labor government proposed a wage freeze monday in an emergency measure to put a lid on inflation, which leaped to 8.7 percent last year
the government said the freeze, which also covered stock dividends, would be temporary until economic planners can prepare a more comprehensive program to regulate salaries
the second stage was due to be introduced in about two weeks and would keep salaries under control at least until 1989
norway's inflation rate has grown steadily over the past three years, from 5.7 percent in 1985 to 7.2 percent in 1986 and 8.7 percent last year. by comparison, the average rate in european in 1986 was 3.8 percent, according to the organization of european cooperation and development
under the proposed bill, prices would be controled but not frozen. an already existing monitoring agency would be instructed to ensure prices were not raised unreasonably
it was the most extreme anti-inflation measure since another socialist government froze prices and wages ten years ago
on saturday, prime minister gro harlem brundtland said she would introduce the wage legislation after the national employers' organization closed a deal with the country's federation of trade unions giving workers wage increases and benefits amounting to roughly five percent
the agreement affected 350,000 union members in the private sector, but the proposed wage freeze would extend the agreement to most of norway's work force
the bill raised a cry of protest from other unions that their own negotiations were cut off and superceded by a deal in which they had no say
exemptions were made for teachers and nurses, who have staged sporadic strikes over the past several weeks and who were holding separate pay negotiations
although mrs. brundtland's government lacks a majority in the 157-member parliament, the storting, the legislation was almost certain to win approval in a vote later this week with the likely support of the opposition conservative party
mrs. brundtland told a news conference the bill was designed to bring inflation down to the level of other european countries and make norway's industry more competative. general news wires</note>
two financial company executives were sentenced to prison today for their roles in bilking mortgage company investors of millions of dollars
oakland county circuit judge norman l. lippitt sentenced barton greenberg to the maximum six years, eight months to 10 years in prison, and sentenced gary l. mitchell to 16 months to three years in prison
scattered applause broke out as the two former executives of a.j. obie &amp; associates and diamond mortgage corp. were led away in handcuffs
lippitt gave the two 56 days to appeal
the pair were accused of defrauding 1,600 investors of about $47 million in what state attorney general frank kelley has termed michigan's largest mortgage scam
greenberg and mitchell were charged last year with 18 counts of securities fraud. greenberg also was charged with two counts of obtaining money under false pretenses
in a plea bargain arranged before trial, greenberg pleaded no contest to one count of obtaining money under false pretenses and mitchell no contest to a count of securities fraud. the other counts were dropped
kelley has said that greenberg, former board chairman of diamond and former obie president, used corporate accounts for personal purposes while drawing a $1 million annual salary
mitchell owned no stock in either company, had little control over bank accounts and drew a $100,000 annual salary, kelley wrote lippitt in a letter last week. kelley said while mitchell knew of two of the fraud schemes, he was not the primary instigator and did not benefit nearly as much as greenberg
diamond and obie were charged with arranging high-risk mortgage loans at above-market rates that obie then resold to investors
because they had more investors than borrowers, obie frequently gave individual mortgages to several investors. diamond also was accused of failing to account properly for escrow money to pay taxes and insurance
the chairman of prudential-bache securities inc. has agreed to a censure by the new york stock exchange for failing to oversee e.f. hutton &amp; co. properly when he was president of that firm during an illicit overdrafting scheme, sources familiar with the settlement said monday
the sources, who spoke on condition they not be identified, said the exchange determined george l. ball wasn't aware of the scheme, which was conducted in the early 1980s and played a role in hutton's later demise. but the exchange felt ball still bore some responsibility, the sources said
hutton's former chief financial officer thomas lynch also will be censured, and hutton must pay a $400,000 fine to the exchange, among the largest ever levied, the sources said. because hutton was acquired by shearson lehman brothers inc. late last year, shearson will pay the fine
norman epstein, a former hutton executive responsible for overseeing some of its operations, also faced discipline by the exchange but reportedly has been resisting a settlement
ball was away from his office and did not return telephone messages for comment, but a prudential-bache official said the chairman agreed to the settlement in order to put the matter behind him
this is the mildest form of action available to the exchange,'' said the official. ``there is no fine, no restrictions, it's a censure.''
the action by stock exchange investigators is regarded as largely inconsequential. it isn't expected to have any effect on ball's position at prudential bache
what they're saying is, `we realize and acknowledge you weren't aware of any of the improprieties,'' the prudential bache official said
stock exchange spokeswoman sharon gamsin declined comment in accordance with its policy on investigations that haven't been concluded
shearson officials did not return calls for comment, and the whereabouts of lynch and epstein weren't clear
shearson has said previously that in acquiring hutton, it scrutinized the firm's legal history and potential liabilities
the exchange's investigation stemmed from a 1985 check-overdrafting scheme that hutton orchestrated through its retail brokerage network. the firm earned up to $8 million in interest income at commercial banks by deliberately overdrawing checking accounts and putting the money to use elsewhere
hutton pleaded guilty to 2,000 federal fraud counts and paid a $2 million fine in may 1985 because of the scheme, which exposed serious management lapses at the firm and led to a chain of events that forced hutton to sell itself
ball departed hutton for prudential-bache in 1982, after a federal probe of the overdrafting scheme had begun
the stock exchange routinely disciplines member firms for violating its rules of conduct, with punitive actions ranging from expulsions for severe infractions to fines or censure for less serious offenses
previous large fines levied by the stock exchange included $400,000 against first wall street settlement in 1981 and $400,000 against bache halsey stuart shields in 1982
carlo de benedetti reached a partnership agreement with two belgian firms monday, bringing the italian investor closer to gaining control of societe generale de belgique sa, belgium's biggest holding company
de benedetti, belgian industrialist andre leysen of gevaert nv and pierre scohier of cobepa sa, a belgian investment firm, said they agreed to form a new holding company with 4.5 million, or about 16 percent, of societe generale shares
the group's aim is to control a stake of 20 to 25 percent of societe generale shares, scohier said
de benedetti, together with allies, already claims to control 45 percent of societe generale's 28.2 million shares but it was unclear monday whether the new partnership could give him a majority stake in the company at the expense of an alliance of mainly french and belgian companies that claims 52 percent of the shares
the alliance, built around the french investment cie financiere de suez and belgium's biggest insurer, groupe ag, wants to keep societe generale, which has a stake in a third of the belgian economy, anchored in belgium
de benedetti wants to use the 166-year-old firm as a platform for a pan-european holding company
but in the deal with the two belgian companies he seemed more willing to let societe generale maintain its belgian identity
de benedetti's french investment firm cerus sa will have a stake of 55 percent in the new holding company and gevaert and cobepa holdings of 22.5 percent each
scohier said copeba, the belgian subsidiary of the french investment group paribas, currently did not own shares of societe generale, but that it planned to buy about 1 million. he did not elaborate
paribas and suez are fierce competitors on the french investment market and are in opposing camps in the battle of societe generale
the three parties said in a statement the new holding company will ensure that societe generale will have a belgian base and invited other belgian as well as international investors to join the holding company
societe generale has interests in some 1,400 companies world-wide and in about half of belgium's top 50 firms. it has such pervasive influence in the national economy that it is sometimes identified with belgium itself
leysen told the west german magazine der spiegel the importance of societe generale was reflected in its stake in ``all vital economic sectors of belgium: the energy sector, gas, electricity, petroleum and (belgium's) largest bank.''
the announcement further said that de benedetti will be president of the new holding company with leysen and scohier vice-presidents
de benedetti's insistence on having personal control over at least day-to-day management of societe generale had been a stumbling block when he failed to forge a partnership with leysen last month
but the statement released monday said ``the decision-making center of the company will remain in belgium and the essential interests of belgium will be preserved,'' which had been a constant demand by leysen
de benedetti said prior to monday's agreement he controlled 45 percent while the alliance opposing him claims 52 percent
maurice lippens, managing director of belgium's groupe ag, said on belgian rtbf radio the shareholders meeting would not be called to assess the size of the two factions trying to take control of the company
lippens further said he and officials of the suez group, which holds the largest single known bloc of shares within the coalition, had met with belgium's caretaker prime minister wilfried martens over the weekend
no details of the meeting were available
the battle for control of societe generale started jan. 18 when de benedetti announced he was seeking effective control of the holding company in view of the completion of the european internal market of 1992
by that date, the common market hopes to free all movement of goods, services and people within the 12-nation european economic community
the value of midwestern farmland is up about 7 percent from depressed 1986 levels, but still is little more than half what it was seven years ago, the federal reserve bank of chicago says
the bank says its survey of about 500 agricultural bankers in five midwestern states shows farmland values rose 3.2 percent during the last three months of 1987 _ the fourth consecutive quarterly increase
the reversal last year of the long downtrend in farmland values stems largely from the improving income trend of the sector,'' said peter heffernan, an analyst for the chicago bank
net farm income in 1987 rose 20 percent from the previous year's level, said heffernan
while much of the improvement in farm-sector earnings is attributable to large government payments, strong livestock returns over the past few years and sharply curtailed production expenses have also contributed to the sector's improved income performance,'' said heffernan
the most substantial increases in farmland values during the fourth quarter of 1987 were the 5.8 percent reported in indiana and 4.9 percent in iowa, the survey showed
illinois bankers reported a 2.1 percent increase in farmland values during october, november and december, and wisconsin bankers reported a 1 percent increase
michigan bankers said there was virtually no change from third-quarter values
heffernan said the best annual increase in farmland values was 13 percent in iowa. the others were 8.2 percent in indiana, 7.2 percent in illinois and 2 percent in michigan, with no change reported by bankers in wisconsin
district bankers remain optimistic regarding the farmland market in 1988,'' said heffernan. ``the vast majority of surveyed bankers _ almost 70 percent _ expect farmland values in their areas to remain stable during the first quarter of this year.''
he said 28 percent of the bankers expect farmland values to continue to rise this quarter, while just 2 percent expect a decline
even with the latest increase in farmland values, the survey showed that they are 45 percent below their 1981 peak
more than 5,000 northern telecom ltd. production and office workers went on strike in five canadian cities monday after the union rejected a last-minute economic proposal from the company
we are quite a ways apart on some very basic issues,'' said bob white, president of the canadian auto workers union
white said the company wants to cut cost-of-living allowances by 35 percent and has failed to meet the union's proposal for indexed pensions. the union is also seeking higher wages and a sweetened benefit package. wages now are $15 to $18 an hour
the contract expired sunday at midnight and the strike began after a deadline of monday at 11 a.m. est
affected by the strike are a repair facility in saint john, new brunswick, and manufacturing plants in ontario at bramalea, belleville, london and kingston that make wire, cable, telephones and office telecommunications equipment
the company is 52.3 per cent owned by conglomerate bce, formerly bell canada enterprises, and has 24 plants and repair operations. fourteen of the company's plants are located in the united states
the number of oil and gas rigs working in the united states posted a small increase of five this week to total 983, baker hughes inc. announced
the total reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for oil as of last friday, not the number rigs producing oil. the previous week, the count had increased by 10 to total 978
a year ago, the rig count was 801, baker hughes announced monday
houston-based baker hughes, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number of working rigs and the count is the widely-watched industry index of drilling activity
hughes tool co., which merged this year with baker international corp. of orange, calif., has kept track of the number of working rigs since 1940
the rig count reached a peak of 4,500 active rigs in december 1981 _ the height of the oil boom. but as oil prices plunged to less than $10 per 42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, the count fell to 663, the lowest since hughes began compiling figures
among the major oil producing states, oklahoma gained 12 rigs this week, followed by texas with 11, wyoming with three and louisiana with one
michigan's count dropped by seven and ohio and colorado each lost three. kansas and new mexico were down by two each, while pennsylvania and california each lost one
futures prices for corn and soybeans were higher while wheat prices were mixed at the close monday in moderate to good volume on the chicago board of trade
soybean prices closed near 7 cents above friday's prices
lighter than expected delivery notices for soybeans helped support higher soybeans prices, said jerry gidel, grains analyst for g.h. miller &amp; co
wheat prices were supported by import interest from the phillippines, 175,000 tons worth, and talk that the soviets may be back in the market, gidel said
corn prices were restained somewhat by lower than expected exports for that commodity, said steve freed, grains analyst with dean witter reynolds inc
