security pacific corp., the nation's seventh-largest bank holding concern, said monday it has agreed to acquire san francisco-based hibernia bank for $160 million, or about 1{ times its book value
hibernia was put on the auction block by its parent, hong kong-based first pacific holdings ltd., last summer. but after october's stock market crash, first pacific said it was no longer actively seeking a buyer
acquisition of hibernia will strengthen los angeles-based security pacific in the northern part of the state
hibernia, the 13th largest bank in california, has 35 branches in northern california, including 28 in the san francisco bay area. at year end, it had $1.2 billion in deposits and more than $1 billion in outstanding loans. it posted a profit of $11.2 million last year
however, the sale of hibernia doesn't mark a pullout from california banking for first pacific, which will continue to own smaller united savings bank, with operations in the san francisco and los angeles regions
tom yasuda, one of first pacific's directors, said the holding company's plans call for it to expand united savings
first pacific also owns a bank in hong kong, an investment-banking concern in the philippines, and a trade-confirming operation and minority interest in an export-finance business in england
security pacific, whose chief subsidiary is los angeles-based security pacific national bank, the second largest in the state, has assets of more than $72 billion
santa fe southern pacific corp. has completed the sale of a timber subsidiary to sierra pacific industries for $460 million, officials announced monday
the two companies had announced their agreement oct. 12 on the sale of santa fe pacific timber co., which owns and manages about 520,000 acres of timberland in northern california
sierra pacific is a privately-held company based in redding, calif
closing on the timber company sale nearly completes santa fe's restructuring program, leaving only one non-core business for sale, the black mesa pipeline
before taxes, the company has taken in $880 million from the sales, which included robert e. mckee, a general building contractor, bankers leasing and financial corp. and two pipeline systems. pay hike</head>
the government has authorized a 3 percent increase in the minimum wage in march and ordered a freeze in official prices and the value of the peso
the new measures, announced late sunday, marked the government's most aggressive attempt yet to rid the nation of its no. 1 economic problem, inflation
president miguel de la madrid told a meeting of labor, business and campesino leaders, ``the national motto is no increase in prices in the month of march.''
labor leader fidel velazquez worried, though, that merchants would quickly mark up their prices before tuesday, the first day of the freeze
prices in march are going to try to be checked ... but last night and today they have been raising them,'' he contended late sunday
the small increase in the minimum daily wage to 8,000 pesos _ about $3.50 _ was a blow to velazquez and his 3 million-member mexican labor federation, which had been pushing for a 10 percent gain
workers, he said, have agreed to ``put the interests of the country ahead of their own interests.''
about half the nation's 25 million workers are estimated to earn the minimum wage
analysts calculate that the purchasing power of workers' making the minimum pay has deteriorated to about half of what it was in 1978
de la madrid said he was quickening the pace of his inflation-fighting program, unveiled in mid-december, because fresh price figures showed ``an important de-acceleration'' in february
consumer prices, the president predicted, would rise in february at about half the record 15.5 percent of january. last week, the government announced a a gain of 8.7 percent in prices in the first half of february
jonathan heath, senior economist at the forecasting firm of macro asesoria economica, predicted an inflation rate of about 8.5 percent in february and 5 percent to 5.5 percent in march
the new economic program, he said, appears to be successful so far. but, he added, ``we can't look at short-run indicators.''
we want to see if it is a permanent drop and the government is not inducing a temporary, artificial drop. we want to make sure it's a permanent, once-and-for-all drop in inflation,'' he said
the government had been expected to release a target level that would be used, starting tuesday, to index wages and prices. the indexation plan was designed as the centerpiece of the anti-inflation program, called the economic solidarity pact
the government drew up the solidarity pact because of worries the nation was on the verge of hyper-inflation. consumer prices skyrocketed a record 159.2 percent last year
but in a surprise move, the president's office authorized the smaller-than-expected increase in the minimum wage and ordered a freeze on the prices of government-regulated and -controlled itms. such products range from gasoline and electricity to tortillas and milk
it also urged private companies to join in the freeze, refraining from marking up prices to make up for higher wage costs
moreover, officials said the exchange rate for the peso will be held steady in march at monday's level. the bank of mexico, the nation's central bank, trimmed the currency's value against the dollar by 3 units each trading day in february
at midday monday, the peso in free-market trading ranged from 2,300 pesos to the dollar to 2,360 pesos at the private firms. it was 2,237-2,267 on friday. the free rate is used in tourism and border transactions
a second rate regulated by the government was 2,281 pesos to the dollar. this rate, used in about 75 percent of all commercial transaction, stood at 2,270 on friday
the supreme court on monday refused to revive lawsuits that charged the government and federal contractors with negligently causing deaths and disease among people exposed to open-air atomic tests
the court, without comment, let stand a federal law that effectively spared the government from having to defend itself against claims seeking billions of dollars
in another case, the court asked the reagan administration for its opinion of a ruling that states indirectly may tax interest paid to financial institutions from investments in federal home loan bank (fhlb) bonds
the court said it wants to hear from justice department lawyers before saying whether it will review fully a challenge to a maryland bank franchise tax
in other cases dealing with economic or business-related issues, the court:
_agreed to decide whether the u.s. customs service may force applicants for drug enforcement jobs to be tested for drugs. a federal workers union challenged the tests, calling the taking of urine samples from employees a humiliating invasion of privacy
_let stand rulings that warrantless searches of illinois racetrack employees' on-grounds living quarters violate constitutionally protected privacy rights
_said it will decide whether employees of a pentagon intelligence agency are entitled to administrative hearings when the government fires them as security risks
_agreed to consider letting the federal government apply retroactively a formula that limits reimbursement paid to hospitals treating medicare patients. the court said it will hear reagan administraion arguments that some hospitals could reap a windfall from the ban on retroactive application of the formula
_asked the reagan administration whether it thinks high-stakes bingo games run by indian tribes are subject to state sales taxes. the court said it wants to hear from justice department lawyers before it says whether it will review an attempt by oklahoma officials to tax revenue from a bingo game in tulsa run by the muscogee creek nation
the atmospheric nuclear tests that gave rise to the case involving the government and federal contractors took place between the closing days of world war ii and the adoption of a treaty between the united states and the soviet union in 1963 banning open-air testing
suits were filed on behalf of 29 people _ civilians and members of the military _ including 26 who died from cancer or cancer-related causes. the suits alleged that the health problems were caused by radioactive fallout from the explosions
charged with negligence were the university of california, which operated the los alamos, n.m., project; lawrence livermore laboratories, which helped develop the atomic bomb; sandia corp., which provided engineering for the weapons program; and reynolds electric engineering co., which helped build and operate a test site in nevada
the suits accused the private contractors of failing to take adequate safety precautions at the test sites, and also said the government was responsible for failing to enforce its own safety standards
if the suits were successful, the government ultimately would pay the claims because it had insured the private contractors for any losses
but in 1984 congress passed a law supported by the reagan administration that says only the u.s. government may be sued for negligence allegedly caused by a private contractor in the atomic weapons testing program
the result was to bar the claims since the government is immune from such suits unless it surrenders immunity under the existing federal tort claims act
in the fhlb bond interest case, the maryland national bank challenged the tax, seeking a refund of $197,310 it paid under protest to the state for the years 1979 through 1982
during that period, the bank reported $2.82 million in interest from fhlb bonds
the sum was included in the bank's earnings that were subject to maryland's franchise tax, which is imposed on financial institutions for the privilege of doing business in maryland
the difficulty over whether earnings from fhlb bonds are taxable arises because of two apparently conflicting federal laws
the 1932 law that created the fhlb generally exempts the bonds from taxes
but a law enacted in 1862 permits states to levy a ``non-discriminatory franchise tax'' on ``stocks and obligations of the united states government'' that generally are exempt from state and local taxes
the maryland court of appeals upheld the state franchise tax, ruling in october that the 1862 law takes precedence
preston robert tisch, former loews corp. president and chief operating officer who served as postmaster general for 19 months, will return to the company as president, co-chief executive and a director
loews said monday that tisch, who announced jan. 5 that he was leaving the postal position to resume private business, was elected to the posts, which include the newly created title of co-chief executive. he will share that responsibility with brother laurence tisch, who will remain company chairman
the office of loews president had remained vacant after preston robert tisch became postmaster general in august 1986. he agreed to stay on until the march 1 arrival of his successor, california banker anthony m. frank
based in new york, loews is a holding company with interests in tobacco products, hotels, real estate and insurance. injuries</head>
a federal appeals court has upheld a lower court ruling that blamed defective design of a winchester rifle for an accidential firing that injured two new hampshire teen-agers during a 1977 hunting trip
the 1st u.s. circuit court of appeals rejected arguments from the manufacturer of the rifle, olin corp., that a federal judge in new hampshire erred when he held the company liable for the shooting
damages were not an issue in the appeal, but the victims, henry fortier and raymond croteau, were awarded a total of $560,000 as part of the sept. 16, 1986, decision by u.s. district judge martin f. loughlin
fortier and croteau suffered foot wounds when a third teen-ager, paul croteau, stumbled and fell during the hunting trip near berlin, n.h. the rifle discharged when it hit the ground, and the bullet passed through raymond croteau's left foot then pierced fortier's right foot
it could reasonably be concluded from the evidence that the defective design made the rifle unreasonably dangerous for the purpose sold _ to be used as a hunting weapon,'' the appeals court said in a decision published thursday
there was evidence that defendant, despite its denial, had a consumer product safety committee which was aware that there could be an accidental discharge caused by a hunter falling while carrying a rifle in a position similar to that of paul croteau on the day of the accident,'' the court said
howard b. myers, the new hampshire attorney who represented the connecticut-based company, did not immediately return telephone calls from the associated press on monday. an olin spokesman said he did not know if the company would appeal
at the new hampshire trial, three firearms experts who testified for the victims blamed the accident on the design of the winchester model 94 rifle, a commemorative replica of the original 1866 winchester. one of them testified that because of its weight, the firing pin was thrust forward when the rifle hit the ground and caused the bullet to discharge even though the gun was half cocked, which acts as a safety on the rifle
two of the experts testified that they had tested the rifle and said it would fire, even when in the half-cocked position, if rapped with a hand or a rubber mallet
the victims also introduced evidence that olin conducted tests on the rifle in 1974 and 1976 to determine if it would fire when dropped to the ground. the tests indicated that the gun fired a small percentage of the time
also introduced as evidence by the victims was a 1976 letter in which an olin weapons engineer said it would cost between $1.75 and $2.50 a rifle to add an additional safety
in 1982, u.s. repeating arms of new haven, conn., which had obtained licensing rights to the winchester name from olin, introduced a modified version of the rifle with a lighter weight firing pin. u.s. repeating arms since has been purchased by another company
fidelity investments, the nation's largest mutual fund firm, said monday it would lay off 800 workers hired to handle the rapid growth it enjoyed before october's stock market crash
the firm said it would base the need for future cuts on the pace investors return to mutual funds
we will be monitoring business conditions,'' said spokeswoman karen ernst. ``we don't anticipate anymore layoffs at the moment, but that will depend on the market.''
fidelity attributed the 10.5 percent work force reduction to a slump in new stock transactions and slower money management business since the oct. 19 crash
also, the company reported a drop in individual retirement accounts due to new federal laws limiting the tax deductability of ira contributions
ernst said most of the dismissed fidelity workers were from corporate staff departments and ``volume-sensitive'' jobs, such as telephone representatives, order takers and mail processers
these were the people directly affected by a decline in new business,'' she said
approximately 530 workers were laid off in boston area offices, with about 150 in dallas and about 50 in new york. the remainder of the cuts are from other offices around the country
the action reduces fidelity's nationwide staff to approximately 6,850, about the same number of workers employed by the firm in mid-1987. fidelity operates 53 u.s. offices and one in london
ernst said fidelity's boston headquarters was most affected by the cuts since it was one of the company's largest growth areas during its rapid expansion
since 1982, fidelity increased its work force four-fold to about 7,800 while assets swelled from about $19 billion to a peak of about $85 billion dispersed among nearly 100 funds, including the extremely popular magellan fund
the firm also branched to other ventures, such as real estate, a discount stock brokerage and institutional pension management
eric kobren, a former fidelity employee who publishes an independent newsletter that monitors the company, said fidelity may be forced to reduce services and bring additional layoffs if business does not accelerate
this is a first step,'' said kobren. ``i would not be surprised if we see further cuts after the ira season if business stays at the same pace. this may be the first round of cuts, and they will digest it and see how they are doing then proceed with others.''
the company dismissed about 300 part-time and 50 full-time workers feb. 11, including 50 in boston and 125 each in dallas and salt lake city
earlier this year, fidelity laid off 32 workers at investment centers nationwide
while mutual fund activity is less than one-third of last year's bull market levels, there has been a steady resurgence since the crash, according to kathryn morrison, spokeswoman for the washington, d.c.-based investment company institute
net mutual fund sales have risen from minus $5.8 billion in october to $1.8 billion in january, she said. the figures reflect total sales minus redemptions, said morrison
morrison said there are approximately 2,000 funds available
in money market accounts nationwide, total assets have risen from $241.3 billion in september to about $280 billion in january
there's $40 billion on the sidelines now waiting to see what happens with the market,'' said morrison. ``there's no shortage of assets out there, it's just not in mutual funds like before.''
security pacific corp., the nation's seventh-largest bank holding concern, said monday it has agreed to acquire san francisco-based hibernia bank for $160 million, or about 1{ times its book value
hibernia was put on the auction block by its parent, hong kong-based first pacific holdings ltd., last summer. but after october's stock market crash, first pacific said it was no longer actively seeking a buyer
acquisition of hibernia will strengthen los angeles-based security pacific in the northern part of the state
hibernia, the 13th largest bank in california, has 35 branches in northern california, including 28 in the san francisco bay area. at year end, it had $1.2 billion in deposits and more than $1 billion in outstanding loans. it posted a profit of $11.2 million last year
however, the sale of hibernia doesn't mark a pullout from california banking for first pacific, which will continue to own smaller united savings bank, with operations in the san francisco and los angeles regions
tom yasuda, one of first pacific's directors, said the holding company's plans call for it to expand united savings
first pacific also owns a bank in hong kong, an investment-banking concern in the philippines, and a trade-confirming operation and minority interest in an export-finance business in england
security pacific, whose chief subsidiary is los angeles-based security pacific national bank, the second largest in the state, has assets of more than $72 billion
anheuser-busch beverage group inc. announced monday that its asante and saratoga sparkling water brands and its zeltzer seltzer natural soda brand are up for sale
the decision follows the company's recent discontinuance of the dewey stevens wine cooler brand due to a declining rate of growth industrywide in cooler sales
terry poulos, vice president and general manager of the group, said that without the dewey stevens sales, ``total beverage group volume was reduced below the level necessary to financially support our continued production of these brands.''
anheuser-busch will continue to support the brands through current distributors until they are sold, poulos said
he also said that since the introduction of the non-beer beverages, competitive distribution methods had changed from the primary use of wholesalers to direct shipments from producers to major retailers. therefore, the brands no longer fit anheuser-busch's wholesaler system as originally envisioned, he said
the company will continue to market master cellars keg wines and anheuser &amp; fehrs, an imported german wine. the test marketing of the imported ballygowan irish sparkling spring water also will continue, poulos said
stock prices rose sharply today, reaching new highs since the crash last fall
analysts said traders were heartened to see the dow jones industrial average surpass the 2,051.89 level, where it stood jan. 7 for its highest closing reading since the crash
the average failed in a bid to climb past that point last week, but no significant selling pressure resulted, suggest to many analysts that it was primed to make another try
one concern facing the market is the report due tuesday from the commerce department on the index of leading economic indicators for january
analysts generally expect the figure to show a decline. but the firm of smith barney, harris upham &amp; co. said the 0.2 percent drop originally reported for december might be revised to show a gain
that would mean that the index would no longer have a string of three consecutive monthly declines, a phenomenon which is traditionally regarded as a potential recession warning
the dow jones average of 30 industrials jumped 48.41 to 2,071.62
advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 2 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,257 up, 353 down and 357 unchanged
big board volume totaled 236.05 million shares, against 191.09 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index gained 2.76 to 150.46
union flight attendants for northwest airlines were told by teamsters officials monday that a company proposal to delay the promotion of b-scale workers to the higher-paid a-scale bracket is the only major issue separating the two sides in contract talks
about 150 of the company's 6,700 flight attendants were informed of the situation at a rally at a teamsters office less that two miles away from the corporation's headquarters
an 11 p.m. friday strike deadline passed without a settlement in talks aimed at bring former republic airlines employees and their northwest counterparts under one contract. the employees have been working under separate contracts since northwest acquired republic in the fall of 1986
talks broke down saturday at dawn after an all-night bargaining session with a federal mediator. but flight attendants have not been called on to strike and the company has not exercised its right to impose a contract on the flight attendants
jeff musto, a spokesman for the teamsters, said monday that no talks have been held since saturday and none are scheduled
we're still on red alert to strike,'' musto. ``we want to keep the company guessing.''
as musto explained, the one major issue left unresolved in the negotiations are wages, which are governed under a two-tiered scale
all northwest flight attendant were paid under one scale before a 1982 contract created the b scale. all new employees hired since then have started as b-scale employees at rates of pay lower than the old system, musto said
but the 1982 contract called for b-scale employees to jump to a-scale levels in their sixth year of employment. the company has proposed extending that wait until the ninth year of employment, musto said
for the average flight attendant, that would mean a loss of $16,776 over the three years, musto said
the company said the hourly wages it has proposed for the flight attendants would make them the second-highest paid in the industry. musto said he agrees with that assessment, but he added that the union has a commitment to flight attendants hired under the b-scale not to break ``our promise'' that they would be promoted to the a-scale in their sixth year
they could see light at the end of the tunnel,'' musto said. ``now all of a sudden the company is dangling the carrot out in front of them a little further.''
about a third of the company's flight attendants are at the b-scale level, musto said. by delaying their promotion to a-scale, the majority of flight attendants would be under the b-scale when it is time to negotiate the next contract
then the company could win support for cutting the wages of a-scale flight attendants because a-scale employees would be in the minority, musto said
under northwest's latest contract offer, base pay for senior flight attendants would be about $35.18 an hour based on a 78-hour work month, about half of what most americans work. that would increase to $36.60 an hour by may 1, 1991, the company said
william wren said a large number of senior flight attendants make more than $40,000 a year, plus meal payments when they're working
most entry-level flight attendants are making about $15,000 a year, wren said
the chief negotiator for the flight attendants, william genoese, was denied a request monday to meet with steven rothmeier, chairman and chief executive officer of the airline, musto said
there was no further word monday on whether pilots and mechanics at northwest would honor picket lines by the flight attendants. officials from the unions representing pilots and mechanics have said they will wait to make a decision
wren has said the mechanics are barred from sympathy strikes under their contract and pilots are barred from sympathy strikes under the railway labor act
wren said the company was operating under its normal flight schedule monday. about 2,000 non-union flight attendants are on call to fill in if a strike is called, he has said
american telephone &amp; telegraph co. said monday it will make sure that its widely used unix operating system, the internal traffic cop of computers, is readily available to all the computer hardware companies that want to use it
some major computer companies had charged that at&amp;t was playing favorites by giving early information about future versions of unix to sun microsystems inc., a silicon valley maker of engineering workstations that is a close partner of at&amp;t
people have had a big misconception about what the nature of the agreement has been,'' bill klinger, an at&amp;t executive in charge of unix product management, said in an interview
klinger said it would be a mistake for at&amp;t to play favorites because that would delay the spread of unix, an operating system that is used mainly for scientific and engineering work
motorola inc. said monday that the london-based unisoft group, working closely with at&amp;t, would work to make sure that unix runs on computers that contain microprocessors made by motorola
combined with at&amp;t's support, this will ensure motorola's customers the same full and timely access as early as any competitive architecture,'' gary tooker, motorola's chief operating officer, said in a news release
motorola claims that 80 percent of all unix-based computer programs run on computers containing its microprocessors
motorola's goal is to have programs run without modification on any computer that uses one of its microprocessors
simon &amp; schuster inc. said monday it had acquired a group of travel publications from rand mcnally &amp; co. for an undisclosed price
the gulf &amp; western co. publishing and information services unit said it had acquired rand mcnally's campground directories and national park guides and other travel location products including the places rated series, which rates cities according to quality-of-life attributes
rand mcnally retains its map-related travel publications
the titles will become part of simon &amp; schuster's prentice hall trade division which publishes and distributes travel guides and other travel-related products under such imprints as access, frommer and mobil
steven murphy, president of prentice hall, said the acquisitions represent ``a perfect fit in terms of product and strategy.''
it will not only add new destinations to our travel title list but will greatly enhance our capabilities in the development of new product for the travel market,'' he said
roger wildermuth, president of the rand mcnally publishing group, said the divestiture is part of a strategy of concentrating its consumer publishing resources on road atlases, road maps, world atlases and other map products
american express chairman james d. robinson iii on monday suggested creation of a new international financial organization to help ease the debt crisis of developing nations by buying their loans
robinson, in remarks prepared for a meeting of the overseas development council, said the organization, which he named ``the institute of international debt and development,'' would buy outstanding third world loans at a discount
one possibility, he suggested, would be for the loans to be acquired at about 60 percent of face value
the organization would then offer the banks which had held the loans ``new, long-term, high-quality obligations,'' including bonds and certain forms of stock, robinson suggested
i hope it (the proposal) will at least serve as a catalyst to start an active dialogue,'' he said. he said new approaches were needed because ``the risk of a debt crisis still hovers over the fianancial markets.''
under robinson's proposal, the new organization would oversee and manage many facets of refinancing of loans owed by latin american and other developing nations
total third world debt now stands at about $1.2 trillion. however, robinson's proposal would be targeted to some $250 billion owed to commercial banks by developing governments
because the plan involves purchase of outstanding loans at a discount, it would involve partial write-offs of the loans
such an approach has been a part of some previous proposals, including those advanced by sen. bill bradley, r-n.j., and rep. john lafalce, d-n.y., but long opposed by the reagan administration
instead, the administration favors instead a rival plan by treasury secretary james a. baker iii that calls for new lending to developing countries on a nation-by-nation basis, both by international organizations like the world bank and by commercial banks
but, robinson said: ``the case-by-case approach has bought time and set the stage for a solution. but many believe it has not helped the (developing country) debt problem get much better.''
robinson long has been active in international financial matters and he had previously advanced earlier versions of his proposal for a new international debt agency
he said the new agency should be a joint venture of the world bank and the international monetary fund and that major industrial nations would provide start-up capital for the organization totaling about $12.5 billion
under the existing formula by which the united states contributes 20 percent to the funds of the imf, this would result in a u.s. share of about $2.5 billion
the current strategy of case-by-case negotiations ... has so far held a crisis at bay ... but it has not brought with it adequate resources to support sustained growth in (developing) economies,'' robinson said
the stock market climbed to its highest level since the october crash with a broad advance monday that gathered momentum as the session progressed
the dow jones average of 30 industrials jumped 48.41 to 2,071.62, posting more than half its gain in the last hour of trading
advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 2 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,255 up, 351 down and 374 unchanged
big board volume reached 236.05 million shares, against 191.09 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index gained 2.76 to 150.46
as measured by wilshire associates' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market increased $44.95 billion, or 1.73 percent, in value
analysts said traders were heartened to see the dow jones industrial average vault past the 2,051.89 level, where it stood jan. 7 for its previous highest closing reading since the crash last year
the average failed in a bid to surpass that point last week, but no significant selling pressure followed, suggest to many analysts that it was primed to make another try
one concern facing the market is the report due tuesday from the commerce department on the index of leading economic indicators for january
analysts generally expect the figure to show a decline. but the firm of smith barney, harris upham &amp; co. said the 0.2 percent drop originally reported for december might be revised to show a gain
that would mean that the index would no longer have a string of three consecutive monthly declines, a phenomenon that is traditionally regarded as a potential recession warning
the dow jones industrials finished february with a gain of 113.40 points. the average stands some 333 points above its close of 1,738.74 on black monday oct. 19
observers said enthusiasm for stocks was fueled by continuing brisk takeover activity
on the takeover scene, roper corp. jumped 10} to 36~. the company agreed to be acquired by whirlpool corp. for $37.50 a share
homestake mining climbed 3{ to 18. mesa limited partnership made a $20-a-share offer for the company
stop &amp; shop picked up ~ to 43{. the company, fighting a hostile bid by dart group, reached agreement on a buyout at $44 a share by a group organized by kohlberg, kravis, roberts &amp; co
point-plus gainers among the blue chips included general motors, up 3[ at 72\; merck, up 4| at 165]; international business machines, up 1} at 117{; general electric, up 1~ at 45{, and international paper, up 1| at 44]
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 265.09 million shares
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials rose 6.80 to 309.43, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index was up 5.36 at 267.82
the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market gained 3.55 to 366.95. at the american stock exchange, the market value index closed at 288.46, up 4.14
investment losses and high interest expenses for money it borrowed to buy santa fe southern pacific corp. stock gave henley group large deficits for the fourth quarter and all of 1987
however, the losses were 44 percent less for the quarter and 35 percent less for the year compared with the year-earlier periods, the investment company said monday
for the three months ended dec. 31, the company said it lost $197 million on revenues of $863 million, compared with a $354 million lossk on revenues of $825 million in the final period of 1986
for the full year, the company said it lost $278 million on revenues of $3.52 billion, compared with a loss of $426 million on revenues of $3.17 billion in 1986
the 1987 results reflected investment losses of $112 million for the fourth quarter and $102 million for the year, plus higher interest expense for loans to acquire 15.1 million shares of santa fe, the chicago-based railroad and natural resources concern that henley has been seeking to take over
in all, henley owns 24.6 million, or 15.7 percent, of santa fe's 157.3 million shares
the 1986 results included $286 million in pretax restructuring charges related to writedowns and asset revaluations
for nearly a year, henley has been courting santa fe, but the chicago company has repeatedly spurned its unsolicited overtures
the 1987 results represent henley's first full year as an independent company
henley was formed in 1986 from 35 construction, environmental, energy, chemical, manufacturing and finance businesses spun off 1{ years earlier by allied-signal corp., which itself was formed by a $5 billion merger in mid-1985
henley has focused on paring costs and improving results of the operations, then spinning them off at a profit
futures prices for livestock plunged monday on the chicago mercantile exchange, and analysts blamed it on a ``nervousness'' over slaughter house shutdowns
prices fell as much as 127 points, or 1.27 cents, and only one contract, live hogs for delivery in december, managed to finish higher
selling interest in cattle was heightened by inactive cash markets, traders said
packers, with squeezed margins, have reduced their slaughters. they're closing some plants and there's nervousness in market,'' said tom morgan, head of sterling research corp. of arlington heights, ill
live hog prices followed a lower cash market, and prices for frozen pork bellies followed the lead of traders in the live hog pit, morgan said
live cattle settled .40 cent to 1.12 cents lower with the contract for delivery in april at 71.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent higher to 1.27 cents lower with march at 79.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent higher to 1.07 cents lower with april at 43.25 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .25 cent to .63 cent higher with march at 51.85 cents a pound
futures prices for corn and soybeans were up sharply while wheat prices were mixed on the chicago board of trade
some soybean contracts closed more than 10 cents above friday's prices
lighter-than-expected delivery notices for soybeans helped support higher soybeans prices, said jerry gidel, a grains analyst in chicago for g.h. miller &amp; co
wheat prices were supported by import interest from the phillippines, 175,000 tons worth, and talk that the soviets may be back in the market, gidel said
corn prices were restained somewhat by lower-than-expected exports for that commodity, said steve freed, a grains analyst in chicago with dean witter reynolds inc
wheat settled 1\ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.15{ a bushel; corn was 2\ cents to 3 cents higher with march at $2.03} a bushel; oats were 2\ cents to 4\ cents higher with march at $1.94{ a bushel; and soybeans were 8{ cents to 10{ cents higher with march at $6.36 a bushel
energy prices finished higher in moderate volume on the new york mercantile exchange
the heating oil contract for march rose 1.46 cents because it had been oversold at the end of last week, said peter beutel, a petroleum analyst in new york with elders future inc
crude oil prices were supported by a recently published report that production by organization of petroleum exporting countries was lower than expected, he said
crude oil settled 12 cents to 23 cents higher with the contract for delivery in february at $15.49 a barrel; heating oil was .38 cent to 1.46 cents higher with february at 45.85 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .41 cent to .70 cent higher with march at 45.71 cents a gallon
gold and silver prices climbed higher on the commodity exchange in new york
a technical adjustment, known as a short-covering rally, in platinum trading _ where futures prices rose $25 a troy ounce _ triggered the higher prices in precious metals, said marty mcneill, a metals analyst in new york with dominick &amp; dominick
in a short sale, a trader sells borrowed contracts in hopes of replacing them _ or ``covering'' the sale _ later with others bought at a lower price
grains were up sharply, that always helps,'' he said. ``oil prices were rising, and the dollar was mixed among foreign currencies. that played a part in the market, too.''
gold settled 10 cents to 90 cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $430.50 a troy ounce; and silver was 8.4 cents to 9.7 cents higher with march at $6.23 a troy ounce
gold prices tumbled monday in europe but rebounded sharply in new york, based on a stunning rally in platinum that traders ascribed to fear of unrest in south africa, a leading producer of precious metals
the dollar vacillated in a narrow range in sluggish foreign exchange transactions, reflecting what brokers called the lack of economic news and a typical trading slowdown at month's end
european gold traders sold the metal aggressively, based on an underlying fear that gold was becoming a less attractive investment because of evidence of eased inflation
in london, gold fell $6.50 a troy ounce from friday levels to $425 and in zurich it fell $5.50 an ounce to $426. earlier in hong kong gold was down about 15 cents to $430.19
later in new york gold recovered the loss, and by 4 p.m. republic national bank of new york quoted gold at $430.50 a troy ounce, up from $429.50 friday. on the new york commodity exchange, gold bullion for current delivery was quoted at $430.50 an ounce, up 90 cents
the one word to explain it was platinum,'' said john norris, a precious metals analyst at citibank in new york. ``we saw a sharp rally in platinum, based on continued unrest in south africa, and that helped firm gold prices.''
on the new york mercantile exchange, platinum for current delivery surged $25.30 a troy ounce to $475
silver prices also advanced on the new york comex, up 8.4 cents from friday to $6.24 a troy ounce. earlier in london, silver fell to $6.14 a troy ounce, down from $6.20 late friday
currency brokers said dollar trading was uneventful and there were no financial developments to influence the currency's behavior. but some said government reports later in the week providing evidence of the u.s. economy's direction might affect the dollar
traders got fed up with the market today,'' said toshihiko masaki, a foreign exchange trader at the new york office of japan's sanwa bank. ``there was no economic data, no news, no factors. people got bored.''
the dollar fell in tokyo to 128.12 japanese yen from 128.35 yen at the close friday. later in london, the dollar edged higher to 128.35 yen. by the time trading concluded in new york, the dollar was quoted at 128.24 yen, down from 128.37 yen late friday
in london, the british pound eased to $1.7725 from $1.7730 late friday. but later in new york the pound was worth $1.7742, up from $1.7715 quoted late friday
other late dollar rates in new york compared with late friday included: 1.6874 west german marks, down from 1.6887; 1.3931 swiss francs, up from 1.3863; 1.2592 canadian dollars, down from 1.2634; 5.7155 french francs, down from 5.7170; and 1,243 italian lire, down from 1,245
other late dollar rates in europe compared with late friday included: 1.6875 west german marks, down from 1.6895; 1.3903 swiss francs, up from 1.3897; 5.7150 french francs, down from 5.7175; 1.8945 dutch guilders, down from 1.8965; 1,244.25 italian lire, down from 1,245.45; 1.2622 canadian dollars, down from 1.2838
united parcel service announced monday that its wholly-owned subsidiary, ups italia srl, has entered into a contract to acquire one of italy's leading domestic and international package carriers
the purchase price for alimondo was not disclosed. the transaction is expected to be completed in april
founded in 1907, greenwich-based ups handles about 10 million parcels daily in combined ground and air service around the world
since september 1986, ups and alimondo have been service partners in a delivery service between italy and the united states, and between italy and west germany
john w. rogers, ups chief executive officer, said the acquisition is ``an evolution of a successful service partnership.''
alimondo managing director roberto pacchiono said the acquisition will enable his firm to benefit from ``the long experience and expertise of one of the most qualified operators in the parcel delivery field.''
all ``dial-a-porn'' telephone messages would be placed under one exchange and customers would be allowed to block all calls to that exchange at no charge under a plan announced monday by new york telephone co
it will give parents a means of preventing their children from calling these companies,'' company spokesman steve marcus said of the plan which has been proposed to the state public service commission
the proposal is similar to plans now being implemented elsewhere around the country as phone companies have sought legal ways to pull the plug on sexually explicit telephone dial-up messages
new york telephone proposed that adult messages be grouped under the 970 exchange. customers in the new york metropolitan calling area could control how their phones are used by having the phone company block that exchange
the metropolitan calling area includes area codes 212, 718, 516 and part of 914. calls from other points in the state to the 970 exchange would be blocked automatically, the company said
customers would also have the option of blocking all calls to group bridging services, numbers which allow several customers to participate in the same conversation
there would be no charge for ordering the block for 90 days after the plan becomes effective _ march 11 if the psc approves. after that, residence customers would pay $5 for instituting the block and business customers $10
currently, adult messages and other mass announcement services are spread over the 540, 550, 970 and 976 exchanges. the phone company supplies the lines but does not control the content
new york telephone has about 4.2 million residential customers in the metropolitan area. about 26 percent of them would require a number change to implement a block because not all exchanges have the updated switching equipment required for the move. those needing a number change would be given it free of charge, the company said
mcorp officials on monday reached a definitive agreement to sell the company's 80.1 percent interest in mtech to electronic data systems corp. for about $281 million in cash and securities
gene h. bishop, chairman and chief executive officer of mcorp, and les alberthal, eds president and chief executive officer, made the joint announcement
the dallas-based eds is a wholly owned subsidiary of general motors corp
we are particularly pleased to reach this agreement with eds,'' bishop said in a prepared statement. ``the transaction will allow mcorp to realize significant value which has been previouosly unrecognized.''
the agreement's terms call for mcorp to get about $30 in cash and securities for each mtech common share. the transaction, subject to gm approval and satisfaction of other conditions, was expected to be completed by april 15
holders of mtech common stock and convertible debentures would be offered the same package of cash and securities as that received by mcorp. public holders of mtech common stock would also get a ``cash election'' for payment entirely in cash at the rate of $30 per mtech share
holders of mtech convertible debentures will be offered the opportunity to receive $1,000 plus accrued interest for each debenture
mtech has been an eds competitor for some time, said eds spokesman roger still. mtech does business in 18 states with 1,400 financial institutions
we have no intention of laying off anybody,'' still said. ``there's a lot of good talent at mtech. it would be really premature to talk about any changes in their assets or management structure.''
about 19.9 percent of mtech is owned by individual stockholders, said still
mcorp is a financial services company with assets of $20.2 billion as of dec. 31
stop &amp; shop cos. inc. announced monday it has agreed to be acquired in a $1.23 billion leveraged buyout by the investment firm kohlberg kravis roberts inc., but dart group corp. said the news will not deter its attempt to gain control of the retailer
stop &amp; shop said a kohlberg kravis subsidiary, ssc holdings corp., will purchase at least 66 percent of the 28 million outstanding stop &amp; shop shares at $44 each
if all outstanding stock were purchased, the leveraged buyout would total $1.23 billion. in a leveraged buyout, investors borrow heavily to buy out a company and then pay off the debt with the target company's cash flow or the sale of its assets
dart, which launched the hostile takeover bid in january, extended until march 9 an offer of $37 a share for all outstanding stop &amp; shop stock and indicated it planned to go ahead with a proxy fight to replace stop &amp; shop directors later this month
dart spokesman jeffrey gast said the landover, md.-based firm planned to continue the cash tender offer past march 9 on a day to day basis
however, harry wells, an analyst at adams, harkness &amp; hill in boston, said it was unlikely dart could match the $44 a share offer
i think it's over,'' said wells. ``you've got to be able to support the debt with some level of safety ... and ($44) is about as much as one can reasonably afford to pay (for stop &amp; shop).''
stop &amp; shop has rejected as inadequate dart's $1.03 billion offer and filed suit in federal court, seeking to block dart
a countersuit filed by dart claiming stop &amp; shop illegally withheld corporate information was rejected last week by u.s. district court judge rya zobel, who ordered that the suit must be filed in state courts
dart, which purchased nearly 730,000 shares through its jefferson acquisition corp. subsidiary, announced feb. 26 it received approval from at least 10 percent of stop &amp; shop shareholders to call a special shareholders meeting on march 30
at the meeting, dart wants to remove the stop &amp; shop board and replace it with jefferson nominees
under the deal with kohlberg kravis, stop &amp; shop said it will retain its present management and remain based in braintree
the sale, which must be approved by a majority of stop &amp; shop shareholders and the securities and exchange commission, is expected to commence on or before march 4, stop &amp; shop said. kohlberg kravis has received a financing commitment from manufacturers hanover trust co., the retailer said
other companies reportedly have been interested in stop &amp; shop, including thomas h. lee co. of boston, and riordan, freeman &amp; spogli inc. of los angeles
stop &amp; shop has 113 supermarkets and 169 bradlees in 12 states in the northeast
the company's stock has gone up more than $25 a share since dart first announced its takeover intent in january. it rose 87{ cents a share in new york stock exchange trading monday, closing at $43.50
dart is known for a series of unsuccessful but profitable bids to gain control of other companies, and its chairman, herbert haft, and president, robert haft, have acquired reputations as corporate raiders
in its most recent bid, dart dropped an attempt for minneapolis-based dayton hudson corp. following the october stock market crash
other dart takeover attempts include a 1986 bid for safeway co. and supermarkets general last year
kohlberg kravis, which acquired safeway following the failed dart bid, has conducted about 33 leveraged buyouts since forming in 1976, including a $6.2 billion deal that took beatrice cos. private in 1986
last week, kohlberg kravis acquired new york-based seaman furniture co. for $350 million. in july 1987, the firm obtained control of jim walter co., a florida construction material manufacturer
john m. stafford resigned as head of pillsbury co. monday, and will be replaced by former chief executive william h. spoor, who will come out of retirement to assume those duties, the company said
the announcement was made in a prepared statement, which did not indicate why stafford resigned as chairman, president and chief executive officer, nor why spoor was elected by the company's board of directors to replace him
spokesmen for the company did not immediately return a reporter's phone call seeking comment beyond the statement
spoor, 65, returned to the company last september as chairman of the executive committee. he had retired in 1985 after spending his entire career with the company, the last 12 years as chairman and chief executive
spoor said shareholders and employees will long remember the many contributions made to the company by stafford
jack stafford has been totally dedicated to the success of pillsbury and to the values that make it great. we deeply appreciate everything that he has achieved for this company over the past decade,'' spoor said
in addition to the above action, the board of directors appointed a search committee to seek a chief executive for the company to succeed spoor
pittsburgh-area residents should wake up if they're still dreaming that empty steel plants will come back to life, say city planners from an international architecture conference
you've got to face reality. they're gone,'' said tony mcgann, whose hometown of liverpool, england, lived through the decline of dockyard industries. ``if you wait for the steel industry to come back, you'll wait forever.''
the planning team, 12 americans and five britons, toured monongahela valley communities whose economies have been gutted by the decline of steelmaking. they addressed about 100 mon valley residents saturday in homestead and released a report monday suggesting how the once-thriving steel centers of homestead, duquesne and mckeesport could recover
the planners' effort was organized by the american institute of architects, a sponsor of this week's remaking cities conference in pittsburgh. britain's prince charles, an advocate of better city planning, is scheduled to address the conference saturday
plants last operated by usx corp. in homestead, a river gateway to pittsburgh, could be leveled and replaced by five-acre flower plots like those featured in european garden festivals, the planners recommended
we can't use all the land at once. but if it looked green it would be easier to sell,'' said team leader john clarke of trenton, n.j
the planners envision turning one old ironmaking blast furnace into a museum, developing the riverbank as a yacht landing and perhaps within a decade building luxury riverfront homes
it's the greening of industrial america,'' british architect richard burton said
it sounds innovative, anyway. most of us around here though were looking for things that were going to create more jobs,'' said robert anderson, a founder of homestead's rainbow kitchen, which feeds about 100 unemployed people per day and distributes groceries as needed to about 600 households
at its peak, about 15,000 workers were employed at the homestead plant. the last steel was rolled in may 1986
few white knights are likely to ride into the mon valley and bring thousands of jobs at once,'' the report said
the report recommended that a former usx plant site at mckeesport be used for sports events, a giant flea market, a discount sales center and a factory outlet
it's better than using it for a warehouse. it would employ people and bring activity to downtown mckeesport,'' clarke said
duquesne seems best suited as a center for recycling trash or converting it to energy, the report said
homestead councilwoman betty esper and mike stout, a member of the steel valley authority and tri-state conference on steel, were among the town meeting speakers who said steel plants should not be redeveloped so quickly because the industry might need them again
you have to move forward. this is like a lingering divorce that, until it is finally settled, is very painful, and even after it's settled will be painful,'' said architect michael swartler of new york
longstanding dependence on one industry has left mon valley communities with little experience in developing their economies, clarke said
we have heard from mayors who don't know what role they play in development of the sites,'' he said. ``our work is an illustration of how to embark on that process.''
whirlpool corp. said monday it has reached an agreement to buy roper corp., an augusta, ga.-based manufacturer of appliances and lawn equipment, for $350 million
whirlpool, one of the nation's leading appliance makers with $4.2 billion in sales last year, will pay $37.50 a share for all outstanding stock in roper, whirlpool said
acquiring roper is a major step in our strategic plans for growth and is evidence of our commitment to the major home appliance marketplace,'' said david r. whitwam, chairman and president of whirlpool
charles ryan, an analyst for merrill lynch in new york, said the two companies were a ``good fit'' and each offered something that the other needed
ranges has been one of the weak areas for whirlpool,'' which now will have an internal source for them, he said. roper, on the other hand, faced the threat of a hostile takeover and found a friendly suitor in whirlpool, he said
whirlpool had net income of $191.9 million in 1987, down from $199.7 million one year earlier. earnings from the two years were the company's best of the last decade
under the agreement, robert cook will remain as president of roper and will become a vice president of whirlpool, whitwam said
this new relationship with whirlpool is outstanding for the future of both companies and is excellent for our stockholders, employees and customers,'' cook said
roper employs about 4,750 people at plants and offices in lafayette, dalton, mcrae and swainsboro, ga.; kankake, ill.; orangeburg, s.c.; chattanooga, tenn., mississauga, ontario. it had sales of $703 million in the 12 months ending july 31, 1987
roper produces electric and gas ranges, tillers, lawn mowers and lawn and garden tractors
like whirlpool, roper is a major supplier to sears roebuck &amp; co., the nation's leading retailer. the companies produce appliances that are sold under the sears brand name
joining forces with another reliable supplier of quality goods to sears can only serve to enhance the whirlpool-sears relationship,'' whitwam said. graf: monroe h....; uppicks penultimate graf: he added,...</note>
sears, roebuck and co. plans a major management overhaul in its retail division, but will not reveal what the restructuring will include until the changes are described to the company's headquarters staff, a sears spokesman said monday
philo holland, the company's national public affairs manager, said sears merchandise group officials would meet with employees in chicago this week to discuss the restructuring, ``which will take place over the next several years.''
holland said he could neither confirm nor deny a report in crain's chicago business that the nation's largest retailer planned to transform its 27 merchandise buying groups into independent business units and lay off some headquarters personnel
we need to hold these meetings this week with our own people to lay out the plans,'' he said. ``i can't confirm or deny (the crain's report) until we're able to talk to our employees. for them to read it in the newspaper before we tell it to them would be inappropriate.''
crain's, a weekly newspaper, reported in its editions out monday that sears planned the overhaul because of sluggish sales and profits
quoting a sears source it did not name, crain's said the company planned significant workforce reductions among its headquarters personnel through layoffs or attrition
while holland declined comment on the company's future plans, he said, ``there will not be any layoffs announced this week.''
crain's reported that, as part of the restructuring, sears would reorganize buying groups for every product line and scrap its past policy of using one management structure for each unit
the company also plans to analyze the competitiveness of each product line, from hard goods like washing machines to soft goods like fashion, to see if its profits are at an acceptable level in individual areas
while wall street analysts said they did not know what sears executives had in mind, they said the company could be trying to reposition itself in the retail industry as well as cut costs
they've been an underperforming group for the company,'' said karen sack, an analyst with standard &amp; poor's corp., of the sears merchandise group. ``they've turned in a really mediocre performance and it's a difficult retail market for at least 1988.''
they're going to have to do something to become more flexible and responsive to the changes in what's going to be a very lackluster sales environment,'' she said
monroe h. greenstein, an analyst with bear stearns &amp; co. inc., said sears has been considering a shift toward more fashion retailing
he added, ``they're trying to get rid of some of the fat.''
crain's also reported that sears would promote three executives to newly created management positions to oversee the restructuring, but holland said that step was not planned
unemployment in japan fell to a seasonally-adjusted 2.7 percent in january from 3.0 percent a year earlier, but was up 0.1 percentage point from the previous month, the government announced tuesday
the number of job holders rose during the one-year period by 1.12 million to 58.28 million, an increase of 1.9 percent, according to the statistics bureau of the prime minister's office
bureau officials said the number of people employed rose sharply in the latter half of the year as the economy recovered from the effects of the higher value of the japanese yen. the strong yen curbed overseas sales and earnings and forced japanese manufacturers, particularly shipbuilders and steelmakers, to slash production and manpower
after hitting a record 3.2 percent last may, japan's unemployment rate has drifted lower as manufacturers adjusted to the high yen
japan's unemployment rate would be higher if calculated by u.s. and european methods
in japan, members of the armed forces and people who worked more than one hour during the last week of the month are counted as employed. in the united states, military personnel are not included in the work force and those who work less than 15 hours a week are considered unemployed
